name: Drill em all
description: P1 climb left facing corner past a small roof and onto grooved slab above. Cams available then clip a bolt, move up to next bolt (crux) move right to flake. Clip a pin in another flake then follow diagonal right about 20’ to 2 bolt belay. P2 head up and left from anchor. 5 bolts to another anchor. Don’t be tempted by flare on the right, it is nasty! Stay left on good clean rock. Rap with single 60.

name: Making America grope again
description: Three pitch friction slab with gear and bolts. Bolted on lead so not a sport route. Start middle of wall by an obvious pointy flake under an overlap roof. Flake offers sling pro before a bolt. Face moves past bolt to roof and gear2-3 Camelot and wire at lip. Pull around onto slab above. Shallow water runnels and good friction past 3 bolts takes you to a nice scoop and a DBB. 30m, 5.9.    Pitch 2 is the money, climb up and right of belay small cam in slot up to an obvious vertical groove with a bolt. Weird moves here and a good piece of pro then up to a left trending corner and large cam. Move out of corner left under horizontal roof to a smooth ramp and another bolt, keep smearing left to another bolt and smearsmearsmear left till you can reach a vertical crack at left end of roof (crux) and a hanging DBB. Whew! Watch rope drag on this one, 25m, 5.10+PG13.   Pitch 3 follows the crack past 2 bolts then it lays back DBB,15m 5.9.

name: Andre the giant
description: The arete immediately right/ upstream from attack of the spider monkey. Climb an unprotected slab about 20 feet to a horizontal crack, medium cam or reach up to slab above for the first bolt. Pull onto this slab from right side and move left to arete and a good small cam or wire. Another thin crack above holds a small cam. Move up arete to a slabby ledge below a roof. Piton here and long sling recommended. Move right then up till you can clip a bolt. Harder moves past this and hard clip for second bolt, harder moves past this to double bolt belay above. Great rock and fun this moves.

name: Attack of the spider monkey
description: This is the left most route and is recognized by a square cut arete leading to a small tree. Start by large tree at base, stepping left onto arete and a bolt. A small cam is available in a slot above this, then a small runout takes you to the next bolt. The crux is thin moves above the bolt to the tree, sling and a good .75 under the roof. Move right and pull the roof, good medium cam, then to double bolt anchor. This route was climbed ground up free, so the bolting was done where I could get a good foot hold, Not a sport climb sorry!

name: The green iguana
description: The scrappy right facing corner to the right of KOTSW. It is the back of the tower the previous route climbs. With a dedicated cleaning crew, half gallon of gas and a fire hose, this would be pretty classic 5.8 crack climbing. Climb the corner with a crux about half height, it becomes wider at top. Either climb over rim and a tree belay or stem onto summit of tower and use KOTSW anchors.

name: Coral Sea
description: a very long single pitch.

name: Barely Legal
description: Enjoyable climbing leads to a seriously thin crux. Balance and friction will get you through the top (maybe).

name: Dr. No.
description: Short and difficult. Thinner and steeper than Oddjob, this one's a challenge.

name: High Society
description: Start on unprotectable chossy slab to access the flake. Take caution as a fall here will grate you into skin-ribbons.  After the slab, place gear and pray to your gods that the flake won't flex outward (as it did mine), rendering your puny placements ineffective. This one will test your convictions.  Descent: Walk off or rap from the chains on Barely Legal, drive home to shed tears upon your pillow.

name: Oddjob
description: Short little climb with fun movement. Easy start, easy finish with engaging middle.

name: Thunderball
description: Start with some thinner moves up to a flat jug rail. Then bust out the hard bouldery section to the anchors. Really fun moves!

name: It Ain't a Perfect World
description: Fun and easy low-angle slab.

name: Same at it Never Was
description: A notch above Wish List in difficulty, similar slab climbing on positive rock. This one ascends left of the cave/pod.   More run-out than Wish List, a bit heady if 5.8 is your limit.

name: Wish List
description: Fun route at the grade. Sustained 5.7 climbing on easy slab. Ample space between bolts, so be comfortable with 5.7 climbing.

name: Canvas of the Sheepeaters
description: Sometime in the last three or four years, somebody decided it would be a good idea to bolt a route in perhaps the most conspicuous location in the canyon. Despite the dubious development, this short route features some interesting movement on mostly side pulls. Follow the vertical series of two-finger pockets. No definitive crux, but sustained at the grade.  Having found no one to illuminate either the developer, the FA, or the route name, I'm calling the route Canvas of the Sheepeaters since the routes on this wall are closely adjacent to a panel of pictographs. If someone knows the actual name, please let me know.  Please offer grade suggestions. I’m saying 10c based on the one time I’ve been on it, but I don’t really know.

name: Lemhi Winds
description: Good clean fun. I wish there was a second and a third pitch

name: The Thread
description: Very delicate slab climbing. Named for a threaded sling at about 1/2 height.

name: Rite of Passage
description: "Super quality Rock".  A good mix of technical and powerful, this route is spicy fun!  Also, this route stays cooler with the shade and sometimes the strong wind blowing through the natural air plenum that it lies.

name: Nappy Dread
description: P1- 5.7 start just left of a big boulder with a giant anthill at the bottom. the bolt line trends right through easy terrain, then steepens to an awkward lip encounter right before the belay.     P2- 5.9 Go straight up for two bolts, then move right. short pitch, maybe 5 bolts.     P3- 5.10b Get up on the ledge and take 3 steps left. getting to the first bolt is pretty thin. bolt line trends left.

name: Spirit World
description: P1- 5.9, 195'   I'm told this is one of the best 9's around, especially because of its length.    P2- 5.11a, 160'

name: Hollowed Ground
description: The crux of the route is at the beginning getting up to the first bolt. it starts to ease up after the second bolt and then merges with Pocket Full of Corprolite at the sixth bolt. Rock quality up to the first bolt isn't that great so be careful.

name: Pocket Full of Corprolite
description: Fun climb with great position. For a single-pitch rock climb, this one allows you to feel nicely exposed. You've already hiked a couple hundred feet from the canyon floor, so halfway up this route, you're soaring. A great opportunity for a moderate climber to get high in the sky.   No real crux, just fun, steep and sustained face climbing on the right side of the arete.    Just for fun, an anecdote: My first time climbing this route, I was belaying my climbing partner, and the golden eagle that used to inhabit the canyon (I haven't seen it in nearly two years, sadly), came swooping around the arete, just above my partner's head. Impressive and intimidating!

name: Curious George
description: Very thin start, easing after 3 bolts.

name: The Grinch
description: Good longer route. Cryptic start, easy middle, steep finish.

name: Ms. Rumphius
description: Fun slab, tricky start.

name: Texas Barbecue
description: "Super-sharp rock.  No greasy slopers".

name: Weaner Dogs Ripped my Flesh
description: "Only slightly painful".  This climb serves as a good warmup assuming your fingers are in good shape because it's sharp!  Cool pockets and some fun moves on this one.  The hardest moves are the first few right off the ground.

name: Die Another Day
description: Pitch 1. Start to the left of the afore mentioned corner system, on a ledge at the base of a crack system that splits the slab. There is a single bolt from my anchor for the rope solo FA. It was cleaned and bolted on aid prior to the first free ascent. Climb the crack till it peters out, make a move left past bolts to a bulge, more bolts and pins past easier blocky rock to a DBB up and left. 5.10a Pitch 2. Move directly right across a slabby face to the obvious left facing flake corner. Beautiful crack climbing up this to a mantle move onto the ledge above and DBB. Classic but short.

name: Dam nation
description: An excellent outing up the right/ upstream arête of the crag. Start at toe of arête, or in the tight corner to its right. Good gear in the small range gets you up to a bolt, then a hard move up and right to a good hold. There is good gear in the crack, another hard move leads to one more bolt and the anchors on the ledge above. Rap the route.

name: Eddy out
description: Not actually on the dam wall at all, but there is only one route at this crag. If you have rafted to the dam buttress and want to do one more route, follow the river down another six miles or so, past the dam, piece of cake and the narrows rapids. This climb is on a buttress in the middle of the narrows rapid on the river right. Eddy out just above the confluence of the warm springs creek , the climb is on the right side of crag, the obvious twin crack with as slight  bulge, it faces upstream. Climb the crack, gear anchor on top, scramble off the back and down a gully on the upstream end. There is a very hard arête on the left side which I cleaned and tried to,top rope but found it too hard so it might make a good project for someone.

name: The fish ladder
description: Look for this isolated pillar between the dam buttress and upper Dam buttress. The route climbs the slabby face with thin seams and a hand crack. A little dirty. Start left of center, move up thin seams, small cams and a fixed pin, then into hand crack which ends at roof. Run it out above roof on good side pulls to top of pillar and tree belay.

name: Hydro electric
description: This route is in the center of the face, facing the river. Look for an obvious roofline about 25 feet off the deck. Hydro electric turns this roof at its left/ downstream end. Climb the thin seam that leads directly to left end of roof. A couple of pieces of gear small to medium gets you up to a bolt and some Hard moves, a second bolt protects a hard move around the roof. Clip another bolt and follow the same seam up a steep face and another bolt. At the top of seam the crack gets wide enough to place a cam in the .4-.5 range. One more bolt protects some slab moves to,the two bolt anchor. Great climb!

name: Kung fu fighting( everybody was )
description: This is the right trending diagonal next to Kung fu orgy. Hard jamming across diagonal with very little for the feet, then pull up and mantle around flake on top. Easy slab to two bolt belay.

name: Kung fu orgy
description: This climb is actually on another feature about ten minutes up the hill from the dam buttress. For now it is the only climb but there is definitely potential for more climbs here. Head up the hill and to the left until you reach a small buttress with two obvious cracks. Kung fu orgy is the right hand crack. Move up onto a left trending ramp that steepens into a short right facing corner. Follow the crack to the top, being mindful of the exit and the not so great tree you belay off. There will be a bolted anchor here soon!  Until then, scramble off to the right and down a gully to base of route.

name: What the salmon said when it hit the wall
description: The first route climbed here, used as access to top of crag. From the upstream end of crag, scramble up gully which leads to back of crag. About half way up, look for an attractive, though short hand crack on the left. Start from a ledge , moving up and left to base of crack(crux) then up good jams to a gear anchor on top.

The namesake route for the wall, this is a bolted crack that trends right before heading straight up at the top.  It's possible to escape right into the chossy flakes down low but staying the line is just as easy.  Exit the crack up high to a cool undercling and a pod.

name: Escape From Choss Angeles
description: On the left side of the wall, this has one hard move to gain the pod and a rest, then continue up brown, sharp, and chossy stone to join the seam at the top.  Worth doing if you've done the other 11s in the area.

name: Wascally Wabbit
description: Wandering up the center of the wall this route might get the award for sharpest route at the Fins.  Start with a surprisingly hard move off the flake to 3 bolts of easy and sharp climbing angling right.  The business starts as you make your way into the sloper and a very sharp pocket pinch.  One long move gains the last obvious hold until you reach the anchors.  Overall great climbing but docked a star due to the amount of cleaning I had to do up top, the sharpness down low and an anchor setup that isn't ideal.

name: Atomic Potato
description: A fun little route that keeps you thinking the whole way.

name: Bees? BEES!!!
description: Fun little route on the Jet A wall. Great warm up! Description from the FA " there are NO BEES on this route. a truck spill set loose 20 million bees, whom proceeded to harass the fins indiscriminately for many days luckily, there was enough reprieve to bolt this route"    Thanks for all the routes Tom!

name: Bunny Massacre
description: Start left of G.I Joe Bouncy Tanks. Head up easy ground to the right facing flake.  above the flake is the first crux, thin & sharp! after is more challenging climbing with an OK rest just before the final mind boggling crux.  Good Luck!

name: Curse of Mumm-Ra
description: fun in-obvious climbing. Sustained climbing with a slab crux near the top.

name: G.I. Joe Bouncy Tank
description: Don't be deceived by the start; the challenge is at the top. The flake leads to pockets.

name: Jet A
description: Straight as an arrow, climb between two dark streaks right up this plum line.

name: Mr. Long Arm
description: A sharp route that climbs very well.  Starts with easier climbing then builds to more difficult moves as you trend right a bit, centering around one hard pull off crimp to a good pocket, compose yourself then head left to a sidepull then one more sharp crimp to a 'thankgod' rounded comfortable pocket.  Easier climbing to the top.

name: Outnumbered But Not Outgunned
description: Climb up into the crack and under the steep blocky section.  Make a couple big moves through a sharp pocket and good hold to the forth bolt.  Now here is where the men/women are separated from the cheaters.  Go straight past the fifth bolt.  You could cut right and escape the difficulties, but know you will be a cheater!  Follow a left leaning ramp to the 6th bolt and into the real crux.  Fire straight up to another seam through some big moves and bad feet.  Finish in the crack to the right of the chains

name: Rise of Cobra
description: Short fun little route with the business up top. Cool movement on a vertical face to a rad sequence to gain the anchor.

name: Viva Mantequilla
description: Power endurance! Short but oh so sweet.  Just to the left of Water, start by traversing on a finger rail right then back left and up a thin seam. Move right just below the anchors

name: Water from Stone
description: Another fun climb. Head straight up the seam.

name: Algorithm
description: Idaho's hardest sport route. From first ascensionist Jonathan Siegrist's description (with permission): "The climb begins with a pumpy and cool 13a called 'Son of Discovery', before breaking dramatically right as the grips gradually decline to a sequential, powerful and very low percentage mid-height crux. One specific move in this crux thwarted me repeatedly. Pure difficulty was certainly an issue, but mainly it is characterized by an off balance, super accurate and long move. At best I was doing this move 1 of every 3 or 4 times from the hang. Linking it from the ground was going to be a heinous task. A few hard exit moves take you into easier terrain and the main rest. Above the rest, an ultra thin, beautiful headwall, 60 feet or more in length remains. The meat of this section is 2 well spaced bolts long, and requires finger strength, creative thinking and a surprising amount of power. The final bolt is crimpy 12+/13- terrain to the top... pulling up over 40 meters of rope to clip."  Needless to say, I have not climbed this route! (Nor has anyone else . . . yet.)  EDIT: Paige Claassen claims the brilliant second ascent September 2018.

name: Beafeater
description: Tech your way through small holds for a few bolts, then wander through a sea of chalk-less rock above.    This is the way it's spelled in the topo posted by Jonathan.

name: Bubble Boy
description: Standard bubble climbing.  A nice addition to the warm-ups.

name: Chapstick
description: Begin on a vertical section of pockets and crimps. Jog to the right and pull onto the upper slab enjoying chert holds near the anchors.

name: Decon
description: Bouldery, and a little sharp.

name: Dinner Roll
description: Start on the far left of the choss band.  Make some hard/bouldery moves on sharp holds off the ledge and past the first 3 bolts.  Continue up on amazing pockets.  This route was originally equipped to go right at the second to last bolt and end on Shaken's anchors.  It now has its own anchor straight up.

name: EBR-1
description: Balancy crux at the start leads to excellent pockets. Pumpy finish.

name: Fallout
description: This route has two bouldery cruxes, one at the halfway point, and another near the top.

name: Hazmat
description: A tricky little route with mostly positive holds, a nice addition to the wall. Get on it, quite fun movement.

name: Lemon Drop
description: First bolt is a little high due to rock quality, but can be stick clipped from the ledge. Climb Yellowman-esque pockets to a ledge at 3/4 height. Continue through a blank section to the (shared) Martini anchor.

name: Make it a Double
description: A formidable extension to 'Shaken not Stirred' with exceptional rock and a cool position. A short boulder problem meets you just after the chains of Shaken, and another one - the redpoint crux of the route, guards the anchor. Several options exist for the final boulder. Do not expect a clip up, this thing is a weee bit airy!

name: Manhattan Project
description: An incredible new route that climbs interesting and diverse features to an anchor at just under 100 feet. Begin as you would for Martini - just before the crux of Martini break off to the right and do several big moves between good holds to reach a rest on the far right side of the Martini finishing flake. From here fire through some near perfect stone and very memorable movement -- big spans through edges and pockets, ending with a cross-over pocket move and an accurate standup to a left hand side pull (crux). Journey through the relatively easy run out to the chains but save some juice for clipping! Low in the grade.

name: Martini
description: Climb up and end at the flake for which this sector is named.   A beautiful route with fun movement.

name: Pure Rock Fury
description: Climbing in a tan streak leads to a horizontal break around bolt 4. A large flake feature is on the second half of the route.

name: Rumchata
description: Climb the extension to Yellow Man past the Martini flake and up excellent rock following the distinct brown streak. I have removed any useful description of the climbing so as not to offend overly sensitive MP users. Think of this route as an easier, less runout sibling to Make it a Double.  Please post a comment if you know the FA info.

name: Shaken Not Stirred
description: Stellar pockets and crimps, low crux to endurance finish.

name: Son of Discovery
description: Stellar movement on awesome holds. This thing is mega good. Get on it!

name: Vesper
description: Bold, difficult, technical and involved. This is a stunning route to the top of the breathtaking Discovery Wall. Expect small grips, thrilling run-outs and unique movement. It will leave a lasting impression on you, I promise.     Start the same as Martini, when you reach the chains traverse right and establish on the ledge. Don't clip the anchor of Martini. From here fire into the sustained difficulty to the very top, there's one decent rest but otherwise it's on til the bitter end.

name: Yellow Man
description: Fantastic route for the 5.11 climber. Despite the space between the bolts, this route is very safe. Do it!   An area classic on beautiful pockets. Crux is at 2/3rds height on thin but positive edges.

name: Bare Knuckle Boxer
description: A wicked extension to Marc's classic, 'Bushido' 13b. After a good rest carry on through rad pocket pulling to the right side of the huge hueco at the top of the wall. Relatively straight forward climbing, adding a nice pump to the top of Bushido.     Probably mid 5.12 in itself -- hard to say that after a good rest it really adds any substantial difficulty, but it certainly adds quality.

name: Bushido
description: This is hands down one of the best routes here.  Big moves, good rests! it has it all, techy, dynamic, lock-offs, good/bad feet.  It fully embodies the Fins.  get on it!

name: Gulag Dance Party
description: Short, sequential and thin with cool movement. Riddled with small holds. Choose your own adventure. May need occasional cleaning due to its location in a water streak.

name: Hapachulo
description: Starts just to the right of Mothership.  make some big moves with bad feet, find a good rest and do more of that.  Real Hapachulos clip the chains AFTER the finishing mono move! 12+ if clipped from the mono

name: La Cabanita Especial
description: An extension to 'Hapachulo' (13a). After the burly mono crux of Hapachulo follow the rail left with no feet up and left to an okay rest. From here fire into sustained pocket pulling with still poor feet up and straight into a burly move--  rock over, stand-up to a good right hand 2 finger. The crux move is accurate and super long. Sustained 5.12 climbing leads to the chains. Reachy throughout. A rad little route.     Docked a star because of it's close proximity to Mothership...

name: Mission Control
description: A classic line (probably more logical than Bare Knuckle Boxer as the rope line is straighter and the extension is easier than either Bushido or Mothership). Solid for 12d... Maybe 13a if you're shorter or have large fingers?  Climb Mothership. Once you clip the crux bolt, reach down and unclip the previous draw to reduce rope drag. Continue... past the anchor... and past four more bolts to the giant Mothership pod.

name: Mothership
description: Awesome pocket pulling to a distinct crux (pinky mono). Pull though this and hang on through some small holds to a good rest, fun moves to a shared anchor with Bushido. Stellar route!

name: Skeletor
description: To the left of Bushido. Short but bouldery.

name: Yellowbrick Road
description: Start just to the left of Skeletor. Climbing slowly get more difficult the higher you get.  Beth little in the way of rests are offered.  Bolting is a little exciting near the top, but just relax and enjoy the ride.      This route has a reputation for holds breaking, travel lightly and be careful.

name: Al's Diner
description: Easier climbing on bigger holds lead to a marginal rest, then the crux at mid height where you can get settled on the 'shocker monos' (index and pinky) or a double set of marginal crimps. Either way you have to make a BIG move to a nice pocket to clip (big for me at 5'8", -2). Find your way through a multitude of interesting holds and either escape right of the bolt line in easier, but harder to read grey rock, or use the nice pockets up the face for a little harder finish.

name: And The Thunder Rolls
description: head straight up easier climbing with some interesting moves and amazing crimps to a hard crux with bad feet.  After you stick the crux moves, crimp your way to the top.

name: Bad Ass Weed
description: (aka Line of Weakness)  11a (Stems and Seeds) to the first set of anchors, 12a to the top. 11a part is quite sharp but good movement, the top climbs well with a very distinct crux.

name: Baked Potato
description: A terrific direct finish to Yukon Gold.  Clip the first six bolts of Yukon Gold to the giant pod hueco.  Instead of heading up the right side of the pod to the shared anchor, continue up the left side of the pod past four more bolts of amazing climbing.  The crux of the route is still at the fifth bolt, but the new finish is much more satisfying than the Yukon Gold finish.

name: Bean Fiddler
description: Despite the whimsical name, this route is a challenge!   Tree stump marks the start of this climb.

name: Bolt to Bolt Sailsman (aka: Virgins of Howe)
description: A somewhat cryptic off balance route.  A few big reaches and a technical sections will see you to the chains

name: Bong's Away (aka: Clips from the Bong)
description: Tall! This route goes to the top. Climb the pockets and finish on thin slab.

name: Don't Stop Retrievin'
description: The headwall has a 5.10!  Begin by clipping the first four bolts on 'S Curve' but instead of traversing way out right, continue straight up the easy slab on perfect rock.

name: Drunk As A Skunk
description: Longer and slightly stiffer than Hydroponics (aka Standard/Warm up #2), this is a fun, slightly thin slab.

name: Ghost in the Shell
description: Classic Fins pockets.

name: Hydroponics
description: A worthy warm up which is not quite as sharp as those to the right.  Fun movement and tight bolting where you clip the last bolt just 8" from the anchors.  As you struggle to clip the anchors you'll realize two things: 1) why the last clip was so close and 2) there is a big jug up and right of the anchors.

name: Koona
description: A shorter route on the headwall, long moves on good holds with a tricky crux on smaller feet.

name: Koona Kahuna
description: A 3 bolt extension to the rad Koona, move left after the anchor of Koona on good holds to a delicate finish. Good stuff. Just adds more climbing to a good route, doesn't increase the grade.

name: Little Black Spot
description: Starts out mellow to a bit of an awkward move out right, then though some smaller hard to find holds to a good slab. Good Route. Don't let people hate on this route it is not as bad as people say. Fun holds and movement.

name: Middle Man
description: Positive pockets most of the way, to a crux just below the last clip. Make sure to find the two finger jugs!

name: Munchies
description: Extension to Middle Man.  Climb Clips to Middle Man, clip one of the chains and take off into a 3 bolt bouldery crux.  Big moves with thin holds make for a very fun and engaging crux high on the route.  One of the best and more challenging routes on the wall

name: Prompt Critical
description: Fun little route with a couple reachy cruxes.

name: S Curve
description: Starts on the leftmost part of the Headwall down the hill a bit from Ghost in the Shell. It climbs up and right to a ledge on somewhat sharp rock. At the ledge it goes up and continues right towards the crack on incredible pockets. It then trends left and up to chains.

name: Seven Arrows
description: Another good route.

name: Stems and Seeds
description: AKA (Line of Weakness) Quite sharp but good movement. Short route, but a good warm up for the head wall if the others are taken. The extension is Bad Ass Weed 5.12a.

name: Time Will Tell
description: Great line of pocket pulling that shares the finish with The Bean Fiddler. A very worthy route that is on par with The Bean Fiddler with a easier crux.

name: Two Hitter Quitter
description: A more unique line at the headwall, this thing is sustained for the majority of the lower section and lets up a bit towards the top. Great line that climbs various features. Rad!

name: When Vegans Attack
description: One of the better warm-ups on the head wall. 11b to the first set of anchors. 11c if you continue though the slab to the upper anchors. Long moves on good holds.

name: White Rhino
description: More fun 12a pocket climbing. Follow a white water streak straight up and to the right of the large pod on Yukon Gold.

name: Yukon Gold
description: Start directly below a large pod about 50 ft up.  Climb up fun pockets with a couple big moves to a good rest.  Make a very difficult crux move (can be done several ways).  Once at the large pod move slightly right and meet up with White Rhino.

name: Cicada
description: Excellent route at the grade. Start on fun, dead- vertical face, ending on huge chicken-heads.

name: The Ginsu Variation
description: Stares first three bolts with Unknown 5.7, then trends right to end on same anchors as Cicada.

name: The Ginsu
description: Fun, mellow slab climb. Finish on cool chert knobs.

name: The Boys are Back in Town
description: Climbing is thin, protection is excellent

name: Grateful Deadpoint
description: Moves are very sequential and fluid, enjoy.

name: Momma Told Me Not to Come
description: Work up a slab to a bulge just left of a deep, dark gash.  Pull over the bulge and face climb up steepening terrain to finger crack.  A hard move gains the finger crack.  A few tip jams with bad feet lead to the anchors.

name: Reeling in the Years
description: Climb up pulling a mantle/lie-back - upward on interesting holds - buckets of water and chert finishing on the right side of the south ramp.

name: Sharp Dressed Man
description: Start at a bulge just off the ground and make a move up a left onto a steep slab.  Pass a short overlap and stay right of the deep, dark gash.  Continue up on steep climbing with small holds to a couple hand jams under a small bulge.  Move left around and over the bulge to easier terrain with a pair of cracks.  Follow the cracks to a flat shoulder and clip the anchors.

name: Swangin'
description: Climb up the ramp/rib on the south side of Gateway Rock. Well protected and fun at 5.5.

name: Whip
description: Moves may be difficult - pro is more than adequate.

name: Beggar's Banquet
description: Climb up a left facing dihedral.  Step right below the overhang and join the last few 4 bolts of Start Me Up.

name: Brown Sugar
description: Climb up until you can gain a  left facing corner of a pointy flake.  From the tippy top of the flake, stem left across the gap and pull onto a very thin face.  Technical climbing on good holds and rock past a few bolts leads to flake and a stance.  Climb up to a horizontal crack and blast over a small roof to a *not obvious* clipping hold left of the anchors.

name: Monkey Man
description: Begin on fun chert that gets thinner as you approach a huge 25 foot flake.  Stem/jam the right facing corner of the flake to small stance.  Climb a steep face up and left on small but decent holds. until you grab the edge of rail leading to the top.  Pull over the rail to easier ground and move up and right to the anchors.

name: Satisfaction
description: Face climb up to an obvious orange streak. Pass left over the streak and continue up to a steep bulge.  Crank through the bulge and continue to the anchors.

name: Start Me Up
description: Climb a thin, techy gray slab up and leftward until you can step left to a small stance below a 16" roof.  Pull the roof to a steep finish before you pull onto a small ledge and the anchors.

name: Sympathy for the Devil
description: Climb up to an obvious arete and follow until you can join the final few bolts of Brown Sugar.  Start on a steep, slightly mossy ramp until you can cross the arete to a small stance.  Move up to a burly undercling and pull thin cranky moves and work the arete untill to can gain the flake on Brown Sugar.   Continue on the last few bolts of Brown Sugar.

name: Bad Company
description: Work up a featured slab left of a bush to gain right leaning seams. Work a couple jams, liebacks and gastons up a thin face. Continue up the headwall until the pockets run out at the anchors.

name: Free Falling
description: Start in the approach gully and work up yellow rock past a couple bolts to a patch of pockets.  Pull over the pockets to some pinches on a horizontal rail and move right to the arete.  Follow the arete and easier climbing to the anchors.

name: Gimme Shelter
description: Work up a featured slab to a narrow pillar between two bushes. Continue up on well spaced pockets and  features to the final headwall.  Thin technical moves gain the anchors.

name: Johnny B. Goode
description: Climbs the north rib of the Classic Rock Fin.  Mountaineering flavor with sections of good rock punctuate by vegetation and fractured rock.  Steeper with big holds towards the finish.

name: Maneater
description: Start right of deep groove that goes more than half way up the crag.  Follow fun and featured rock staying just to the right of the deep groove.  A final thin slab move leads to the anchors above a ledge below the headwall.

name: Revolution
description: Start on left (uphill) side of a nice platform behind a large, burnt dead tree. Work up fun and very featured rock to the final headwall.  Delicate liebacking leads to the anchors.

name: Rock Me
description: Work up a zig-zag groove to a very thin section.  May be harder if you don't use the bush. Continue up to a stance and move up a thin crack to left side of a large overlap.  Big moves lead to the anchors.

name: Sticky Fingers
description: From the right side of the platform behind first large, burnt dead tree work up feature rock staying left of a long deep groove.  Work up excellent with thought provoking climbing to a steep headwall.  Follow good holds to the anchors just above a crescent shaped overlap.

name: Sweet Emotion
description: Starting just uphill from a large burnt dead tree, work up featured rock staying right of a deep groove. Climb steeper rock on pockets and pinches.  At the final headwall follow well spaced but good holds to the anchor.

name: Touch of Grey
description: Furthest left route on the wall.  Climb up a featured deep cleft.  Ends on a ledge below an obvious bulge.

name: Wall Flowers
description: Climb beautifully featured rock where the wall transition from yellow to grey.  Climb up to ledge with the Maneater anchors and continue for another 15 feet up a shallow groove to the anchors.

name: Yer Birthday
description: Ten feet right of Touch of Grey.  Start in deep groove with a dead snag.  Work up and slightly right on thin face climbing.  At about 2/3 height move left onto an hour glass feature and make tricky moves up steeper, spaced out pockets to the anchors.

name: Bang and Blame
description: Start with some sharp pocket pulling on tan rock and pull through to a stance.  Work up grey limestone until it possible to move up and slightly right into yellow/tan rock to a stance below a small overlap.  This is where the fun begins.  Move  up and left then right and then left connecting discontinuous shallow cracks and jams with with big face moves.

name: Dookie
description: Fun climbing on grey limestone yeilds to some chert pulling near the top.

name: Give It Away
description: Start in steep featured rock with big pockets.  Pull through the steep section and onto a brief grey rock slab.  Move up to a yellow/tan corner until you can face climb out left to a hidden flake.  Lie back or a move or two and launch right across a thin face to the anchors.

name: Nevermind
description: Climb straight up featured grey limestone until gaining a pair of left slanting cracks.  Follow the cracks to near the top and step up and right to a stance and the anchors.

name: Born to Be Wild
description: Fun route.  Formally the top rope route in the Bingham and TeNgaio guides.  Likely starts a little right of the original TR.  Climb solid grey limestone and the occasional chert knob to the anchors of the route Burning Spear.

name: Burning Spear
description: Work up to a thin move by the second bolt.  Get your feet high using low hand holds. From the stance, continue up on enjoyable chert, edges, and flakes.

name: Light My Fire
description: Start up vertical featured grey limestone. Lieback up to a stance and continue up and slightly right to a slab move.  Gain a chert line and follow the easy but fun climbing to the anchors.

name: Maybe I'm Amazed
description: Start uphill on the last staging platform.  Move up and left to chert blobs the size baby seals.  Step up on the large blobs of chert and clip the first bolt.  Continue up very large chert on fun climbing over amazing geology.

name: Another Brick in the Wall
description: This is one of 6 routes that is accessed from the broad ledge below a broad steep face called "The Wall". Use one of 4 approach pitch options (Don't Bring Me Down, I Turn to Stone, Stairway to Heaven, or Barracuda) to gain chain anchors on a comfortable ledge.   Another Brick in the Wall starts just left of the chain anchors and climb continuous, steep thin chert staying right of an obvious alcove about half way up the 100 foot wall. The chert is strong but brittle, especially when wet.  Be careful to place feet on holds and don't kick them. The holds are half pad crimps to full on jugs. This is another thin, technical climb that is continuously engaging. Just before the second to last bolt you can make a move left and grab a good rail to ease the tension.

name: Barracuda
description: This is the easiest way to gain the large ledge below The Wall.  Start right of Stairway to Heaven on featured rock.  Move up and then right to a shallow right facing corner.  Move left and make the same mantel and step across as Stairway to Heaven.  Follow easy climbing to the ledge below The Wall.  Shares last 3 bolts with Stairway to Heaven.

name: Cajun Hot Stick
description: Nice Climbing down low to an obvious crux. 10+ slab climbing for sure.

name: Comfortably Numb
description: Follow the left side of the prominent grey pillar to the right of "The Wall" and just right of the huge alcove.  This is one of 6 routes that is accessed from the broad ledge below a broad steep face called "The Wall". Use one of 4 approach pitch options (Don't Bring Me Down, I Turn to Stone, Stairway to Heaven, or Barracuda) to gain chain anchors on a comfortable ledge.   Use one of several approach pitch options to get to the comfortable ledge below "The Wall". Move the belay to the anchors on the far right side of the ledge. Move right to gain the face of the pillar. Work up the face sometimes working a hand or more on the left edge of the pillar. Continue up to a steep bulge with a short finger crack. Continue up on vertical chert to the anchors.

name: Don't Bring Me Down
description: Start below a couple shallow depressions in the wall.   Move straight up into the first depression and move up and slightly left to the second depression.  Make a tough move right then up to a gaston in a featured water groove.  Struggle for a couple moves through the water groove to gain a small ledge.  Continue up past another bolt to gain a large ledge and anchors below a large featured chert wall - "The Wall".      This is one of four options as an approach pitch to the climbs on The Wall.

name: Empty Spaces
description: This is one of 6 routes that is accessed from the broad ledge below a broad steep face called "The Wall". Use one of 4 approach pitch options (Don't Bring Me Down, I Turn to Stone, Stairway to Heaven, or Barracuda) to gain chain anchors on a comfortable ledge.   Empty Spaces has a couple ways to begin the climb.  From the anchors on the broad ledge below 'The Wall', move left and stem up an easy corner past a couple trees clipping a couple bolts along the way.  From the big dead spruce tree, pull onto the wall and follow good chert up to a small ledge about 1/2 way up, continue on amazing, easy huge chert to a final headwall.  Work up a couple of runnels with occasional baseball sized chert knobs to the anchors.  Alternatively, it's possible to move the belay from the chain anchors on the broad ledge below to 'The Wall' up the easy stemming corner past the trees to another set of chain anchors just past the dead spruce and lead the climb from there.

name: The Flaming (c)Lips
description: This is a fun, but very short climb on excellent featured rock.  Unfortunately the route ends when the featured rock ends.  Climb up a weakness with a discontinuous crack to a small ledge.  Continue on enjoyable rock for another 20 feet to stnace where the rock blanks out to a thin desperate slab.  Clip the sport anchors and lower.

name: Highway to Hell
description: Just right of a bush climb past a bolt to a narrow ledge.  Work up and right towards a large chert knob.  Once standing on the knob, make a couple moves laterally to the right and gain a stance below a large chert patch just out of reach.  Make  a thin cranky move (or two) to gain the chert. Campus up the chert on decent hand holds and terrible feet until you gain some stabilizing jugs.  Easy climbing past a couple more bolts leads to the anchors.

name: Jumping Jack Flash
description: This is the right most route on Psychedelic Rock.  Move quickly left through 2 bolts on marginal rock to gain the good rock on the obvious arete. Face climb up and left to a stance below a grey, very featured and sharp overhang.  Negotiate the overhang to a stance below a shallow right facing corner.  Make a few easier moves past a couple more bolts to the anchors.

name: Let it Burn
description: Long route that needs traffic to clean up. Fun! Cool pockets, flakes, and runnels.

name: Matchhead
description: Cool features on this climb with a cruxy middle section. Climb a short wall to a stance below a left trending left facing corner. Climb up and pull over the overlap (right over the shallow corner).  Continue up to the anchors just below a ledge.

name: Money
description: Climb up featured, sculpted limestone with distinctive right diagonalling fissures. Work straight up across the fissures to a thin move.  Continue on slightly easier climbing to the anchors.

name: Run Like Hell
description: This is one of 6 routes that is accessed from the broad ledge below a broad steep face called "The Wall". Use one of 4 approach pitch options (Don't Bring Me Down, I Turn to Stone, Stairway to Heaven, or Barracuda) to gain chain anchors on a comfortable ledge.   Run Like Hell starts 15 feet left of the chain anchors and climbs continuous, steep thin chert for 100 feet.  Work up on thin chert until you are close to the right edge of a huge alcove in the rock. Work your right hand and foot on the edge for a couple bolts until pulling fully back onto the chert face. Continuous climbing on chert continues to the anchor.

name: Stairway to Heaven
description: Move up solid grey limestone on good holds.  When the good holds run out move up one more bolt on thin crimps and thin feet until you can get a right hand out around the edge of a shallow right facing corner.  Continue up the face working the left hand up the face and the right hand on the edge.  Make a mantle onto narrow ledge and do an awkward step left on slopper footholds and no hands.  Continue on easy ground to gain the large ledge below the headwall - The Wall.    This is one of 4 approach options for getting to the climbs on The Wall.

name: Thriller
description: On the rightmost face of Psychedelic Rock, there is an attractive grey face next to an orange streak.      Face climb on chert until you get a mono. Begin moving up on increasingly larger pockets into yellow/brown rock and large overhang.  Pull the overhang on mostly big holds and move into large alcove.  The the top of the alcove traverse left a few feet over a shallow right facing corner.  Continue up to a stance and work a vertical edge for a few more moves to the anchors.

name: Time
description: This is one of 6 routes that is accessed from the broad ledge below a broad steep face called "The Wall". Use one of 4 approach pitch options (Don't Bring Me Down, I Turn to Stone, Stairway to Heaven, or Barracuda) to gain chain anchors on a comfortable ledge.   Time starts 10 feet to right of the chain anchors on the comfortable ledge.  Move up the left side of a small alcove just off the ledge.  Continue on thin chert and aim for the larger alcove up and left.  Climb to the apex of the alcove and pull onto the chert face above.  The climbing eases up on huge chert.  Continue to the anchors of Another Brick in the Wall.

name: Total Eclipse
description: The far right wall of Psychedelic Rock has a very prominent steep right facing corner with a crack. Start on a steep face and traverse left until you can establish a stem in the corner.  Follow the corner/crack until the crack ends (about 80 feet). Face climb between discontinuous cracks for another 40 feet to the anchors just below the crest of the fin.      Long and sustained climb.      First climbed on the afternoon of the 2017 Total Eclipse.

name: Turn to Stone
description: Steep climbing on solid grey limestone.  Make a series of interesting and challenging moves between grooves and pockets.  After 5 or 6 bolts, pull onto the narrow ledge shared with Stairway to Heaven.  Follow easy ground and a couple more bolts to the large grassy ledge below The Wall.    This is one of 4 approach options for getting to the climbs on The Wall.

name: Us and Them
description: This is one of 6 routes that is accessed from the broad ledge below a broad steep face called "The Wall". Use one of 4 approach pitch options (Don't Bring Me Down, I Turn to Stone, Stairway to Heaven, or Barracuda) to gain chain anchors on a comfortable ledge.   Us and Them starts just right of the chain anchors and climb straight up continuous, steep thin chert for 100 feet right up the middle of the face. The chert is strong but brittle, especially when wet. Be careful to place feet on holds and don't kick them. The holds are half pad crimps to full on jugs. Thin and thoughtful climbing starts immediately off the ledge and doesn't let up until you clip the anchors.

name: Evil Ways
description: Start on the staging platform up and left from the start of You're So Vain.  Move up and right between a couple plants on steep rock.  Gain a slab and step left to a crack in a very shallow right facing corner.  Move up increasingly steep rock using pockets on the left and crimps and liebacks on the right.  Make a thin committing move onto the bulge. Crimp and pinch and continue on mostly small but positive holds to a stance below the chains.

name: Go Your Own Way
description: About 8' right and uphill of "Shakin'", climb up and slightly left towards discontinuous cracks and a couple brown/orange blobs of protruding rock.  Gain the right hand edge of the "Shakin'" ledge and continue up and right on a ramp to thin crack to flake and a belay at the top of the flake.

name: Goodbye Yellow Brick Road
description: An excellent route that starts and stays right of a prominent body-sized alcove about 30 feet off the ground.      Pitch 1 (5.10):  Climb straight up to right side of the alcove and work up and slightly right up a couple right diagonalling seams until you can move up and left to a nice stance and a belay.    Pitch 2 (5.11-):  From the belay scramble up easy terrain past a couple bolts to a grassy ledge below a double overhang.  Make a couple big moves to gain the vertical headwall.  Pull up on tiny orange knobs and dance your way up to a comfortable ledge and the anchors.

name: Heart of Gold
description: On the right side of Rock of Ages are two routes that end on the same anchor. Heart of Gold is the right route. This a fun, moderate route but is still engaging and no give away. It is sustained for the grade and there are a number tricky moves.

name: It's So Easy
description: About 20 feet right and uphill of "You're So Vain", climb very featured rock past a couple bolts until you can pull left into a shallow left facing corner.  Continue up to a big comfy ledge and the belay anchors for "You're So Vain".  Rap or continue on the second pitch of "You're So Vain".

name: The Joker
description: On the right side of Rock of Ages are two routes that end on the same anchor.  The Joker is the left route and has a crux bulge about 20 feet off the deck.  The route remains high quality and fun climbing.  The final headwall is negotiated by pinching large to small chert knobs.

name: Octopus's Garden
description: Start on a bushy slab and work up to a right facing corner on mostly brown/orange rock.  Continue up the corner and pull a bulge on nice grey rock with pockets and pinches.  Step left to the anchors.  Shares the anchor with "Orange Crush".    This route is a little dirty down low but will clean up with ascents.  The crux bulge is clean and on excellent grey rock.

name: Orange Crush
description: Work up featured rock staying just to the left of an orange streak of lichen.  At the last bolt step right and continue to the anchors.  Shares the anchors with "Octopus's Garden".    This rock is a little dusty through the orange lichen but will clean up nicely in time.

name: Purple Haze
description: Just left of the center of the wall is a body sized alcove about 30 feet up the rock.      P1 (5.10):  "Purple Haze" climbs straight up to the left side of the alcove.  Step right into the alcove for a rest but then continue up and out of the alcove on excellent stone staying just right of a grey water streak.  Continue to the anchors at the top of the grey water streak.    P2 (5.10):  Move up over easy stone to the grassy ledge and pull onto a steep face with abundant chert knobs.  Continue up as the knobs get smaller and fewer and do thin moves to gain the ledge near the top of the fin.  Move right to the anchors of "Goodbye Yellow Brick Road".

name: Shakin'
description: Starting about 10' right and uphill from "It's So Easy", climb more less straight up towards some large brown/orange blobs protruding from the rock.  Make some fun moves past the blobs to gain a ledge. Step left and clip a bolt and continue up grey, featured rock to gain a crack left of a bush. Pull the bulge and continue up to the anchors on amazing orange knobs.  Shares the top anchor with "You're So Vain".    It's possible to step left at the ledge to the anchors of "You're So Vain" and make this a 2 pitch climb.

name: Slow Ride
description: This is a proud line more or less up the center of the face.      P1 (5.11-):  Start on the left edge of a staging platform and work up featured rock through a couple bulges and a blank section before a good stance. Then continue up slabby rock to the anchor.  Clip the anchors and take a step right onto a small but comfortable stance.  A belay bolt for the 2nd pitch backs up the anchors.      P2 (5.10+): Move right to broad grassy ledge and start the second pitch in right facing corner.  Stem up and pull onto the vertical face using an assortment of protruding knobs.  Fun knobby facing climbing leads to the top with a thin move to gain the anchors.

name: You're So Vain
description: Start at the lowest point of left rib of Rock of Ages.      P1 (5.8):  Start o a slabby ramp with chert knobs down low and continue on excellent featured limestone to a pleasant ledge and a belay.      P2 (5.7):  Follow amazing large chert knobs, trending up and right to a belay just below the top of the ridge.  Shares the top anchor with "Shakin'".

name: All Along the Watchtower
description: Start on the slab to the right of the alcove (and start of Hold the Line).  Thin starting moves lead to easy romp to the first set of chain anchors.      From the chain anchors, step across a shallow gully and pull over a bulge.  Follow very featured, steeper rock to the summit.  Once on the bulge the climbing significantly improves.    Can be led in a single pitch if you take precautions for rope drag.

name: Hold the Line
description: Start in an alcove and stem up until you can pull left onto a grey slab.  Move up to gain a line of chert that leads to the summit.  Long climb with fun climbing to gain a true 5th class spire.

name: Black Betty
description: This climb follows the gully system between between American Beauty and Sea of Joy.  The first pitch works up a series of short faces to ledges and stances (5.6).  The second pitch (5.7) continues on steeper rock and works up really interesting runnels and sculpted grey limestone with the occasional chert hold thrown in.  Worth doing for the second pitch.

name: Black Hole Sun
description: Start 30 feet left of "Truckin" and climb up a smooth grey face with big moves on good pockets.  Gain a ledge below a chert face.  Thiin moves off the ledge lead to slighlty bigger holds.  Continue up engaging chert climbing to the anchors.

name: Fire & Rain
description: Crux is at start of second pitch. Excellent climbing on good solid chert.

name: I Can See For Miles
description: Pitch 1:  Start with tough moves past the first two bolts and climb just left of a white streak on a orange face.  Aim for a a break in the trees to a ledge.  Continue up a short face to a second ledge and belay at chain anchors.  Pitch 2: Work up to and over a tough bulge 2 bolts off the ledge.  Continue on thin chert to a second smaller bulge just below the top anchors.

name: Stage Fright
description: P1:  Start between "Truckin'" and  "I Can See For Miles" and climb up pleasant, solid large chert to chain anchors at a small ledge.  P2:  Continue face climbing up to a second small ledge and continue on a steep chert face with right diagonalling crack.  Continue to the top anchors on thoughtful and technical face climbing.

name: Truckin'
description: Climb up the wall using large chert nodules.

name: Cross Faded
description: P1:  Start on the left side of the shady alcove between Sea of Joy and Dark Side of the Moon. Move up on easy terrain to a comfortable stance below a short steep headwall.  Make a couple thin moves up past two bolts and grab a deep runnel and pull up onto the big party ledge and chain anchors.  P2:  Stem up an easy corner until you can pull fully onto the face.  Climb 2 bolts of Under My Thumb then stay left on a separate bolt line through the big overlap.  Pull the overlap on thin hands and feet and continue up on improving holds and fun moves to sport anchors.  Note: this pitch crosses Under My Thumb and after the two shared bolts, takes the left bolt line while Under My Thumb finishes on the right bolt line.

name: Don't Fear the Reaper
description: Start in the deep gully between the Sea of Joy and Dark Side of the Moon formations.  Stem up a an overhanging corner until you can pull slightly left onto the face.  Climb up to a small stance below a final steep wall of dark grey streaks.  Unlock the puzzle and continue to the big party ledge.

name: Magic Carpet Ride
description: Another excellent 2 pitch climb on Sea of Joy.  The first pitch (5.9) starts on featured rock just left of Sea of Joy.  Continue up to a funky slab move.  Continue to the belay ledge with chain anchors.  Straight above the anchors, the second pitch (5.10-) follows another chert line to the left of Sea of Joy. Continuous and fun.

name: Sea of Joy
description: Sea of Joy is the right hand of two routes whose 2nd pitch climbs broad continuous face to the fin's high point.  First pitch (5.7) starts in a 'v' notch and climbs dark chert over a couple ledges to a set of anchors.  The second pitch (5.10-) climbs straight up on amazing chert embedded in impeccable limestone.  Continuous fun face climbing for 90 feet to the anchors.

name: Sledge Hammer
description: Two pitch climb with chain anchors 18 bolts total.

name: Space Cowboy
description: P1:  5.7.  Towards the left side of the Sea of Joy formation, start on an easy slab and work your way past a couple small ledges to a decent stance and a set of chain anchors.    P2:  5.9.  This is another fun chert pinching pitch on the left side of the major headwall of Sea of Joy.  Work straight up the outside face of a left facing corner.  As the corner arches left and forms a major roof, stay on the face and foot traverse on chert across a crack and just above the roof.  Continue straight up on excellent chert holds to the anchors just below some large bushes near the top of the face.

name: Under My Thumb
description: P1(5.10-): Work up a ramp to a steep chert face with engaging chert knobs.  Gain a small ledge and continue up another exciting steep chert face to chain anchors and a small stance.  P2(5.10):  Step across a left leaning right facing corner. Move up a couple bolts and head up right to a very obvious 2 foot overlap feature. Pull the overlap on chert holds and continue on thin holds to the right side of a flake and make a couple burly lieback movest to bigger holds.  Follow bigger holds to the next bolt.  After the lieback, it is slightly runout to the next bolt but the climbing eases up and is on big holds.  Climb some amazing chert holds to finish at the chain anchors just below the rim of the wall.  Note: P2 shares two bolts with Cross Faded and Cross Faded takes the left bolt line through the overlap and Under My Thumb takes the right bolt line.

name: Another One Bites the Dust
description: This route starts on large party ledge on the right side of Sea of Joy.  From the anchors on the ledge, move right and stem up the dihedral that is the boundary between Sea of Joy and Dark Side of the Moon.  Continue stemming up and over a bulge and pull onto the face with some chert holds.  Follow a left trending line of chert to the anchors.

name: Cherts So Good
description: Climb the first 4 bolts of Creep (5.9) and step left across the prominent black streak and continue up for another 10 bolts of steep chert pinching to the anchors.  Steep and fun with solid chert.

name: Crazy Diamond
description: Climb steep featured limestone runnels and chert to right leaning crack.  Mostly face climb plus a couple jams until you can stem up a shallow steep corner on exciting chert holds.  At the second to last bolt you can step left to the party ledge and the sport anchors of Don't Fear the Reaper on the Sea of Joy formation or stay on the steep ramp and move up and right past one more bolt to the chain anchors on the first pitch of Wish You Were Here.

name: Dream Weaver
description: Start in a broken right facing corner and move up to a stance below short blank section of rock.  Using tiny handholds and bad feet move slightly right and up to big hand hold. Pull up to a stance and continue more or less straight up on big chert.  Continue up as the route becomes steeper, the chert smaller and holds more spaced apart.  Pull a second thin crux for the last couple bolts before the anchors.

name: Freebird
description: P1: 5.7.  Climb featured grey limestone up runnels and past small ledges to a large ledge with chain anchors which are left of a prominent large bush on the wall.    P2:  5.8.  Continue more or less straight up on featured limestone and chert.  About 1/2 way up there is a move left to gain crack.  Follow the crack back left and then up to the sport anchors at the top of the pitch.

name: Golden Years
description: P1 (5.9) Start 10 feet right of Freebird and climb a steep thin section, then trend left to a ledge just left of a large bush.  Belay at the first anchors of Freebird.  P2 (5.10-) Move up and right following a diagonalling chert line until its possible to make an exciting move left to the edge of a shallow left facing corner.  Make the move left as soon as possible to keep the grade 10- (if you wait the move becomes more like hard 5.10).  Move up from the corner onto large chert holds.  Continue more or less straight up on sometimes thin chert holds.  Pull a headwall and move left to the the top anchors of Freebird.  Note: can be led in one long pitch with 22 quickdraws and some rope management to reduce drag.

name: White Rabbit
description: This is a long single pitch route up the middle of the Dark Side of the Moon formation.  Start on featured rock and move up to stance below a blank face. The crux is moving up and left into left facing corner.  Follow the corner/arete until it becomes a chert face climb.  Continue on fun but easier climbing to the anchors.

name: Wish You Were Here
description: P1: 5.8. Scramble up to the grassy ledge in the deep gully between Sea of Joy and Dark Side of the Moon formations. On the right side of the grassy ledge start climbing very featured limestone that is splattered with a generous amount of chert. Fun climbing on big holds leads to chain anchors in a small scoop.  P2: 5.10. Continue up on big holds and eventually the climbing gets steeper and the holds smaller. There is a steep white headwall guarding the chain anchors at the top of pitch 2. Fun crux.

name: The Art of Letting Go
description: P1:  5.7 climb up and right to a left facing dihedral and stem up to a nice ledge and the mid-point chain anchors 75ft. P2:  5.9  start up  and left of the mid-point anchors (straight up and trending slightly right is "Hold On Loosely But Don't Let Go").  Climb the weaknesses to the top anchors - 90 ft. The second pitch is outstanding climbing for 5.9 - steep with holds and protection where you want them!

name: Creep
description: The left-most route on Stone Temple goes up just to the right of the prominent black streak that separates Dark Side of the Moon from Stone Temple.  It is approximately 100 feet of excellent climbing on solid limestone and chert.

name: Hold On Loosely But Don't Let Go
description: Climb directly above the 1st pitch anchors of "The Art of Letting Go".  Follow a right trending line on thin grey limestone and some chert holds to the top anchors of "The Art of Letting Go".

name: Papa Was a Rolling Stone
description: Excellent climbing up a face with chert features. The climbing is consistent at 5.10.

name: Perdida
description: Perdida 5.12-/5.11+ 2 pitches – 160 feet. First pitch (80 feet) 5.12-, 14 bolts to chain anchors at top of flake. Difficult moves off the ground lead to a series of cruxes requiring a wide variety of climbing techniques. Second pitch (80 feet) 5.11+ 14 bolts to chain anchors (fifty feet below actual summit). Ascend the white/grey face following the line of bolts up a right-trending line of chert, then follow a crack system (climbing left and right of the bolt line as needed) up the right shoulder of the Stone Temple.   This is an amazing line and you should find it challenging and interesting from top to bottom!

name: Riders On The Storm
description: Start on a narrow grassy ledge with a belay bolt.  Move up to a shallow overlap on grey rock.  Make thin undercling/side pull moves until gaining some good chert holds about a third the way up the climb.  Follow good but widely spaced chert holds up and right to a very thin section of grey rocks.  Continue up on micro runnels and shallow finger pockets to a slabby thin move to gain the anchors which are just below a ledge on the top of a broad pillar..

name: STP (Stone Temple Pilots)
description: First pitch - 5.10+  follow the line of bolts up the face to the gray face and anchors above. Climbing is very sequential and strenuous for the grade. Second pitch - 5.10 climb the crack above to chain anchors OR : 5.11 climb the face just left of the crack/crevice above the first pitch.

name: Tiny Dancer
description: At the base of the big wall of Stone Temple, currently the farthest left route on the lower face.
Climb up the chert filled face to sport anchors above.

name: Anyway You Want It
description: Climb the chert filled face above between Jaws and Dreamer.

name: Cherry Bomb
description: Climb up chert. Chert balls are unique and can be quite interesting. Have fun deciding which chert ball is better than the other.

name: Dreamer
description: Climb just left of small vertical crack up chert filled face.

name: Dreams Die Hard
description: Climb up the chert filled face just to right of small vertical crack.

name: Eye in the Sky
description: Climb up using the large chert balls/holds and limestone features. Sooo much fun!

name: Jaws
description: Climb up the chert ball filled face above

name: Nowhere Man
description: Climb up the chert ball face.

name: Stir It Up
description: Climb up  on the chert balls choosing only the best.

name: Won't Back Down
description: Climb up enjoying every chert bomb/cannonball handhold/foothold plus the featured limestone.

name: AC/DC
description: Starts on a grey face, underneath a large hueco. Climb the face, take a bomber no hands in the hueco, then fire the thin tips seam to the left of the hueco. This one turns on quick and doesn't let up til you're at the chains.

name: Be Here Now
description: Short but engaging route.  Climb in from the right to an obvious chert jug about 9 feet off the ground.  Continue on technical thin crimps and pinches working up and slightly to the left.  Route ends when the hard climbing ends.

name: Come As You Are
description: Start up hill from Stone Free.  First 20 feet is easy climbing on lichen covered holds.  From a comfortable stance move up through a small bulge and continue up a left trending, left facing open book and at the top make a move left to the anchors.

name: Come Together
description: Start in a very obvious shallow right facing dihedral.  Climb to the top of the dihedral and make thin move to gain a small ledge.  Continue up on easy but fun climbing to the anchors.

name: Emotional Rescue
description: Start on a weakness than leads to a right trending rail.  Work your hands then feet up the rail and onto the technical grey slab.  Continue more or less straight up to the anchors.

name: Hey You
description: Climb the left side of a grey slab.  Excellent quality rock.  Finish on a short steep chert headwall.

name: Just What I Needed
description: This is a thin and techy slab climb on very good grey limestone.  This route is slightly a squeeze job especially near the top but before the route is confounded with the climbs on either side you reach the anchors.

name: Penny Lane
description: Climb up the right side of the cleft between Stone Temple & Wonderwall avoiding potential rockfall from gully above.

name: Rubber Soul
description: Start on a broad face with a thin horizontal about 8 feet off the deck.  Work the edge and get stood up and gain a jug about another 6 feet up.  Continue up techinical grey limestone on small holds until you reach a very thin scoop.  Make a couple thin moves to an obvious jug.  Continue up easier rock to the anchors.

name: Stone Free
description: P1:  Start with a move over a prow close to ground and follow much easier terrain to a large ledge and chain anchors.  Pleasant easy climbing but nothing special.  P2:  This is an amazing pitch.  From the chain anchors on pitch 1 follow a steeo band of "C" shaped chert holds.  Good hand holds but poor feet.  Pumpy and super fun all the way to the anchors.  With a little rope management and long draws at the top of P1 it is possible to climb the route as one long 100' pitch (as was done on the FFA).

name: Take a Walk on the Wild Side
description: Thin, tricky section down low, lead to a fun chert knob romp to the anchors.

name: Ticket to Ride
description: Long and fun route.  Start on obvious featured holds just right of a blank orange face.  Make a couple moves to to get established and follow easy good stone to a ledge about half way up the wall. From the ledge, pull onto the face and climb up a right facing dihedral to a steep bulge with a crack on the right.  Stem up and over the bulge using the crack on the right and occassional holds on the left.  Very engaging from the ledge to the anchors.  Full length pitch.

name: Exodus
description: Follow a distinctive thin tips crack up and left to small overlap.  Move past overlap on hand jams and continue to a stance and sport anchors below a blocky secton near the top.

name: X-Crack
description: Tricky start and rightward traverse leads to better holds in the crack and finish.

name: X-Files
description: Start on a steep grey ramp and climb up to a right diagonalling crack.  Burly liebacking and face climbing lead to a slight bulge.  Continuous, hard and sharp in places.

name: Antithesis
description: This line is completely atypical for Fins climbing! A tricky compression boulder problem gains a flat jug up and right. Traverse leftward from here to technical laybacking and stemming up a leaning slabby seam. A few jams later, merge into the top of Morning Dwellers, sharing an anchor.

name: Clair de Lune
description: Boulder past the first bolt to a thin face of nice stone. A slab crux midway brings you to a rest below the bulge. A neat sequence through this bulge using an incut undercling flake and a big flyby move takes you to the anchor.

name: Dawn Yawns
description: Fun compression moves between the edge of the flake and vertical face holds. Beautiful stone!

name: Morning Dwellers
description: Fun horizontals with good holds leads to a mantel into a scoop. Stem right to a few jams. When this weakness ends, a few tricky slab moves finishes things out.

name: Open Project
description: Begin with a hand jam pod into a bulge past three close bolts with a few monos. Easier low angle terrain takes you to another bulge finale. Conduct another hard boulder to reach the anchor. The grade is a guess.

name: Shadow's Edge
description: Perhaps the most obvious line at the wall. Beautiful rock linking a few obvious features. Powerful laybacking with tiny feet leads to thin slabby climbing up to a stance. Boulder past with some compression moves and a mono. Enoy one last stance before a stemmy finish to the anchor. Very sustained for the length.

name: Blue Tape Route
description: Start with some easy moves along the flake heading left then into the broken arete.  It gets a little harder here but there's a nice jug at the last bolt.

name: Enter the Dragon
description: Enter The Dragon is a striking crack line on the left side of the Solstice Wall.   Start on the same rail feature as the "Blue Tape Route". Climb on crimps and pockets past four bolts to a ledge and rest. The rest of the route is gear protected.  Climb the obvious seam either straight in or via a compression sequence. Continuous climbing leads to a series of boulder problem separated by rests.  The fight doesn't end until you clip the chains. The gear on the route is tricky.

name: Huck You
description: Nice short route with big moves on good holds.

name: Mind Your Manners
description: An extension of Huck You. After the anchor there is essentially no resting until the hard climbing is over. Many long and demanding moves in a row, just keep coming. A pounce-dyno is the first cruxy section followed by worsening holds to a crap rest. From here a complex crux with a left hand side pull and a terribly small right hand chip takes you then leftward to reach the arete. A very engaging and run out crux (albeit much easier) guards the anchor. So good.

name: Solstice
description: A very unique route for the fins. Climbs on flake features and rad underclings. DO IT!

name: Wings for Marry
description: start up some chossy rock for a few bolts then move slightly right using a corner and face holds to the right.  Squeeze your way through the ok holds and bad feet.  A giant rest half way up give you plenty of time to recover for the fun pod climbing up high

name: Antidote
description: A massive pitch on the right side of the Yellowcake wall. After the first anchor fire through some fun lay backing to a good rest below an impeccable shield of one and two finger pockets. From the top of this section you will trend left through a series of underclings to an airy and incredible finishing boulder problem near the last bolt.     Great position, killer movement and bomber rock. A full 40 meter line.

name: Avatar
description: Standard Fin's pocket pullin' fun!! get on it

name: Fifty One
description: Cool climbing through a pocket crux followed up by a semi-slabby crux up high

name: No Country For Old Men
description: Extension off of Fifty One.  From the chains head straight up.  Big moves between good holds leads to a powerful crux up high.  Finish in the crows nest alcove.

name: Separation of Church and Skate
description: This is the first pitch/to the first anchor of Antidote.  Used to be easier but the chains were moved sometime in the past making it more challenging.

name: Yellow Cake
description: So many holds you wont be able to use them all.  Fun climbing up crimps and finger jugs.

name: El Sendero Gloominoso
description: This is a long pitch and is shaded by the large chimney corner. Clean, compact limestone. Toes and fingers were numb in March, but it should receive afternoon sun later in the year. Climb the face to the left of chimney, sustained moves with an occasional rest stemming to outside of chimney. There is a slightly run out crux moving right through a bulge about fifty feet up. Look for cam placements in some crystal pockets. At around 100 feet, the chimney jogs out to the left and the climb goes behind it. Polished rock and some squirming gets you through this till you are on top of a large ledge. Then climb the clean hand crack directly to the anchors.DBB. Two rope rappel. 150feet, 5.10a

name: Cliffside Camp Crack
description: I've never put a route into MP that I haven't climbed but I'm making an exception here.  The first time I was there we had a rope but didn't have any luck getting to the top to set a rope.  The next time I didn't have a rack so we just floated by.  Looks like a fun climb but unfortunately you have to start right out of the raft - there's no ledge at the bottom.  There were slings at the top when I first saw it but I didn't see any this time.  You'll probably have to leave a sling or two to get down.    The route is a nice handcrack (see the pictures) - there's room for plenty of other routes if you want to spend a day there.  It's not a very tall crag compared to the upper part of Impassible Canyon but looks like good rock.  Hopefully this will inspire someone to climb it and post a better description.  The rating comes from the Matt Leidecker book.

name: Local's Lieback
description: Steep dihedral on the south face of the Massive Boulder.  Laybacks and jams to the chain anchor a few feet back from the edge.  Looks like you can get to the anchor from the back side to set up a toprope.  I'm sure local climbers have a name and a grade for this worthy route.

name: Unnamed
description: Hand-jam up the central crack to the top. The crux is a large reach crimp near the top.

name: Be Line
description: SDS up slanting crack & rails to jugs top out.

name: Between Two Trees
description: High step up a slab to good topout holds.

name: Big Stinker
description: Sit start the southern arete using balancy crimps.

name: Bigger than hip-hop
description: Start in a low undercling/stem and make a big move to a well textured sloping ledge (crux) then continue straight up utilizing small holds to gain the top.

name: Family Affair
description: Sit start the SE arete, laybacking the obvious rail to a gain a jug at the lip.

name: Pocket full of crystals
description: On the west side of the boulder climb the deep pockets if for no other reason to check out the crystals inside.

name: Unkown
description: Lie backs and pinches could really use a brushing covered in black lichen.

name: What chu bonobo bout that
description: Located on the short north west side of the Boulder start matched on a low good rail make a few moves out right then thrutch to the higher rails toping out maybe 3-4 feet right of the start hand. Short and silly.

name: Where'd the tree go?!
description: Low left start to Between Two Trees. Start on the obvious undercling and pull up into it.  Adds a bit of difficulty before you get up onto the slab.

name: Diamond Back Crack
description: The crack is so named because during bridge reconstruction a saw cut into the rock face leaving elliptical indents resembling serpentine scales.  During the bridges 2017 reconstruction a diamond back nest under the crack was found to be troublesome for bridge workers, so the construction foreman used old people tongs to pinch rattlers and throw them into a cooler for relocation.

name: Egg shell
description: I wish the eggshell part went on for another 100 feet! Though small, this is a fun little climb that involves a little lie backing and jamming up a wide flake Resembling an eggshell peeling off of the mountain. Pitch 2: From the top of the eggshell pitch, build an anchor and traverse out right and up the crack system to the top of the formation. once at the top, walk to your left and find a small tree to rappel from.

name: Lifestyles of the Poor & Dangerous
description: Quite an excellent pitch. #3’s nearly all the way up until you hit an off width pod of sorts that takes a .5, .75, and or number 1 Camelot. This is a sweet, lichen-free splitter crack that ends on a nice clean ledge to belay from.  At the high ledge, slung around a large block is some very, very old and rotten webbing. There is only that one strand which makes me think that the the route has hardly been climbed. The first time I did this route I didn’t bother to scramble to the upper ledge and so without seeing the ancient webbing, thought I’d done the FA But Some enterprising, and unknown crack jammer spotted the line apparently long before me.

name: Lil’ River Dance
description: Climb under the roof or up the arete to reach the roof and jam to the top.

name: Moon Crazed
description: This is the best, most fun climb up the river road. It offers a short approach and great rock.  There are two bolted rap station at the top. The top 8 meters of the climb are runout scrambling over dirt and loose grass to the anchors. Use two ropes to rap. On this same formation are three other routes as well. One of them is a heinous run out slab climb, the other two are cracks. Above these climbs is a sweet splitter crack as well. It lies left of center on a triangular face.

name: Nubbin' But Fun
description: Start on the red tinted rock and move up to a tiny roof. Follow bolt line up the face of the rock to a great slanted crack going up the rock. One little reachy move towards the tree on the right in the middle of the climb. The there is some moves at the top that involve walking on the dirt and grass on the rock. Can be top roped if you hike up to the right of the formation and around.

name: Slab in the Sky
description: This is a mixed gear/sport route.  The slab has three routes on it but the biggest one is a spooky run out slab climb on dirty rock. Like most of the bolted climbs along the river road, certain bolts and anchors have been updated and are trustworthy.  Start at the base of the center of the slab and gradually climb up into steeper rock. You will notice this climb from the road because of how featured with knobs and chicken heads it is.

name: Bamm Bamm
description: Start with a right hand in the crack and left hand crimping the small diagonal crack (same as Twinkle Toes). Move up and right utilizing the crack to the right.

name: Barney Rubble
description: Get your feet on and make a couple easy slab moves.

name: Betty’s crack
description: Super fun chimney climb!

name: Dino’s dyno
description: Do it in your approach shoes with no pad necessary! Super short but surprisingly fun little dyno!

name: Flintstoned
description: Short, but super fun finger crack.

name: Fred’s forehead
description: Hug the forehead.

name: Pebbles
