description: <not pictured>   Climb up to a small roof below a steep corner, make some big moves to gain a stance.  Easier climbing up and right leads to the anchors.

name: Lip Service
description: Start on a grey face and move up and left to an awkward stance below a 4 foot roof. Make a burly move over the roof to a nice brown face and finish with a few thin moves.

name: Maker’s Mark
description: Boulder up to or stick clip the first bolt.  Continue up steep blocks to a knee bar under a roof.  Climb up and right the overhang to small edges. Pull your feet up and continue on a nice brown face to the anchors.

name: Ms. Smiley
description: Start with big moves through overhanging territory.  Gain a stance and work up to an amazing smile shaped hueco and jug hauling to the top. Fun climbing.

name: Ph – Bomb
description: Climb the face to the right of the big triangular shaped roof.  A hard move off the ground leads to a stance below a block.  After the block, climb a crack/corner and move left to the anchors.

name: She Fuckin’ Hates It
description: Climb up steep tan rock with edges and a pocket or two and pull onto a stance. Move right on a slab under a roof and make a blind reach around the corner. Pull though and cruise to the anchors.

name: Shed Your Skin
description: <not pictured>   Starts between two Junipers.  Difficult climbing down low on so-so rock leads to fun moves on much better rock for the upper half of the climb.

name: Thumper
description: Start up a few steep blocks to gain excellent stone.  Climb up the corner to a big  roof and hand traverse left until you can pull past the roof to a stance.  Continue on thin face climbing to the anchors.

name: A Stone’s Throw Away
description: Start on the left side of a prominent triangular roof and follow bolts to the anchor.

name: Avalanche
description: Climb through a series of gaping overlaps to a thin tricky crux move below the anchors.

name: Black Magic
description: Start on a nice pillar like feature and follow a slightly left trending line through a couple of small roofs to a crux finish below the anchors.

name: Blackout
description: Starts in finely grained and featured grey rock. Pull the roof just off the ground with pockets, edges and big moves. Continue up through a couple more slightly easier roofs and overlaps.

name: Block Party
description: Start in the middle of a cream/tan colored face.  Climb to a crack that turns left and into a burly undercling.  Pull the bulge to a stance.  Continue up a crack/corner on good rock.

name: Burly Girl
description: Shares the opening move with Block Party   then move right up a ramp to a big roof.  Pull the roof with big moves and wild stemming.  Move up to the final overlap and jam through the roof to a brown face with sloping holds. Make a tough move to the anchors.

name: Chain Smoker
description: Start on a slab with 2 bolts, gain a stance and step right around a corner and climb the surprisingly tough face and arête. Continue to a pair of roofs that lead to a big corner below the cedar tree on the rim.

name: Coffin Nails
description: Climb up low angle stacked blocks to a bolt in vertical rock. Work up a series of corners to a big roof and pull it on the left side to gain a stance. Move up and left to the anchors on Chain Smoker.  It's worth putting up with the scruffy but easy start as the finish has excellent movement on great rock.

name: Demon Monkey
description: Start on an overhanging boulder and climb up into a deep corner. Pull the left side of a roof past and face climb over the monkey face (the eye sockets make great undercling holds). Continue up through 2 more roofs and manage a very thin move below the anchors.

name: DOPAPOD
description: Start with big moves through an overhang just off the ground. Work up and slightly left trending through 3 more small roofs with a cruxy move or two (or three) at each roof.

name: Dune
description: Start behind a large tree and follow a series of steep blocks to the rim.

name: Déjà Vu
description: The start is about 100 feet right of Coffin Nails.  Climb the deep, dark corner on excellent stone. Face climb and hand jam to the anchors.

name: Head Stone
description: Follow a right trending line through a couple of small roofs to an anchor high on the wall near the rim.

name: Miss Trixie
description: Lie back and stem a short face to a big ledge.  Step across to excellent rock and technical moves leading to an exciting finish on a pocketed face.

name: Ramble On
description: Face climb up featured rock avoiding the hard deep 'v' slot.  Move right to a stance. May share a hold or two with Black Magic then move left to a corner.  Continue more or less straight up steep rock.  Make a couple thin crimps on a brown face to gain the anchors.

name: Rock Head
description: Climb up grey rock and through a blocky section.  Finish on good brown rock.

name: Rock Junkies
description: Work up overhanging rock to a small roof with an attractive clean tan and grey face. Pull on to the face with small crimps and stabby pockets. Continue up and slightly right to an obvious large hueco. Bust one more big move to easier climbing and the anchors.  Excellent sustained climb.

name: Run the Gauntlet
description: Climb up grey rock and a small roof to highly featured cream colored stone that looks more like limestone than basalt. Make fun and easy moves to a stance below a small roof, pull over the roof into a pod, and finish slightly right up and over a blocky ledge.

name: Seismic Event
description: ,   Just right of a blank tan face, climb a bulge and gain an obvious crack.  Continue up, passing a roof on its right and another roof on the left.  Finish on a steep brown face.

name: Sole Sacrifice
description: Work up to a grey and tan streaked face to a stance below a small roof. Negotiate this and two more roofs including a crux move over the last roof just below the anchors.

name: Upside Down
description: Stick clip first bolt or clip the first bolt of Run the Gauntlet.  Shares a hold or two with Run the Gauntlet then move left and pull straight over the bulge.  Continue up steep rock and a deep cleft.  Interesting rock and fun moves lead to a 2nd crux in a slightly overhanging corner.

name: Astro Poodle
description: Start 15 feet right of Astro Bear and climb up large steep blocks. Continue up to the pointy top of a large flake. Move up and left to a ledge. Continue up the steep terrain on decent rock to the top of the Astro Bear Pillar.

name: AstroBear
description: This prominent line is on the pillar/buttress between JR’s Place and Send Town.  Climb up steep rock to a large andinteresting hueco feature.  Exit the hueco out left to excellent brown rock on crimpy moves. Continue to a ledge and follow fun but easier terrain to the top.

name: Bully Pulpit
description: Start on the left side of a brown pillar and work up to a tan face and shallow right facing corner.  Continue up the crack to a brown face and the anchors.

name: Caveman
description: An obvious off-width climb that is more fun than it looks.

name: Homo Erectus
description: Climb a left facing corner to an extremely difficult mantle. Easier and fun climbing leads to the anchors.

name: Rastaman
description: After a loose start, this route improves.  Climb the big corner to the anchors.

name: Rough Rider
description: Start on the right side of the brown pillar and pass a double roof system on the left side of the roofs. Continue up a crack and face on excellent brown stone. Shares anchors with Bully Pulpit.

name: Barely Legal
description: Start 15’ left of the big cave with the huge fire ring. Scramble up blocks to a right facing corner with a lieback crack, move right to an undercling flake to gain another crack, then pull a small bulge. Continue up a steep, ramped corner to a huge roof. Pull the roof at its weakest point and power through a blocky overhang on mostly big holds. Step left and finish on an easier face.

name: Beat Down
description: Climb up to the right side of the same roof as Slave Boy and make a hard and balancy pull over the roof and onto the black slabby face. Dance through a tricky section with some rat poop and pull through the roof to a thin finish on excellent tan and brown rock.    During an FA attempt, Terran unintentionally discovered that Mike and Chris had drilled the last bolt but forgot to put the bolt and hanger in it.  Unfortunately, he took a massive whip on the hard finish at the anchors.  After the missing bolt was installed, Terran went back and sent the route.  The crux is still pulling onto the slab above the roof 10 feet off the ground.

name: Beginning of the End (aka JR’s An Asshole)
description: Climb the corner system right of big graffiti “JR”.  Begin the lie back moves of Barely Legal   then move left under a flake and small roof.  Pull the roof and follow a crack to the next larger roof.  Big moves up and left through the roof.

name: Black Lung
description: Climb up sandy hueco’s and make a thin move and long reach to a ledge. Follow steep rock to a final committing overhang.  FA:  Mike Engle, Chris Barnes, SupeVitali Mar 19, 2017.

name: Black Ops
description: Climb up to a really hard pull through a bulge at mid height.

name: Buck Fever
description: Climb up featured grey rock with huecos and pull a small roof into a long right facing corner that gets steeper towards its top. Move over a small overlap and continue up to an awkward clip at the anchors.  First climb bolted at Send Town.  Great warm up climb.

name: Caleb’s Corner
description: Climb up to the bottom of a large prow and move to the corner left of the prow on insecure liebacking. Once established, follow the corner system to the anchors.

name: Chaos (Open project)
description: Climb up to the start of a white crack.  Traverse left on tiny crimps to a blunt outside corner.  Continue up on small crimps.  Thought to be 13.

name: Danger Zone
description: The start is a little squeezed between Dust Devil and Slave Boy, jam a small roof just off the ground. Continue on a fully independent line up through 2 more roofs to the anchors.  3 cruxes.

name: Desert Solitaire
description: Climb up featured rock to a major blocky roof. Continue up to another small roof and finish on thin tip jams.

name: Dust Devil
description: Climb up tricky slab moves into a creamy colored right leaning double dihedral, stem up to the roof and pull through on mostly big holds.  Excellent climb on great rock.

name: Egomaniacs
description: Scramble up to stance below an obvious nice looking corner.  Stem up and until it possible to pull into the right hand   crack.  Continue up into a very nice corner system. The route ends at the top of the corner and under a small roof.

name: Entropy
description: Shares the first two bolts with Chaos.  Chaos moves up and left while Entropy continues straight up the crack.  About 15 feet of tough sledding leads to finally a good jam.  Continue up the 5.10 crack to the anchors.   Great route.

name: Flop Sweat
description: Climb up a steep corner and move over a bulge and right to a face below the anchors.

name: Futurama
description: Move up and left to an undercling flake below a small roof. Climb left on underclings and gain small holds just above the lip. Crank through roof to the anchors. Short, powerful.

name: The Gloves Come Off
description: Stand on a small boulder under a roof. Pull up on starting holds to gain a block. Use the block to gain the hand crack.  Burly initial thin hands lead to more solid hands. Pull onto a ledge and gain the top of a small pillar. Pull on to a classic prow and face climb for 3 more bolts to the anchors.  Super fun!

name: The Gloves Go On
description: Stick clip the first bolt and boulder up to the bulging hand crack, pull into the offwidth and exit right to ledge. Move left and climb a fun corner on excellent rock.

name: Holey Moley
description: Climb on the right side of a prow like formation with swiss cheese features. Pull left around a steep edge to a stance. Follow easy rock to the anchors.

name: Holey Roller
description: Climb up featured rock to an obvious thin finger crack. This is the left route of three routes that share the same anchor. Shares anchors with Holier Than Thou and Holey Moley.

name: Holier Than Thou
description: Take the left side of a prow through featured ‘bubble rock’ to a suspect looking flake. Take care not to snap it off and pull through to gain easier terrain. Shares last bolt and anchors with Holey Moley and anchors with Holey Roller.

name: Jailbait
description: This is the rightmost route at Send Town.  Climb up streaked tan and grey rock to an obtuse corner.  Continue up the corner to the anchors.

name: Mad Max
description: Climb vertical grey rock to a small ledge, continue up to the first of 3 roofs. A heel hook leads to a hard pull with a lot of body tension over the first roof. Pass the second roof on the left. Pass the 3rd roof on the right and work up a crux corner to a horn like feature and a hard pull to the anchors.

name: Ms. Snatchural
description: , Pitch 1 (5.9): start left of the large cave and work right into a large slot. Move up and right to a stance below a feature face. Fun face climbing leads to the anchors below some stacked blocks (about 40 feet below the rim).  Pitch 2 (5.11):  Climb up and left around an outside corner and pass a roof system to the anchors.   Can be done in one long pitch but adds a difficult roof (5.11+?) staying left of the P1 anchors.

name: No Time
description: Climb up to the bottom of a large prow and move right into a right facing corner. Stem, face climb and jam up to a blocky small roof. Pull through and climb to the anchors.  Fun, moderate warm up.

name: Road Warrior
description: Start on a short vertical wall and pull onto a ledge. Continue on easy ground to a large roof and pull through with a tough barn door lie back to a stance over the roof. Continue on steep terrain to a small roof at the top. Pass it on the right and pull up to the anchors.

name: Rocktoberfest
description: Start on the right side of the large cave and fire pit. Climb up to a stance below an obvious overhanging smooth corner with a jam/lieback crack. Struggle to the lip and do a burly pull onto a small ledge. Continue up two short but challenging overhanging corners to the anchors on the rim.  Great route.

name: Sandstorm
description: This is the middle of three routes on the shortface on the uphill side of Send Town. Move up and right over a bulge to a small roof. Pull over the roof into a shallow corner and crimp to the anchors.  Short, fun, and powerful.

name: Shogun
description: Pull a small roof off the ground to a steep shallow dihedral with thin crimps.  Crimp and stem to the right side of a large overhang.  Climb the corner above to a stance below the final face.

name: Steep Thrills
description: Scramble up to left diagonalling crack. Face climb from the left or make a couple jams to a stance. Continue straight up on pinches and crimps to the anchors.

name: Thor’s Hammer
description: Climb tough opening moves up grey rock to a stance below a small roof. Exit to the right (10-) or stay left and pull the roof (10). Both variations finish on the same anchor.  Named for Vernon Phinney's aggressive cleaning from big blocks at the rim of the cliff above the climb.  The aftermath makes good seats for putting on your shoes at the base of the climb.

name: Warpath
description: Start on a sandy ledge a few feet off the ground. Work up a corner with body smears to gain a couple difficult holds. Continue up the corner until you can make easier moves to the left. Work up to a stance below a corner. Continue up the corner to a small, fun roof up and slightly left. Pull the roof and continue on easier terrain to the anchors.

name: The Whuppin’
description: Climb up grey stone and move over a small roof into a shallow corner. Continue up hard moves to a second roof and head right on tan rock to shallow tan obtuse corner.  Great climb with continuous movement.

name: Wild Thing
description: Start in the same corner as Buck Fever and move right to an undercling below a big roof. Reach out and gain a series of hueco features and follow them up the wildly overhanging arête until you can pull left onto the face. Continue on the face with moderate climbing to the anchors.

name: Devil’s Tool
description: Start on fractured but surprisingly good stone. Work up to an obvious undercling and lieback around a huge flake.

name: Feeding Frenzy
description: Scramble up the base of large Juniper tree.  Follow a fun and challenging corner system in mostly tan rock to the anchors. Steep and pumpy.

name: Get Over It
description: Scramble up blocky, scruffy terrain to an obvious weakness in the roof band and pull the roof.  Climb heavily featured tan rock and follow the corner system to the anchors.

name: GoDoG
description: Scramble up to the base of a bulge.  Pull over a bulge and work up to the steep overhanging corner guarding the anchors.

name: Jump Street
description: Layback off the ground over a boulder and move up to a steep brown face that is a little easier than it looks.

name: Snake Eyes
description: Climb a brown slab to blocks to a tan bulge.  Crank over the bulge and continue on good stone.  Finish on a long technical steep face.

name: Sunsigns
description: Scramble over acceptable stacked blocks.  Work up a creamy face on some large huecos.  Climb the overhanging right facing corner to the anchors.

name: Unrepentant
description: Great stone and continuously engaging movement make for an excellent route.  Make a cranky move past the first bolt.  Work up to some finger jams over a roof.  Continue up to another slightly overhanging finger crack and finish in a technical slot.

name: A Little Cranky
description: Climb up to an overhang with a small shelf and follow a left leaning overhanging corner to the anchors.

name: Beauty Climb
description: Carefully pull on fragile but cool hueco features to a stance below a steep headwall. Take good but thin crimps to the anchors.

name: Cry Baby
description: Stem up to a hand crack and follow the sharp crack to the anchors.

name: Shake It Off
description: Climb up and right to a huge ledge and continue moving right to a steep fun finish.

name: Under the Radar
description: Move up a corner with orange lichen to a stance below a steep brown face with a right trending thin crack. Follow the crack and good pockets to the anchors.

name: Air of Feasibility
description: Hard, steep climbing off the ground leads to left leaning rail and a very hard pull onto a shelf. Move right then left up a tricky arête to the anchors.

name: Air of the Dog
description: Face climb up to a big roof and follow a weakness to a left facing corner and the anchors.

name: Baby Steps
description: Follow a wide crack in a corner to a bulge and pass the bulge by moving slightly right.  Continue to the anchors.

name: Back in Business
description: Start in a shallow double dihedral to gain a ledge, make a hard move off the ledge to gain a left facing corner.  Continue on sustained pockets to the anchors.

name: Bad Boyz
description: Follow cool hueco features up and right to balancy corner.Move slightly right to gain a stance below the final headwall.  Trend left and follow pockets and crimps to the anchors.

name: Bedtime Story
description: Climb a slab to a steep corner and follow it to the anchors.

name: Bromancing the Stone
description: On the right side of the pillar, move up to a thin crack and follow it over a bulge to a stance, move left on steep pockets to the anchors.

name: Busted
description: Start in a left facing corner with excellent rock.  A series of stout moves leads to a finger crack through the bulge and a stance below a tree.  Move up and right on slightly slabby rock with good pockets to the anchors.

name: Hey Boo Boo
description: About 200 feet to the right of Vern’s Jewels and Bedtime Story is a detached pillar with an obvious chimney. Continue right around a buttress where the crag aspect turns from North West to West.  Jeff Rhoads put 2 routes in this area. There is potential for more.  Hey Boo Boo is the bolted line and shares anchors with Yogi.

name: Holding Out for a Hero
description: Start on featured rock and move up into an overhanging left facing corner.  Pull through the apex of the corner on pockets and move left to the finishing slab of Busted.  It’s possible to avoid the crux and move left to the stance below slab sooner.  This lowers the grade to 5.10.

name: I Need to Move
description: Climb the left side of a small pillar to a stance below a bulge.  Move left on ok hands and horrible feet.  Finish on a nice face following pockets and crimps to the cable anchor around the tree.

name: Neo Con
description: Directly behind the big juniper climb a tough crack to a deep double dihedral. Take the left side of the double corners to the anchors.

name: Pacifier
description: Start in an orange corner and pull a tricky bulge, follow a crack and corner to the anchors.   About 200 feet to the right of   Pacifier   , there are a couple short routes.   Routes are listed Left to Right.

name: T-Rex
description: Climb up a crack to a right facing corner.

name: Vern's Jewels
description: Starting on the left side of a slab, make a steep move left across an arête to gain a stance.  Continue on easier rock.

name: Coyote Crack
description: Scramble up the lower section to attain the true climbing through the bulge moving left then up the hand crack to the chain anchors above

name: Flux Capacitor
description: After a blocky start, pull into a very obvious left facing yellow dihedral with a beautiful hand/finger crack.  Pull on to a stance and move right to a shallow brown corner with nice facing climbing to the anchors.

name: Sense the Power
description: Climb fractured rock to flared finger jams up a shallow left facing corner.  Finish on a very nice brown face.

name: Static Line
description: Work up to a decent crack/corner system.  Climb an overlap to a brown face and finish on the anchors of Watt’s Up.

name: Surge Protector
description: A broken start leads to a triangular flake and a steep hand crack.

name: Watt’s Up?
description: Climb up to a very shallow corner and make some delicate face moves up a brown face.  Finish in a left facing leaning corner.

name: Better Than She Looks
description: Scramble up to the bulging bubbly rock, pull up and move left. Climb the fun face to the chain anchors above.

name: Hot Line
description: The center route - climbbrown and tan rock to a steep bulge.  Pull up on big holds and continue up to start of dark brown rock.  Finish in a tough but very appealing shallow dihedral.

name: More Power Needed
description: Climb up using a multitude of skills to the anchors

name: Off the Grid
description: This is the right of three routes that share the same first 2 bolts.  From the grassy ledge, move slightly right and up to a pillar like formation.  Wrestle the pillar and step left avoiding a large bird nest.  Finish on a discontinuous crack in excellent brown rock.

name: Power Discharge
description: Right of "More Power Needed".  From the grassy ledge, move left to a blocky corner that leads to a clean crack through tan rock. Pass an overlap on the left and finish on brown rock and a shallow left facing corner.

name: The Bat
description: Climb another corner system to the right of Monkey Woman.  4 bolts.

name: Cherokee Social
description: Climb the south side of the detached pillar.  2 bolts.

name: Chu WannaGunks (aka CB’s Roof)
description: Just right of the pillar, face climb up to large roof just below the anchors.4 bolts.

name: Enter Sandman
description: Start on brown rock and face climb into a nice and continuously thin shallow open book.  3 bolts.

name: Enticement (aka Forgot to Remember)
description: Start on slabby moves on a large detached flake. At the top of the flake, step across to the main wall and follow a featured blunt arête to the top.  4 bolts.

name: Feeling Frisky
description: Scramble over blocks down low to a flared hand crack.  Continue up and right to a splitter crack in a brown face.

name: Ghost Rider
description: Hard boulder problem start on excellent rock.  Pull past a flake, slap left and crimp right to a small ledge.  From the ledge follow good holds on brown rock in a shallow corner.

name: Interstellar
description: Climb 10 feet of chossy blocks to gain a tough thin hands crack and crank hard through a small overlap to fully gain the crack, continue to a ledge at 2/3 height and work slightly left up a tough face with a hard move at the anchors.  6 bolts.

name: Lady Love
description: Work a corner/arête with the right hand and face climb with the left.  6 bolts.

name: Mirage
description: Hard opening moves with good feet and bad hands, lead to a shelf.  Finish on easier, pleasant climbing up a white creamy face with pockets.  4 bolts.

name: Monkey Woman
description: Climb a slabby move to a shelf and climb into a tan dihedral.  Follow the dihedral to the top and move left to the anchors on Your Own Private Idaho   .  4 bolts.

name: Needing Whiskey
description: Follow thin parallel cracks to a right facing corner until you can move left to the anchors of Feeling Frisky.  4 bolts.

name: Nice Guys Finish Last
description: Follow a crack in a brown corner to a ledge and finish on the last two bolts of No More Mr Nice Guy. 4 bolts.

name: No More Mr. Nice Guy
description: Jam up a steep thin hand crack in a white corner.  Gain a ledge and climb the face just left of a wide crack.  6 bolts.

name: Palm Tree Garage
description: This and the previous 3 routes share a shelf about 8 feet off the ground.  From the shelf, move up into the shallow corner and make a hard reach to a decent 3 finger pocket.  Easier climbing leads to the top.  4 bolts.

name: Pillar Talk
description: Climb the east face of the pillar.  3 bolts.

name: Prophet of Dune
description: -   After a brief chossy section, pull onto nicely featured rock and work a seam and hueco’s to a roof with a triangular block at the lip, pull through and face climb to right side of a huge cap stone roof.  6 bolts.

name: Sand Blasted
description: Start in a creamy tan corner low to the ground and pull through a tough overlap on relatively big holds and follow a discontinuous slotted crack to the top on mostly brown rock. Decent hands and poor feet; sustained and pumpy.  4 bolts.

name: Sand in Your Crack
description: Start on stacked blocks to gain a nice hand crack and follow it to the top.  4 bolts.

name: Sand Surfer
description: Climb up to stance below an obvious blunt arête.  Tricky face climbing right then left leads to a stance below deep short corner.  Pull through the corner to a ledge and the anchors.  6 bolts.

name: Sandman
description: Stem up the gap between the pillar and main wall.  Finish on the Pillar Talk anchors.2 bolts.

name: Sands of Time
description: Start on creamy tan rock, pull through an overlap to a thin seam in a shallow corner.  Climb up to the anchors situated in an alcove above a small roof.  4 bolts.

name: Your Own Private Idaho
description: Climb a right arcing tan crack featured with small finger pockets.  4 bolts.

name: Desertion
description: Climb up to an overhanging handcrack in an obvious deep corner. Difficult moves out and right to gain the anchors.

name: John Paul’s Alter Boy
description: Formerly a trad line 10’ right of Warm Fuzzy, now a bolted line.

name: Warm Fuzzy
description: Climb up to a nice looking left facing corner with a couple welded in blocks at the bottom of the corner.5 bolts.

name: ? *aka The Question Mark*
description: Climb a slot through a small roof using face holds to the left.  Continue up to the question mark feature and grovel up an offwidth or layback the edge and swing right onto the face.  Finger jams leads to a stance and the anchors.

name: Crazy Rap Bolters
description: Scramble through brief, easy choss to solid rock and a super fun right facing dihedral.  Pull onto a small stance and follow good rock to the anchors.

name: Jungle Boogie
description: Follow the left side of “Africa” to a steep headwall crack with fused, stacked blocks.

name: Zulu Queen
description: Climb the right side of an “Africa” looking feature high on the crag.  Cruxy moves leaving the continent for the anchors.  6 bolts.

name: Aroma Lip Traverse
description: Start as for Aromatherapy, but follow the lip of the overhanging east face and top out at the southeast corner.

name: Aromatherapy
description: Standing start on the northeast corner, pull up to sloping holds and mantle powerfully to top out. Short but kinda fun.

name: Brett's Aroma
description: Summed up by two hard, big moves. From the start, *basically* make a big move to a sloper up right, and another big move to the lip. Easy top out.

name: The Dainty Morsel
description: Hard, strange compression climbing up a short, steep arete. Highlighted by pulling hard on a heinously small 1/4 pad crimp and a difficult, prolonged heel hook. Very easy topout.

name: The Secret Garden
description: Very fun slopey route on the North side of the Aromatherapy boulder.

name: Another Dam Sit Start
description: Sit start on the large sloping rail on the south face of the boulder. Hard moves to start out then an easy traverse to the left.

name: The Big Dam Pump
description: Start all the way right and traverse the entire lip.

name: Dam Nation
description: Sit start using the obvious big edge in the inside corner. Traverse left on small pockets and follow the arete to the top out. A classic 2004 route!

name: Dam the Man
description: Same start as Dam Nation. 3 big moves straight up to the lip.

name: Hate Hate Hate
description: Start on jug and pocket (same as love hate love) and go direct not using the jug rail, but instead use a series of small crimps and pinches and toping out at the prominent nose a little bit left.  Theres about 5 crappy pinches or crimps. use whatever makes you happy.

name: Hell Hooks
description: Sit Start on same holds as hate hate hate and love hate love (jug and pocket). move up and left using very small crimps. slap out left on some slopers and finish on the same finish as left hand love handles (nose). It is called hell hooks because immediately following a very demanding right heel hook is a another demanding and powerful left heel hook.

name: Left Side Love Handles
description: Sit start as far left as possible. follow the lip all the way around the prow, merging with love handles to top out.

name: Love Handles
description: Sit start in a large vertical pocket at the base of the prow. Follow obvious juggy rail to the topout.

name: Love Hate Love
description: Sit start just left of Love Handles. Big dynamic pull for the jug or more static moves on small crimps. Top out with Love Handles.

name: Slot Shot
description: A one move wonder to a mantle. Pretty short and silly, but it is a pretty cool move, I guess. Start with right hand in the good slot and left hand on a sloping crimp. Toe into a little divot and shoot for the lip. You CAN do a left heel on the large sloper rail to the left, but what's the fun in that?

name: Angelina Jolie
description: Start on the right side of the pit. Traverse the lip, trending left, until you connect at the top with Jennifer Aniston.

name: Jennifer Aniston
description: Sit down at bottom of pit. Pull the left side on positive holds. Top out.

name: The Coffin Lid
description: Fun, challenging lip traverse with a bit of variation.   Start on large block to the right of San Callisto and gain the prominent, horizontal rail. Traverse rail to the left. Using strenuous pinches, go up!

name: Rocket from the Crypt
description: Awesome jug haul. Start on the right corner, traverse left on big holds. Watch the topout hold, it has been known to crumble unexpectedly

name: San Callisto
description: Incredible tension moves on a horizontal roof. Kneebar start in the very back of the cave. Follow large blocky pinches to the prow and pull around.      The boulder on the right is off.

name: Scream Dracula Scream
description: Sit start on thin crimps in the middle of the crypt block. Go straight up, bisecting Rocket from the Crypt.

name: Chamber of Secrets
description: A great jug haul to warm up on before making a pass at the Chambermaid

name: The Chambermaid
description: Sit start the right side of the cave. clench your cheeks and slap nonexistent slopers. Super classic.

name: The Big Cheese
description: Same start as Feta, but trend right about halfway up. Move right across the face using a sidepull. Big finishing move.

name: Feta
description: Overhanging moves on slopers and large crimps. Sit start on large sloping rail, go direct. Don't use the jugs from "sakura".

name: Goat Cheese
description: Sit start with side pulls on left and right corners. Pull up to crimpy corners, then long reach to top. Much love is needed to send this one. Climb and you'll see why.

name: Lactose Intolerance
description: An eliminate problem. (Left and right aretes are off, hence eliminate) Sit start using the two obvious lowest large down/right slanting edges and a low left foot. Make a few balancy moves straight up the short overhanging face on cool slanted edges up to a false lip and one more move up to a top out jug.

name: The Little Cheese
description: Start on the jug in the center of the mini "alcove" rail on the right side of the same face as Feta and The Big Cheese. Make a couple moves left to get your heel on the start jug and move straight up on a gaston and a sloper to get stood over your foot. Easy top out.

name: Sakura
description: sit start on tiny crimps, a couple big jugs up higher.

name: Center Route
description: Indistinguishable from the other Chick Rock routes in terms of difficulty or quality.    Standing start.

name: Left Arete
description: Low angled slab. Great for beginners who are just learning to trust their feet.

name: Right Arete
description: This one is probably the best route for a first time boulderer because of the convenient step-off ledge.     Standing start.

name: The Tick
description: Fun moves on great rock.  Harder than it looks.

name: Bauhaus
description: Climb crimps to big edges on the right side of this left facing wall.

name: Bela Lugosi
description: THE HIGHBALL of highballs. Bring multiple pads and spotters. Tricky start. Undercling and toe cam in the back of the roof. Make the span out to the good rail along the lip of the boulder. Follow the rail to the right corner and then go up from there. Take care to not collapse the edge of the landing zone.

name: It's Not Easy Being a Hobbit
description: Steep juggy problem.   Sit start, fully underneath the rock. Original ascensionists had a hell of a time climbing while being gang-attacked by the ants that formerly inhabited this hobbit hole.   Problem tops out.

name: Joel's Traverse
description: Awesome sloping rail traverse. Start on the west face of the boulder all the way left. Traverse right to the corner.

name: Kendra's Crawl
description: as far as i know this is an unsent open project, so the v6 rating is really just a placeholder until someone nabs the FA and suggests the official grade.    The route is a linkup of Joel's Traverse and Lilly's Manchild, which are conveniently arranged end-to-end.

name: Lilly's Manchild
description: start on the southwest corner, slap and struggle up the south face, topping out at the peak.

name: Lilly's Mantle
description: The namesake of the boulder.     It's a one-move-wonder, but the beta is so unique it's definitely worth a visit.     Start in the jug under the roof (same as simon says) instead of exiting the roof to the left, grab the lip and mantle to the right.     see picture.

name: Simon Says
description: Sit start in a large jug under the low roof. pull out of the roof to the left and follow the southeast corner rail to the topout

name: Chad Sr.
description: Standing start on sloping crimps. Long pull to the right edge. follow the edge up to the peak and top out.

name: Chad's Traverse
description: This traverse is best done from left to right. sit start at the east tip of the mothership, then match and heel hook to your heart's content. Top out above the cave.

name: Control of Nature
description: Start standing with an obvious right pocket slightly above lowest horizontal rail and a low and far left edge below horizontal rail, both as underclings as the lowest natural start. Climb out the center of the roof on obvious holds and finish just left of the boulders apex on good incut edges.     This was likely a project for so long because the horizontal rail looks like the probable start. However,the double underclings turn out to be the logical start and set you up for the rest the of the problem.

name: Crop Circles
description: Start as for the Alien project, but go straight up on slightly crumbly crimps.

name: Driving Rocketships
description: Sit start the southeast corner, pull up through blocky crimps. Top out with a large chickenhead.    A standing start goes at easy v1.

name: Ufology
description: This used to be called touch and go, but alien names are cooler.   This is a lowball route that gets you all scrunched up. sit start in the scoop with a large sidepull. tension to a powerful undercling and unwind to the topout.

name: Hairdresser on Fire
description: A short problem, but very technical. Sit start on tiny holds and slap left for the sloping bulge. Stand on nothing and wrestle a top-out.

name: Smallest is Best
description: standing start on crimps left of switcheroo. remain on the face. (rail is off)

name: Smith
description: Recent bullet wounds on the rock give the route some interesting foot pockets while going up a very balancy and fun short slab.

name: Switcheroo
description: One of the first routes from the 2010 revival. Standing start on incut crimps. Look for decent feet and pull straight up. top out at the peak.

name: Switcheroo Sit Start
description: Adding a couple fun hard moves to Switcheroo, this route is home to some of the coolest moves at the Dam!

name: Tweedle-dee
description: The most probable line on the switcheroo boulder. Sit start in the scoop at the lower right corner of the arrowhead-shaped face. (the east face). find okay feet and reach above the lip for a couple of shallow seams. Traverse left onto the face, merge with Switcheroo and go for it.

name: Tweedle-Dumb
description: Alternate direct ending to Tweedle-Dee

name: Bazooka Joe
description: Brilliant overhanging arete.

name: Biggy Slabs
description: Fun slabby corner. Pretty tall. Standing start.

name: Campfire Headphase
description: This is a short vertical problem on very small pockets.     sit start with the left hand in a sidepull, pull up through monos and shallow "1st team" pockets. Look for crappy feet and top out.

name: Cool Ranch
description: Sit start the right corner rail of the dorito formation. Lieback to the apex and top out.

name: E.P.H.
description: Super easy ledges and edges up to a couple thin crux moves at the very top.   Easy to bail onto platform to your right if you don't want to pull final moves. If you pop off on the crux moves, you might break your back on the giant knife blade boulder pointing straight at you.   It's also very easy to break off the tiny nubs and edges used at the top. Tread lightly.

name: The Floor is Liquid Nitrogen
description: Easy moves down low lead to a couple of long crimp pulls up high.   As to the name, the first ascent was done sans pads, and the name Hot Lava was already taken.

name: Heebie Jeebies
description: Big moves on a blank slab. Inspiring and unsettling!

name: Hot Lava
description: Difficult one or two move problem. Most people dyno from the start to the lip, but the right variation is fairly static. The obvious start hold is a shallow mono; it will be your right hand if you choose the dyno, or your left if you do the right variant.    Standing start.

name: Jack in the Crack
description: Awesome dihedral crack. Easy but the crux is up high.

name: Long Black Cadillac
description: Big moves on miniscule holds. Jump start to a prominent 2-finger pocket.

name: Lumber Jack
description: Sit start to the right, traverse up and left along campus board crimps. Crux down low.

name: Lumber Jill
description: Standing start on Campus board crimps. Good holds close together. Really fun

name: Not Cho Cheese
description: This problem and its neighbor, Cool Ranch, are pretty common warmups for the sector.     Not Cho Cheese follows a series of sloping crimps on a low angled slab. The rail is off; remain on the face.

name: Seven Deadly Sins
description: This is a cool sloper problem to the right of Long Black Cadillac. It follows the left-leaning outside corner. Don't use the crack or anything right of it.

name: Sidewinder
description: A good rail traverse with a slightly freaky landing. Nothing too spicy.

name: Sipping on Sunshine
description: Easy but committing slab climb, very comparable to its neighbor, Vendetta.

name: The Thing That Only Eats Hippies
description: Start low on the right, traverse the lip and top out.

name: Vendetta
description: Relatively easy slab climb, with committing moves up high.

name: Booty Call
description: A cool little roof problem with a foot-first start.    There's potential for an extended start from the left, but a pretty large boulder needs to be moved.     I need to get back there and brush it off properly, it's still quite dirty.

name: Caveman
description: Fun BIG move and hard top out.

name: Chocolate Eruption
description: Start at the bottom of the positive rail below Savoir Faire and follow it to the top. Holds thin out towards the top. Be careful.

name: The Edge of Left
description: Climb the narrow east face, using the right rail and thin crimps.

name: Savoir Faire
description: Start on a good pinch and a flat edge on the southwest corner, near the cave opening. Throw left to a prominent sloping crimp, sink a blind right heel and gain the rail. Move back right to a tiny razor crimp, and  then a series of slopers up the right edge. Currently my favorite boulder problem... ever.

name: Slabtastic face
description: Sketchy low-angle slab.

name: Grace Under Water
description: Difficult sit start on southeast corner. follow the corner up to the apex.

name: In the Pooper
description: A bit smelly at times. Start on the obvious large horizontal edge about waist level. There are numerous small edge features on this little face, but I opted for a large first move to a left gaston and then a few right hand bumps. Basically, start on the aforementioned start hold with a couple low feet and go straight up. Kinda scrunchy start move.

name: Snake Eyes
description: One of the oldest established lines. Sit start far right in a horizontal crack, then follow the sloping rail through the snake eyes. Top out at the peak.

name: Snake Eyes Direct
description: A straight line into Snake Eyes from underneath. Sit start on a large crimp almost straight down from the Snake Eyes monos. Climb up through crimps n stuff into the finish of Snake Eyes.

name: Snake Eyes Indirect
description: An early exit from the original Snake Eyes. Makes for an easier, fun little top out. Climb from the beginning of Snake Eyes for just a few moves until you reach the jug in the flat slab face. Then climb straight up the "slab" to the top.

name: The Walrus and the Carpenter
description: start in small finger pockets, pull for the lip and traverse right to the apex.

name: The Walrus
description: Start low on crimps, move straight up into pockets, then veer right onto the low-angled face.

name: Ballroom Dancing
description: varied and fun moves up the left side of a bulging water streaked slab. ends at the same anchor as fall ball. (can be continued up and left on easy runout bolted slab to an anchor on top of the wall....this will be over 120ft from the ground.)

name: Balls and Beauty
description: Super fun climbing through a large, juggy, horizontal roof then up a clean shallow corner. Fantastic climb.

name: Balls to the Wall
description: Fun slab moves past a bolt lead to a beautiful finger crack on the upper portion. Definitely fun and a great intro to the area.

name: Bawling
description: Fun water streaked slab to an awkward inside corner/roof. Insecure slab exit left.

name: fall ball
description: harder than it looks face/slab route

name: Free Balling
description: A finger and toe intensive climb in an airy position. Start up the low angle ledges and seams directly under the arete to the right of money ball. Steep crimping leads to an awkward sequence to stand on the slabby right side of the arete. Enjoy the dime edges to the top.

name: Have a Ball
description: Sustained 5.11 climbing through cool features.

name: Money Ball
description: Excellent route through a crux bulge then following face moves and fun pockets on the left side of an exposed arete. Great features and excellent position. May be grade or two harder for those under 6' tall!

name: Monkey Balls
description: Steep, open-handed climbing that follows unique features through orange and grey streaked granite.

name: play ball
description: Bolted slab leads to an inside corner crack and vertical face.

name: Un-ball-ievable
description: Great route following the prominent corner crack at the start of the wall. Be ready for everything from slab moves to off-width.

name: All my friend are flakes
description: First route encountered on the approach trail. characterized by vertical flakes and granite crystal knobs for the feet. Going right mid-route ups the pump and grade.

name: Bomber pinky jam
description: The beautiful thin crack splitting the right vertical face on the "5.9 wall". Enjoy the boulder sequence mid route!

name: Classic Crack
description: great finger to fist crack in a deep inside corner. Great hand jams for most of the route!

name: Ma Nature is a Drama Queen
description: Fun flakes and granite crystals lead you up the right edge of this wall. If the boulder move off the ground stumps you, you can sneak in from the right. You can watch ma nature brew up her storms over the selkirks to the southwest. If the mosquitoes are bad it can be more pleasant to belay from the top.

name: Major Razor
description: Start far right on low, double-handed sloper then travers left past long, powerful moves on razor crimps to gain rail at mid height.  Throw to good holds and top out on the sloping prow at the heights point in the center of the boulder.

name: Surf'n
description: Striking and fun slab on the left side of a gradually sweeping steeper arête. Balancy moves in a fun airy position.

name: Wiggle, wiggle, wiggle
description: A harder than it looks face/slab. Easy to make this harder than necessary!

name: Banana Split
description: Fun, hidden splitter with bouldery start. More challenging than it looks.

name: Finger Lock'n Good
description: Extremely short, but also quite fun. This route is a great way to practice insecure finger locking and crack technique.

name: Gorilla Crack
description: This is an area classic and likely the first route climbed here. Short, yet surprisingly fun, this fist splitter is a great way to warm in to the area.

name: Monkey Makeover
description: Thanks to the father/son team for cleaning up such a fun climb! Much scrubbing and block chucking later....truly a quality bouldery route. This was first led directly over the 1st bolt which certainly adds another 5.10 sequence. The crux moves off the ledge getting situated in the dihedral will test your finger strength and flexibility.

name: Monkeys On Crack
description: Fun route with a steep crack start. The route follows an overhanging crack to a horizontal then a fun off-fingers and hands crack to the anchors.

name: Split Finger
description: The line that follows a moderate corner and finger crack on the right side of a left-facing corner until mid-route where it transitions into a thin seam for the  last 30 feet to the anchors. Thin gear and technical climbing make this an excellent route.

name: Two Cheeky Monkeys
description: One of the few sport routes at Naples. A fun, open-handed set of moves thru the early on crux leads up a series of cool features on the far left side of the crag.

name: Canary Legs
description: Crack in the middle of the photo below. No offwidth technique necessary. Lie back through the the wide sections. The crux is at the top, climbing up and right towards a couple thin flakes. Like most routes on Chimney, you’ll want to be solid at the grade. Great climb, worth doing as a single pitch, but can also be used as the start for a few different multi-pitch routes.

name: Cooper-Hiser
description: Pitch 1 (5.9 @chimney): Head up the left angling finger crack to the dead tree; Crux. As the tree would almost certainly break, if fallen on while being used as natural pro, I would bring a #6BD to place behind the tree (thin pro below). Continue up to the large belay ledge, and bolted anchor; then keep going, up and right, off the ledge, to the second bolted anchor, 30 ft above  (could be split into two pitches).  Pitch 1 Alternate: See Canary Legs (5.10b @chimney)  Pitch 1 Alternate (option 2; highly recommend) climb “East Face Direct” .10b (two pitches, still intact after rock fall, see Laird guidebook) to a ledge system directly below the splitter crack on pitch two of Cooper-Hiser and build a gear anchor, or traverse out right to the Cooper-Hiser pitch 1 belay ledge.   Pitch 2 - Post-Rockfall Pitch: (150 ft; 5.10; money pitch) Head straight left off the anchor, complete a delicate traverse (place a small nut or .01BD midway through to protect the follower). Continue up the spliter, off-finger/thin hands crack; Crux; can be protected safely without triple .75s, but bring them if available. Look for a large chockstone to your right at the top of the crack. Make sure you have good pro, and make an airy step right onto the chockstone, then head up and right, under the overhang. Climb through the overhang, to the two bolt anchor above.  Pitch 3: “Direct Finish Variation” (90ft; 5.9) head straight up off the belay through 10ft of lieback climbing, head right and up through 3 mantles. The third of which, the Laird guidebook, correctly, refers to as, “a frantic mantle move,” Crux, (look at the seam, where the mantle ledge meets the rock face for pro before committing to the mantle). Continue right then head up and left, using hand cracks, to the two bolt anchor.

name: East Face Direct
description: See description in Laird guidebook.

name: Eye of the Tiger
description: 3 pitch route with a ridiculously tough 5.8 bottom where you can choose between the off-width hand crack to the left or the dirty crack to the right. Follow the crack line up to the first belay ledge.  Then its up to a roof that you traverse right a few moves with great hand and fist jams(look for the 1" cam jammed deep into the crack).  From the roof you reach up into the off-width fist sized right facing flake system which is considered the crux of the route facing flake to the second belay station.  Then it's a simple 3rd pitch going right to the top with one last balancy move.

name: Free Friends
description: This is one of the premier routes on Chimney Rock. Steep, sustained, well protected crack climbing nearly all the way.  P1) starts in the left of two cracks. Vertical sustained liebacking right off the deck. About 15 feet up, and from a good stance, you cross into the right (dirty looking for a few more feet) crack. You’ll see the crack soon turns perfect hands through an overhang. After the bulge, easy face climbing takes you up to a very large ramp. The best belay is around the corner left via an airy step to a nice ledge. 5.9+?  P2) the money pitch. More steep liebacking just below the surfboard shaped roof. Fixed piece here as of 2017. Pull the roof via hero moves and get rewarded with 40+ feet of off width climbing via large flake. This thing will eat as many #4 Camalots as you can feed it. Pro can also be placed in cracks/flakes on the adjacent face. Belay just before (very small ledge) or just after the thin hands bulge that comes after the offwidth climbing is over. Missing the ramp could be devestating. After pulling the sharp, black ‘roof’, exit right onto the large ledge, though the handcrack appears to continue upwards. 5.10c  P3) Follow the ramp to the right until a large block. Above is a thin hand crack splitting yet another roof. The slab protecting this roof is pretty interesting. Thin hands through the roof turns to perfect hands in a corner. Above the hand crack, rock quality deteriorates, but gentle pulls on the larger blocks lead right to the summit.  5.8+?

name: Illusions
description: Shares the first fifteen feet with free friends. Instead of stepping right, as for free friends, continue straight up, the route trends slightly left. About 3/4 of the way up, the crack narrows to tips, probably the crux.

name: Tsumani
description: Start up the Cooper/Hiser but take a right asap and climb up a bit of thin crack to a hanging belay below the wide crack and obvious roof.  Climb up through the roof on hands and stemming (the crux) and finish the tips crack on the headwall and then climb right into Free Friends.  Instead of traversing right when possible finish by the PG13 last pitch up the crack to its end finishing with face climbing and the mantels through the over laps.

name: Fun Roof
description: Starts from the belay ledge above "It Ain't Hay".  Follow the dihedral crack system on the left to the large ceiling overhead.  Work the crack in the ceiling with a series of hand and fist jams to the crux which is pulling around the roof.  There are good hands just around the corner of the roof.  Then follow the easy crack/flake to the top.

name: It Ain't Hay
description: Start off on the right facing flake (I thought the crux was near the top of the flake)and work your way up around the right side of the thumb.  Stem up behind the thumb to a belay ledge just above.

name: Rappel Chimney
description: This great route provides the second easiest line to Chimney Rock's summit.  You only briefly climb the actual "rappel chimney".      p1) easy 4th/5th climbing turns into awkward climbing as you near the belay ledge above a large right facing corner (2 wide cracks up the left side of the corner help identify the target ledge).  Belay at the large ledge just right of a rappel station.    p2-3) the routes crux, is a nice short crack leaving the belay ledge leading to a bulge. Pull through the bulge or step right at the bulge for an easy exit.  Belay at the 2-bolt anchor just 30' above or continue by stepping right into a great open book feature.  Follow the open book, with great pro opportunities to its end.  Move left into the belay/rappel notch. Belay here, then a short pitch leads to the summit.

name: Sancho's
description: Pitch one is a steep and interesting pitch with abundant protection possibilities.  Pitch two is the 5.9+ crux with some tough liebacking. A short third pitch goes to the summit.

name: Scuffin Up
description: Good movement up a well protected series of cracks.  Would be a lot better if there was less lichen.  The flare is wide and strenous and would be a considerable challenge to the 5.9 leader.  Easily done in one pitch if rope drag is managed.

name: South Nose Exit
description: The South Nose exit is a popular way to top out Chimney Rock. Several routes will get you to the S Nose. “It Ain’t Hay” is probably the most popular route to gain the S. Nose. From the belay ledge (gear anchor) identify a single bolt on a clean face. Plug a couple small pieces of gear and then make some delicate moves to get to the bolt. Continue up easier terrain to a two bolt anchor at a ledge. Unrope here and scramble to the summit or do another short pitch. There used to be a large block and a piton, that protected one more difficult move. No idea when this block fell (sometime after 2017).

name: West Face Direct
description: Pitch 1 climb the flakes to the ledge below the off-width chimney pitch.  This ledge has a dead tree on it and makes an excellent belay for the crux pitch 2.  The chimney is excellent with mostly stemming but some jamming the off-width.  Just warning that this is old school 5.9 and very strenuous for the grade.  However pro is good with large pieces low and options on the left side for smaller gear middle and up.  Exit the chimney and move left on excellent ledge for belay.  Pitch 3 is a fun crack, flake, block climb 5.8 with good pro.  Move into the crack off the belay ledge was the hard part, after which it eases.  Move up and left before a committing move out from under a small roof and your done.

name: West Face Standard
description: The original route to the summit, and still the most  popular.

name: Peanut Butter and Hand-Jam
description: Very short and sweet. Use the crack to jam your hands and feet into, trad-dad your way up and mantle to the top of the boulder.

name: Stray Cats
description: Start sideways and get your hip on the small ledge just off the ground. Bring your right foot up and sink it into the crack to use as leverage to pull your body right side up. Use a crack and decent jugs to top out.

name: Boo-Nana
description: Start as low as you can get on the boulder, with both hands holding onto the ledge of the diagonal crack. Pull yourself up onto the edge and traverse left slightly, then squat low and use a side-pull crimp and under-cling crimp to get under the overhang, set your left foot on a dime-ledge under the edge, left hand high to the edge of the boulder, then throw right hand to the top. Pull your feet up and mantle that boulder, mantle it good.

name: Crawdad
description: Start low on the north side of Cut Fin at the bottom of the diagonal crack, and work your way up the right (west) side of the boulder to the top.

name: Bee Line
description: Follow the low angled right facing diehedral up to a tree.  You'll figure out how this route got its name when you're about two thirds the way up on a sunny day.

name: Main Line
description: Starts off with a large right facing hand crack on a boulder out of the ground then heads straight up to the roof above.  Work your way around the horn past the fixed nut and then straight up to the chains.

name: Ogre
description: If you've been looking for a sustained 10" wide crack to practice your off-width skills in the Inland Northwest, then this is it.  This dirty crack will wear you down and spit you out five feet from the bottom.  The climbing eases up once the crack offsets into a flared chimney.

name: Blast Zone
description: Scramble up to sloping grassy ledge. Follow bolts right, then through small roof and along right side of prominent column to top anchors.

name: Devil in Disguise
description: Might be more than you bargained for! Fun climbing on outside of a right-facing dihedral formed by a set of prominent columns for first half of route uses crack in dihedral to right for gear. Bust a move off last piece of good gear (#2 TCU) in the thinning crack to first bolt, which protects crux move above. Clip second bolt to move up to ledge above and anchor on inset column to right.

name: Devil's Advocate
description: Route starts in left-facing dihedral formed by set of prominent columns to right. Reaches a sloping ledge at about a third of the way up, then follows a fantastic crack for a series of fun moves on prominent column in groove formed by a series of missing columns. Move left to join No Fury once crack runs out at widow-maker towards top.

name: Devil's Brew
description: Follows crack that splits a pair of prominent columns, using the next crack to left in places. Angle right at top to clip final bolt on Hell's Bells and top anchors.

name: Devil's Hands
description: Follows hand crack to right of prominent set of columns.

name: Devil's Hopscotch
description: Hop, skip, and jump your way back and forth along this fun route. The 1st bolt is just up and to the left of the small roof. The route generally moves rightward as you move up, with the bolts spanning 3 columns. Make a choice at the 3rd bolt to go left or right- both options are interesting and worth trying out.

name: Four Horsemen
description: You gotta love basalt columns. Hug these four beauties all at once to inch your way up to the top. Climbs the four pillars at base of main drainage. Good gear placement right at the start, then 4 bolts through the crux moves on the blank face. Finish by using crack on left side for gear to reach anchors on ledge at top.

name: Give 'em Hell
description: A Hells Gate test piece. Crimps and smearing stems are sprinkled with just enough in-cut holds to make this spectacular climb go. Git fired-up for this one!

name: Good Intentions
description: Short but sweet. Start on ramp that leads to left-hand crack of prominent column. Switch to right-hand crack half way up, and finish on ledge at top anchors.

name: Hell Hath no Fury
description: Climbs arete on right-facing dihedral system formed by set of prominent columns. Gear protects easy climbing for first half of climb. Crux moves above are protected by 3 bolts that lead to top anchors.

name: Hell in a handbasket
description: Start a bit right on sloping ledges near Good Intentions. Follow 5 bolts in groove formed by inset column to top anchors.

name: Hell or High Water
description: Climbs crack to right of the four pillars on water-smoothed rock below main drainage.

name: Hell's Bells
description: Route follows prominent groove formed by missing column using side-pulls, in-set holds, and a stem or two to reach top anchors.

name: Hellion
description: Starts right  off as a hellion, but it's an angel in places too. Route stays left of bolt line.  Fun route, some technical sections.

name: Road to Hell
description: Several options. Pull a small roof at start. Left of bolts on prominent column is a bit easier, right on face is a bit harder. 6 bolts to anchors.

name: Seventh Circle of Hell
description: Follows crack to left of prominent pair of columns. Start in next crack left, then switch to main crack next to column, and finish on bolt just below top anchor.

name: Smear Campaign
description: Starts 3rd/4th pillar to the right of the anchor (avoiding the dirty/crumbly and step-ladder like pillars directly below it).  Once you arrive near the 2nd bolt move into the gully.Smearing/Stemming is the name of the game. It can be done either by staying purely in the gully using stemming for the most part (increases the difficulty some) or it can be done using a few holds on the edges of the route.  Fun climbing, even a short section top half that can be done layback.

name: Sneaky Little Devil
description: Scramble up several crack systems on set of prominent columns to left of Seventh Circle to gain ledge system above. Move right on ledges to catch top of Seventh Circle. Shares top anchors with Seventh Circle.

name: Scenic as Hell, left
description: Solid rock with great views. Climb the left crack of main column.

name: Scenic as Hell, right
description: Climbs right hand crack of main column.

name: Bloody Hell!
description: Sequence of high-steps up to 4th bolt, then move right through crux, a balancy sequence with delicate footwork. After 5th bolt, move well left  to clip the 6th bolt.

name: Catchin' Hell
description: Climb starts in crack to left below prominent widow-maker. Gear in crack protects climb to sloping ledge, then switch to bolts as crack disappears. Climbing is varied between stems and inset holds up groove below widow-maker, then sneaks left to top anchors.  Sport variation: Clip the first two bolts of A Match Made in Hell (5.10 moves)  and step left to clip the first bolt of Catchin' Hell.

name: Colossus
description: One of the Seven Wonders of north-central Idaho. Climbs the absolutely insane, completely detached column at Hells Gate. Rest assured as you delight in climbing that which should not reasonably exist, when this 6 ton behemoth collapses (next week? tomorrow? In 10 seconds?), the bolt line will still stand. Route directly climbs the main detached column past 5 bolts on the right. Move right after the fifth bolt to clip the last bolt and the top anchors. More fun than you can shake a stick at.

name: Deal with the Devil
description: Climbs back and forth in several crack systems on a prominent double-column. The right column is completely detached. Good pro, great climbing, but a fall on any of your gear will give you a split second to wonder if that detached column will stand or fall as you load it. You might just end up making a deal you'll regret.

name: Devil's Jenga
description: A game of skill, strategy, and balance. Try to keep a steady hand and don’t knock over the tower! Stand on a short pillar to clip the first bolt. When the climbing starts to blank out make your way over to the crack on the right, clip the 4th bolt, and mantle onto the top of the column. Then step up and out onto some tiny holds (with some exposure) to make the clip. After that it eases up a bit and it's fun climbing on up to to the anchors.

name: Different Kind of Hell
description: Boulder start. Route stays right of bolt line. Climbing stays consistently interesting all the way up. High-step crux move towards top. Move left to anchors.

name: Hell Bent for Leather
description: Thin crack with interesting moves.

name: Hell to Pay
description: Climb the bolted route just to the left of Different Kind of Hell. Climbing is consistently delicate and balancy throughout the route with a powerful crux after clipping the 3rd bolt.  Trad start variation: Easy moves on gear in obvious crack to right of a pair of prominent columns gets you off the deck. Crack necks-down a third of the way up the route. Move right to clip the 3rd bolt and then encounter the crux. Delicate maneuvering from there gets you to the top. Gear to 2".

name: Jenga Jam
description: Climbs the obvious crack to the right of Devil's Jenga, then finishes on last 3 bolts of that route. Shares the same top anchor.

name: Match Made In Hell
description: A challenging route that toggles back and forth between powerful and balancy. It has a few specific sequences that seem to be required to get you through the cruxes, the 1st of which comes after clipping the 3rd bolt.  Catchin' Hell sport start variation: You can use the first 2 bolts of this route and then cut left to clip the 1st bolt of "Catchin' Hell" (bypassing Catchin' Hell's trad section).

name: The Robot Devil Plays Jazz
description: A short but very fun route! Easy climbing to the 1st bolt. After the 2nd bolt stay left, choosing the right is very deceiving.

name: Three Little Devils
description: Climbs three prominent columns right of a major groove. Sustained. Do whatever you can, crimp, pull, and slap any divot you can find, but in the end you're stuck with 3 little devils all the way to the top anchors!

name: To Hell with Lewiston
description: Start to the left of the tree and detached column. Head up the space left by a missing column starting with pro in the narrowing crack behind the detached column on the right, then shift to small wires and cams in the left crack. Stem and step up to the undercling then move left. stoppers and cams up to 1". Doubles up to .25" are nice. Anchors with rings at the top.

name: UI Route
description: Originally climbed cracks on both sides of the prominent column to the right of top anchors. This column is quite solid under body weight, but it rotates slightly with a crowbar and could fail in a hard fall on a cam. To avoid having a hell of a bad day, put your gear into the next obvious crack located 2 columns to the right of this prominent column and diagonal left at the top to reach top to anchors.

name: Arya's Ledge
description: This route follows the crack just to the left of ShitBalls that ends on a big ledge about halfway up. Climb the arete above the ledge for the last ~20 ft of the climb.

name: Ascend the Throne
description: Pretty easy problem up to a nice seat. Small feet and wide hands transition to slopey ledges. Quick problem if you can dyno to the ledges!

name: The Chimaney
description: Pretty easy climb up a chimney that slenders as you go up. Good jugs most of the way, and you can always just stem your legs in a pinch. The routes name is purposely pronounced "chim-uh-knee" like the weird way that some people pronounce that word. This is important.

name: Culture Revolution
description: Not much of a crack on this route, so be prepared to use those fingertips! The crux is about 2/3 up where either side becomes very blank and the crack only barely fits your fingers.

name: Dr. Gonzo
description: Short, easy route. Crux is close to the bottom, about 10 feet up where the rock gets a little rotten.

name: Hookerbot3000
description: Pretty hard route that works its way up a tiny crack that widens out to hand jams at the top. It is pretty pumpy, I will occasionally jump over to ShitBalls on the left halfway up the route for a proper rest.

name: Left Labia
description: Fun climb that tends to contort the climber in strange positions as a semi-chimney to the right allows for some stemming, but precariously.

name: Overthrow the Crown
description: Climb an easy wide crack with good jugs up to The Throne.

name: Pussy Crack
description: This is the first route we started with at Kittle Rocks. This route is easy and fun as heck if you are good at crack climbing. It cruxes about 10 feet down from the top at a spot we affectionately refer to as "The Clit." The bolts at the top can be accessed by walking around the cliff to the right.

name: Right Labia
description: Climb a crack to about 10 ft up, then work your way up the arete to the left of Pussy Crack. Gets kinda tough towards the top and occasionally you may have to pop a leg over into The Chimaney to have a proper rest.

name: ShitBalls
description: This is a super fun route. The crack turns from finger jams at the bottom, to a full on chimney at the top that feels like it is chewing on you and spitting you out simultaneously. About 1/3 of the way up is a nice little ledge to rest on that we call "Asscheek Ledge," as it is just barely big enough to sit on.

name: Stza Crack
description: Very short route that goes up a crack but has some nice jugs on either side on the way up.

name: The Usurper
description: Climb the crack just next to the throne to tower over and become THE USURPER.

name: Crackle
description: Start on the lowest chalked holds. Work your way up the crack to the top out. Name and grade are made up. Let me know if you have more information.

name: Drill Sargent
description: Start low with a good right hand side pull and left hand ledge with your feet far out right making you horizontal. Make a big move to a bad sloper then another powerful move to the manufactured pocket with your right. I topped out to the left on the slab. A more direct finish could be possible with a decent amount of cleaning. The name I made up because “unknown” is boring. Grade is based solely on my opinion. If anyone has more information Let me know and I will make changes accordingly.

name: Mother of All Battles
description: An intimidating route up the center of the obvious scooped feature. After the route was bolted it sat collecting dust for many years. The routes developer reports a successful top-rope ascent but he was not able to get the redpoint. The first known redpoint happened in 10/2017.     The route is characterized by powerful moves in steep terrain.

name: Survey Says
description: A tricky start and finish with moderate dihedral climbing between.

name: Chicken Little
description: Great beginner lead or toprope.

name: Do You Feel Lucky?
description: Enjoyably easy moves lead to powerful moves over the roof.

name: The Fiction of Friction
description: Surprisingly awkward yet fun moves lead thru the groove in the large roof.

name: Locomotion
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: Rail Yard Blues
description: Clean crack that traverses right up the wall to the chains.  Some really good hand jams.

name: Poop on Toast
description: Surprisingly challenging yet fun moves lead to a bouldery headwall mid route. The route was put up in February out of frustration with the lack of snow and ice in the mountains.

name: Pumped Stumps
description: Fun vertical wall near an arete with some tough/balancy moves down low before the climbing eases up near the chains.

name: Who Stole the Holds Off of the World's Hardest 5.2?
description: Physical yet thought provoking moves leads to fun rambly climbing in a great position.

name: Chicken McNubbins
description: Starts off with a fun ceiling in the bottom that is juggy vertical fun, then it's nothing but dirty friction nubbins for the rest of the route.  This route can be TR if you don't feel comfortable on the slab.

name: Give a dog a mint
description: If you enjoy slab with minimal holds thru the crux (3rd-4th bolt area) this one's for you! Mostly a fun warm/dry climb in the off season. Easy to TR a direct line (5.10+); and provides a good anchor for the gear route Drag Queen (5.8).

name: Lichen Fools
description: A great climb up inside corner to the steeper right side headwall. It's hard to leave the bucket holds in the corner for the crimps and knobs on the right wall, but the fun bouldery moves thru the crux make many of us want it to continue for longer!

name: Mono Blanco
description: A dynamic throw leads to a thought provoking slab.  Route was re-cleaned in 2011 and 2012.

name: Santa's Stairmaster
description: The pleasant sweeping arête to headwall climb is bolted friendly for easy lead purposes to get to the top of the wall. Great positions and fun moves. It's easy to make the crux up high harder than necessary.

name: Jugs to Jugs
description: The crux is between the 1st and 2nd bolt. Reachy moves and may be more difficult for the shorter climber. Positive holds if you can reach them. A top rope can be set up by walking to the top of the climb. Lots of lichen near the anchor that will clean up with more climbs.

name: Sensitive Destruction
description: Climb up to the arete and once you reach it, use it along with delicate holds to reach the anchors. Thin feet once you reach the middle of the route.  The guidebook created by J. Luthy has this route as a mixed line with 3 bolts and gear. When I climbed this in June 2020 I counted 7 bolts to an anchor. If this is incorrect please let me know and I will correct this description.

name: Shark Bait
description: Most likely the longest Trad route at Laclede. Boulder the thin crack left of a menacing looking off-width to a small ledge at the top of the off-width.  Placing your first piece could be tricky (first crux).  Then, continue up steep terrain stemming and jamming your way to easier ground and leads to a square overhang(2nd crux, 9+/10a).  Climb left of the overhang making some interesting stemming moves.  A few more feet brings you to a small tree and a crack.  Sling the tree and plug a #1 or 2 BD and belay your partner up.  You may be able to set up a Top-rope.  I recommend extending your runners as far past the tuft at the top as possible to keep from bring dirt down on your head.  The more it gets climbed the better and cleaner it will get.  Walk off the top in either direction.

name: My First Boul
description: Start on the two juggy hands, with a fantastic foot out far left. Move right, make a big move up to a flake-ish jug, and top out. Good to warm up before working the harder problems in the area.    I'd never seen or heard of this problem before, I just saw it while going out to standoff. Feedback is appreciated for grade/name/any info.

name: Short Warmup
description: Just a short problem I found after clearing out some vegetation. Start with both hands split. Move the left hand to match the right. And then go up with the right to a good single pad hold. Then the left can go to a good hold above that. After that it’s just pulling yourself over the top and finding holds that feel comfortable up top.  Be careful as you step up top, I almost slipped and slid off the top.

name: Standoff
description: Left hand starts down low on a pinch, the right starts on a triangular looking pinch a bit higher. The route moves up and to the left, never moving far off the ground as it follows the hill up the side of the boulder. EDIT: After figuring out a better beta for this route, I'd say it's toss up between a V5 and V6. Definitely more powerful and reachy than technical

name: 5.4 crack
description: gear to 3 inches, great beginner lead.  Crux is about half way up and favors taller people.  Use the boulders on the top of the crag to belay off, not recommended to top rope this route due to excessive rope drag.

name: Exclusion
description: Climb the dividing slab just to the left of the major crack system.  To keep the grade, use only the tiny edges and crystals, while avoiding the cracks.

name: Unknown Crack
description: Follow the crack to the left of Lil' Feller, about 25 feet up, veer left into another crack and head for the small tree.

name: A Climb Named Sue
description: An overbolted 5.8 route that is a good route for new leaders. The crux is at about the 5th bolt and lasts about 3 moves over slabby terrain. A good first lead route.

name: Alpha one
description: This route climbs the dihedral to the right of Courtney love. Start on the flake and lieback, fist jam, and grab big jugs to surmount the two small overhangs onto dirty ledges and finally the large ledge on top.

name: Blowout
description: This is a good instruction route for teaching multipitch techniques to new climbers. a belay station is setup about 2/3rds the way up this route at a good stance. If you plan on doing this in one pitch make sure to bring long runners in order to reduce rope drag as this route wanders first left then right.

name: Courtney Love
description: The crux is at the 3rd bolt.  A little balancy getting through this area.  Runout at the top to the anchor (@20ft).

name: Fredrick
description: Start in the right facing flakes (crux) behind the big tree and lieback until you reach the single bolt. Easy face climbing and navigating around moss leads to chain anchors.

name: Inspiration Day
description: The crux is definitely down low moving over the first 3 bolts. Thin and technical face moves off of lots of side pulls to easier climbing up high.

name: Disco
description: This climb is a bit contrived and moves through some easy bulges down low then to some slabby moves up higher. The rock is good but the grading in the "Climber's Guide to North Idaho..." is way soft. He rates it at 5.9+. I would say it's around a 5.8 to 5.8+ at the most. Moves are all straight forward.

name: Distractions
description: This is the obvious roof/flake on the most right section of the block. Rarely climbed, and often done on top rope. The route has been lead on gear.

name: Rock Whoopie
description: The left bolted route on the Block. Crux is near the top. The top of the climb is a bit contrived as the last bolt is way to the left of the second to last bolt then the anchors were back to the right. It's a good thing the route is so short or there could be serious drag issues with this route. The second to last bolt also had a very loose hanger on it. The bolt may need to be tightened down. Just something to beware of if you plan on leading the route.

name: Ankle Breaker
