description: The top has a commuting move to a slick horn that Josiah Fundaburg didn’t stick and fell off and broke his ankle

name: El Luchador
description: Scary fall, super fun climb. Potentially contrived but once you see the line it makes sense.

name: Death Blocks
description: A very fun boulder problem brings you to your first opportunity for gear about 30 feet up. Enjoy thrilling sequences on good holds through very steep terrain for the grade. The cost of entry is the loose nature of the blocks that give the route its name. Many of the blocks are big and only temporarily attached to the face. Protection is marginal and hard to get. The kind of route that you do once, and never again!

name: Death Fall
description: A really fun balancy route, probably the best on this wall.  This route starts atthe ramp with all the hash marks on it. Walk up the ramp to clip the second bolt of Death Fall Direct (OUT ON YOUR LEFT).

name: Death Fall Far Left (Unknown)
description: This is a very fun route on the far left side of Death Fall Wall. The crux is moving through the first two bolts (glue ins).  Please comment if you have info on this route, as I have none.

name: Dolly Parton
description: Crux is low after the first bolt getting above the overhang

name: Fatboy
description: Begin on the prominent horizontal rails on the beautiful smooth rock just left of Death Fall. Make a few large (though still possibly static) moves down low, following the lighter rock up and slightly left to the most prominent roof. Two options here: the first breaks left around the roof, then cuts back right traversing just above the roof and up to the chains. The second pulls the roof - more difficult.

name: Jude 24
description: The difficult part of this climb is the bouldery moves down low over a roof. The climbing eases off a bit after that but becomes run out to the bolts. Clipping the 3rd bolt could be pretty scary if you aren't in a good stance as there may be groundfall potential.    Per Scott's comments I've edited the route description to no longer reflect the R rating that this climb used to carry as it has been retrobolted to be a safer lead. Thanks Scott.

name: Lil Dabby
description: Star Destroyer shaped boulder below the main wall. Powerful slapping moves on the left and jugs and ledges on the right. It long but falls aren't bad (you'll see when you get there)

name: Moms Spaghetti
description: Jugs to big gaston crux and hard move to a pinch. Common spot for spider webs.

name: Free Mahi Mahi
description: Stand start. A big first move gets you to the first of many jugs. The crack is available, but not likely to be used? Climbs straight up to a mantle on the ledge. The blocky rock left of the crack/seam and near the top may be loose and was not used on the fa. Climb carefully.

name: JP!
description: Start low on chalked holds and move up to the sloper. Top out straight up while avoiding the choss to your right.

name: That’s Not Punk Rock
description: Up a left trending rail, and then straight up and over the ledge.

name: “Are you topping out?”
description: Start matched on the obvious horizontal chalked edge. Work your way up to a small right side-pulling crimp. Make the crux move to a slot in the triangle feature. Finishes straight up.

name: Beached Whale
description: Starts with right hand in pocket and left on crimpy ledge with the obvious feet. Move left and up the crimpy rail till you reach good hands. Reachy top out with small holds and no feet will let the route name speak for itself.

name: Excalibur
description: Starts with right hand in pocket with the left on a side pull. Move left using low side pulls and feet in crack. Set up for the crux by stepping up with the right foot while holding the “hilt” of the crack, then,dyno or reach depending on height to a final top out jug. Walk off to the left and find a trail back around to the base of the boulder.

name: U-Turn
description: Starts at the far right side of the boulder, hands matching on sloper jug with your feet in the lowest part of the crack. Move left using the crack for your feet and the small crimps, match and set up for a long reach for a hidden hold(Crux). From here move right to top out using the overhanging rocks. Walk off to the right back to main trail.

name: Between Good and Evil
description: From guidebook. Difficult bulge at start (stick clip) with small steep jugs above.  It helps to take a small selection of smaller cams and nuts for the upper section.  Originally it was rated 5.9.

name: Eat Your Roofage AKA Sandra Bullock
description: This is a fun route with two roofs. All the hard moves are well protected. The crux is at the the first roof, and the left variation is easier. If you go straight over the roof it probably is 10c, otherwise about 10a, in my opinion. The smaller roof before the chains is a bit cruxy, but easier. This is one of the best routes on the wall.

name: The Jagged Edge
description: A superb line: tricky, technical and tenuous. Well equipped

name: The Last of the Summer Wine
description: Nice dry line, gets some winter sun. A great route for a new leader or first time climber.

name: Organic  1
description: I thought these 4 trad routes were great and there's never a line. Just right of Tossed Salad, climb into the short corner and pull the intimidating but easy roof onto the face.

name: Organic  2
description: I thought these 4 trad routes were great and there's never a line. Right Tossed Salad, climb into the 2nd short corner and pull the intimidating but easy roof onto the face.

name: Organic  3
description: I thought these 4 trad routes were great and there's never a line. Right of Tossed Salad, split the face between the right and left facing corners and pull directly through the roof.  This is by far the hardest of the 4 trad routes.  The holds above the roof are not as good as you hope.

name: Organic  4
description: I thought these 4 trad routes were great and there's never a line. Just left of Sherman, climb into the left facing corner and step right onto the face.

name: Peabody
description: The 2 distinct cruxes on this route are great. The lower move through the first roof is classic. A pumpy little move through the upper roof founds out the troubles.

name: Sherman
description: Tricky moves down low lead to fun climbing higher up and through a large ledge. Traverse left at the top of the climb to gain the chain anchors.

name: Spinich Free Flinty
description: Two distinct cruxes characterize this climb. The bottom crux moving through the first roof is the easier of the 2. Steep blocks near the top round out the climb.

name: Tossed Salad
description: An easy first lead, jugs and rails everywhere.

name: Tulip
description: Easy route to setup for top rope.  Per the local guide - thin crack on the far left.  Good pro. A little tricky to place.   Left - keep left of the thin crack proing the crack   Right - take the steep face right of the crack proing in the horizontal slots    The local climbers guide says this is 5.9 and perhaps on trad it rates that way,but on top rope it feels more like a 5.7.

name: Chimney
description: This line is one of my favorite moderates at Q'emiln Park.  Plus this climb is always in the shade and a great place to go on a hot afternoon.  The rock is a bit more smooth and polished than other areas in the park but the climbing is super fun.

name: Chimney Sweep
description: This climb starts deep inside the chimney.  It is always cool in here!  The rock is a bit more polished than other areas of the park.  It gets a little tight as you go up!  Shares anchors with "Chimney" route.

name: The Words of the Prophet
description: Currently (May of 2013) this is the only bolted line on the face to the right of the chimney/cave area.  The crux is down low pulling through the 2nd bolt on thin and sharp crimps.  The route is supposedly listed as an 11a, but that is really on the soft side.

name: A Little Bit Country Music
description: Do we really need drilled holes in the rock to tell us where we can find a trad route? WTF?     This fun route starts in the overhanging crack. Take the obvious route from here, The climbing is very chill, easier than it looks, and quite good.

name: Betty Cragger
description: Fairly clear cut route with only a couple tough moves consistent with the rating.  Good warm up (actually the only one) for the surrounding climbs.

name: Blunderbuss
description: Check this route out! This is my favorite climb at Post Falls. I won't give any beta on the low crux, but it's fun to figure out. Tricky moves over a bulge to the second clip. After the steep section, you move into a nice dihedral that will have you stemming in a very cool, exposed position.

name: Bugaboo aka Rusty Trombone
description: Use the overhanging corner start for Pack in Pack out.  Continue up left over easy terrain to the thin crack in the yellow headwall. Bust over the bulge to the chains.

name: Cacophony
description: From The Northwest Passage Guide Book:    Starts on the lowest part of the buttress, just right of Country music trademark. Nice little dyne, some balance and a steep right traverse up high to avoid the chop blocks.    (Thanks to Rusty Baillie, Maxine Whiteside, Andrea, The Gifts and Marty Bland for these route descriptions and beta photos.)

name: Coup De Poing
description: A groovy-robby line right of a big roof.    (Thanks to Rusty Baillie, Maxine Whiteside, Andrea, The Gifts and Marty Bland for these route descriptions and beta photos.)

name: Hang It Out
description: From The Northwest Passage Guide Book:   The object is to get into the dramatic, hanging, left-facing dihedral-by traversing in under the roof from the right. Climb the bolts of Pack It Out to the resting ledge where the roof starts. Start good natural pro from here. Traverse L fairly sensationally and swing into the dihedral. Fun for a while then a crux bulge to a  shallow groove (tricky but OK pro).    (Thanks to Rusty Baillie, Maxine Whiteside, Andrea, The Gifts and Marty Bland for these route descriptions and beta photos.)

name: Harquebus
description: Harquebus starts in a steep corner and will have you thinking right off the bat. You'll move onto the arete and find another crux in a corner just below the top. Moving to the last bolt is very spooky because you're moving over a bulge on slopers with your forearms flamed. Be aware that if you blow the last clip the fall has some nasty potential, but two climbers I know have whipped from here and threaded the needle and taken a clean fall right into the corner.

name: Little Bit Rock & Roll
description: From The Northwest Passage Guide Book:    The one starts to the Right, where the cliff begins to be capped by a large roof. Steep bulges and a lot of traversing around roofs. This is a real rope drag management challenge. long draws help and double ropes work great. The route is best cleaning by following it. There is now a halfway belay at the end of the traverse.    (Thanks to Rusty Baillie, Maxine Whiteside, Andrea, The Gifts and Marty Bland for these route descriptions and beta photos.)

name: No Pryor Experience
description: Follow the bolts through cool edges and a hard finish. Bolts to chains.

name: Northwest Passage
description: A steep start with the crux low down leads to very fun climbing in a dihedral. It feels more like 10c if you miss the hidden hold around the 2nd bolt. Well protected, safe lead.

name: Out of Juice.
description: The crux 10 ft. off the ground. take care at the first bolt as it's a pretty tricky clip. This climb is rated 10d in Marty's quide. A tricky traverse across a thin slab followed by some very reachy moves.

name: Pack It out
description: From The Northwest Passage Guide Book:    Belay from a single bolt next to a large flake. Go down a bit then move up right to the broken ledge. Angle back left along sharpe ledges to a smooth wall. Up to the small roof. Reach into the hand jam slot then back to the edge and onto a resting ledge. Move out left onto the upper face and up to LO chains.    (Thanks to Rusty Baillie, Maxine Whiteside, Andrea, The Gifts and Marty Bland for these route descriptions and beta photos.)

name: Schizo
description: Easy start with more technical climbing as you continue.  The 5th bolt can be a bit tricky coming off a slab section.  The finish is a bit thin until you get to the anchors.

name: Snaphaunce
description: Very good route. This should have more stars in Marty's guidebook, as it's better than Rocky, which gets 4 stars.

name: Caveman
description: A very good first lead for a strong top roper. Also a fun warm up, the crux is pretty much the first 2 moves, the rest of it is a cake walk.

name: Cavity Nester
description: Climbs directl up the face to the tip of a left pointing roof

name: The Dance
description: A delicately thin slab requiring precision footwork and proper breath holding technique.

name: Darcy's Law aka Rock of Ages
description: This is the crack that coincides with the start of The Great Controversy. The initial starting position for the 2 routes is the same. Start in under the alcove as for The Great Controversy but follow the overhanging hand crack that widens gradually to #5 and #6 BD size through a short horizontal roof section. Once the horizontal section is surmounted, easier climbing leads to the top.

name: Distractions
description: Just to the right of Rock Whoopi (5.7) lots of big features. This route is also a fun top rope. The anchors can be reached easily by going up the trail to the right of the route.

name: Folk Dance
description: Rap from the Tree Route staples and hang Top Rope Draws on the chains that are just above the tree stump, about 30 feet down from the top.  Pleasant face climbing underneath the tree keeping left of the edge of the Tree Crack Route

name: Freely Given
description: The grantite on this route is beautiful, the sequence is fun and it is well protected. This is definitely one of my favorite warm up routes on the Ledge Wall. Don't miss this climb! (This would also make a good first lead for a competant climber, all of the holds to clip off of are bomber.)

name: The Great Controversy
description: This is a pumpy endeavor after the first bolt. It starts in the crack system below, but the crux is pulling your butt over the obvious roof. =) This involves a sweet heelhook and a series of crimps once over the top.    One note: If you are attempting to toprope this route, be careful of your rope snagging on the third bolt as you pull over the roof!

name: McJugs
description: This climb starts at the base of the arete for Great Controversy.  Climb up and left following the sloping ramp.  Climbing isn't too hard but it does feel a little awkward.  Mantle the famous ledge and then thin climbing leads to anchors.

name: McMantle
description: The Climber's Guide to North Idaho gives this climb an 5.11a rating which is very soft in my opinion.  This route is just left of McJugs.  It actually meets up with McJugs after at the 3rd bolt.  Climb up the thin face to the namesake ledge.  Mantle over ledge and up thin face to anchors above.

name: Open Book Direct
description: Climb up the obvious right-facing corner in the center of the cliff through some blocky overhangs.    Pretty cool moves and decent protection.  Short.

name: Rock Whoopi
description: This route is on the rock to the far left of the lower ledge. I believe it is the only bolted route on this particular rock.   The crux is definitely at the top.     5 bolts to HA.

name: Shark's Tooth
description: Climb straight up the face and traverse left (the crus) to a "shark tooth" like feature

name: Tree Crack
description: Climb the blocky ramp to the left of the obvious crack, using said crack for pro.  At the roof/ledge, either go straight up (5.7) through a shallow left-facing dihedral, OR go left along the ledge and then back right along the huge ramp to the top.

name: Wilma
description: Left of Caveman. 7Bs to HA

name: Arete
description: Middle of the wall.  Very large crack with lots of blocky holds.  Easy first lead very well protected.  Some of the bolts are deep in the crack.

name: Barrier Reef
description: The crux on this route is moving over the third bolt. It's a fun reachy route that has a little of everything.

name: Crocodile Dundee
description: This is a fun but really easy route that climbs up through some unique rock.

name: Didgerdoo
description: Begin by going over a blocky low-angle section to a ledge (a block). Continue straight up the face through horizontal cracks (plenty of cam placements). At the top, the wall steepens, with the crux being the last move before the chains.

name: Footprint
description: Far left of Outback wall. Shares the first few bolts with Walkabout.  When you reach the slab instead of turning to the right and going up the slab to the chains at Walkabout - continue directly up over a small roof to the chains.

name: Kangaroo
description: Route goes up and left and then up again. 3rd route from the left of the Outback Wall.  Very well bolted easy lead.  Lots of rope drag.  It would be wise to extend the draws on the right side where it starts with full length slings to reduce drag.  Once you climb to what appears to be the top - you have about 20' more to go on dirty slab to reach the chains.

name: Mad Max Crax
description: Just right of crack  Quite easy if you jam in the crack.  More challenging if you layback up the outside flakes.

name: Stingray Steve
description: Between Mad Max and Crocodile Dundee.  5-6 bolts to chains.  Interesting face climbing to bulge.  Hidden jug makes bulge easy to navigate once you find it.

name: Tri-amine Crack
description: This crack is located directly below a small pine tree toward the left end of the outcrop.  It is immediately right of a corner which leads to a gently sloped ramp adjacent to a right facing dihedral.  The crack starts slightly left leaning and about mid-way the crack is slightly right leaning.  The face climbing to the side of the crack is easy.  There is still some moss--I cleaned it as I went the first time.  At the top sling the tree for protection and continue up the ramp to bolts and chains--this part needs more parties and some easy cleaning.  This is a nice moderate climb for someone new to placing gear who wants some practice.  The route name is meant to be a word play on terms an organic chemist will appreciate and find fun.

name: Walkabout
description: Farthest left route on the Outback Wall.  Good climbing at 5.6 grade and then once you get to about  the 3 bolt. Slab up to the chains with very easy climbing.  Lots of rope drag

name: Wall O.B.
description: Look for a small roof and right-facing corner. Climb through this on the right. The climbing through the roof is juggy and straight forward.

name: White Whale
description: The crux is down low moving over the first bolt. Please note that clipping the first bolt can be a little scary if you're not confident at the grade. The next 3 bolts the climbing stays nice and consistent and this is the only reason I'd say it deserves the 10a rating.

name: Expanding Doubt
description: An awesome bouldery climb that eases after the 6th bolt. it's steeper than it looks from the ground and can be a little devious. Really fun!

name: Greybeard
description: Great route that needs some traffic! Fun route finding and movement leads to a bulge where the climbing becomes a little cryptic! Get on it!

name: Just A Tease
description: Don't leave until you've climbed this route! Sustained and steep; this climb has it all.

name: K27
description: Great movement on jugs, crimps and a few slopers. Sustained and long route makes this a great addition to Q'emiln

name: Lahaina Noon
description: Good holds every 5 feet, not much in between. Big moves for big fun! Don’t miss the sweet spot.  The sit start and then moving off the sharp intermediate before the first good rail probably goes closer to v3/4, but a jump start makes it more like v2.

name: Leonard the Dragon
description: Follows the arete of the prominent part of the dihedral,  to the jug rail that traverses right to the center of the boulder and tops out there. Big holds all the way.

name: She’s a Keeper
description: Rails and an obvious jug make it easy to move up the face of this boulder. Getting to the lip and the subsequent mantle is the crux, Though a pretty straightforward one.

name: Variety Pack
description: Better, and more challenging, than it looks from the ground.

name: Wallflower
description: Once very ran out , it has now been retro bolted with bomber glue-ins. A fun climb that requires some thought and endurance.

name: [Redacted]
description: Follow two bolts to to some nice jugs under the roof, allowing to clip the third bolt prior to pulling over the roof.  Continue over easier ground to the anchor.

name: Big River
description: A fun climb on good rock. Starts just left of Frostbite.  Climb up steep face passed 4 bolts, then traverse left onto face around upper roof.

name: Big River Direct
description: Starts just left of Frostbite. Climb up a steep face passing 4 bolts, then instead of traversing left onto face around upper roof, head directly for the roof passing a single glue-in bolt. Once at the roof, clip the last bolt protecting the crux (Clipping it might be a bit tricky for shorter folks). The crux involves big moves on small crimps.

name: Billy Goat
description: A good practice lead route for beginners or a nice warmup route for harder climbs on Post Wall. This route climbs up through in-cuts and past a small bulge near the top which is easily surmounted via jugs.

name: Cadence
description: Bolted route on the far right side of Post Wall.

name: End Piece Goes to Night Flight
description: A route which is better avoided:  Clip an oddly placed bolt in a large chalkstone/flake feature. Then climb up and over crappy rock to a moss covered slab. Now tread lightly near the bulge beneath the anchor, there is loose rock here.

name: Frostbite
description: A good, juggy climb with a tough roof finish. you can also turn the roof to the right and take a couple letters off the grade.

name: Janet Jackson
description: A one move wonder route. Climb up past 2 bolts to the roof.  Pull over the roof and up the face beyond to the top.  Doesn't get climbed enough so the upper face has quite a bit of lichen on it, although it is really easy climbing up there.  The roof isn't nearly as hard as it looks especially if you throw in a good heel hook.

name: Lion of the North
description: This is a fun route with a crux down low. The crux is moving over the second bolt. Scoot out to the right and is a few liebacks to surmount most of the troubles. There is a small runout from the 4th to the 5th bolt on this route. The ground is pretty easy going though.

name: Quit Your Whining
description: This climb starts in the crack just right of Lion of the north. Climb up the crack for 1 bolt and then traverse out right onto the face. Now just up the edges to the anchors, pulling over small bulge near the top.  Note: there is a direct start to this route as well. Start in the face directly under the route and clip 1 bolt then it joins the regular route. This variation is more around 5.10b.

name: Quit Your Whining Direct
description: Just to the right of Quit Your Whining. The crux is right off the ground past the first two bolts. The difficulty really depends on how short or tall you are. Guidebook suggests 11a. In reality, the difficulty is short with one or two moves on small crimps and then eases up to 5.9.

name: Rolling Thunder
description: This route has a great start then kind of peters out in the end. The crux is over after the 2nd bolt is clipped and the holds get much bigger from then on. A fun varied route.

name: Step It Up
description: fun route right of Billy Goat

name: War
description: Crux is two moves off the ground to a small roof pullover.  Nice jugs to start then tapers off to crimps.

name: Whitewater
description: This is a great route that requires quick thinking and quick movement. The crux is in the transition from jugs to the face climbing near the second bolt. Clipping the second bolt can be pretty sketchy as there aren't many positive holds to clip from. You can avoid a sketchy first clip by starting on the left to clip then down climb and start the route from below the first bolt.

name: The Young and the Pampered
description: Jugs at the bottom lead to a grainy slab at the top.

name: Bullwinkle
description: This is a great route. The lower section is all overhung and may be a bit dicey clipping the second bolt. After that you are safe the entire way. The crux is moving over the second bolt. Bring a long runner for the 3rd bolt or unclip the 3rd bolt after you cliup the 4th in order to avoid drag.

name: Duddly Do Right
description: A great moderate route that climbs up through flakes and a devious middle section that can give some climbers fits.

name: Fearless Leader
description: Very well protected, crimpy route. Crux is about halfway up. A straightforward, fun route.

name: Garden Weeder
description: The direct start goes straight up and is about 2 moves of stiff 12a after hitting the chalked up sidepull, but you can use the start of Duddly    Do Right as an alternative. After this the route squeezes in thru lower blocks and comes to a crimpy crux halfway up.

name: Paleface
description: This route has been bolted/chopped/ then rebolted. Originally a Trad route it is now a sport route. The crux is near the top moving from the last bolt to the chains. The second to the last bolt is way out to the right of the route. Clip this bolt then traverse back left to stay in the grade.

name: Rocky
description: The lower section of this route follows an obvious weekness up and left through a flaring crack. Lieback the lower section to a rail with huge jugs. Clip the 3rd bolt and then move straight up through the bulge to easier climbing above. Clipping the 4th bolt is tricky as only slopers are there for the clip.

name: Trailer Park
description: A crimpy and thought provoking jaunt up the wall left of Paleface.  Bolted now but chopped before? Maybe it's here to stay.

name: Hot Salsa
description: A short and bouldery finish to the route 'Salsa'

name: Ring of Fire
description: Make your way up to the obvious roof that is split by a crack. Pull the roof directly or move out left for some good feet. Find a few good ring locks and mantle up and left to a bolted anchor (Possible to skip the belay and link the two pitches). Plug a few more small cams until you run into some glue-in bolts. Follow the bolts past a very cool series of big moves on jugs.

name: Salsa
description: A fun and sometimes awkward climb that you will want to pitch out due to rope drag.   First pitch - Find two bolts close to the base, once you've clipped the second bolt you will run into a horizontal crack (pro) and then two more bolts before reaching a finger crack. Follow the finger crack until it deposits you on a large ledge - head right and belay around the corner.   Second pitch - you have two options for this short section. keeping the grade low, follow the slab up to a crumbly looking crack (it's actually more solid than it looks). Following the crack right, under the roof, pick your way up the path of least resistance.

name: Spice of Life
description: Make your way up into the awesome splitter finger crack. Mantle up on a large ledge and head left into a hand/fist crack for ~15 feet until it deposits you on another ledge. Belay here if you are doing it in two pitches, otherwise make your way up to the obvious roof/flake and jam and layback your way to the top!

name: 7) Identity Crisis
description: Sustained through steep hidden jugs with an technical balancey start.

name: Alice in Jugland
description: The leftmost route.  Lots of barndooring.The overhang is most sport direct, but a rest and a cheat is possible out left. Endless jugs on steep rock. Like Hueco Tanks. Belay on top or use anchors as a directional to lower off on Looking Glass

name: Black Diamond
description: Begin in the large corner via LSH and climb the crack to a good shelf just over the buldge. Move left at the shelf and continue up bolts to the top. Moving (and clipping) through the first 2 bolts is the crux. Very thin and very steep.

name: Bonzai
description: Sharp crack to roof, traverse left under roof then exit up past the pine. Short route. This was rated 10a in the Northwest Passage guidebook but it felt more like 5.8 being able to get into fairly easy positions to place gear...maybe I was tall enough to be able to do so. Good moves in the beginning crack and pulling up past the small pine.

name: Dyno Boy
description: Pulling the first roof is the crux. You get two holds that are just good enough to get you over the lip to a crimpy rail. Now you face a long move with no good feet to establish yourself on the vertical face. Fun and juggy over the second roof, you'll work up a good pump to the chains!

name: F.S.R.
description: This route moves through steep thin face moves down low. Then goes to low angle slab through the middle and finally tops out through a beefy bulge that requires some serious power. Great varied climb.You may want to put a longer runner on some of the lower bolts to avoid rope drag near the stout finish.

name: Free Taters For Out Of Staters
description: A great route! The start is steep and the first bolt is high. Unless you're very solid at the grade, I'd recommend bouldering up Lost Arrow to clip the first bolt, then lower down to start.     This is not a great TR route. I've got one friend with scars on his back from a TR fall at the crux.   The tree lurks just behind you, but is not a problem on lead.    A strenuous and steep start on good holds leads into sidepulls, slopers, and small crimps till you hit the next jug above the last bolt. The crux is at the fourth bolt. It's stout and not obvious.

name: In Reverse
description: A fun little route that is a bit of a one move wonder. The crux is down low moving over a bulge. The top gets a little tricky your first time up (hint stay left of the bolt).

name: Layback
description: A couple easy face moves past a standard bolt lead you up into a crack/flake/arete and a line of glue in bolts.   From here you can layback, jam, offwidth, face climb, or whatever suites you.  Lot's of sweet kneebars to be had.    I dont know who bolted this or FA but all the routes on this wall are well worth doing.  This wall has the best cluster of moderate routes at Post Falls and should get more traffic.  Don't miss them!

name: Lost Arrow Spur
description: Described as a right of passage for local area climbers by some guide books. This is an excellent climb through mixed terrain. A little slab work combined with overhanging bulges make this route excellent. It is very well protected (actually a little over bolted) so is a good moderate lead. The crux is moving through some thin face moves after the first bulge is surmounted.

name: LSH
description: This is a great beginner route that has some really fun lieback moves throughout the climb. Start in the large corner and climb the crack to the top.

name: Mangled up in blue
description: A balancy climb that keeps you guessing. If it feels too hard look for better feet. The crux is about halfway up as you reach the arete. It looks like it's going to be hard. but go for it! the hold will be there.

name: The Mangler
description: A blocky climb that feels like it's just about to get hard, bet never does. Feels awkward and balancy, but has great hidden holds every time you need one.

name: One for Sisiphus
description: Steep jugs and slopers. Sunny.

name: Peter Beater
description: A fun but short pumpy route leading out of a large west facing corner. A start going to the left of the bolts is much easier than going over the top of bolts themselves and may lower the grade a little. Bolts are well placed and the climbing is pretty straightforward. Grade seems a little soft.

name: Safeway Supply
description: Not much of a description in the local climbing guide. Hangars for belay are well below the top.

name: Sidewinder
description: Start right of the belay block. Once over the crimpy crux roof the jugs get bigger though the angle  does not relent.

name: Spur of the Moment
description: This route trends right along a flake. Lieback the flake and pull past the reachy crux move to surmount the flake. Make sure to place a long runner on the 5th bolt to reduce rope drag. Once past that bolt immediately trend back to the left. Don't clip the 2 bolts to your right as you will be on FSR instead and will be wondering why the 10b you signed up for feels like 11 right before the anchors. Surmount the reachy roof move to gain the anchors.

name: Through the Looking Glass
description: The middle overhang can be lightened by a small detour via hidden holds to the left.

name: Baby Beef
description: Start right, reach over and clip bolt.  Head left, or, stay on the arete, clip second bolt then step left and up (cams in cracks), or, follow arete (no pro for awhile: take care!) then pass cam eatin' horizontals to summit anchor.

name: Chit Happens
description: Scramble up lump of rock at base.  Eyeball the first bolt, and decide if you need pro to get to it and, if so, place a small cam up and to the left (long sling to reduce rope drag).  Climb up to bolt, then continue by milking weaknesses and horizontal cracks for pro to the top.

name: 10b or Not 10b
description: From the anchors of Castles Made of Sand, move right and follow the bolt line straight up the long slab to a final headwall with a stout move.  An excellent link up is to climb Crimson Arete (5.10a) and pull over the lip to the stance above the anchors then continue up to Castles Made of Sand anchors clipping a bolt along the way.  It's possible to link Crimson Arete and 10b or Not 10b into a single long pitch.

name: Castles Made of Sand
description: This route is just left of Crimson Arete and at it's crux, it's easier to cheat over to holds on Crimson Arete and then veer back.  The intended crux is on sharp crimps making long reaches.  Some fun moves on the rest of the route.

name: Crimson Arete
description: A short, enjoyable route with great arete moves and one hard move about 2/3rds up.  May be harder,(10b?) for shorter climbers.  This route faces SE and gets late afternoon shade.

name: Deadwood
description: This somewhat uninspiring looking line has continuously challenging and interesting moves. The crux for most people is likely to be the final bulge move before the anchors.  A small roof/bulge move 1/3rd up may be the crux for others.  The rock is a little gritty at the start of the route but is good the rest of the way.  Deadwood had a large variety of fun moves.  The climbing reminds me somewhat of some of the routes at Lover's Leap (CA).

name: Down and Out
description: This is the visor roof crack that sticks out on the East face of Castle Rock.  It is easiest to approach via the walk off above the Crack House.  Be careful if you choose to scramble to the belay just below the roof as the rock is still lichen covered.    Climb into the back of the roof then come out, I used a jug around the final lip and heel hook.  This has a 5.11 rating, but it is more similar to a roped up boulder problem.

name: Hospitaliano
description: This is a fun route that begins with the first pitch of Smiley Face, then traverses right on a easy 5.7ish terrain.  The third and money pitch goes up a bolted slab before getting into a dihedral/roof formation.   Rap the route Smiley Face as the final pitch is a rope stretcher and even an 80m won't get you back to the second pitch anchors.

name: It's Hard To Be A Saint In The City
description: Route starts out on a prominent layback edge. Thin moves above the third bolt, then super thin moves above the fourth at a thin horizontal to easier climbing above.    Brian (below) said he thinks it was put up by Chris Harmston?

name: Moral Kiosk
description: Step up off the low angle white slab and climb through steeper rock to gain lower angle face above.  A cam or three will protect the climbing to the first lead bolt.  "It's so much more attractive inside the moral kiosk"

name: Slow Children Playing
description: Start at the left side of the white base slab.  Traverse up and left to a steep bit.  A long sling or two down low will help immensely with rope drag up higher.  At the crest of the steepness to the transition to slab, there's a shark tooth shaped horn that would take a sling for pro.  Continue up the slab.  Some cams optional.

name: Smiley Face
description: This is a fun 4 pitch climb up the center of the Southeast face that seems to see little to no traffic. Start on a gritty slab left of a gully.  Climb the slab past 2 bolts to a short crack section fallowed by one more bolt and a small roof.  Pull over the roof using gear for pro to a chain anchor.  Pitch two climbs a somewhat dirty (should clean up nicely after a few more ascents) dog leg crack using gear and 3 bolts to a chain anchor. Pitch 3 climbs the bolt protected steep face to a chain anchor.  Pitch 4 climbs past a few bolts on huge holds to the top and eases up a lot.  Rap the route with 2 60 meter ropes.

name: Sudan
description: Start on a steep ramp that leads into a stem / chimney. Some weird moves eventually puts you on the face where you finish out the climb moving up through jugs.

name: Absence of Authority
description: This route starts with a somewhat dirty but fun 5.9+ dihedral. After about 70' you reach a small roof where the real challenges start.  Protect well before leaving the crack and launching up into devious thin face moves (crux) leading to a seam that protects only with very small gear (ie. RPs, etc).  Finish by veering right on a horizontal crack that leads to the top anchors of Hairstyles and Attitudes.     Note:  The start of the route has vegetation in the crack that can be climbed around.  Please don't remove any more vegetation at the start of this climb.

name: Hairstyles and Attitudes
description: This arete route has a lot of enjoyable moves and a good position but is somewhat contrived in a couple spots. The start can be skipped by scrambling up some boulders to the right and stepping onto the route above the first bolt, and the crux (just below the roof/right-veering crack) can be by-passed by following the chalked holds left a few feet to the crack and then heading back up and right.  Avoiding the crux makes the route around    10b.

name: Jesus and Einstein
description: Continuously challenging throughout, this very nice route has a technical crux midway to a large ledge.  From here, a tenuous balancy move up and right leads to the anchor.

name: Milk Toast
description: Start in little groove fifteen feet right of the climb on the right side of the gully (that's North Face 10d). Crux is right is in your face through the second bolt, head to fun climbing and a little roof above.

name: No Climb for Old Men
description: A tough couple moves off the ground and some getting to the last bolt. Might want to stick clip the second bolt because the first won't be enough to keep you off the slab below.    There is a second pitch that works it way up and right then finishes on the right side of a prominent pillar, 5.7. Not particularly great second pitch except the view might make it worth it.

name: North Face
description: Start in an awkward crack in the gully, gear to first bolt or maybe stick clip? then pull onto face and continue up line o bolts. Follow left arete on both pitches. Quite a bit o lichen.

name: Bellissimo
description: We traversed right 20 feet from the base of High Road on the low angle slab then pulled up onto the steep patina face to clip the first bolt.  Follow 6 more bolts angling slightly left to the chains.

name: Big Time
description: This route is located on the south slabs of the main formation.  This would probably be a 3 star route, if it was not so overbolted.  Most climbers will feel OK clipping every other bolt on the majority of this route.      There are 4 30M pitches to this route and is a good intro to the area.  There are bolted anchors at each belay, so it makes for a quick outing to top of the formation.  Rap the route with a single 60M rope.    A good way to climb this route is to combine the first and last 2 pitches together for 200ft pitches.

name: Big Time Direct
description: Took your beginner friends on Big Time for a multipitch outing?  Wanted to climb something harder instead?  Try this variation to the 3rd pitch or make it a 4th pitch of Big Time!  Slabby start to small patina edges, you can run this as a victory pitch and easily clean it.  Continue on to the summit or call it a day and rappel from here.    You can descend with a 60m in 3 raps.

name: Carpe Spot
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: Castle Keep
description: One pitch fun slab route. Pretty good holds up until about three bolts from the top, then slab scoops to the anchor.

name: Corrin's Crack
description: Easy crack and face climbing to a thin dihedral that pinches off, leaving thin jams and pinches and heel hooks on the lip of the dihedral. Run out to chains of big time, or high road if you are feeling spunky.

name: Diamond in the Rough
description: A really fun variation on Big Time.  Just after the start of the third pitch on Big Time, traverse right to the obvious left facing crack.   Skip clipping the first couple bolts on the 3rd pitch of Big Time or you'll pick up some heinous rope drag.    Word of caution for night climbing: Bats live in the crack, and if you shine your headlamp in at oh, say 2am, you might scream like a little girl as they fly out 2 inches from your face.    After the crack ends, finish by topping out on the 4th (final) pitch on Big Time, definitely need a 60m rope.

name: High Road
description: This route is located on the south slabs of the main formation. It is 2 routes to the right of Big Time, which is a 4-5 pitch bolted 5.7.  The first pitch is 5.8 except for the attention getting start at about 5.9. There is a little loose rock at the start. This pitch ends at a bolt anchor.  The second pitch has some quality slab climbing in the 5.9 range and is a real treat. I recommend combining the first two pitches in one long lead for the full experience.  The third pitch is the business pitch of the climb. Climb loose rock with trad gear to the first bolt. Fun patina face climbing leads you to another bolt anchor. (5.11a) The best descent may be with one rope, by rapping Big Time if it is not to crowded. It is a little scary getting to the first bolt due to the poor rock.

name: High Times
description: Awkward thoughtful fun more easily climbed by the dedicated yoga enthusiast.    Start up the low angle face and place a piece of pro (.5 Camalot or thereabouts) in the crack on the flake features right side.  Sandy step up to the first clip below a couple of protruding knobs.    Go left and right to keep the route doable.  Improbably sweet transitions off mantles and friction moves.    NOTE (!!):  a single 70m rope just barely works for this route.  Please (please) tie a knot in the bottom of your rope if you plan on lowering off from this route.

name: Imagine Wagons
description: Climb up a steeper than it looks finger crack via sharp painful first digit locks. at 3/4 height milk the rest as long as you want before you venture into the crazy boulder problem defending the finishing jug.  Stick the last move and you will be smiling ear to ear

name: Little Time
description: Not really a crux to this route unless you climb in the middle of an afternoon in summer.  First pitch is WAY mellow but the second pitch while mellow is still a lot of fun.  I recommend only doing these two pitches and save the top out for "Big Time" route but they easily can link up!

name: No Pack Crack
description: The chimney full of bird dung.

name: Oh My Gosh
description: Another slabby route in between Big Time and Little Time. Still a bit grainy, 2nd pitch is thoughtful friction, more so that it's neighbors.  Pitch 1: 115 ft angling slightly left to chain belay in a depression Pitch 2: 95 feet:  Angle sharply left to gain a slight rib which is followed up to the next belay  It may be possible to join the third pitch of Big Time with a 15 or 20 foot runout.  Can be climbed with just one full rope length then rappelled (one 70M rope, two raps).  Take care especially rappelling the first pitch (or lowering!!).  A single 60m rope doesn't reach.  Tie a knot or your partner into the blunt (bottom, follower, belay) side of the rope.

name: Pollo Negro
description: Pollo Negro has a handful of thoughtful moves that are difficult to read for the grade. The well spaced bolts adds to the entertainment factor. A good change of pace from the over-bolted routes to the left.

name: Poster Chicken
description: This long cruiser follows a right leaning crack system for 175ft. There are two sections with 20-30ft runouts, one of which is near the ground.  The climbing is enjoyable and the crux section is protected by 2 bolts.    You can descend with 2 ropes and clean your gear.  A one rope descent is possible to the anchors on the sport climb to the left.

name: Tiny Time
description: Slab climbing to a wide crack. More slab climbing to the bolted station on Big Time.

name: Wedding Gift
description: This route follows the curving crack to the left of Pollo Negro. Once the crack ends, you do a bit of face climbing and clip one bolt to access the right leaning crack above.    There are no fixed anchors, so the route ends once you get to the height of the chain anchors of Pollo Negro over to the right...lower off those.    However, there is a nice and easy crack that continues up for another 40+ meters.

name: Bold Yellow
description: A fun little crack with a crux overhang. Fun moves

name: Gargoyle Gardens
description: Climb up the vertical features and than traverse left when you are 20ft or so underneath the anchors. Lots of awesome feet that allow you to either find protection or rest.  An alright climb to get warmed up for The Crack House.

name: High Desert
description: Continue on after the belay bolts on Gargoyle Gardens. Lowers with a 70 meter rope.

name: Jug-A-Lug
description: A fun overhung route on a highly featured face.  The crux is at the end of the steep section just before the route slabs out at the finish.

name: Mountain Mahogany
description: Great, juggy route.      Easy flare start leads to "OMG" holds all the way up, with a very short stretch of pure hand crack for a move or two.    Mostly a face climb with drop in pro nearly anywhere, and, a variety of sizes.    With a single 60m, rope, belay at the anchor then rappel, carefully, back down with the rope ends barely reaching the ground.    DO NOT LOWER OFF WITH A 60 METER ROPE!!!!  It won't reach.  Tie a knot in the belay end or have both people tie in.

name: No is a Four Letter Word (aka Ms. Alleneus)
description: A fun jaunt up very featured granite, with good protection through all but the first fifteen feet or so.    Start on a flat-ish spot below the large boulder on the slope at the base of the wall, and climb up through some hard-or-impossible-to-protect terrain. Eventually you'll reach a spot where a hand-size cam will fit (eg., #2 C4). From here go straight up through to a crack and from there to a small roof.     Head up the crack on the right side of the roof to a small overhang between two blocks, the left-most of which looks rounded and vaguely puffy. Surmount the steepness and head up the crack to the chain anchors.

name: No Is Hard To Say
description: Fun moves, mostly big holds and not much jamming needed on the highly featured rock.

name: Snafu
description: The crack right next to "No Is Hard To Say". Just another cruiser crack at The Crack House. A single 70 will get you back to the ground.

name: Stub-a-Chub
description: Clip the first bolt of Jug-a-Lug and diagonal up and right for 5 more bolts through steep juggy patina to the anchors.

name: Bacon Slab
description: A fun route that offers well-protected friction slab climbing. Few actual hand and footholds until near the top of the route, but the mellow angle and adequate rock texture provide plenty of friction.

name: Cracked Chorizo
description: An alternative start to Scrambled with Chorizo that offers some easy trad. climbing.  This route is not in Bingham's guidebook.

name: Eggstra Special
description: Climb the mellow slab (bolts and gear) before reaching a crack feature and placing gear for the last 30 feet or so of the route.A good mix of gear and bolts on this route.

name: Hard Boiled
description: Climb the slab below the obvious roof, following the line of bolts upward and trending right.

name: Hard Poached
description: We suspect that this is another Duane Ackerman route but can´t find any record.  Adding it to MP since it´s a fun route and is not in Bingham's guidebook..  Bolt protected below and above the trad. protected "white step". Crux is finding a key hold to pull on/over first small roof, then finding another key hold to move up.  May want to protect second move with a #3 in the horizontal.

name: Holy Moly
description: This route shares the first 4 bolts with Hard Boiled before cutting left and heading up to the obvious roof. Pull straight over the roof with bolts offering protection. Can use gear to supplement bolts before reaching the roof, although any runout between bolts is on pretty mellow terrain.

name: Mahogany Corner
description: Climb through a couple of overlaps in the corner, placing gear and clipping one bolt along the way, before arriving at the large tree below the nice looking dihedral. The final 10 feet or so makes this climb worth doing! A bit of lichen at the bottom made the initial friction moves a bit dicey with limited protection so use caution getting off the ground.

name: Riblet
description: A fun start leads past a couple of bolts to some mellow ground mid route where some gear can be placed. Up higher, the route gets a bit steeper where more bolts are found before reaching the anchor.

name: Scrambled
description: Head up the right side of the Egg Wall, mostly a slab climb with a couple of small roof/overlap features.

name: Scrambled with Chorizo
description: Climb Scrambled until about mid-height, then follow the bolts that head out left.

name: Stage Left
description: Climb the low angle dihedral that trends up and left, and then head straight up a featured face.

name: 13b
description: Follow the bolt line through 2 overlaps (5.9) to a small stance about 2/3 the way up the wall.  Use the optional belay or continue up the bolt line (5.7) to the top anchors.

name: Between Heaven and Earth
description: A long sport climb just left of It Takes Two.     Start out with a couple easy slab moves to a small roof/bulge with a bolt. Continue straight up on perfect rock for another 100' to a bolted anchor. Rap with two ropes.

name: Blind Pig
description: Start on the large boulder for Honeymoon in Almo. The first crux (5.9/10) is pulling over the small roof at the second bolt. The route curves left until a second small roof, then moves back slightly right. A small cam is nice for protecting the roof move since you're 15 feet out from the last bolt; although the move isn't too difficult. Climb the smooth friction face above (5.10a) to a bolt and to the chains. Rope drag can be a bit of a problem. Sporty bolt placements. From the chains a 70 M rope will just make it to the starting boulder (with rope stretch). 60 M will require a little down climbing.

name: Country Western Ballad
description: Arete climbing at its best!   This beautiful feature holds a series of cryptic edges and blunt arete pulling. Make your way up through some sequential crimps until you're forced up onto the juggy headwall and, bam, you're home free.

name: Cup Cake
description: Fun climb on featured rock. Runout in places. Supplemental gear possible. Rap with 2 ropes. Pull rope from boulder away from cliff base

name: Das Boot
description: Mixed route with two bolts near the ground then work your way up intermittent cracks keeping an eye out left for the last bolt on a nice looking face. Climb past the bolt to the anchors.

name: Earth Muffin
description: Early crux. Technical start to a roof pull, the rest of the route is probably 5.9. Long and similar quality to redtail.

name: El Castleton
description: Find a way up to the lone bolt and start of the obvious left trending crack line.  The original line starts below the chockstone following a left trending line of good climbing up to the first bolt.  Alternatively, some people either start from the top of the chockstone and climb straight up on not so good rock or follow a line of unprotected edges coming in from the left.  After clipping the bolt, pull into the crack and follow it's elegant arching line until near the top where you jog up and a little right to the anchors.

name: Fruit Filling
description: This is a 3rd pitch variation to Fruit Pie 5.8.  The crux is the face climbing before the crack.  The crack climbing is in the 5.8-5.9 range and leads to the top.  Gear may be needed for the top.  Rap Zinger with one rope to get down. An enjoyable route with some loose rock on easy terrian.

name: Fruit Pie
description: This is one of the first routes on the west side gully on Castle Rock. There are 3 pitches with each being ~ 100 ft long. The 3rd pitch leads left to join the 3rd and last fixed anchor on Zinger. A harder variation for the 3rd pitch (Fruit Filling - 5.10c) goes straight up the bare granite face above the 2nd anchor and into a wee crack and leaning corner that require gear.  The first pitch angles up and right through two small roofs. The 2nd pitch is easy face climbing on granite.  The 3rd pitch arcs left from the 2nd anchor to join the 3rd and last anchor on Zinger.  Rap x3 with one 60M rope.

name: Get Your Fixe
description: From the belay anchors at the start of 13b, stem up to the bolt line that starts deeper in the gully. Follow the bolt line to a really fun finish high on the wall.

name: Ho Ho
description: This route is located to the left of Zinger and Twinkie on the west side of Castle Rock.  Face climb straight up the face on thin crimps to the anchor.  You will see a small arch above you.  May be easy for the grade.

name: Honeymoon in Almo
description: The route is the highest route in the gully on the west side of Castle Rock.  Approach from the south side trails.  This one is a real gem!!!    Follow a clean plate of patina with very thin edges.  Hard mantles, crimping, and high steps lead up and left to a set of anchors.  One of the best routes on the west side.

name: Hot Sticky Bun (P1)
description: A safe route with a roof pull down low (on surprisingly tricky holds). Above is more fun, classic Hostess Gully goodness. Bolted anchor  Pitch 2 is a 12c I haven't attempted.

name: It Takes Two
description: Excellent route well protected and recommended.  A wee-bit hairy getting to the first bolt so be careful and nothing bad about the climb unless you do it on a hot afternoon in the summer!

name: Numbshull
description: Next line left of Red Rib, chimney up to first bolt or climb up slab to the left and into gully below first bolt. Not as traveled as Red Rib but worth the while.

name: One for Matt
description: An obvious crack feature that doesn't have many crack moves on it.  Stem and puzzle your way to the chains. Engaging!  Pitch 2 is bolted climbing.

name: Patina Atoll
description: This incredible and bizarre route starts with a ramp to an angled dihedral and then heads up to a lip edge where the fun begins.  Puzzle through a continuous series of fascinating crux moves along the lip of a left-leaning rib, figuring out when it's best to move on top of the lip and when it's best to hang below it.  This rib lip area has scattered patina plates with a lot of blank sections.  Standing above the lip tends to be blank for hands.  Near it's end, exit right and head up to an easy crack section and finish with a thin slab/face move.

name: Piece of Cake
description: Pitch 1: Flakes and cracks for 120'. Pitch 2: Crack in right-facing corner.

name: Red Rib
description: Red Rib is a long, beautiful, single pitch route (~200 feet--you'll need two ropes to descend safely) up the SW ridge of Castle Rock. Great position and good exposure are it's strongest points. The crux is right off the ground but the climbing remains interesting and in the 5.9/10- range for most of the first ~150'. From here, it's an easier romp to the anchors. This route is a full 60 meter rope length.

name: Slab Happy
description: Follow the bolt line up the obvious slab, step across the top of the large flake and continue up steeper easy patina to the anchors.

name: Southern Rock Opera
description: An amazing splitter crack on the upper headwall, hard to miss walking up.      Climb the crack, build and anchor then rap a route in the hostess gully or walk off and downclimb into the Crack House.

name: Three Bits
description: The bolted line left of "Honeymoon in Almo." Fun and varied climbing with good rests in between moves.

name: Twinkie
description: This route is located to the left of the start of Zinger.  The need for some trad gear makes this route interesting.  Follow a few bolts and place gear in the thin cracks until you hit an anchor.  A fun outing...

name: Unknown
description: The route feels like 5.9+ with no scary crux moves.

name: Zinger
description: This route is located on the west side of Castle Rock and is the second bolted route on the west side gully.  The start is in a group of manhogany trees.    This route consists of three pitches of 5.7-5.8 face climbing that is well protected.  Nothing too exicting,  but a fun outing to the top of the formation.  Rap the route with a single 60M.

name: Cash Crack
description: Just to the right of Ring of Fire. Plug a few small pieces up the crack and step left into the runnel passing two bolts to the top.

name: Country Trash
description: Fun, short route with a sunny aspect.    Start with a steep pull of the deck with smooth feet.  Crimp the crispy patina edges then relax as your feet catch up.    Couple body length to the first bolt.  Take care.    Clip the first bolt, up on nice face moves, clip second bolt then head up for a run to the juggies.

name: Five Feet High and Rising
description: Trickier than it looks. Thin moves followed by jugs. Climb past chains if TR'ing Ring Of Fire is desired.

name: Man in Black
description: Kinda gritty down low.  Pass a couple of bolts protecting some semi insecure face moves.    Finger size-ish cracks and face climbing lead to the summit.    (Mike is the man in black...ha ha).

name: Pepper Sprout
description: A nice easy way to get to the top of Johnny Cash.  Start at the same place as "Cash Crack", then go up and right following the smaller crack system diagonalling up to the arete.  Sling the horn, then join the lower angle face/crack of "Country Trash" and head for the anchor on "Ring of Fire".

name: Ring of Fire
description: Steep techy moves lead to some long reaches and clips. Steep moves give way to thin face crimps. The third bolt seemed like a stretch. Getting onto the face is tricky.

name: Walk the Line
description: Start just left of "Ring of Fire".  Climb low angle wide, awkward crack up to ledge.  Then stay to the right and ascend the wide bombay chimney to OW crack to top, continue to anchor on "Man in Black".  Kinda burly.  Can escape the last wide bit by stepping to the left and finishing on "Man in Black".

name: Darn Boor
description: Left of Small Fry. A short and fun route.

name: Small Fry
description: A nice kids' route, or, a fun lead for folks just breaking into lead climbing.    The route is fairly low angle with maybe not as many big hand holds for the uninitiated-to-friction climber.  Very good foot holds in low angle divots.      High hand hold might be tough to grab for folks just getting past the first bolt, but, a mantle off the low rail edge, with good feet position, and, you're off to the races.    Fun!

name: Liberator of Baghdad
description: A short route with a very height dependent crux. Crux comes at the third bolt just under the roof. I found the route to have 2 difficult moves(v5-6), other than that it is cruiser.

name: Sloppy Seconds
description: Hardest part is at the beginning getting to the first bolt, could fall further than the start.  Fun jugs that traverse you around the side of the wall to a sloppy finish.  Small roof to chains

name: Groom with a View
description: This short route starts with an awkward mantle-type move to a ledge (crux) and then veers up and left through a bulge and onto a finishing ramp. The crux may be height dependent and harder than 10b for shorter climbers.

name: Opuntia
description: A fun and varied route that starts on a rounded steep   slab.  Has several harder moves on it that could be considered a crux.

name: To Have and to Hold
description: Superb, continuously interesting climbing.  Starts with a layback flake and veers up and left through varied challenging moves to the anchors.

name: To Honor and Obey
description: Climb up, clip first bolt on Groom with a View.  Clip second bolt with a double length sling, then step down and traverse back to the right.  Ascend past a thin horizontal seam, to another, and climb up to the flaring crack, which gets not-as-flaring the higher you go.  Finish at To Have and To Hold anchor.

name: Chicken Pie
description: Great trad lead for the entry-level trad climber.  Lot's of good protection, a bit slabby and exposed.  Really enjoyed this route as an experienced sport climber new to trad.

name: Chicken Slinger
description: The left (north) most route on the west face of Poultry Pillar. With overhanging jug pulls onto the summit, the last 20 feet are what really make this route worth doing.

name: Historic Route
description: Stay to the right of the notch as you ascend, guidebook describes a ramp - I found it easier to just take the path of least resistance up to the notch. The climbing down low is very easy and doesn't warrant pro. When you get to the notch sling a knob and enjoy the views as you scamper to the top.

name: Fool For the City
description: Climb either crack to reach the ledge. Six or so bolts. Harder to go right after first bolt. Most go left to crack. You can also scramble up slab to left to get to ledge.

name: Oops! I Did It Again
description: Bolted face right of "Sleeper" Crack. Fun undercling move.

name: Sleeper
description: I dont think this route has bee done to many times.  When I climbed the rock was very grainy and there was lots of lichen coming off.

name: Alcove Corner
description: Obvious, but not excellent, inside corner fist-size crack.  Gear to 4 inches.  Build your own anchor at the top or just head left to the chains on B. S. Face.  Not a worthy objective, but if you’re climbing in Tiny Town, it’ll only require sixty seconds of your time.

name: Ray of Heaven
description: The short, bolted arete with no real crux. This lone is pretty straight forward and easier if you stay left. A good warm-up for its neighbor, Six Feet Over.

name: Short Sport
description: Short sport route up a patina face, with small but solid crimp edges and good feet.

name: Six Feet Over
description: A nice route with lots of interesting moves for only 36 feet and will keep you working from start to finish. This route is shorter if you don't count the opening slab move to crack with ample gear protection. The Bingham guide rates this route 5.10a, and feels hard for the grade.

name: Tiny Town Alcove Face
description: Not in the guidebook, this route is unlikely to attract a lot of attention as it is quite short. Still, its location and lack of time commitment make it an attractive choice if you’re in the neighborhood and have kids in tow.  Start behind the large flake and either use chimney technique or face climb past two bolts. Positive edges abound on the near-vertical face above. Run it out on easy climbing to the chains or protect with stoppers and cams to .5 inches.  This short route is one of the better kid-oriented climbs in Castle or the City for those who want to climb something other than slab but aren’t fond of getting too high.  Well-protected, easy, and fun!

name: Tiny Town Pillar
description: Climb the steep, patina-laden west face of the obvious pillar south of the main rock in Tiny Town. This looks like a pillar from the west but less like a pillar from other angles.    It's a short but fun route and worth doing on your way in or out. D. Bingham gives this route three stars in his Castle Rocks book.

name: Lacey’s Smile
description: Start up easy slab past a low crack. No pro is needed here. Above the crack, start clipping bolts and head up to the ledge. When you reach the ledge, stand up and snag the lip. Compression, thumberclings etc can help you be static here. Grab a crimp just over the lip and to the right. If you’re normal height you can clip the bolt on top of the ledge from here. Get your feet up and mantle onto the ledge (crux). Wander up more easy slab to a small roof. Grab jugs and pull up and over roof to the chains.  The climb was bolted by Diana Lincoln-Haye, Stan Haye and Caleb Hopwood June 2019

name: Little Warrior
description: A nice kid route to set up a TR on.  Starts with a slippery slab crux right off the ground (can boost them past it).  After the crux, follow the 5.0- crack to the top.  Do not damage the tree in the crack! Gear anchor can be made just over the edge from a couple cracks (lowest ~0.5-0.75 C4, and upper crack 1-2ish).  Walk off down easy slab to your left, or rap from chains of other routes.  You can also easily set up a TR anchor by walking up the backside.

name: The Road Back Home
description: Climb up and over some slabby ledges to a final, short headwall. Pull the eggshell patina to the chains.

name: Thirteen Warriors
description: Named for the 13 veterans who participated in the original Warrior's Rock event at Castle Rock.  Start just left of the tree.  Friction up some slab to a final crux on a steeper face just before the chains.

name: Warrior’s Tribe
description: Start up friction slab clipping bolts as you go until you reach the head wall. Like the route next door, the climbing is relatively easy, culminating with a crux mantle. Crimp your way up the headwall and then a techy mantle guards the chains.  TR can also be easily set up by scrambling up the backside.

name: Accidental Spice
description: This is the last route on the left side as you move up the gully. Although short, it is fun and worth doing. The holds are all positive. You will want at least 2 pieces (gear to 2 inches) to supplement the bolts and prevent ground fall.

name: Bug City
description: This is the natural line just to the left of Olympus Wrecks.  Start about 20 ft to the left in a very thin tips/finger crack.  The meat of this climb is fairly short but hard right from the start.  Take a right leaning very thin tips crack up and into the crux of Olympus.  The two routes meet for 10 feet, using the highest bolt of Olympus when gear disappears.  Once you have reached the good stance take the left crack/corner to the roof and out left to the anchors of Ad-vance to Idaho.

name: Claim Jumper
description: The striking and enjoyable arête just left of the classic Shock and Awe is, in my opinion, just as classic due to the position and crux moves. But then again, I'm a huge fan of arêtes and airy, exposed climbing. If you're like me in that respect, you're sure to enjoy this fine line.  From the same big ledge belay for Shock and Awe, head slightly down and left to get to the start of the arête. Clip a couple of bolts from good holds to a small roof/bulge. Figure out how best to pull this bulge and then clamber up the tiny dihedral past a few more bolts to a good ledge below the obvious arête crux above.  Slap and heel hook the arête and pull through a few committing moves to the great clip hold above the crux allowing you to get established in the huge hueco just right of the arête. Take a moment to enjoy the airy and exposed position before making the final moves to the anchor.  According to Bingham's book, the 5.11c crux can be avoided by going far right of the huge hueco near the crux. I didn't try this and think that would be quite a pendulum swing if you didn't make it. The crux moves are cool and well protected so you might as well keep it real on the arête.  The 11c moves require height and reach.  Move right along the ledge/slab to the right side of the hueco.  Climb the jugs and chicken heads on the right side. Make a long reach left to clip the bolt in the hueco. Either step into the hueco and stem upward or continue to hug the jugs on the right to gain the final bolt and anchors.

name: Drew's Corner
description: Climb a mungy, low-angle left leaning crack to access the corner.  The actual corner climbs well with lots of face holds and fun stemming. The crux is a short section requiring a layback.  Traverses right at the top to the anchor.

name: Friction Pants
description: A great climb to do if there is a wait for Shock and Awe. This short climb starts with 5.8-ish friction up a slab. You can pro the slab with a small TCU. Once at the top of the slab, you can reach up and clip the first bolt. Power-move your way up over the roof and then finesse your way up a friction face to a set of chain anchors.

name: Genevive
description: Good beginner route. Steep start crux is bolt-protected. Three moves of 5.7 or 5.8 climbing, but then it eases into enjoyable 5.5 climbing to chain anchors. Big holds from start to finish.

name: Just Right
description: Another of Duane Ackerman's recent additions to the single-pitch side of the Hostess Gully. This route is very well-protected and would make for an excellent first lead. With 7 bolts in 60 feet on huge holds, this route is a fine choice for kids and anyone looking for a mellow romp on steeper terrain than much of the standard Castle Rocks slab.  This route leads to the same chain anchors used by Genevive.

name: Poking Holes in the Firmament
description: One kinda crux move is stepping off the ground onto the climb.  Very mellow but fun climb recommended for beginners, good bolts, big holds, cool featured rock!

name: Ryobi
description: Friction up and over an early overlap, continue up the slab towards the cedar tree and pull across a flake edge to a steeper patina line to the anchors under an overhanging dihedral.  Above this is the 2nd pitch of Tiers of Joy.  It was discovered after the fact that Ryobi loosely followed some sections of the somewhat runout original Tiers of Joy first pitch. Brad Shilling (FA of Tiers of Joy and climbing ranger at the time) was notified immediately of the potential retrobolting and he gave his blessing to the new line.  It can now be used as an approach pitch to the excellent 2nd pitch of Tiers of Joy (5.10 full on trad).

name: Scorpio Rising
description: A fun steep start, then a short break, leads to a slight over hang on big holds.  Up the face to a corner, around just to the left, then up to the anchor.

name: Sexcellent
description: P1 one is a very fun outing of ever steepening patina until you pull the 5.10 crux at the final bulge.  P2: step up right to the edge of the arete and make a desperate but well protected 5.11 move to gain a line of patina to the anchors.  P3: A short but nice 5.7 pitch takes you to the top of the formation. One 60 meter rope will get you down in 3 rappels.

name: Shock and Awe
description: This fun diverse route starts on patina edges.  The crux hits low with in a maze of small patina holds facing different directions.  Continue on with tricky pull-down edging leading to a steep jug finish.

name: Sqench
description: A fun and interesting line bolted by someone with a keen eye! 6 bolts diagonal up and right following the diagonal crack lines and ramps. Smartly bolted, this route offers great rock and a huge variety of climbing styles in 45 feet. Two crux sections- the first is from bolts 3 to 5- sneak through with in-obvious balancey moves that seem like trickery. The second is around bolt 5 and is a little more thuggish. In cool conditions i'm sure neither of these cruxes would be harder than v4, but in the summer heat 12c is probably correct. Listed as 12b/c in the Bingham guide.

name: Tiers of Joy
description: Strenuously pull through the roof and follow the crack until you can easily traverse left to the top anchors of Sexcellent.

name: Excalibur
description: Originally claimed to be 5.11b, but very doubtful, more like 5.12.    Beta according to Guide book:    Pitch 1: Start in splitter crack to cave belay (70').   Pitch 2: Climb roof crack (20').    Pitch 3: Climb wild arete on bolts (30').     My beta:    Pitch 1: Start on easy slab that works into a dirty thin crack with shrubs that you must climb through. Once past the shrubs, it's clean climbing on thin fingers up the left side into the cave. Instead of making a gear anchor here, keeping going twenty more feet past the roof with moderate rope drag to a chain anchor.(90')   Pitch 2: Climb sporty arete (30').    Rap two times with a 60m rope.

name: Chuck Norris
description: Start on sidepulls; dyno to a  unique sloper for the city. One move wonder of awesome.

name: Eagle Grove Variations
description: I chose to list the problems as one with the intent that the variations are about the same and harder variations seemed to not warrant a specific problem. Feedback is welcomed.

name: Checkerboard Traverse
description: Sit start on the right side and traverse left.

name: Global Tetrahedron
description: Steep climbing on good holds leads to tough mantle.

name: The Bag Piper
description: Right of HCB. Follow the roof right, into a hard face.

name: Golden Chandelier
description: Start standing on a boulder, move right to a big jump

name: Green In The Face
description: right of golden. Start on and big flake, move up and left to finish golden.

name: Heart
description: A roof line on the back side of the green wall. Strong, powerful moves lead into a crimpy face.

name: Pissy Pants
description: Start on a big flake in the middle of wall move right.

name: The Rail
description: An obvious rail right of The Bag Piper. Traverse up and right on this slightly overhanging rail. Finish when you run out of the rail.

name: Waxie Darbles
description: Waxie Darbles starts on the rightmost side of the Green Wall on low right hand and mid left hand crimps, then moves up and right to a good jug just over the lip, top out on easy slab.

name: Waxie Pants
description: Start low on good holds move up and left. From the crimpy gaston go straight up. A variation goes left. Variation V8/9.

name: Hornet's Prow
description: Start high on a sloper and right hand crimp, big move to an easy top out. Stays dry through the business.

name: Mad as a Hornet
description: Traverse the rail right to a committing throw near the top.

name: Unknown
description: Short powerful climb on the backside of the hornet boulder. Other problems and variations are possible to open up.

name: Bow Tie Arete or EZ Arete
description: One of the super classics at Castle Rocks State Park. Great movement on impeccable rock.

name: Columbian Bowtie
description: See beta video

name: Jared's Roof Sit
description: See beta video

name: Jared's Roof Stand
description: see beta video

name: Out of Africa
description: See beta photo

name: The Smell
description: see beta photo

name: Taco's for Two AKA Pink Taco
description: see beta video

name: Warpath
description: See beta photo

name: Pow Pow
description: Sustained climbing on large huecos then crimps.

name: Southern Sauce
description: Start on favorable holds, make some powerful moves to get over the lip then an easy mantle if you can reach the chicken head.

name: Rose Crack
description: This is a fun dihedral marred by rose bushes about a third of the way up the route. Climb up a ramp with a useful hand crack to the left, pull over to the right to a stance where rose bushes await you, fight your way past them, and enjoy a slowly widening hand-crack to the top.    (The route name was obtained from Dave Bingham's guide to the park.)

name: Shut Up & Scrub
description: An interesting but short route.  Start with a heel-toe plus stem, arm bar plus stem, fists plus stem, hand jams plus stem, and then finally a top-out.

name: Unnamed 5.10d
description: A thinker!  Protection in the first 10 feet after the approach ramp is tricky.  Beyond this, options open up and the climbing improves rapidly.  Finish off with a jam-jug-mantle to chains!

name: Already Been Done Crack
description: Alternate finish to Handy.  The crack is the one to the right of the uppermost bush visible on the face from the base.  There are two options for getting there:    1. From the top of the Hand(y) crack, traverse right, try to avoid getting covered in sap bushwhacking past the pine tree, and head up a dirty, mossy finger crack.  Unpleasant but well protected.   2. From the first bolt on Handy, traverse right and up on 5.7-5.8 dikes and slabs to the crack.  Good climbing but totally unprotected for 30'.    The crack itself is more like a seam with tiny nut placements.

name: Bathing Beauty
description: Start 50' south of ?Wunderdog?, in a wet grassy depression. Climb patina jugs. Belay at a 2-bolt/chain station. The route is very short and isn't very interesting.

name: Castle Rocks Gardening Club
description: First Pitch: Right facing dihedral with thin gear crux and one bolt down low.  11a/b    Second Pitch: (The goods) A steep "stellar" pitch on great rock with good laybacking and jamming.      You can make it to the ground from the second pitch anchor with one 70M rope.  Build an anchor for pitch 2, a #3 camalot can help here.    It is feasible to take the route to the top with a pitch of difficult to protect chossy OW (5.10ish), and a 5.4 unprotected sandy slab.

name: Continental Crust
description: Start as for Mantle Dynamics by pulling the fun mantle move onto the gigantic chicken head. Clip another bolt or two and veer right following the numerous bolts through a series of fun, positive moves in dishes and depressions in the rock.     Near the top, continue on easy third class terrain to the some anchors where you will need two ropes to get down or two raps with one rope using the Mantle Dynamics anchors.     If you don't feel like pushing out through the easy finish or you only have one rope, you can traverse horizontally to the right clipping a lone bolt and the anchors atop the 5.7 hand crack route (Handy) or move left to the anchors for Mantle Dynamics. A single 60m will get you down from either set of alternate anchors.

name: Cryptic Vision
description: A bouldery start leads into a moderate traverse. After moving right you end up in a corner / arete where you start to move up. The climbing eases up as you get closer to the chains.

name: East Ridge Variation
description: This is a bolted variation start to the East Ridge route. It's a little more interesting than the chimney start, but pretty contrived and currently still flakey/loose. If you want to do something short and not get on the actual East Ridge Route, you can just rappel from bolted chains at 100'.

name: Handy
