description: Fun perfect hand crack on a slab.  Crack peters out, route continues up the slab past 2 bolts to a chain anchor.

name: Humdinger
description: Start by moving up on a face with a juggy zig zag holds. The jugs turn into slopers and more of a steep slab. You'll get to a roof and do a fun move to get through. Once over the roof its easy climbing to the chains. The second pitch is continues this type of climbing (5.8).

name: Mantle Dynamics
description: This shares the start of Continental Crust but continues straight up the arete. The arete may seem a bit exposed to some but it's almost impossible to climb above your protection on this one. A couple of "cruxy" moves in the middle spice up the route and as you may have guessed at least one is a mantle.

name: Mein Komp
description: Start on easier climbing up to the first bolt.  Lay back/stem your way up a blob like feature to a just out of reach finger lock.  At the second bolt move back right via a body tension cross through to a sloping dish.  Match that, mantle up, clip 3rd bolt and get a ok rest.  Here comes the fun stuff.  30ft of stemming and slapping, get gear where you can in the seam.  When possible, cut right to the next crack system over and head up over the last crux section.  If you have made it this far, you get a sweet 25ft of dessert crack to the chains

name: Companeros
description: An excellent romp starting from the bolted belay at the top of pitch 1 of Red Corner.  Climbs through bolts and gear up excellent patina  to a sequential crux getting into a scoop at about 60 feet, then steep jugs to the top.  Has sustained, interesting movement up perfect rock -- classic!

name: La Vida
description: An excellent mixed multi pitch on the south face of the comp wall.  P1 Ascend a right leaning thin hands to finger crack stepping right (crux dynamic 5.9++) and proceeding up the easy terrain until a 3-4 inch crack is reached.  Big cams are not needed as there are bolts to the right of the crack for pro. We skipped the first belay and linked to P2 with some rope drag.  P2 steep juggy patina mostly 5.7 with a move or two of 5.9  P3 Traverse climbers right from the belay seeing the bolts on the wall. A cam protects the airy unique "step across" move.  Steep climbing that improbably stays at the grade to more moderate patina above.  Top out on the formation!  Rappel the route in 3 60 M rappels. WE used a 70 but a 60 would work.

name: No Competition
description: A fun outing with bolts at the cruxes.  Balancey crimp moves to a glorious patina upper half.  A few underclings down low for variety!

name: Question of Balance
description: Excellent route on the South face of Comp Wall with (as eloquently described in the Bingham guide) an awesome, exposed face to the top of the wall. The route does not actually top out, although it may be possible to bypass the chains and continue on to the top; we didn’t attempt that.  P1.  Start with P1of La Vida on gear and then, when bolts appear, take the left bolt line which breaks off at about the fourth bolt on La Vida.  Cruise a few more bolts to a set of bolts with chains.  See La Vida for the complexities on this pitch.  P2.  5.10a Slab, thin and steep in spots.  Follow bolts to a big ledge with a set of bolts with chains on the left wall above the ledge.  P3.  5.10c Thin start onto a balancy mantel leads to an intimidating-looking bulge that is great fun.  A crux may be the last move to the chains...I have to put an asterisk on my send as I french freed on a chain.  There is a variation on P3 called La Vida Loca that takes a line of bolts left after the mantel. We didn’t do it and the book rates it at 5.11a.  Rappel the route with a 70m rope. It looks like a 60m would work fine.

name: Red Corner
description: The big corner to the left of the bolted line, "Shop and Compare." Two pitches, chain anchors (final set of anchors is the same for that of "Shop and "Compare").

name: Shop and Compare
description: This is a great journey through steep patina plates, cracks, and edges.      P1: Follow the ramp to the left of the Splitter crack. Use a finger/hand crack (gear) to reach the first bolt. Angle back right to reach the steep juggy face above.     P2: Continue up the wall with more steep climbing to belay on a good ledge. A small wire could be placed after the last bolt, but it is easier here.    P3: Angle left to hit the arete for the final bolted pitch.    I highly recommend linking P1 and P2 with a 70M rope. A 60M rope would also probably work.  You will need to back clean a couple clips and use long runners on a few key bolts to reduce drag, though.

name: Splitter
description: This is one of prettiest 5.11 crack lines at the City and Castle Rocks.  The rating has been documented as 5.11a, but the moves at the overhang are stiff and a little bit heady for the grade.    P1: Follow a shallow RF dihedral to the small overhang. The best crux gear consists of medium hexs, since the crack flares in the back.  Fire the crux sequence with poor feet and hit a jug above the the overhang. There is a short section of poor rock at this point. Also, watch your gear placements at the lip, the rope my force you gear into the crack.  Then enjoy 60ft of splitter crack around the #2 friend size to a 2 bolt anchor.    P2: Pitch 2 traverses to the right into a large hands fist crack crack to another 2 bolt anchor.    Rap with one 60M rope.

name: Straight outta Compton
description: Climb up a ramp to gain a finger crack.  Climb the crack through a few difficult bulges until the crack seams out.  Venture upward into the featured face. There is gear, but it requires some creativity. Original route climbed to the top meeting up with Splitter's second anchor

name: Women's Semi-Qualifier
description: Great sport climb from the comp, follow bolts left of a thin crack. Stepping off the block to the right is way easier than straight up the guts.

name: Baby-Free
description: Easy short chimney section gets you to the first bolt. Pull onto the slab and negotiate a height-related crux. Easier ground leads to the chains.

name: Exstacy
description: Laybacks, patina, bear hugs - this route has it all. Damn fun! Might want a stick clip for the first bolt.

name: Sancho Rama
description: Look for the obvious bolt line on the beautiful sweeping face left of the grand huecos and above some large boulders. Thin slab start.

name: Aguila
description: Start up a slab to clip 1st bolt. Crux is passing 1st bolt, which seemed at least 5.8, maybe 5.9. (5.6 rating preserved from Bingham 2016 guidebook.) Easy scrambling after 2nd bolt.

name: Eagle Eyes
description: Start up a corner on the North West side.  Few tricky moves low sees you to a fun chimney and up a face.  Keep cutting left around a corner to the north east face and a chain anchor.  Second pitch takes the north face/arete up a fun bolted slab and another chain anchor

name: Fool Value
description: Start at base of right-angling crack/flake. Follow crack right to end, and then left up face to ridge, following bolts. Cams for supplemental pro in cracks on face and ridge. Ends at shared anchor with Corona. Crux on lower crack.

name: Heel Thyself
description: Start at flake and climb up the flake/shallow right facing corner until you can move left under a small overlap.  Continue through the overlap on the left side and crimp up small edges to gain a blunt arete.  Eventually the angle eases and bigger holds appear.  The climbing continues up a pleasant slab to the anchors.  Thanks goes to Brad Shilling for gifting this FA to Chris and I and for his initial cleaning of moss and lichen on this line.

name: Jolly Rancher (aka Carrion's Delight)
description: Start up a clean fun looking arete.  Follow the arete until it eases up, move onto the face and to the same anchors for the first pitch of Eagle Eyes.  Take the second pitch of Eagle Eyes to the summit.  easy to link as 1 long pitch.

name: Kaya Bunga
description: Start in the same crack as for Fool Value but traverse left in the crack system, with the crux being in the middle of the traverse as you move under Lollipop Lamb Chop. Solid hand jams, great protection options, and creative footwork come into play through the crux. Follow the crack all the way up to the chains at the top of Aguila where you can lower off.  *Not sure if we made the first ascent. There's no record here in Mountain Project or in Dave Bingham's new guidebook. If you know who made the first, let us know.

name: Lollipop Lamb Chop
description: Small but savory!  A powerful first move to a jug starts you up a steeper than it looks face.  Cool moves between crimps and side pulls to a final move that will have you begging for more.

name: My Corona
description: Start up a chimney with optional gear (#3 cam) and move left onto face. Face protected by bolts plus gear in crack.

name: Wings of Wax
description: Pitch 1: Short but fun sport pitch.  Start at the base of the large crack/chimney, clip the first bolt and traverse left onto the face.  follow the grove up until it is possible to exit out right and to the anchors    Pitch 2: Climb up the shallow corner above the anchor (gear) to the first bolt.  Follow 3 bolts up and left on some killer crimps up the just over vert face.  Traverse the crack out right (gear) until it is possible to pull over onto the slab.  3 more bolts of slab that will make you feel like Icarus, shoes melting off with each step higher.

name: Bella
description: AKA: Redball Project, recently renamed, I just got back from City and Castle and was told that this beauty was freed at the end of last season. The consensus seems to be 12-. Climb the bouldery start with small pro and finish on the upper flaring section. Finishes with insecure fingers or layback to a good jug.

name: Borderline
description: An unrecommended route recorded for historical avoidance.    Route climbs face next to a sensitive and fragile moss runnel and finishes on the big corner right of Really Fun.

name: Crème brûlée
description: Start left of Tiramisù and climb up the creaky crack to the steep featured face.  Don't pass up protection opportunities.    Half way up the route goes lower angle and passes across some diagonal cracks.  Top out left of Tiramisù on the ridge, then right to that anchor, or, take the lower angle trough to the right and up just left of the finish of Tiramisù.    A fun route with good, fairly solid features and a lack of protection.  Take care!    Also, this route is best done with a 70 or 80m rope.  Tie a knot in the blunt end!  If lowering off, be very careful as a 60m rope won't reach the ground.    One protection bolt mid way up the route.    Descent:  rappel from anchor to the right (Tiramisù anchor) with a 70m rope.

name: Don't Fence Me In
description: Start below the small tree/shrub on the start of the ledge to the left of Really Fun.  Climb up and clip a protection bolt, then, passing the tree, use the crack for pro.    At near where the crack goes over to horizontal, step up, clip a bolt, make some steep moves, clip another bolt then step up and finish at the anchor.    A fun little diversion...

name: Free Range
description: Pick one of three starts (left - finger crack layback, right - short hand crack in corner, middle - short overhanging hand crack).  Middle crack is recommended.  All three variations for the start are approximately 5.8 in difficulty.    From the low angle slab past the short, intial steep section, aim for the thin crack that is straight up the face, which cuts through the summit ridge.  Horizontal cracks, up over laps, then up to thin crack.  Follow crack up then slightly right to finish on slightly overhanging rock.

name: Odoriferous Harmony
description: A fun little jaunt with good rock and fairly good protection.    Start just left of the wide crack flake and move up right into a thin crack.  Go up to lower angle terrain, then up the shallow trough to the anchor on Tiramisu.    Protection:  Standard rack of trad gear.  No bolts except the anchor at the top.    Location:  to the right of South of the Border (and the bolted sports route Pop Tart) and to the left of Creme Brulee.

name: Patina Pie
description: This route goes up the arête just left of Really Sweet. There are three bolts close to the ground, then two more bolts up towards the top separated by highly featured 5.easy terrain in the middle that you can either run out or place some gear.

name: Pockets Full of Sand
description: East face of Fenceline, climb up short, steep left leaning crack.  Face climb and/or traverse to lower angle right slanting crack which is followed up until its end.  Traverse left and finish up wider crack to chockstone on summit ridge.  See route topo photo.

name: Poetry in Slow Motion
description: An easier gear option on the west side of Fenceline.    Climb up the trough past the start of Tiramisù.  Head up on nice big features to the crack below the orange face (clipping the sole bolt on the way).  Follow the crack up and left.  Continue up to the anchor on Tiramisù.    Nice rock.    Suggest belaying at the top.  Cannot lower safely with a single 60m rope!  Might be able to lower with an 80m rope.

name: Poptart
description: Another fun climb.

name: Really Fun
description: Fun easy bolt line.

name: Really Sweet
description: Towards the right side of Fenceline Rock if looking at it from the Taco area. This route is just to the right of a huge right facing corner. It climbs up a bit of slab and then some cool looking patina.

name: Riding Fenceline
description: A fun little jaunt which milks the big features and fixed anchors enroute to the crest of the Fenceline ridgeline.    Start at the north end of the formation, and, climb weaknesses crossing back and forth to keep the grade reasonable.    Can clip a number of anchors for protection.

name: South of the Border
description: A fun route with varied features.    Start on a thin smooth slab, left of a right facing crack slab, or, climb the crack.  Smooth face up to dishy bucket features.    Trend right up nice edges.  Up high, cross a couple of wide cracks to the summit ridge.

name: Tiramisu
description: Nearly a sport route, Tiramisu is great for aspiring 5.7 trad leaders, or, even jaded old timers looking for a nice route.  Crux is a thin move past the upper crack that is followed for a short distance.  Requires either a 70 or 80 meter rope to rappel, or, down climb the low angle slot to the chimney (take care!) if you have a single 60 meter rope.  Also note that you cannot lower a climber to the ground with a single 60 meter rope (so, bad candidate for a TR too).

name: While You're Here
description: A worthy diversion from clipping bolts next door...  Climb up the face to the right of the big corner on plate-ish slabs with little overlaps.  Good gear to be had in the plates.  Use the anchor on Patina Pies or Really Sweet for the git off.  Might as well...

name: Bear Paw
description: A bit of a wandering proposition...    Start up on the right side of the Pork Chop face.  Up over blocky terrain to nicely featured face.  Trend left to end up on a nice crack to summit.

name: Eeyore's Smile
description: This route lies just right of the bolted Pooh's Honey and the tunnel trad route Heffalump Trap.  Climb directly over the blocks, mantling and clipping bolts as you go. Easy patina with one bolt of cruxy slab moves at the top.  Shares the same chains as all the other west side routes.

name: Heffalump Trap
description: This is an amusing little diversion, and, quite unique.  Climb up to the right of Pooh's Honey (first couple of bolts can be used for pro, slinging long will help with rope drag).  Stem around/over to easily avoid the low angle moss runnel.  Climb up to the small tree, sling it long for pro if desired, then up to the horizontal roof crack.  Get yer guns loaded, start pluggin' cams for gear and jamming whilst moving to the left.  Aim for the hole and wonder if you can a) get into it and b) get through it.    Pooh says, "Then would you read a Sustaining Book, such as would help and comfort a Wedged Bear in Great Tightness?"    "For some minutes he lay there miserably, but when the five hundred and eight-seventh Heffalump was licking its jaws, and saying to itself "Very good honey this, I don't know when I've tasted better," Pooh could bear it no longer."    Fun stuff.    Pooh likes his honey.

name: Humor Me
description: Coming Soon

name: Knobhobbin
description: Mostly bolted face climb. Crux in lower half. "Best route on the Heffalump?" (Bingham, 2016)

name: Oh, Bother
description: Grunt up into the crack.  Follow crack up until the shallow ledge.  Then, either straight up the face above, or, traverse left and up.  Top out, walk off.  Or, just climb the newer sports route slightly to the right at the start.

name: Piglet Tip Toes
description: Make the easy move onto the ledge and clip the first bolt. Move right onto the slab and work upward using the slab and the little water runnel on your left. After sustained slabbing through the 2nd and 3rd bolts you'll finally reach some actual handholds up in the vicinity of the 4th bolt where the challenge eases up.  The 2016 Bingham guide calls this a 5.9 but it seemed harder than that to me. Overall a really fun and challenging little route that was well-protected.

name: Pooh Corner
description: Fun route starting on flake features with trad gear then switching over to a sports climb finish.    Pull up a right slanting shallow flake to a shallow foot shelf and up a right facing corner.    Face climb up past the block (on the left) and finish on face climbing bolts to anchor.

name: Pooh's Honey
description: Fun short little face climb.  Climb up the flake crack on the right, then, clip the bolt and climb up the low angle face.  Steeper rock leads to a bolted anchor, or, walk off (straight back and slightly to the left).

name: Pork Chop
description: Climb up initially blocky horizontal shelfs to face.  Up face to anchor.

name: Sweet Roberta
description: Climb an easy slab past several bolts.  On a block just to the right of a large crack, with a large and obvious belay area.  You climb 3 distinct blocks stacked on top of each other on your way to the anchors.

name: Tiddly Pom
description: Start on Pooh's Honey, climb up the short corner crack, then stay right and traverse over and finish on Eeyore Smiles.

name: Two Fer
description: Climb the face and arete between Eeyore's Smile and Sweet Robert.  Shares same chains and last moves as Eeyore's Smile.  Climb patina edges to a few final slab moves.

name: In Without Knocking
description: A pleasant, thin start up a smooth face leads to a couple short horizontal roofy breaks.  Up ya go.   In Without Knocking was the lone album from the Mission Mountain Wood Band and the album art was the Charley Russel painting of the same name.

name: Meadowlark
description: A nice, straight up line to a very thin, pointy summit spire.    Friction with some thin seams, a short, shallow roofy section, and a nice finish.    Take care tagging the spikey summit as the fixed anchor is below the very top, where the rock is more robust.

name: Morning Red
description: Climb up the arete on the right side of the formation with the pointy tip, just right of Meadowlark.  Clip three bolts, then, take care with a large kind of secure block which dubiously accepts a couple of small to medium sized cams for protection.  Clip another bolt, ascend up to a low angle break at the shoulder of the formation, then traverse to the left and up to the fixed anchor.   Morning Red's gonna set me on fire...   New sun is coming gettin' higher and higher...   Mission Mountain Wood Band

name: Ancient Mariner
description: Clip the first bolt from boulder. Step off boulder onto slab (crux). The route eases up a lot after the first 10 feet.

name: Handsome Sailor Boy
description: Bouldery start to first bolt, then thin friction and edging to the second bolt.  Somewhat runout to the third bolt (take care if you're short clipping the third bolt, ie, under 6' tall).  Near the top, step left to the arete just right of the crack to the left.  Up to the anchor on the rim of the formation.

name: Sirens of Almo
description: Mostly bolted face climb with a little small gear near the top.  Fun Crux move about mid route.

name: Chumming
description: A brilliant sport route on the overhanging side of the Shark's Fin. A burly move gets you off the ground - and shorter climbers might find this to be the crux. From here clip a few bolts on easier terrain before the crux at mid-level. Several different options exist for this super thin stretch of beautiful patina. Engaging 11+/12- climbing leads you to the chains from there.     Bolted by Mike Spaulding a few years back, I finished this project at the 2013 Idaho Mountain Festival. A great route.

name: D.E.A.
description: Start up easy slab climbing past the first two bolts. After clipping the third bolt, follow the holds slightly leftward until you can move past the slight overhang and onto the upper slab. Pass a couple more bolts straight up to the chain anchor.

name: Great White Tuna
description: Climb up to large flake above a small tree.  Ascend the finger crack over a small bulge until you are established on the face.  Step to the right and clip the first bolt.  Transfer in a layback up large patina jugs.  Make a few hard moves and follow crimps to the top.

name: Paw Prints
description: A fun short route with the crux right of the ground. Balance your way up on minimal feet and less than ideal hands just enough until you can move past the first bolt. Cruiser climbing above to the chains.

name: Sorta Handy
description: A very mellow, short little route that is just over too quickly. Clip a bolt as you work up to the crack, place a cam or two in the crack, and then finish on easy slab climbing, clipping one more bolt on the way to the chains.

name: Winking Gargoyle
description: Climb 15' up patina holds below a winking eye past 2 bolts. Traverse 10' left across white slab to 0.5"-2" cracks. Reach for a patina flake (right eyebrow) and climb up to a 1 bolt/ring. Climb a 20' 5.11 slab past to a 2-bolt/chain station on top.

name: Wall Candy
description: As you approach Sweet 17 from the notch in Comp Rock, there are two bolted routes on the south face.  This is the one to the right.    The crux is most likely the mantle to get started on the climb.  It's not that fun.  There is some exfoliating rock near the top.

name: Big Brown Eyes
description: As you approach Sweet 17 from the notch in Comp Rock, there are two bolted routes on the south face.  This is the one to the left.    Start up a slab to mantle on big patina buckets.  Granite patina climbing to the chains.

name: Comb-Over
description: A bit difficult off the ground and then another section at a small bulge in the middle which can be harder or easier depending on whether you go straight up, or move to the right (easier).

name: Monkey Funk
description: Start up a shallow, left-facing corner through steep, lesser quality rock using the featured rock on the right and the gritty, non-featured rock on the left for a feet. A nice, heavily-chalked block in the corner offers a nice clip hold but doesn't look like it'll be there for long. (I broke two holds in the first 15' of the route in Sept. 2008.)  Pull the crux around the 4th bolt into less steep and easier but run-out climbing past a few more bolts to the bolted anchor.

name: Bandito
description: Fun RF flaring finger to hand crack/flake system on great rock.  The first half is the hardest then eases up a bit.  Takes gear great.  The crack ends about 40 feet from the summit and the run out is a bit heady to the anchors on the west side.  Not hard climbing (5.5 or so) but watch the rope drag.

name: Conejito
description: A fun jaunt in a more secluded location on the Taco.      A gritty start in/near a corner with a bolt a ways off the deck leads to a low angle slab to a steep finish.    Take care getting to the first bolt.  Low angle but a tumble a ways off the ground might not be fun.    Low angle slab with a couple of bolts.  Steeper finish on fun edges to a change in character to pure friction below the anchor.    Take care on the steeper bit...rock is good, edges are crispy, but, with that much rope out a short fall could land you on the low angle slab.    Don't lower off this route with a 60m rope!  Tie a knot in the blunt end!  Route can be CAREFULLY rappelled with a 60m rope with no extra, but, since the route wanders a bit, lowering would be not recommended.

name: Horchata
description: Variation to "Mole' Problano". After the third bot on "Mole'" move right to the thin crack and continue to same anchors.

name: La Cruz de la Norte
description: A fun jaunt up a variety of features.    Start on the slab, a little steep bit on jugs, then another slab, to the steeper featured face.    Route seems to go with a single 60m rope but be darn careful with any top roping.  Tie a knot in the end!!!    Bueno!

name: Leapin' Leaner
description: Start on the slightly overhanging face on the hunk of rock that leans against the Taco.    Traverse up, sling a less than inspiring horn, then up to the arete to the right, where a pocket takes a large (#4 camalot) cam.  Up the featured face to top of the leaning rock.    Route can be continued at a fairly low grade to the summit ridge of the Taco.  Descend from there.    Or...use the fixed anchor at the top of the leaning hunk of rock on "Not a Taco".  Unknown how much of this route shares with the sport route "Not a Taco".  As such, presented here for historical perspective.

name: Molé Poblano
description: Scramble ontop of large detached flake to reach first bolt.  Continue to the top clipping a few more bolts to a chain anchor.

name: Nacho Libre
description: Chimney up the leaning block, clip one bolt in the chimney, place a cam where the chimney pinches off. Clip two more on your way to the top.  Traverse to the right and use "Vote for Pedro" anchors.

name: Not a Taco
description: Crux is start or slabby moves left after 4th or so bolt

name: South Ridge
description: Start like the name implies in a fun hand craft in a dihedral at the base of the South ridge. Jam up the corner until you can reach the large horn and pull onto the slab of the ridge line.  A bit run out on the ridge but a bolt can be clipped about mid-way. Cruise up the ridge line to the top and use anchors for "Mole' Plablano" on the West Side.

name: Taco Chip
description: Fun, mostly bolted route up the center of the slab.

name: Taco Supreme
description: A great line that starts off with some intricate moves on superb stone with interesting feature. The crux is getting past the third bolt by negotiating a small overlap. Delicate friction and edging while deciphering the unique holds will get you through it. The route lets off for a bit, only to re-engage you for the last thirty feet on pronounced smears. The rock is course textured yet surprisingly solid and non-gritty.

name: Taco Time
description: Just left of the tunnel, climb the nice slabby face past bolts and a couple of gear placments to a chain anchor.

name: Vote for Pedro
description: A stiff slabby start leads to easier fun moves above.

name: Cleft Palace
description: Climb the face just right of Gullet, ending at a lower anchor. Clip two bolts on the low-angle part then head to your right. Bolts follow a jagged arete then up to slab.

name: Elf's Cap
description: Mixed. Mostly bolts with 2 gear placements in largish cracks. This is a well bolted, very fun line. The grade from the guidebook seems about right.

name: Gullet
description: From DB's 2016 guide: "Start in the back of the alcove and move right, finishing with a short crack. Chain anchor."    My climbing partner and I clipped four bolts going up to the back of the alcove then could find no more going off to climber's right. I think here it must be all gear to the top following a good-looking large hand crack, though we didn't get to do that since we didn't bring gear.

name: The Patriot
description: From DB's 2016 guide: "Start in the back of the alcove with the wooden bench and move left and up to chains. Bolted on lead." Clip your first two bolts (one on very low-angle, the other another 10 feet up) then start looking left. Do not clip the next two bolts higher up the alcove -- these seem to go nowhere at all! 7 or 8 more bolts along some nice classic Castle granite up to some solid 5.9 slab.

name: Big Kahuna - PERMANENTLY CLOSED TO CLIMBING!!
description: Step up, clip, then make an awkward and kinda tricky traverse to the left.  Fight the pump, find a clippin' jug, then head straight up.  Gets easier higher (thankfully).  Fun!

name: Blue Crush - PERMANENTLY CLOSED TO CLIMBING!!
description: Thin start leads to shallow left facing crack which will readily accept your medium cam (.75 camalot or equivalent).  Milk this crack for pro and take advantage of holds either side.  Continue up, gettin' good protection with more cams until a step back right finishes at the KP 109 fixed anchor.

name: KP 109 - PERMANENTLY CLOSED TO CLIMBING!!
description: Start with a thin move near the bottom which leads to fun, steep jugs.

name: Point Break - PERMANENTLY CLOSED TO CLIMBING!!
description: Tricky thin at the bottom.  Gets easier the higher you go.

name: Riding Giants - PERMANENTLY CLOSED TO CLIMBING!!
description: Fun climbing up the chimney (5.3-ish) leads to the thin, steep face above.  Thin climbing, poorly protected with dubious thin cams up the steep face.  Take advantage of all potential gear placements.  Thin cams seem to work in some shallow cracks.    Near the top, theres a shallow pod feature with a corner crack which accepts larger cams (whew).    Take care.  This is a thin lead demanding a cool head and very honed gear placing skills.  A fall from above the chimney could have dire consequences (especially if your gear pulls).    That said, the climbing is fun and the rock pretty good.  Test all holds as this hasn't seen much if any traffic.  Go lightly and be solid.

name: Tidal Wave - PERMANENTLY CLOSED TO CLIMBING!!
description: The moves may seem hard to find from the bottom but once you get up on the wall the holds are all there. This is the funnest route on the wall and well worth the hike. The summit of this wall can be reached by scrambling up from these chains, be very careful getting back to the chains.

name: Cartwheel
description: Climb straight up the crack in a corner. Diagonal left on a face protected by one bolt.

name: Handstand
description: Follow the bolts straight up the face.

name: Squish
description: Start at a bush on the west side of the rock. Scramble 20' up to the first bolt, right of an arete.

name: Blarney Stone - PERMANENTLY CLOSED TO CLIMBING!!
description: Slab move start, low angle face left of crack, steeper face above.

name: Alpinista Sista
description: The new book says 3 pitches but i think the second set of anchors is intended for the decent and can easily be done in 2.  Great route with varied climbing and a fun mantle move.  A little grainy but with a little more traffic should clean up nicely.

name: B Bro
description: By the end of this route I was calling it the Chocolate Rib.  That should be its name.    This is in the Bingham Guide to the area.     First pitch melow 5.8.    Second pitch is tricky and steeper...cruxy.    Third pitches is Full Value 5.9.  Maybe 5.9+.  Exciting trad climbing leads to bolted slabby arete rib feature sweet patina.  Rap from chains.    Hardest 5.9 on Bracksieks Pillar.       We had two 60 meter ropes for descending.  We rapped back to top of Lil Buckaroo in one rap.

name: Coo Coo Cachoo
description: Starts on a slabby rib with some interesting moves. Second pitch is amazing, fun, slightly overhanging, patina surfing goodness.

name: Cool Crack
description: This route ends with the beautiful slightly overhanging thumbstack and thin hands crack.  Crack Class shares the less than vertical top.  The first pitch is full value with an akward thin slot .  Building an anchor as close to the crack on the second pitch will really help out.

name: Crack Class
description: Super route! Start with a curving finger crack (10a) then jam up a nice splitter from fingers to large hands to a ledge. Belay here.  Next, Chimney up behind the unprotected giant leaning block,  Once on top of the block traverse climbers left to where the block ends, locate hand crack on opposite wall, sack up and step across from the block to the main wall ( a fall here would be bad) and jam up the fun 5.8 hand crack.  Build anchor on top and rap down " Pre-Emptive Strike" on the North West Side.

name: Eye-Full Tower
description: Climb up the huge plates on steep jugs finishing at the belay anchor atop the first pitch.  100'.  Ascend to the right, then up face to corner to top of spire.  60'.  Rappel route.

name: High Center
description: Climb up and clip the first two bolts on the face to the right (2nd pitch of Eye-Full Tower).  Use of a long runner on the second bolt will help with any rope drag.  Traverse to the right across and up the lower angle ramp in the middle of the face to the corner to the right and continue to the belay anchor (hanging) just below the summit rim.

name: L'il Buckeroo
description: One Pitch, Bolts to a Chain Anchor.

name: Lucy in the Sky
description: This is the attractive finger crack in a left-facing corner above the first pitch of Alpinista Sista.  Unfortunately, the climbing is not as enjoyable as it looks because the crack is abrasive and the surrounding face is grainy.  From the spacious ledge atop the first pitch of Alpinista, face climb to the crack then persevere until several feet below a tree.  Step out left and join the last few moves of Alpinista to the chains, or if a real glutton for punishment, lunge for the tree then ascend the mossy, rotten, wide crack above.

name: Mano Izquierda
description: Furthest left route on Bracksiek's Pillar's East face. Climb the 5.8 approach pitch as for B Bro and Lil Buckaroo but from the chains below B Bro continue left of the trough on a bolt line. Pull a fun mantle move to gradually steepening slab climbing. Clip the rap chains mid pitch at a patina face and keep climbing onto another slab and to the top of the feature. Fun varied climbing that is protected well.    We descended with 3 rappels with a 70m rope.

name: Mid-Eye Collision
description: Bolts and Small Gear lead up to Eye-Full Tower's anchors.

name: Oatmeal Stout
description: Climb the first pitch of Crack Class.  When you get to the top of the first pitch build your anchor low, because you wont want it in your way as you head straight up the steep finger crack.  Crank through the first 20-30' and enjoy the ride to the top.  One of the best routes in the area.

name: Pre-Emptive Strike
description: Climbing is on excellent patina granite, pulling on significant jugs/edges. Start with a difficult side pull/balance move off the deck and move up the patina face. 10 feet of easy 5.10 and then cruise the rest of the route at 5.7. There is a second set of anchors at approx 50 feet up so the route can be broken into two pitches if desired. (and also rappelled in two pitches). We used a 70 meter rope and did one  pitch lead and rappel.

name: Twilight Years
description: This is a fun route that has some interesting moves down low and then fun jug hauling up high. After climbing easily to the first clip, moving past a thin-hands crack (placing a cam along the way if you like), and clipping the next bolt, things get interesting. Make crux moves past the next few bolts to a good ledge. Some bolts down low cannot be easily seen from the starting ledge but show up when you need them. After gaining a ledge with a no-hands rest, continue more easily to the top on big holds.    (The route name was obtained from the guidebook to the park by Dave Bingham.)

name: Down And Out
description: Lots of hard climbing. Follow the nice diagonalling hand crack on the west face that starts about 60' right of 'iron cross'.  Move toward a roof just to the right of the arete and step down and join 'iron cross'.  The step across places you several feet above a blue/green alien size piece - hence the pg-13 rating.  Belay on the face to the left of the arete and get ready for the crux on 'iron cross'.

name: Dungeon Master
description: Poorly protected but mostly low angle slabbing.  Added to the database for historical perspective.  Very sparse protection up rock that was sorta loose.  Loose plates on the first pitch.  Rappel was from a black sling off the summit down the west side from a knot block in a crack.

name: Figure Four
description: An obvious line up the weakness in the west face of this formation.  An interesting and wide move utilizing a figure 4 move on a horn forms the crux of the route.

name: Iron Cross
description: A beautiful line that moves under the large roof and escapes to a ramp to the right of the steep N face (shown in photo for Figure 4).

name: North by Northwest
description: As you may guess this route can be found on the N by NW corner of the formation.  One can scramble up the first 40' slab to belay at a bench or climb this in 2 pitches.  Great, well protected climbing in an airy setting.

name: Get 'er Done
description: Good climb, all bolts, several hard spots - including the start.

name: Let 'er Buck
description: Fun climb, all bolts.  The left hand bolted climb on the east side of the Duke.  A bit hard to clean.  Best to have the second follow to clean.

name: Flaring Chosswidth - PERMANENTLY CLOSED TO CLIMBING!!
description: Start (or better yet, turn around) on the S corner of this formation follow poorly protected crumbling face veering to the SE face and create a scary 'anchor' in a pod (80'). Make a difficult balancey smearing move to the right (right off the bad anchor) and continue up into a strenous flaring chimney to summit.

name: Jug Massacre - PERMANENTLY CLOSED TO CLIMBING!!
description: As the name implies, this route is crazy, juggy, hueco goodness just waiting to be slayed by your climbing prowess.  The first crux between the first and second bolt feels a bit bouldery, while the second crux is up high and involves a fun deadpoint (height dependent). Overall, this route is super fun and worth the hike in my book, if you are in to moderate sport climbing.

name: Ode to Doda - PERMANENTLY CLOSED TO CLIMBING!!
description: Start on the steep décolletage on the right side of the Jug Wall formation.  Stay well abreast of the protection by milking any available options.    Grope your way up the large jugs.  Plunge in a few snug cam placements.  Augment using slings to harness any suitable protrusions.    Wiggle a large nut into the bosom slot formed by robust cleavage.    Bust slightly left and deposit yourself at the anchor on Jug Massacre, you motorboatingsonofa...    Named for the famous Carol Doda.

name: Begging For A Bolt
description: Great climbing but it needs a bolt in the blank upper section.  Be confident for the grade before heading up.

name: KandK
description: A short route with nice rock and nice flat sandy spot to rope up.

name: A Sand Castle
description: Interesting climbing up what you might guess to be like the slab top outs around. The first bolt is a bit up there but its not too hard to get too. Flip your rope over the feature on the opposite side of the chimney to have pro to reach over to clip the first bolt. Continue up fairly featured rock clipping 6 bolts total to the summit. Bring some chord for the anchor.   There is some exfoliation still but its not bad and will improve with traffic. Fun.

name: Pole Cat - PERMANENTLY CLOSED TO CLIMBING!!
description: Great rock and location with amazing finger and hand crack near the finish.

name: Pole Dancer - PERMANENTLY CLOSED TO CLIMBING!!
description: P1 - fun 10a climbing up a left facing corner to belay atop a small tower (90')?.    P2 - the crux (11a), step right about 15' then hand jam and heel hook up a crack which diagonals up and left on a steep face.  Continue up a beautiful hand crack in a corner and belay where the crack ends near the arete (100'?).    P3 - move left about 20' and up a chimney (10a)(100'?).

name: Pipes of Pan - PERMANENTLY CLOSED TO CLIMBING!!
description: All natural line with some surprises.  The crux is a very interesting and unexpected move at the short left jog indicated in the photo at about 40% up the route. The first pitch ends about 20' after the short jog.  Many potential lines, all easy (5.5 to 5.7) to the summit.  Photo shown with 'Where the Banshees lie'.

name: Where The Banshees Lie - PERMANENTLY CLOSED TO CLIMBING!!
description: The crux is getting out of the chimney about 60' up.  Good rock, but a little rough on the hands.  Nice line.

name: Brokeback
description: A nice, thin face climb on crispy edges.     Steep at the bottom to a break over with a thin pull.  Lower angle run to the anchor.    Well bolted.

name: Rat Writ
description: Starts out fun, then gives way to hard pulls on steep rock.    Steep arete to steep face with thin, crispy holds.    This didn't have to happen if General Sterling Price had been on task.

name: True Grit
description: Great sport climb on the southeast side of True Grit Tower. Face climbing, bolt protected, gets steep at the end.  Lowers with a 70 meter rope.

name: Western Family Values
description: Climb 3 bolts up to a flake. Jam or layback the flake and place gear. Climb 2 more bolts to the anchor. Fun route that feels secure the whole way. A little gritty due to low traffic

name: Animal Cracker
description: Animal Cracker is the prominent flake leading into an offwidth on the Southwest side of Animal Cracker Rock.  Start up the finger crack in the flake, traverse a bit right to a hand crack, then follow the flake up and right.  Finally grunt up the offwidth through a roof to a set of chain anchors.  Rap from here or continue for another pitch.    Pitch 2 angles left into a hand crack.  Climb this, which seams up quickly for a runout, yet easy finish on jugs to the top of the formation.  Gear anchor needed, with a walkoff to the climber's right.

name: Columbine
description: This is a new line on Animal Cracker that showed no sign of passage and we didn't leave much evidence of our ascent either. It's possible that it is an undocumented climb instead of an true first ascent. In any case, this is a good route and deserves some mention and attention.  Start in the clean corner atop the huge boulder left of the route 'The Assassin.' Climb a few features to get up into the crack, place gear and head on up in the corner. Although it gets wide near the top, a few placements are available in the back of the crack, and the climbing quickly eases off the 5.9 grade. Finish up the corner into a chucky 2-2.5" (primarily) crack system that looks steeper from the ground... but holds abound. The climbing here is no harder than 5.8, and mostly 5.7 or below. Ride that to a gear belay on the summit, or just below on one of several shelves, according to what gear you have to set a belay with and what you see.  Bright red 'Western Columbine' flowers were everywhere up there in mid-June.

name: Circus Direct
description: I don't know why I ever even bothered to tie in for this route, but don't make the same mistake. This may well be the worst route at the City. Awkward moves up chossy rock on the arete lead to a desperate reach for the crack of Circus Roof. A better variation is to do any other route in the area besides this one.

name: Circus Roof
description: This climb packs a punch for only being 40ft long.  Start up the right facing corner and traverse under the roof for 15ft.  This climb is well protected and worth the effort. A mid size hex is useful at the lip, in case your second comes off.    Make a some what scary rap from a small tree.  Will it hold?  It did for us...

name: Flyboy
description: This is a great route for morning sun or to avoid the wind.  To start the route, scramble up to the upper ledge from the right side.  You will see a tree at the beginning of the start of the climb.     Follow a handful of bolts and pins up moderate 5.10 face to the crux bulge at the last bolt. It is probably better to rap the route, since the anchor are set back from the top.

name: No Net
description: Follow a some what grainy right facing corner just left of Circus Roof.  This arching feature is worth the effort, if you are in the area.      Rap off chain anchor.

name: Vulture Crack
description: Worthy of a quick spin, the Vulture Crack will deliver entertainment. Solid gear, an aesthetic line, and a rewarding crux make this a good option on a crowded day. Plan on devoting time to this one.      Rack up and belay from the ground then scramble up the slab to reach the start. Begin with a solid hand crack that leads up and into the "vultures den". Crawl out of this trap and forge on to a small, sloping ledge at the base of a dihedral. Follow an excellent crack up for 20 feet to the routes end. Build an anchor.    To descend walk off to the west or north using the anchors of Scream Cheese or Fly Boy to rap.

name: Holding Out For a Hero
description: This route deserves to see more traffic.  The climbing is interesting and the runouts are exciting , but reasonable.     Start the climb from the ground, and follow a thin crack with good gear to the huecoed wall.  The crux is surmounting the first bulge with good gear.  Place some creative gear in one of the huecos, and run it out to a good bolt. This section should be considered "R" rated without this piece of gear. Easier climbing leads to the bolt anchor on Scream Cheese.

name: Scream Cheese
description: This climb goes up the prow next to Swiss Cheese.  It has a fun mix of jugs, face, and slab climbing.  There is a nocticeable runout half way up the route,  but the holds are good.  Rap the route from chains on top.  Probably one of the best 5.9 sport climbs at the City.

name: She Bop
description: This route is located to the left of the cheese alcove.  The good climbing only lasts for about 40ft.  Climb a beautiful thin hand crack to a ledge.  Belay or continue to the top.  Down-climb the chimney to the left or Rap off of Swiss Cheese.

name: Smurf Smasher
description: A small left facing dihedral on the southwest corner of Anteater.

name: Swiss Cheese
description: Most people TR this line after climbing the harder Scream Cheese.  The first bolt is way up there.  A small nut can be placed before the first bolt.  After the second bolt,  you can place a medium hex to the left and a bunch of tiny nuts in a seam.  Pull the final moves around a bulge.

name: track marks
description: Start with powerful layback moves with optional protection via big cam behind flake that can be walked. Work up past more gear and a couple small trees to a good stance, fire up to the crux and get ready to leave skin pulling the roof/flake. You can top out and join up with the anchors on swiss cheese but pro up high isn't great...maybe I'll add a bolt one day.

name: Chip off the Old Block
description: This fun bolted line features technical climbing on smallish holds for the first half and holds that insist on facing the wrong way (read: downward) for the second half.   A few moves on exfoliating choss get you to solid patina jugs and the 2nd bolt. Pull through a steep bulge using funky gastons and sloppy holds and establish below a series of small roofs that all require some form of underclinging to surmount. Keep yourself together when the feet disappear (or lichen renders them useless) and you have to pull one last mantel.

name: The Eviction
description: A bolted line with excellent rock.  Step across crack near the top to stay on bolt line.

name: Like Father, Like Son
description: Short but powerful, this route (boulder problem?) is definitely worth doing if you're wandering around the area.    A thin start on crimps brings you to hidden jugs that pepper the route through its 3 bolts. The further right you go the easier. Sticking to the bolt line is preferred and aiming for the thin diagonal crack can beef things up quite a bit.

name: Cowboy
description: This is a simple route that starts directly across from the Bath Rock parking area. The route varies from guide book to guide book, but basically as a 5.5 it runs straight towards the left crack. It takes the line furthest left of the tree on the face. The climbing involves moving from one large hand hold to the next.  It is on the east face, and a little left of center. Descend via the back.

name: Cowdog
description: Another nondescript slab that is likely best soloed while your caffeine junkies are still waking up.  Bingham's book shows the route following a large crack/flake below the tree, but the slab either right or left of it is more enjoyable imo.  If you take this route, enjoy placing pretend protection in the form of thin slings over marginal "horns".  Don't bother tying anything off, just extend them REALLY long and put some weight on them.  In other words, drag the rope up for others, but leave the gear on the ground.  The tree is a tank and 1 cord around it will work.  Please reference John Long's excellent book about climbing anchors to correctly hitch the tree.

name: Cowgirl
description: A fine climb up the east face of Bath Rock, this route is a classic romp and a must do for every City of Rocks visitor. Easily the best line, Cowgirl is primarily solo'd and "juggy" in nature, expect minimal protection. The climbing is very forgiving and offers a relaxed outing with plenty of opportunities for rests.     Begin with an easy pitch on the east face's mid-left side. Locate a large, prominent crack (Easy Way Up) and start on the face below the end of this crack. Saddle up here and head straight into a large scoop. If using a rope, build a belay at the base of the steep face, or continue climbing. Ascend the steep face ending to the left of a large tree.

name: Eastside Groove
description: This route follows the main crack line towards the Northern end of the East Face. It may be possible to do this as one pitch with a 70 meter rope.

name: Easy Way Up
description: On the east face of Bath Rock, slab up the runout lower face on the left of the lower inclined area.  Belay here.  Move to the leftward trending flake/squeeze chimney that attains the saddle summit.  Enjoy the stagnant bath water up top.  Descend via the rebar steps on the west face.

name: Epic
description: This is a great warmup climb to start things off in the city.  When facing Bath Rock from the Bath Rock parking lot, East face, this is the major crack you see on the far right.  The crack has a few wide sections, but the face is easy so you can always step out of a few friction moves.  The climb is easy to protect.      Descend down rebar route on the back side.

name: Soap on a Rope
description: This line is another fun but runout route up the east face of Bath Rock.  Start up on a shelf to the right of the Cowboy Route, below a right leaning flake system. Follow this 4-6 inch crack (5.4) until it cuts back to the left.  A few fun hand crack moves leads to some horizontal cracks. (last gear)  Run it out for 50ft on positive 5.6 climbing to the top.

name: Tree Start
description: This route on the East face of Bath Rock begins in an alcove behind a prominent juniper tree near the sign "Bath Rock." Climb up and then right following some slanting cracks into a prominent dihedral. Follow the dihedral to where it steepens and set a belay. Gear belay using larger cams.Several options present here, but following line of least resistance upward initially left to a crack and trending right, up through several overlaps to a notch at the top of the rock. Gear anchor. Also described in the Bingham guidebook, and rated 5.5*

name: Euro Beast
description: A short route that is very steep, especially for the City.  Scramble up high to the first bolt.  Easy climbing leads to an overhung wall with huge holds and large moves. After clipping the last bolt on the face, you run into the crux. Throw into a slippery under cling and attempt to mantle out the dihedral to the chains. Holds and feet are sharp without much polish. Super fun!

name: Old Route
description: Actually, on the south east side of Bath Rock - staring you in the face every time you drive up the road.  Starts on a slab where a tongue of rock touches the ground.  First pitch is 5.7 and has two or three places for protection.  Belay in a scooped out dish below a steep headwall with a mid size cam.      Move right and climb the steep headwall using two crack systems for protection.  Probably not a good pitch as your first 5.8 trad lead.  A little grainie near the top, but should clean up if anyone ever does it again.    Belay on top by looping the rope around a large block on the edge.

name: The Pope Got Pumped
description: This pumpy route is located on the south face of Bath Rock. Do a 4th class approach to the upper ledge below a small tree. Traverse straight right for 20-25ft to the first bolt. (optional #1 camalot) Follow well protected climbing through a small bulge to the main event.  A large 6-8ft roof with huecos is the crux. The route finding is difficult, since the clock is ticking.  Pick the right path and you might be a saint.

name: Pope's on a Date
description: This is an exciting and interesting route for a sport climb.  The rock quality is a little lacking, but the moves are fun to work out.      Follow three easy to see bolts through a ledgey headwall.  Work up the white slab to a cruxy mantle above the lip of the roof.  A final fiction/tension crux leads the the anchors. Be careful of the rope drag due to the wandering nature of the route.

name: Sunday Meeting
description: This route starts with 1-2 hard to see bolts to the right of Pope's on a Date.  Follow the runout slab to the arching face above the roof system.  Join Pope on a Date for the final crux moves to the anchor.    Rap with a 60M rope...

name: Calamari
description: Powerful sustained climbing on not-always-so-positive huecos. Body tension useful on this one!

name: Immortal Porpoises
description: Wander up the slab or traverse from climber's left to the base of the route which starts in a left-facing corner with a small crack in the back. You then traverse up and right along a 3-4 foot crack to another short crack/small corner that leads to the bottom of the face/pillar that takes you to the top.

name: Prey for Me
description: A good route that climbs a heavily featured arete.     Trickier than it looks, the aesthetic Prey for Me ascends an ever steepening face using shallow pockets and mis-leading patina edges. Awkward and off-balance, Prey for Me keeps you alert! Not a gimmie for the grade.

name: White Hueco's
description: This steep route is located on the SW corner of the rock and enjoys some late evening rays away from the crowded west face.  You can belay from the ground, but a 4th class approach will deposit you on a ledge below the climb.     Follow "white huecos" through overhanging rock.  There are a number of route finding cruxes, which add to the pump factor. The third bolt is poorly placed and levers your biner open, so be careful. You can place some optional gear along the way, and you should consider an anchor if you belay on the upper ledge system.

name: Coffee and Cornflakes
description: AKA: Scream Machine    This route is located on the far right side of the back side of Bath Rock. It is the bolted route two feet right of the actual Coffee and Cornflakes (5.11X, 80's) The first bolt is 35ft up.  If you start on the right there is no gear.  You can start as for Donini's Crack and clip the Gemini bolt on the way to the first bolt.      This is a fun steep 5.10, and very pumpy for the 5.10a grade.  3 or 4 bolts lead to a 2 bolt anchor.

name: Colossus
description: This is the most popular line on the back side of Bath.  Start just right of Private Idaho.  The climb trends left through a low roof.  The crux is pulling left through the large hueco at about 60ft.

name: Donini's Crack
description: This is a classic tough roof crack on the back side of Bath Rock.  Many try this route, but but few succeed. It is probably a little bit of a sandbag.    Start below the obvious roof crack.  You can clip a bolt on Gemini 5.12a near the beginning.  Work up under the roof and fire in some thin hand gear.  If you are tall,  you can get a no hands sit down rest below the roof.      Jam the thin hand crack through the roof. (tape!!)  Face holds can be found on the left and right.  Picking the right moves and getting your feet in the crack, will gain a rest above the roof.  An easier hand crack leads to the bolt anchor on the sport climb to the left.    I heard a rumor that Donini came back and solo'ed this thing in his 60's.

name: Gemini
description: An outstanding route with multiple cruxes. The name Gemini comes from a roller coaster at Lagoon in Utah, but it also suggests the route's two characters—thin razor edges to big jugs and vice versa.

name: Loch Ness Monster
description: The obvious sport climb up the rib/roof.  Some gear is useful to get to the first bolt.  Follow the rib on the left side and traverse below the roof.  A few desperate slaps will set you up for pulling the bulge.  A hard traverse leads back left.  Get a rest and fire up the technical and pumpy finish.

name: Maximum Impact
description: Easy steep slabs to a ledge suitable for considering your priorities. Pull through a wild roof move (think knee bar above the head, transitioning to something that can only be described as a "drop-knee-bar") and resume moderate climbing.

name: Private Idaho
description: Located on the back side of Bath Rock, just left of Colossus.   Classic Crack Climbing! Climb the obvious crack in the large open book. Move Left at the crux 70' up to keep it 5.9. Straight up might be slightly harder.     Edit: Apparently I got this wrong, don't go left or you will be cheating. Although going left is a lot of fun.

name: Rollercoaster
description: AKA: Broken Face. Just left of Private Idaho is this face that is easily top-roped, after climbing Private Idaho.  Simple straight-forward C of R climbing.  A bit flaky.

name: Tarantula
description: This route fires the center of the west face and is immediately left of Loch Ness.  The bolts leading up to the steep scoop are very run out, but can be supplemented with a few small cams in horizontal seams between the bolts.  At the beginning of the steep scoop, the climb angles up and slightly left through a thin overhanging crux on small crimps.  The sequence is difficult to unlock, but the moves are great and the route is classic City of Rocks enjoyment.

name: The Whip
description: Climb up to the roof passing two spaced out bolts on some easy climbing (no harder than 5.10+). Clip the third bolt on the headwall and duck back into the cave for a no-hands rest. Pull the roof and navigate up the headwall with super small crimps and one jug. Finish off on the chain anchors shared with Loch Ness Monster.

name: Wild Country
description: This route is true to its title, with finicky gear placements all the way up a trending quartz dike. Start out in the thin seam just right of Colossus. Tip toe up the dike until the roof, where some mighty movements await with fairly marginal gear. The crux entails some gymnastic movement on jugs with wild knee scumming, and a desperate move off a pinch to the god send jug. Pull up onto headwall and tip toe up and right to Tarantulas anchors. Try and safe all your juice for the roof and above. All together, a VERY engaging climb and well worth a go!

name: Beef Jello
description: Kimber Almond told me when he was exploring in the Circle Creek drainage and found this crack in the 90's that he was shocked no one had yet climbed it. He said he cleaned out the moss and lichen and discovered a sweet little yosemite like finger/hand crack in a corner.    The crux comes about mid way, and is easily overcome with some liebacking. Patina face holds adorn the right wall of this vertical right-facing route. I would agree with Bingham's guide, and give this climb 3 stars if not for the long approach for only two climbs on the formation, and shortness of the route. A budding 11a leader would likely appreciate this climb more than anyone.

name: NBD
description: Ascends the obvious (and no doubt climbed a number of years ago) crack system on the NE side of BFD Rock.    Face climb directly above the boulders at the base.  The "A" shaped face converges into a single hand/fist sized crack (past a couple of small bushes) which is climbed to a ledge.  Climb to the summit with no pro (30' 5.5) on crumbly rock, or, belay at the ledge.

name: The Smell
description: This is a great and tough route that is overhanging and full of sharp crimps. Scramble to the top of the large ledge with your belayer to start the route. Stick-clipping the first bolt would be a smart idea.    The first two bolts are accessed by pulling on small crimps, making V5 moves. Large edges and small jugs help you run it out to the third both that is very awkward to clip because of the nasty small roof you have to fiddle with. Continue using sharp edges to pass more bolts, using good footwork. After clipping the last bolt, head left on two positive, but small, crimpers to slap the sloppers to top out. Once you are on top of the route, traverse back right to clip the anchors.

name: WTF
description: An open chimney leads to a steep face with just enough features and protection to keep it from being too spicy.    Climb up the open slot, chimney up and step left working the nice handholds.  Follow weaknesses and protection options slanting slightly left until possible to go straight up to short roof (horizontal crack for gear).  Pull roof, and, build belay anchor on top.

name: Do Rangers Dream of Electric Sheep?
description: This little gem deserves more love.  Bingham's guide (2004 version) shows this as more or less as a straight-line and derides it as "contrived" and taking the "line of most resistance," but we climbed the face linking together incipient cracks and horizontals for pro which made for a great climb -- sowewhat reminiscent of the wandering nature of Beware of Nesting Egos (albeit shorter and the rock is not as good) and neither contrived nor unreasonably protected.   Done as described here, this is the best 5.10 on the crag IMO.     Start by scrambling up a low-angle pillar-like formation and leaning across to a thin crack that leads to a horizontal.  From here angle right past a bolt (SMC hanger, and it looks like a quarter-inch sleeve bolt, so look for options to back it up) to another thin crack.  From there, angle back left to the chains.

name: Good Enough for Government Work
description: A nice line in a well shaded corridor.  Two obvious crack system begin about 15 feet off the ground. Good Enough for Government Work follows the right hand crack.  Starts with flaky rock and stiff moves before engaging the crack above.

name: The Ranger's a Psycho
description: Look for the two bolt above a good sized "bush". This climb starts on small crimpers past two bolts to a finger size crack the rest of the way up.

name: Scene of the Crime
description: A fun technical sport route between The Ranger's a Psycho and Good Enough for Government Work. It shares the anchors with both those routes and you can practically start this route on either of the two mentioned routes, although you are suppose to start it on Good Enough for Government work.

name: Where Rangers Retire
description: Starting from the top of a nearby boulder (or, alternatively, pursuing a 5.0 chimney), clip the first bolt into a crimpy and difficult start. Vertical crimp management ensues between healthily spaced bolts. The end verges into slightly R arete terrain that is easy.

name: Boxtop Crack
description: Awesome hand crack just outside of the Corridor. Climb the splitter and then traverse left along and up ledges to the anchor on Corridor Crack.

name: Boxtop Traverse
description: From Corridor Crack anchors, move right under the Boxtop summit block.  Fun hand traverse under the summit block, a helmet will keep you from banging your head.  Birth canal finishes the second pitch.  Access the large ledge to build gear anchor and belay second (minimizes rope drag). 3 bolts to summit pitch and rap chains.  Rap back to Boxtop Corridor on 60m rope.

name: Corridor Crack
description: Finger crack to chain anchors.  Might use as first pitch of Boxtop Traverse.

name: Gravy on the Cake
description: Route to the top of the summit block of the Boxtop.  Face climb up the NE side of the summit block from the flat staging area at the base of the north side of the block.  A bottom belay anchor can be had with hand to bigger cams in the crack formed by the block at one's feet.  Three lead bolts.  A sling could also be used on a horn.  Two bolt chain top anchor on top of route (and block summit).  Approach from the Boxtop Traverse, Master Mechanic or by a grumpy scramble up right of Master Mechanic.  Most reasonable route to the summit?  Certainly safer climbing than the OG route to its left.  Commonly done as the last pitch to the Boxtop Traverse route.  I'll take, "what is a malaphor?" for 100, Alex.

name: Land of the Lost
description: A tricky boulder start leads to the right-leaning diagonal off-width.  Place an optional cam here and then move up and clip a bolt around the corner, then pull around to the face.  From here the climbing is high quality face climbing to the anchors.  The crux is on the face low down but the climbing remains interesting the whole way.

name: Master Mechanic
description: This committing route starts out with a bang.  Traverse in from the right and make the first clip.  A dynamic move to a good hold and a few balancy moves around the 2nd clip are the crux.  Getting to the 2nd clip is a little heady.  After reachy the jug on the arete, enjoy the fun 5.10 arete moves and the perfect position.

name: Nickle Crack
description: Face climb up features below the capstone across from Corridor Crack.  Crux may be getting to and past the capstone.  Once atop the capstone, climb the crack (faces the Boxtop proper) to the mini summit.  Belay from built anchor set in summit features.  No summit anchor.  Simul rappel from feature, one climber off to the outside, one back inside (and make sure you're both down on the ground prior to letting go of the rappel!!).  This rappel should consume most of a 60m rope so be careful.

name: Routine Expedition
description: Boulder up high to the right-angling off-width, place an optional cam (recommended) and move up and reach around the bulge to make the first bolt clip. Pull around to the face and finish on challenging reachy face moves.  The crux is about half-way up with a long reach on small holds.

name: Summit Block
description: The original summit route on the Boxtop.  Two old quarter inch studs with no hangers indicate a long ago passage.  The studs wouldn't do a good job of protecting against decking if one blew the upper face moves.  Face climbing on reasonable features which aren't as secure as one might like.  The original finish to the Boxtop Traverse.  Best left to a historical top rope ascent.

name: Breezeway
description: This is a pretty good climb that is as easy as it is owing to big secure holds, despite the steep nature of the climb in general and it's wide spots near bulges and leaning sections. Climb up and through the cracks to a crux up near the top (good protection) and finish on the rap to belay before scrambling off to the West.

name: Featured Face
description: A good route with good holds and mostly secure climbing, but little for protection. As such, this makes just as good of a solo as a lead. The holds are good and the rock is solid. This would also be an good beginner TR since the moves are fairly intuitive and no special jamming skills or crimping/smearing/stemming is required- it climbs more like a ladder.

name: Hough's Crack
description: On the North side of the Lower Breadloaf are two obvious 5.7 cracks.  Hough's is the right of the two (the other is called Intruding Dike).  Climb up the crack with an awkward bulge move, then wander left up higher to a handcrack.  Top this out, and set a gear anchor.      To descend, wander up the formation, then look on the east side of the formation for a one rope rappel (60m rope).  This is on top of Bloody Fingers (thin 5.10a crack).

name: Intruding Dike
description: This really good route climbs the nice looking finger and thin hands crack left of Hough's Crack on the north face of the breadloaves.  Probably one of the most popular routes at the City, and with good reason.    Climb the obvious steep and lovely crack - easier than it appears.  Chickenheads abound on the upper section.

name: [Redacted]
description: Plenty of good features on this long, straight forward climb.  Would be a great first time lead for the aspiring trad climber at the city - easy climbing, sufficient places for pro, lots of options for anchor building at top.

name: [Redacted]
description: AKA: Another Jay Goodwin Route. A route with another censored name in Bingham's guide, is a fun mix of climbing.  It starts with some fun face climbing to the lone bolt.  From here you get to a stance below the roof, plug your gear, and pull the roof (crux) as you see fit.  Insecure finger jams greet your attempt though.  The climbing stays fun and insecure through the next steep section.  As the fin on the left narrows the holds get bigger and bigger, but the steepness stays with you.  A great route with sustained climbing makes this route well worth it.

name: [Redacted]
description: AKA: Jay Goodwin Route.    This starts just left of Preteen Sex, this bolted line is a good warmup for the tougher routes on the wall.  5.10a crimps abound, with a little bit of runout.

name: Adolescent Homosapien
description: Adolescent Homosapien climbs the obvious long hand and finger crack on the west side of Lower Breadloaf. Great continuous climbing leads to the crux just below the top of the climb. An extremely popular route on an extremely popular wall. Walk left a few feet and rap from anchor's near the top of Double Crack.

name: Another Greg Lowe Route (aka Preteen Sex)
description: This route has many unique moves and is stout for the grade. The start is just to the right of the 3-bolt line, Nipples & Clits (5.10a).  Jam and stem up two steep shallow cracks. This looks difficult to protect, but takes a #2 and #3 camalot quite well. Easier terrain up higher leads to a rightward traverse to a thin crack system. Follow this finger crack to the top with a few tough moves along the way.  Rappel with a 60m rope from either the anchors on Sex, Drugs, Rock & Roll (just to the right), or walk to the anchors near Carol's Crack.

name: Bestiality
description: Start on a ramp, and immediately hit the crux.  A vertically placed 00 tcu gives some mental pro to keep you off the approach slab.  You also have the option of a shallowly placed #1 metolius near the 00.  You can also step up before fully committing to the crux and place an even better #1 metolius that you actually feel good about.    After working your feet up and pulling a somewhat interesting side pull while leaning, you step up into the crack and get some good pro.  Follow the corner system to the top.

name: The Big Easy
description: I explored this chimney with a steep fingers to hands start finding it extremely dirty. This may be an old route, but with the amount of loose rock, dead trees, peeling flakes, bones, guano, plants and dirt I think it was unclimbed. I trundled a 2x2x3' rock out of the chimney, scrubbed and scraped lichen, peeling flakes and dug out the dirt. I think it is really fun, well the climb, not the cleaning.    Begin with overhanging finger locks to good hand jam. Keeps getting wider, fists, OW, few more hand jams, small crack on the right, mantle up on big ledge. You can either continue up chimney (5.6) or finish out on finger- hand crack on the left, maybe 10a.

name: Carol's Crack
description: AKA: Double Cracks. This is on the left side of the west face.  It is in deep shade early morning.  It is easy to identify by the closely spaced double cracks that start on top of the large leftward rising ramp.  Scramble up the ramp any way you choose, then jam the fun crack for 50 feet or so until it lowers angle.  No anchor at the top.      To rap, scramble to your right (when facing the cliff) to an anchor.  A one rope rap with a 60m touches down near the ground, where a short scramble off is easy.    The climbing on this is really good, but the upper crack is so short that it is over too quickly!

name: Dimples and Tits
description: AKA: Kibbles and Bits.     A short, but sweet line up the left side of a randomly featured, face.    Begin off the ground up a steep, blank, slab to reach a very high section of edges and holds (A running start may be needed for some takers). Mantle this bulge feature and work left towards the very high first bolt. Continue up and left toward to the second bolt using a sparse amount of holds and careful footwork. Meet the crux near the third bolt using thin crimps, and misleading patina. Finish on positive holds up declining terrain.    A great line that is often skipped because of its high first bolt. If you're comfortable at the grade and/or have a solid head, this lead won't be an issue. Give it a whirl.

name: Divine Decadence
description: This is the larger crack to the immediate right of Carol's Crack.    A good steep crack with interesting moves and good protection.

name: FDC
description: This is a nice mixed bolt and gear route.  There are a few places where you have to climb a bit above your gear, but it is all pretty reasonable.  Nice rock with some good steep climbing near the end.

name: Flesh for Fantasy
description: Flesh for Fantasy climbs moderate cracks to the base of a bolted headwall.  It is easy to approach by rapping to the ledge below the headwall and pulling your rope.      Follow ~4 bolts through thin 5.10 face climbing to an interesting undercling stand up move to a good hold.  It is a one move wonder, but worth the effort.

name: Impotence
description: For most mortals who take a look at Testosterone Test and mumble some excuse about having left some key piece of gear and their best pair of lead testicles in the car, the appropriately named Impotence can offer some redemption. Sure, the line doesn't offer the steep gear-protected shenanigans of its angry neighbor but it packs some nice punches of its own... Just in case, check your man parts for proper function after getting off this one (ladies are obviously immune).     Prepare to get slapped around right at the start with a scary rail traverse: no feet, no pro and a long ways to the first bolt above a slopping slab (read: stick clip). Once established on the rail, get ready for an ass-whooping as you negotiate thin slabby terrain with a looming chunk of rock at your back (dabbing discouraged or take 2 letter-grades off). Try to stay unfazed when the crux comes at you swinging with a rough high-step to a precarious perch. Regroup at a decent rest below a small roof and a pin then fire up the last easier section on great patina jugs. Scamper left to the chains of TT. Consider the necessity of adding 5.10e to the YDS.

name: Loafers
description: Loafers is a reasonable "more of same" sort of line on this face.  It does not have a particular place, other than being on the face to the right of the Quartz Dike on 'Dykes on Harleys' and left of the Lowe Route.  Without worrying too much about where it goes, most climbers looking for the intersection of the easiest line with some protection, starting just above the ramp of D.O.H. will probably encounter a similar experience.

name: Lowe Route
description: According to the Bingham guidebook: "This Lowe Route is a continuous crack line with decent pro and lots of face holds."

name: McKenzie's Crack
description: Nice little finger/hand crack to nowhere. 8 yr old, McKenzie's first possible FA with D. Tyler.

name: Pluton Playground
description: The route follows a gully-chimney, and is best climbed left side in; upwards movement is facilitated by profuse, positive holds on the right face. Pro possibilities abound. Only occasionally are any chimney-type moves required, and those only for rests while finding the chickenheads and huecos on the face. The well-featured rock salvages what would otherwise be a grovel fest "Bomb" from obscurity.    Descend to climber's left down the chimney; we stayed roped for this and caution is advised.      The climbing is suitble for beginners, but the descent is a bit sketchy.

name: Sex, Drugs and Rock & Roll
description: This route has an interesting bulge right at the first clip.  The next 3 bolts or so cover easy ground to a final steep juggy wall.

name: Sexual Dysfunction
description: An "evil" route with hard presses, thin feet, tough liebacking and awesomely funky moves.   Fun in a sad way, cool moves, but involves some figuring out to get the beta that works for you.

name: Testosterone Test
description: This is a great route with a couple powerful sequences.  Start in a hard lieback past a bolt and then a dicey mantle.  Climb up into an undercling crack with gear and then a powerful section past a fixed Lost Arrow.  Then another tricky section past a bolt on a bulge then climb over more bulges with okay gear to the top.  A great line with some great climbing!

name: Too Much Testosterone
description: TMT shares the start with Testosterone Test, but at the undercling diagonalling horizontal crack below the knife blade on TT, TMT traverses left on all natural gear to the patina'd overhanging arete. The first crux establishes one on the arete. Cams in horizontals protect the climbing all the way to the top, where TMT ultimately traverses back right to share the TT anchors. TMT surmounts a bouldery roof about 20 feet left of the final TT roof, ignoring and staying to the left of a random bolt that may be an old forgotten Boyle route (or an unfinished concept). Pulling this bulge/roof is route's crux-good cams in horizontals 10 feet below you. Fun climbing and a good challenge, despite the folly of skipping the old bolt. One of the only routes I know of like it at the City of Rocks.

name: Twilight
description: This is a decently long route that starts up a crack and crosses over a small fin to the left and then continues up another crack/groove system.

name: Easy Corner
description: This route is on the East side of the Lower Breadloaves AKA Provo Wall.  Although you can park at the West side of the Breadloaves parking lot and hike around, it is easier to park near the campsite, cross the road, and hike up the hill. This route is in a corner with a trough and has an obvious bulge you must climb around about 3/4 the way up.     This climb starts out with a thin hand crack. Climb up around a bulge and then move out onto a pocketed face of easy climbing. Rappel by scrambling down to the right and using Something Sporting anchors.

name: Finer Niner
description: scramble up putting in an optional piece in the flake (not really needed but its there if you want it) to the first bolt.  fun move out to the right and up face.  continue straight up to chains.  you can climb a slightly contrived version by not using any of the jugs off left. either way its about an 8 or 9.

name: Forgotten Trails
