The first 4 pitches and the last 2 are slabby and relatively easy. Pitch 2 is the hardest of these slabby sections and works lright of a roof band. Pitches 4 and 5 can be combined if desired.Pitch 5 climbs up the vertical quartz vein for 60 feet. The final pitch is more of a scramble to gain the summit than a climb.  During the approach, pay attention to the beginning of the route as it easily missed. As you are hiking up the hill on the east side you scramble on the slab forming the bottom of the dome. The climb starts in this vicinity. First time I climbed this we missed it completely and ended up FS'ing it up to the 1st anchors without realizing we had missed it.

name: Southeast Face
description: Pitch 1:  Climb crack through roof or climb left of roof on face protected by 2 bolts.  Then traverse right to slab climbing protected by two more bolts.  Climb straight up to belay on ledge on ramp heading left. 5.8    Pitch 2:  Follow ramp up left to climb a wide crack.  After the crack move right on to a ridge/ fin with one bolt on it.  Follow the fin up and left to a ledge and belay just above the ledge next to big hole in rock. 5.7    Pitch 3: Climb a easy ramp to short crack to the right.  Set belay above crack on slab to allow for easier communication or continue up easy chimney until rope runs out. 5.6    Pitch 4: Continue up easy slab and cracks to the top.  There are alternate cracks to follow to the top on the right all are no harder then 5.7

name: Southern Arches
description: When looking at a topo photo of Steinfell's Dome, the Southern Arches route is likely to stick out the most because it goes from the toe of the dome to the summit in a nice, direct line. The climbing is adventurous with only one old button head bolt as the only fixed gear on the route and easy but run-out slab climbing on the first pitch. Be prepared to do a fair bit of route finding and build your own anchors. This is a fun and rewarding outing on one of the City's most prominent formations. To keep the adventurous spirit of the route, consider stopping reading here and going out to pick your way up this line on intuition. But if you want a few more details, read on.  Pitch 1: Start from a small ledge directly below a steep, moss covered crack and flake and pull up through this to get established on the dome. Work your way up slabby sections between obvious cracks and flakes for protection to a big, obvious left-trending crack/trough. Your eventual goal is the big sideways "V" flake about half way up the dome. Head towards that and run out your 70m rope to a good belay stance in the trough about 60m below the big sideways "V" flake. 70m (5.8)  Pitch 2: Continue up the trough/crack and onto a small ledge. Work up past another flake and crack just below the big sideways V flake. Clip the only piece of fixed protection on the route, an ancient buttonhead bolt and hanger, on the face below the big V flake. Make the crux moves up the face to grab the big V flake and take a sigh of relief (#3 cam). Trend right along this flake and mantle up on top of continue. Cruise the flake's left-trending trough to a belay stance at its top in a baby alcove. 70m. (5.8+)  Pitch 3: Climb around the corner bulge of the alcove to the left and onto a face resist the temptation to continue left into the chimney. Instead, face climb back right up steep but positive terrain and pull up onto lower-angle terrain. Follow a good crack on increasingly easier terrain until the rope runs out at a massive ledge. 70m. (5.7).  Pitch 4: By now you'll probably feel safe enough to unrope and cruise the fourth class/low fifth class terrain to the top. Go for it. (Simuling may be a slightly smarter option)

name: Theater of Shadows
description: This route is on the formation just left of Steinfell's Dome when viewed from the parking area.  It climbs the spine facing the road in 4 pitches.  Find the trail that leads towards Steinfell's, and traverse leftwards on trail to reach this subsidiary formation (called Jackson's Thumb).    The climbing is fun, low angled, and very well protected. If you are a little low on quickdraws, there are some spots where you can unclip a bolt at your knees after reaching for the next clip. The view of the City from the top is great.    One rope is all that is necessary, and the descent is very easy.  Two one-rope raps (we had a 60m, not sure if a shorter rope would work?) from fixed stations get you to a major gully.  From here, an easy trail returns you to the base.

name: Cruel Shoes
description: A fun and easier multi pitch route that does top out.  3 pitches, with the option to do one or all, though rapping from any of the belay stations will take two ropes. The rating on the first pitch is 5.6, though it feels harder.  It is all bolts, take 16-20 quickdraws.  The descent is to the left then down a westward tending ramp to a single double rope rappell.

name: Dike of Gastonia
description: Climb the obvious dike on Stripe rock. Scramble up a small Dyke to gain access to an old homemade bolt and then continue onto the roof. This route is very very runout

name: Poly-Stick-Em
description: This route is located left of Cruel Shoes on the east face of Stripe Rock.    Pitch 1- Climb the slab protected by 4 bolts and some gear to a ledge with a small tree and a two bolt anchor.  5.10c    Pitch 2- Face climb steeper rock past 7? bolts to a two bolt belay near a hole.  5.10a    Pitch 3- Climb the slab past more bolts to a two bolt belay.  5.8    Pitch 4- Easier, more runout climbing leads to a two bolt belay near the summit.

name: Easy Movements
description: We started on a flake, that is maybe 5.6, then the slab climbing above is fun and easy to a two bolt anchor. Just to the left, is an ancient 1/4" bolt. Pitch two, is straight friction slab climbing. You can walk off, or, below the top is a knob where a gear anchor can be built to bring up a second.

name: Suncup Slab aka Outhouse Slab
description: The old school classic on what used be Outhouse Slab (RIP the old, nasty outhouse at the parking lot on the left side of the formation).  Start up below the middle of the overlap eyebrow feature.  Traverse left to an easy up.  Clip bolt, easier climbing to the top.

name: Bikini Candy
description: This is about as fun as a single pitch 5.8 sport route gets.    This climbs the lowest piece of Tahitian Rock left of a significant boulder laying against the rock.  The top accesses the gully that Bora Bora start in.    Climb the bolt line with a crux right off the ground.  After moving past the first bolt, this is wonderful steep 5.8 jug hauling.

name: Bora Bora
description: Bora Bora is the leftmost established route on the Tahitian Rocks wall.  It is to the right and uphill from most of the other routes.  It starts in a gully which separtes the upper and lower portions of this rock.    Climb up ricey rock through 7 bolts to a set of chain anchors.  Several moves of 5.9 are found in the middle of the route.  The climbing is a little ricey, which detracts from the overall quality, but hopefully this will improve with time.  A one rope rap with a 60m gets you down.

name: Chip Seal
description: This is a fun climb on good rock. Shares the start with the route to the left for 2 bolts and then pulls some big moves on steep rock with good holds. Move right slightly following some more bolts to a short crack(gear). Climb out of the crack and finish up to the bolted anchor.

name: The Good Stuff
description: reachy start leads to a left going slabby section followed by awesome steep juggy holds!

name: Roratonga
description: This enjoyable route starts in a short crack section with a high first bolt. There are a number of hard to read cruxes as you head up the slab.  An easy roof is passed before you reach the anchor.  Becareful lowering off, since the route is just at 100ft.

name: Fingers and Toads
description: This is the easiest way to the top of Toad Rock. A gear-protected 5.0 that tops out on a cool formation. Excellent first time climb (if you sufficiently extend your anchor; otherwise, your rope drag will be considerable).  After topping out, many opportunities exist for an anchor. For this route, the nice long horizontal crack works well.

name: Mr. Toad's Wild Ride
description: This is the best and most obvious line on the wall. Steep-ish, on giant holds--this route is perfect for brand new climbers who want something other than slab.  Extend your anchor. Use the sturdy tree and back it up with gear.  This is the closest it gets to climbing a ladder--but more fun!

name: Toddlers and Toadstools
description: Another fine line for the new climber. Not too steep, big holds, and not very tall.  Be sure to extend your toprope anchor using a long sling.

name: Chomping at the Bit
description: Located at the far end of the corridor on the left side.  Stem and boulder up chicken heads to reach a ledge below the first bolt.  Climb up right and reach left to clip the first bolt.  Make long moves up jugs and huecos to reach the second bolt.  Depending on your height and style climb left or directly up to the third bolt, first crux.  Climb 30-40 feet of crack and flakes to reach the 4th bolt, placing gear in the crack along the way.  Make technical and reachy moves between the 4th and 5th bolts, second crux to reach the anchor  Clip three bolts which follow nice patina edges then follow a small crack to two more bolts above which take you back to nice patina holds. A bit reachy here and there.

name: Dynamo Hum
description: Start with a bouldery crux directly below the first bolt and head straight up to the first bolt (easier variation: start ~7 feet right of the first bolt and traverse up and left to the first bolt). The crux comes just after the second bolt with thin sharp crimp moves. After this, the route eases off but stays interesting to the finish with great views of the East side of Flaming Rock.

name: Heat Wave
description: This route starts about 10ft left of the finger crack on Vibrator.  Boulder up the the left leaning crack with small cams to the first bolt.  Follow four more bolts with 1 or 2 gear placements to the anchors.  The original route exited left in the leaning crack system.

name: Just a Pretty Day
description: ...Not such a pretty route.  Actually, it's not that bad, just a little dirty at the bottom.    Just a Pretty Day is the rightmost line on the main Transformer face, to the right of Live Wire.  It starts behind a tree in a shallow corner.  You can either stay in the corner the whole way (offwidth) or traverse left on knobs at 25 feet, up a short diagonal crack and then another traverse back right into the corner.  A good hand crack leads up to fingers through a bulge.

name: Live Wire
description: Located on the right side of the wall, start by climbing from the left side of the boulder to the right.  A direct start, while interesting involves strenuous laybacking to rounded holds and a mantle.  Work up the crack using jugs, small feet, and huacos.  Plan on placing extra gear to avoid hitting the ledge. Make strenuous and awkward moves left to gain a nice crack, poor feet on crumbly rock.  Climb up to the first bolt (at 30 feet) continuing on thin face to the final bolt. Move directly left to gain a crack and follow this around a bulge, placing gear and managing rope drag as you go.  Look right to locate the anchor above the bulge.    This route shares the anchors with Short Circuit to its left. The crux is the diagonal starting crack which is some what committing due to the poor feet. Follow a handful bolts and gear placements to chain anchors.

name: Mystery Bolter
description: This route is technically on the east side of Bumblie Rock, but in the Transformer Corridor.  Starts in the chimney and is long with a chimney start that can be a bit tricky.  Lots of dishes and rounded knobs, and bolts, lots of bolts.  2 ropes for the rap.

name: Short Circuit
description: This line is only 5.10a after you reach the first jug.  At 6'4", you can just make the first move static.  After the first move, which is protected by a bolt,  follow fun patina face climbing protected by finger sized cams.  A couple bolts protect the middle section, but save a .75 camalot to protect the moves to the anchors.     This would be a 4 star route, except for the height dependent first move.

name: Vibrator
description: This simulating route starts with crux face moves off the ground, which is typical for this wall.  There is a low bolt to protect the crux, but a .75 camalot is nice to have ready for the upper crack.  Follow the now moderate finger crack to the well protected patina face climbing above.  A .3 camalot in an undercling will protect the runout between bolts.  A fun outing...

name: The Balcony Route
description: Note: This description is for the historical record only. All information contained within is likely outdated and inaccurate. Many, if not all, bolts have been removed from the Twin Sisters formations and climbing on them is illegal. Do not attempt to climb these routes for your own safety and compliance with the law!    This long, lost adventure route is undoubtedly a City classic that weaves a very unlikely path through natural features and threatening roof systems at a reasonably moderate grade. Surely covered in lichen thanks to lack of traffic, climbers, hikers, and vehicle-bound gawkers alike will gaze to or from this climb and feel as if they have been transported back in time to the late 1800's... Is that a wagon train west-bound on the California Trail? Alas no, it is an SUV speeding along the dirt road. Are those settlers in search of land, fortune, and fresh beginnings? Alas, no, those are telephone poles and grazing cattle. What is that glint high up on the wall above you? Could it be an exposed vein of gold? One thing's for sure: It's definitely not a bolt.    P1 (5.9, 130'): Scramble (5.7?) up boulders to gain a belay beneath the obvious, clean handcrack just left of a pillar on the easternmost buttress of the formation. Follow this crack until it peters out beneath a bulge and traverse right underneath this bulge to gain a second, hidden crack system. An ancient bolt once and perhaps still does "protect" this thin traverse. Continue more easily to a belay at a spike atop the pillar. There was once a bolted anchor here but rumor has it it's been removed.    P2 (5.10w is for weird, 80'): It would be real bummer about that missing bolted anchor because this pitch traverses straight right off the belay for 30' before heading straight up for another 30' to a crux roof; the missing anchor would make this situation very difficult for the belayer to provide a good belay for the leader should he or she fall at the roof. And unfortunately protection post-traverse isn't really ideal for setting up what would be a hanging belay out right. Nevertheless, your goal is the giant, chute-like roof. The climbing up to it is scantily protected, but once there good pro is available: at one time there were two decent pins under the roof, but they could possibly be backed up with supplemental gear (though be careful not to occupy a crucial crimp/slot). I've heard that funky, funky moves that seem extremely improbable pull this roof at what might be 5.10c. Upon turning the lip, build a belay at a sloping stance just beneath a striking rattly finger crack below another blocky roof overhead.    P3 (5.10d, 100'): Climb the rattly finger crack to a wide crack to an awkward hand crack through this final roof (crux). Continue more easily up jugs and incuts to the summit.    If there are no anchors on the summit you might have to leave gear, sling a horn, or simply down climb the southern shoulder of the formation (at 5.5 X). There was once an intermediate anchor halfway down this which would allow for a final rappel to the notch between the North and South Sister, though the rappel would be about 40 meters long.     All my info comes second-hand so I cannot vouch for it's accuracy, but I will say this: There is no hope of rescue here; you're on your own.

name: The Lowe Route
description: Note: This description is for the historical record only. All information contained within is likely outdated and inaccurate. Many, if not all, bolts have been removed from the Twin Sisters formations and climbing on them is illegal. Do not attempt to climb these routes for your own safety and compliance with the law!    The Lowe Route is a fun pitch of crack climbing with a great roof crux. Climb a crack at the far left end of the southeast face. A second crack appears just below the roof, but continue up the righthand crack at 5.9 (the splitter through the roof is somewhat contrived 5.10). A brief section of burliness gives way to more enjoyable climbing up the twin cracks. A second pitch supposedly continues onto the south shoulder of North Twin Sister, but it would be very easy to traverse straight right on a large dike/ledge system to the anchors atop Straight Edge if they still existed. Rap from here with a 70m rope.

name: Northeast Shoulder
description: A fun summit route up the NE shoulder of the "Eberhorn - Higher Sister".  For hysterical porpoises.

name: Safecracker
description: Note: This description is for the historical record only. All information contained within is likely outdated and inaccurate. Many, if not all, bolts have been removed from the Twin Sisters formations and climbing on them is illegal. Do not attempt to climb these routes for your own safety and compliance with the law!    Enjoyable, sustained face climbing. This was the only route on the wall that was fully bolt-protected. Unfortunately, it encroached upon its far more stimulating neighbor (Safer than Sex).

name: Straight Edge
description: Note: This description is for the historical record only. All information contained within is likely outdated and inaccurate. Many, if not all, bolts have been removed from the Twin Sisters formations and climbing on them is illegal. Do not attempt to climb these routes for your own safety and compliance with the law!    Excellent face climbing up increasingly bulletproof rock characterizes this lead-bolted test piece. This route began below a very high, very rusty first bolt. Three well-spaced, original bolts once led to a short, protectable crack, then four more original bolts continued up the slabby upper wall to a former anchor (which was in major need of renovation).

name: Camp Site 55
description: If you camp at camp site 55 you will see this problem downhill. Getting established and topping out are the hardest part of this climb.

name: The Flake
description: Make sure there are no bats in the crack before you climb this one.  Follow the left leaning crack to the top.

name: Right Side
description: Follow a leaning crack through poor rock to the top.  The gear is a little suspect in the crack, so a TR might be good idea.

name: White Lightning
description: A very sweet hand crack in a left facing corner.  Steep fun Layback crux. Some nice patina jugs at the top.

name: Excrement Adventure
description: Short face to finger crack to ledge to corner to summit.  We found a sling on the summit from someone, so, not sure the route was an FA but the formation can be ascended from the north and/or east too.    Note:  this route is called "Two Dogs..." in a couple of guidebooks, with an ascent date of 2001.

name: Pale Face
description: Stick clip first bolt. Use crack to traverse to first holds. Power through sustained climbing for 30 feet before jugs to top.

name: Renegade
description: Third climb from from right.

name: Touch of Gray
description: This undocumented route is the farthest to the right on the wall.  Angle up and right past an early crux to an easier finish.

name: Wonderbread
description: A cruxy start leads to easier varished climbing above along a groove.  It is worth doing if you are in the area.

name: Crunk Cowgirl
description: Unnamed crack in the Bingham guidebook. Just right of Drunken Cowboy. Start just right of the big tree at the base of Drunken Cowboy. Work up the crack on low angle slab. Build gear anchor at the top. Rap from the chains above Drunken Cowboy (recommended) or do the 5.easyish chimney down climb to the right.  See beta pic for more information.

name: Deep Dream
description: Start right of the Rated "R" Route and left of Failure to launch. Move up Crack traverse right on small rail. Up the right crack then traverse left to parallel crack. Belay up on horizontal crack about 100-120ft up.

name: Destroy all Planets
description: Named after an old Martian movie, a pretty nice route. Slabby, well protected crux down low into a nice, though somwhat, flaring crack. When the crack gets funky, run it out to the prominent horizontal for some gear, then wander to the top on dishes. Fun long pitch...a little spicy.

name: Drunken Cowboy
description: In the center of the east face on Window Rock are a series of perfect hand cracks that don't quite make it to the ground.  Look for a bolt below the start of two of these cracks.  The left crack is Good Times, and the right crack is Pure Pleasure.  Both are 5.7, and both are enjoyable.  You should do these as well.  Drunken Climber is the crack to the right of these.    There is a tree at the base of the route.  Start at this tree and head up into the crack above you to its end.  Belay on a big ledge with horizontal placements for an anchor.      Descend with a one-rope rappel off a two-bolt anchor located 5 feet to climber's right of the route, landing at the tree where you started.    Note: I don't know what this route is historically called, but ``Drunken Climber'' is what we have always called it.  If you know more about this route, please speak up!

name: Expect No Mercy
description: In the center of the east face on Window Rock is a fist crack that comes down into a large alcove.  This is Expect No Mercy.  Climb the steep face past a couple of bolts to the crack.  Pull through this pumpy fist crack roof and jam to the two-bolt anchor.

name: Failure to Launch
description: On the east side of Window Rock is this obvious line, often climbed, but not listed in the latest Bingham guide.  It shares the start (and crux) with Pocket Rocket, stays in the flaring crack until it ends, crosses directly over the horizontal gash/crack about halfway up the route utilizing face holds until a second finger-sized crack is reached.  The first 3-4 moves (poor feet) are 5.9, the rest is 5.7-ish.  Going from one crack to the other may provide a modest runout if protection cannot be found in the horizontal.    NOTE: If a name is in common use for this climb, let's make that change here.

name: Good Times
description: In the center of the east face on Window Rock are a series of perfect hand cracks that don't quite make it to the ground.  Look for a bolt below the start of two of these cracks.  The left crack is Good Times, and the right crack is Pure Pleasure.  Both are 5.7, and both are enjoyable.    There is a tree at the base of the routes to the right.  Start at this tree and traverse left on the slabs to the bolt.  Climb the left crack to its end and belay on a big ledge with horizontal placements for an anchor.  When your second gets up there, go check out the Window up and left of your belay ledge.  Huge bathtubs abound on this rock.    Descend with a one-rope rappel off a two-bolt anchor located 20 feet to climber's right of the route, landing at the tree where you started.

name: Indian Summer
description: Start on the slab just left of the start to Good Times and Pure Pleasure. Climb up to a very thin pinched crack, and continue up as it widens.

name: Juniper Jam
description: This right is about 60 feet right of Pure Pleasure and Good Times.  Scramble up a couple of boulders to a great hand crack with an obvious Juniper growing out of the bottom of it.    This climb has fewer facial features than Good Times and Pure Pleasure and requires more traditional crack technique.     Descend) using the same bolt repel anchors as Good Times and Pure Pleasure.

name: Masochist Crack
description: AKA: Take no Prisoners, this water groove/crack is at the left end of the east face of Window Rock.  The crux is down low.  After the start it's easy low angle climbing to the top.  Belay from trad anchor at top, then walk to north end for one rope rappel.  I enjoyed leading this climb despite the name.

name: Pure Pleasure
description: In the center of the east face on Window Rock are a series of perfect hand cracks that don't quite make it to the ground.  Look for a bolt below the start of two of these cracks.  The left crack is Good Times, and the right crack is Pure Pleasure.  Both are 5.7, and both are enjoyable.    There is a tree at the base of the routes to the right.  Start at this tree and traverse left on the slabs to the bolt.  Climb the right crack to its end and belay on a big ledge with horizontal placements for an anchor.  When your second gets up there, go check out the Window up and left of your belay ledge.  Huge bathtubs abound on this rock.    Descend with a one-rope rappel off a two-bolt anchor located 20 feet to climber's right of the route, landing at the tree where you started.

name: Battle of the Bulges
description: Climb shallow right facing corners thru several tricky bulges.

name: Brutal
description: Starts up Chaos. At the intermediate anchor, head left and shuffle out the ramp, then engage the patina-covered bulge. Sparsely bolted.

name: Chaos
description: Chaos begins on a ledge system about 25-30 feet off the ground. This Ledge can be scrambled in on from the right of the route, or you can also climb and belay direct from the ground to reach the ledge system where the real climbing begins in an big and obvious overhanging right facing corner. The corner requires stemming and lie-backing up cracks and huecos and presents one powerful section before allowing for a rest on a sloping ledge about 35 feet up. Bolt placement seemed less than ideal to me in this corner. After a rest on the sloping ledge, a steep bulge awaits. This bulge can be cheated around, but, that's cheating. Above the bulge is the true crux of the route- a powerful section requiring big moves to hidden holds. Above the crux, the rock gets a bit grainy, and the finish follows a really cool dike feature to the chains- endurance is likely required to hold it together for the redpoint.

name: Fear Factor
description: This is the long route to the right of She's the Bosch, starting on the same little ledge but 40ft right of the start of 'Bosch'.  It climbs up obvious bolts, passing first crux about 50 feet up, then romping through 5.10 terrain, passing a pin in an easy section, to the last headwall, where this route really gets good. This route is LONG! be aware that when lowering with a 70M rope you will definitely not be close to the ground. we left a biner on a bolt to get down.  knot your rope ends!   But definitely get on this route! It is a very nice addition to the area, and as good or better than She's the Bosch.

name: Harvest
description: Some slab, body English, great finger locks, and an offwidth finish sum it up.  Harvest would be a classic except for the bushes in the lower crack.     The climb starts in a lower angle V before going vertical in a flared chimney for a move or 2. The crack moves on to the face with the crux above the small roof where rattly fingers lead to a great hand jam and a desperate move (for me) into the offwidth.    Descend from slings around a chockstone.

name: Jet Lag
description: Jet Lag is an excellent, steep sport route just to the left of She's the Bosch. The climb follows an ill-defined corner system.    Steep laybacking is the ticket, as the corner offers little in the way of footholds. Given the engaging moves and the wonderful position, I'd say Jet Lag is one of the best 5.12s in the City.

name: Reaper
description: Power up the short, flared handcrack in the dihedral a little to the right of Harvest.  Finish on ledge about 30 feet off the deck.

name: She's the Bosch
description: This is THE 5.11 sport climb at the City.  It is a must do,  if you can find 2 ropes and enough draws. :)  The west side of Window rock is closed for the birds in the spring,  so check for closures in the parking lot.    This route is the second sport climb on the right side of the west face.  Scramble up a low 5th class ramp system from the right side of the climb.  There is a single belay bolt on the ramp.  Follow 17 bolts through continuous 5.10 and 5.11 terrain, with a crux at 2/3rd's height coming out of a depression in the wall.  The final 40 ft to the anchor is an endurance test on solid 5.10 climbing.    Rap with 2 ropes.  I have heard that a single 70M rope will work, but I have not tested this theory.

name: Singapore
description: Top 5 best 5.11 crack climbs at the City(IMO). Singapore doesn't get done that often as it has a fierce reputation. The pro is perfect until the end where it starts to flare a little and gets pumpy. Also Check out Battle of the Bulge about 50 yards to the right of Singapore.    Here's your list: Brown Flake(Morning Glory)                     Scar Tissue(The Office)                     Crack of Doom(Morning Glory)                     Terror of Tiny Town(Buzzard)                     Singapore(Window)

name: Camp Cupcake
description: On the south side of the rock in the middle of the wall. Start up a slab then go slightly right then back left to a heady clip. Finish up arete. I climbed past the crux bolt to do a waist clip from the arete.

name: Patina Turner
description: Start up a deep hueco heading for a rusty pin about 15' up. climb up nice patina edges until gear is available, bust a move up to first bolt and continue up striking face with bolts. After the last bolt it mellows out significantly, very worth while route.

name: Yellow Wall
description: A steep, exciting, beautiful line involving nice patina and a sustained section of stemming, this out of the way climb is not to be missed, though my impression is that it rarely makes it on to climbers' agendas because of the approach (which is not bad at all). It would be great to hit this on a busy day when all the roadside classics have lines. Combining it with White Lightning on your way in or out makes for an epic afternoon. Skinner's Roof is also on the approach in.    Start in somewhat of a corner on the right end of the formation, and then after 15 feet or so traverse left into a long stemming section. Keep towards the left as you get to the top, staying on the left side of the protruding diving board above.    The route is somewhere in the range of 100-110 feet. Top roping is not advised due to the poor position of the single-bolt anchor relative to the top-out of the route.    Be careful pulling your rope. The way the single bolt anchor is positioned on top of the formation makes it incredibly easy to get your rope pinched and cemented in. When we arrived at the route there was a rope hanging down the line that looked pretty haggard and wouldn't pull from the bottom.

name: Baggy Eyes
description: So far, this is my favorite route at the crag.  Certainly not a looker, this climb has excellent movement, great pro, and varied climbing the whole way.  Jams, arm bars, sidepulls, finger locks, crimps, it goes on and on.  DO THIS ROUTE!

name: The Crusher
description: This is a chimney of a climb located in a small alcove between two columns.  Bring the wide gear, and use it all in the multiple cracks found in the back of the chimney.  You can easily top rope this climb from the anchors on "Little Bunny's Mother"

name: Duck Dodgers
description: Easily TRd off the anchors on "Kill the Wabbit", this climb climbs between to columns offering a few chimney moves, as well as excellent hand and foot jams when needed.

name: I'm the little Bunny's Mother
description: Spot the first little roof while walking up to the crag, and the lazer line that cut just to its left, and you are exactly where you want to be.  Jam your way up the obvious crack, do some body english to pass the roof on the left and reach for the thank gawd jug above if you suck at jamming, or or just the thank gawd jug cuz the hard part is over.    Climb the remaining narrowing crack to the top anchor located above and slightly left.  As of 5/17/2020 the anchor consists of a bunch of webbing around a block, but can be backed up with a #3 or a #2 if needed.

name: Kill the Wabbit
description: The most obvious crack line in the whole place, and one not to miss while you are here.  A straightforward jamming session plugging and chugging to the top.  I found a spot for a #3 cam, your mileage may vary; but hand size pieces are the best cracks anyhow.

name: 420 variation
description: Climbs ledges for days.

name: Geezer
description: Climb a short bouldery section of the blocks then up jugs and ledges. The Crux can be done on the left or the right. The guide book says 11d or 12a depending on which way you go.

name: Knocked Out Loaded
description: Big holds and big pulls through a seemingly endless line of fixed draws. A sustained jug haul with a couple short tricky sequences thrown in the mix.  Stick clip the first draw and climb in from the left. Move up and left at the first draw. At the sixth draw, follow the draw line straight up (the draws on the left are for Grande Rouge). Rejoin Grande Rouge at the long chain draws (8th draw) and continue to the chains of Slug Bait.

name: Lefty
description: Jugs, jugs, jugs, huge jugs. The crag warm-up. Hang on!  Stick clip the first perma-draw and start on a ledge on the far left side of the Big Cave. Continue climbing right until you reach the second set of anchors from the left (shared with Geezer).

name: Slug Bait
description: Two bouldery sequences separated by some good ole' jug hauling.  Start on a rock stack on the right side of the Big Cave, with a right hand sidepull and a high left hand. Fire through the first boulder problem to a ledge rest. Keep it together through the next boulder problem and finish at the long chain anchors (2nd set from the right, shared with Bachelor Party).

name: Unknown 5.10
description: This route starts left of Lefty and climbs up good holds, trending left to anchor that has one bolt on each side of a corner.

name: Weezer
description: Long climb branching right off of geezer.

name: Churning in the Choss
description: This route shares the start with Small Axe and Telache on big jugs through the first couple of bolts.  The crux is found just after the three routes split when you have to make a bigger move between not quite as good of holds.  Overall a fun route if you can figure out which way to go and not get confused among the sea of quickdraws leading you astray.

name: Corporate Death Burger
description: Bit of a boulder problem down low. Then traverse left and up into the shared anchor.

name: Dirty Sheets
description: My favorite route in the little cave. Several boulder problems, cool holds, and cool moves.

name: Fate Tectonics
description: Small crimps and technical movement down low till you join Plate Tectonics.

name: The Frog
description: This route starts up big jugs to gain the obvious flake.  Make a couple of moves up the flake to some good holds just left of the flake.  The crux arrives at this point as you have to make a couple of moves on smaller slopey holds to get to the clipping hold inside the big black hueco.  Stay on the left side of the hueco on big holds up to the anchor.  The guide book mentions that you can climb into the hueco for a good rest but you won't get the full value out of the route.  Really though, once you are to the hueco the holds are big enough that you shouldn't have any problem hanging onto them.

name: Pig Iron
description: Cool route with a tough crux coming out from the overhang on small holds.

name: Plate tectonics
description: Left most route in the little cave. Starts juggy then a tough little crux.

name: Small Axe
description: This route shares the start with Churning in the Choss and Telache.  Start up the big jugs and stay left at the split.  The bolts are very close to Churning, so the goal is to avoid the bigger holds on Churning to get the 5.11b grade.  Crux comes just after the routes split.

name: Sour Grapes
description: Crimpy start and bad feet to a little throw. Then hit the crux. Finish on same anchors as Dirty Sheets.

name: Telache
description: This route shares the start with Small Axe and Churning in the Choss.  Begin with big jugs for the first couple of bolts, then start heading right on smaller holds.  Make sure to head up instead of continuing to the right for the linkup with Tube Steak and the crux is found in this section as the holds are smaller and the movement is bouldery.

name: Tube Steak
description: Start on Pig Iron but continue right after Pig Iron crux, out the arch.

name: Tube Top
description: Easy huecos and jugs to chains.  Still cleaning up; I broke some rather large holds off.

name: Ahoy Pahoehoe
description: Short overhanging section leads to textured basalt face below anchor. Crux is pulling over roof.

name: Ride the Wave
description: Smooth, wavy rib of nice basalt. This is a good first sport lead and also sets up well for toproping.

name: Scour Power
description: Polished slab with cracks. Crux is around 4th bolt.

name: Battle of the Bulge
description: Techy start to fun pockets leads to break between lava flows and "The Bulge" (crux). Work some magic here and fire through nice edges to anchor.

name: Majid's Laugh
description: Enjoy the sweet pocketed lower wall to a tricky fingertip crack move. Solid jugs await and take you to the crux on the upper lichen face below the anchor. Thanks to Magic Valley Gear Exchange in Twin Falls for technical assistance.

name: Par 3
description: Ascend face and discontinuous thin cracks to a small ledge. Move past ledge (crux) to another ledge before enjoying the sweet crack in the left-facing dihedral.

name: Pinky Power
description: This is a mixed route. Three bolts down low lead to corner and crack. Crux is near third bolt.

name: Ride 'Em Cowboy
description: Small crack in corner leads to small ledge below bomber finger to hand crack with one bolt to right. Route climbs to roof then traverses left following three closely spaced bolts. One final bulge below anchor (crux) completes this fun route.

name: Ropegun Henry
description: Finger crack and sweet pockets lead to featured roof and big holds. Above that, enjoy another great crack/fin and finish on small ledge at anchors. Power crux at roof and a more techy crux up near fifth bolt. Thanks to Magic Valley Gear Exchange in Twin Falls for technical assistance.

name: Will-Tay-Mul
description: Awesomely fun pocket shopping leads to small overhang and technical crux moving up and left. Use your mojo to get onto small ledge with one last tricky move to anchors. Thanks to Magic Valley Gear Exchange in Twin Falls for technical assistance.

name: Beavis
description: Hard moves right off the ground, easier up high.   Easy to set up on TR.

name: Bedazzled
description: Shares first 3 bolts with She-Devil. Bust right around the arete and pull the roof then rejoice at the chains.

name: Black Elvis
description: Hard climbing that tends to wander back and forth.

name: Black Thing
description: Steep climbing on large holds that are sometimes hard to see from below.

name: Bunny Bionic
description: Powerful climb with multiple boulder problems broken up by a no hands rest at the pigeon nest. Lots of bird shit.

name: Burlygirl
description: 5.11 climbing to a crux boulder problem at the top.

name: Burlymon
description: Powerful start leads to an awkward mantel after the last bolt. Very pumpy climbing

name: Butthead
description: Fun and moderate climbing

name: Citation
description: A classic steep Dierkes sport route.

name: Diarreah Cha Cha Cha
description: Start to the left of Bevis under roof with nice hand crack. Jam and place gear then clip 3 bolts to the Bevis anchor. Hard jamming of the ground.

name: Evil C
description: Starts just right of Evil D.  Climb up to the death block (feels solid) and pull over the roof to a good rest.  Head up easier ground to three drilled pockets.  finish up and left through the final roof

name: Evil D
description: Very hard roof move at start, and trust me when the holds run out look for the pocket at the 2nd bolt from the top.

name: Fifteen Minutes of Fame
description: Very steep and crux is pulling the roof at the top. Shares first 3 bolts and anchors with Ziplock

name: Gag Reflex
description: Powerful start followed by pumpy climbing.

name: Get a Life
description: Very fun but thin climbing. Bring an additional cams for the bottom and top. (1/2" & 1 1/4")

name: Glomathon
description: Powerful climbing that requires a dyno at the crux.

name: Last Gasp
description: Start under a roof, clip the first bolt from the ground and then lieback a crack, that's better than it looks, to a good jug.  Traverse left and and pull another tricky roof into a smooth dihedral.  Next section is strange; bolt line goes left but holds end in that direction.  I went right and pulled through the apex of the roof (crux?).  A no-hands rest waits above the roof.  From here, steep and pumpy climbing on jugs will take you to the chains.

name: Loser
description: Fun and steep with big holds.

name: Magma
description: Steep with many difficult sections. Less than obvious line that requires climbing out of the bolt line at times.First sport route at Dierkes.

name: Pink Slip
description: Steep with a series of long reaches. Three crux sections.

name: Power Lunch
description: Steep and way hard

name: Sanitary Landfill
description: Fun and steep climbing with a powerful roof move at 3/4 height.

name: She-Devil
description: Steep and powerfull, favors taller folks, stick clip first bolt.

name: Shotgun Wedding
description: Good climbing although a bit run-out at times.

name: Slacker
description: Steep and powerfull, crux at 2nd to last bolt.

name: Snackpack
description: Steep and powerfull, shares first four bolts with Power Lunch then moves left.

name: Soloflex
description: Crux is at the top and it helps to either be very flexible or short. It helps to be taller for the roof crux at the start.

name: Thighmaster
description: Several difficult sections with bizzare body contortions required at the top.

name: Warm n' Fuzzy
description: Climb the short arete on the left corner of the alcove.  The first hold is a large flake.  Match a crimp and clip the first bolt, then flail for holds in a messy chalked up section of broken rock.  Clip the second bolt and commit to the steep section on monster holds in cool huecos that may be hard to see in time.  Pull through the huecos to a huge pocket on the face, clip the bolt on the left side of the arete, and struggle to find that tiny hold that will get you to the jug at the chains.

name: Where God Changed His Oil
description: Loose and oily feeling rock. Bad, Bad, Bad.

name: Ziplock
description: A classic, steep Dierkes sport route.

name: Boys, Like Jen
description: A steep start troubles many people.  Look for the hidden holds and get through it.

name: Dude
description: Good clean climbing fun, shares 4th bolt with Whipper

name: Knuckle Buster
description: Good climbing on good holds, Tricky sequence above last bolt to the anchors.

name: Primitive Man
description: Several pumpy moves protected by ample bolts.

name: Styling
description: Great climbing with crux at 3rd bolt.

name: Whipper
description: Pumpy climbing up bulging overhangs

name: Bizzarro
description: technical slab start.

name: Dudditz
description: Stick clip first bolt, crux is the boulder problem start.

name: Dust in your eyes
description: Slab start.

name: The Greenhorn
description: Fun Crack climbing in small dihedral

name: Ladybug
description: Helps to have a positive ape index. Watch out for poison oak to the left of the start.

name: Lichen the Jam
description: Can lead this climb on marginal gear for first 20' then good hand size to top. Bolted for beginners.

name: Mr. Grey
description: Crux start and at 3rd bolt. Technical climbing with an Iron cross move.

name: The Neophyte
description: Varied climbing following crack

name: The Rookie
description: Varied climbing following crack

name: Ursa Major
description: Shares anchors with Lady Bug.  Very difficult for the grade.

name: Where's Jake
description: Good climbing with the crux clipping the anchor. Best to have pre-placed the anchor slings from the top.

name: Cheeks
description: Climb broken and blocky rock to gain finger crack through small roof. Pull roof on good holds, Strenous.

name: La Figa
description: Climb through ultra steep huecos and up bulging face on good edges.

name: Little Italy
description: Climp through ultra steep huecos then surmount bulging face via good edges. Stick clip 1st bolt.

name: Mistral
description: Varied face climbing through small dihedral, seams, and crack.

name: Olive Oil
description: This route begins on the left side of this crag. Climb through huecos (use a #2 stopper for pro) on lower section to access crack and flake above. Excellent finger jams and laybacking await.

name: Air-ete
description: Enjoyable climbing up face and onto arete. One variation exists that slightly up the grade.

name: Anchors Away
description: Crack climbing that leads up under roof. Then a few powerful moves to gain the ledge.

name: Bert
description: Fun climbing up face or by using huecos.

name: Birthday Wish
description: Crimps off the ground to an off-balance move to a pocket. Cruise over a juggy roof and psychedelic huecos to the top.

name: Casual Cruise
description: Fun route with varied climbing, the crux is just above the 2nd bolt.

name: Circus Trick
description: Start just right of the Hexology crack.  Climb the vertical face then head out the horizontal roof. You'll need a tight belay to keep from decking; the roof is not very high off the ground.

name: Cookie Monster
description: Powerful crux move at the start leads to easier climbing to the last bolt, then a tricky and pumpy finish to the chains.

name: Ernie
description: Shares first bolt with Bert then moves right onto arete. Crux is up top.

name: Get Wired
description: Arching finger crack that leads to a small roof. Guide shows going straight up but I prefer to go right to the Air-Rete chains.

name: Hexology
description: Entertaining crack climbing up a small dihedral through a small roof to ledge.

name: Overtime
description: This is a direct start to Swing Shift. It goes up blank face to an undercling with a powerful move to reach a small crimp, then mantle. It helps to be taller otherwise a small dyno might be required.

name: Reid's Corner
description: Great stemming to the Cookie Monster chains.

name: Sport Dog
description: Hard and thin climbing.

name: Swing Shift
description: Thin and reachy moves lead past the first 2 bolts to easier but powerful climbing above.

name: Unknown Variation to Sport Dog.
description: Stay to the left of Sport Dog while clipping its bolts. One new bolt has been added to decrease the run-out.
To be added. Crux is at roof up high.

name: Abby's Lead
description: Small roof at the bottom is the crux but is pretty straightforward. After the roof, work up over small bulges to a final face just right of a large crack/corner.

name: American Grafitti
description: Clip first bolt above the painted "52" and move left to next bolts. Crux is at 4th bolt where a balancey and reachy move through a slot gets you to a flake. A 60 m rope works fine here.

name: Back to Front
description: To be added

name: Crack Head
description: Stay left of crack moving through brief crux just before ledge. Power up jugs on featured arete to anchor.

name: Forgotten One
description: To be added

name: Forgotten Two
description: Upper two roofs are crux.

name: Gypsy
description: Pull overhang on good holds, trending right to a corner and small ledge. Move left over bulge then wander through various bulges to anchor near the top of cliff.

name: Over the Falls  1
description: Climb small faces and ledges to a large ledge below a wide crack. Lieback the crack to a small bulge and finish on a few large huecos.

name: Over the Falls  2
description: Climb to a large, featured face about midroute to a ledge and finish on exposed, fun cracks and face holds.

name: Over the Falls  3
description: Cruise 5.7 terrain to a large ledge then use stemming, crack moves, and body position to surmount an overhanging corner.

name: RP52
description: To be added

name: Small Arms Fire
description: Crank up jugs and cracks on small overhang to a small ledge. Move right of crack and surmount bulge. Climb featured black rock to crux finish with a crack and undercling.

name: Stone Throwers of Palestine
description: Climb bulges on jugs and good rock to clean white face. Trend toward left side of large roof using steady balance and technique to surmount roof. Crank up arete to a ledge. Stay left and finish on final mini roof with big moves (crux).

name: Ten Pound Sledge
description: Climb nondescript bulges.

name: Two Pound Sledge
description: More nondescript bulges.

name: Vacation Day
description: To be added

name: Centurion
description: Climb funky shattered rock with awkward, but positive holds to a ledge below anchor. Use body tension and stemming to reach anchor.

name: Crimpus Maximus
description: From the ledge, move up and right on crimpers and mostly good feet. First crux is between second and third bolt. Second crux is moving above third bolt. Finish on solid jugs and a nice sidepull that gets you to anchor.

name: Gladiator
description: Clip first bolt of Trajan's Column and fire up a steepening slab to a big, fun hueco. Pull through mini-roofs on good holds and finish with a right-sweeping crack to anchor.

name: Julius Squeezer
description: Climb a huecoed arete to a wide crack surrounded by a pocketed face. Surmount a small roof and finish on an even smaller roof and crack. Magnifico!

name: Remus
description: Scramble up to big ledge via direct boulder start to where first bolt awaits. Hard bouldery moves off of ledge gets you to easier climbing above and then to the tricky ledge move below the anchor.

name: Roman Ruin
description: Scramble up a slot to a big ledge below a bolt. Powerful moves off the ledge gets you to easier climbing above and then a shallow diehedral with technical moves. Move up towards left side of mini-roof, then make long reach left to good holds. This section is the crux.

name: Romulus
description: Boulder up to a big ledge, then climb fun, easy rock to a funky ledge move. Surmount ledge with small holds, body tension, heel hooks, and/or magic to anchor.

name: Spanish Steps
description: Head up to first bolt using small undercling to reach hold out right (first crux). Keep moving right using body tension and balance. Head back left at third bolt through good holds to a seemingly blank open book (second crux) above the ledge. Squirm and stem toward roof then move left to small ledge. One final rightward traverse, then push straight through headwall to anchor.

name: Trajan's Column
description: Trend right to ledge then move back left to fun column using pockets and good edges. At small roof, dodge right, then straight up to anchor.

name: Wasn't Built In a Day
description: Starts in an obvious right leaning crack. Pull small roof. Tan Rock.

name: North Shore (Short Subject)
description: Fun climbing on positive edges

name: North Shore (Transformer)
description: Crux is between 1st and 2nd bolt and if you want to go left that means stay right.

name: Body By Jake
description: Steep and powerful climbing

name: Fire in the belly
description: Steep and powerful. This route has been called "the steepest 5.10 in the country" by Rock and Ice Issue?

name: Mac Daddy
description: Extremly powerful and overhanging. The final clip at the anchors has been dubbed "The clip from hell" Hard for shorter folks. Look for hidden jug out right at top.

name: Short, Hard, & Stupid
description: Easy climbing off the ground leads to a hard, crimpy crux.  Finish just to the right of the anchors and then traverse to chains.

name: Skunk Cabbage
description: Climb out the left side of the steep roof. Two cruxes. Hardest move is right after bolt 3.  Then pull under the next roof and fire out the left corner for the big ledge (redpoint crux). The mantle onto the ledge is touchy and exposed. It's not difficult but the bolt is a ways below your feet.  Walk across the ledge and climb past one more bolt to the chains. Shares chains with Mac Daddy and Fire in the Belly.

name: Skunk Weed
description: Less than vert start that gradually steepens.  Some larger moves between bigger holds leads to a cruxy headwall.  Match a super cool slopey pinch with both hands and throw high, on marginal feet, to pull the first bulge.  Straightforward, but pumpy, finish on an overhanging face.  The guidebook calls it a 11.b/c, but I think it's much softer than that.  Only one really difficult move.  Shares chains with Body by Jake.  Once you unlock the sequence, it flows beautifully!!

name: The Cutting Edge
description: Climb broken rock to a cool series of off-width cracks.

name: Road to recovery
description: Start up the slightly chossy blocks until you reach the second bolt and a small stance.  Get ready for the fun! From here climb up an insecure corner stemming or doing what ever you can until you reach the giant hueco pocket. Reach up to some good crimps and move slightly right. From here reach right to an arete. Slap your way up until you reach the oh so distant jug ledge. Bust out onto a dirty pocketed face and up to a good rest ledge.  Take the roof out the wide crack on the left side working back right slightly. From here only one more roof stands between you and glory.

name: Stretch It
description: Climb broken rock at the start, then fun climbing in wide cracks and huecoed aretes. Top out to belay.

name: Crisper
description: Sit start with right hand in two finger pocket.  Move up crimps to top out.  Avoid using any of the holds/feet on Sweet Pea.

name: Fire in the Hole
description: Sit start in hole.  Move up jugs until you can snag the large underclings.  Throw to the crimp rail on top and top out.

name: Fire Pit
description: Sit start, exit the hole left and pull on crimps or fire for the top.

name: No Hands Slab
description: Work up the slab on the right side of Sweet Pea Boulder without using any of the hand holds.

name: Sweet Pea
description: Sit start.  Move up broken jugs to the top out.

name: Yaniro Exit
description: Exit the right side of the roof on slopers and crimps

name: Bear Hug
description: Dierkes classic.  Sit start then "hug" your way up the fridge sized block to the top.  Finish jug is on the L corner; still a hard mantle after you snag it!

name: Bud Crack
description: Sit start with hands on flake.  Pull up and work up crack until you can throw over the lip to a good hold.  Mantling onto the face is scary!  After you mantle, follow the easy crack to the top.

name: Consolation Prize
description: If you get spit off Splitter to the left, cheer yourself up by crushing this easy crack.  Sit start.  Layback up easy crack, snag big pocket and head for the top out.

name: Monkey Hole Left
description: Sit start.  Move up left flake to tricky mantle.

name: Monkey Hole Right
description: Sit start.  Move up right flake to tricky top out.

name: Splitter Crack
description: Complicated climb. Could probably go at anywhere from V0-Vhard?. You could basically walk up the steps to the R of the problem to reach the finish holds (V0). If you use only the crack, from a sit start, this problem would be extremely difficult. At least it was for me, although I'm definitely no trad climber. Would be an absolutely classic problem this way, if not for the bad landing. Crack is fingers to hands with an easy topout, if you can make it that far.

name: Easy Cleaver
description: Sit start.  Climb the sharp arete with your right hand and use a few left hand crimps on the face.

name: Greenroom
description: One of Dierkes best.  Sit start deep in the Greenroom Cave.  Traverse right on jugs until you gain a crack.  Pull out of the cave and go hard to small crimp on overhanging face.  Going to the finish jug is the next move.  Boulders to the right, and behind you, are off.

name: Greenroom Left
description: Sit start same as Greenroom.  Work up and left on jugs, and exit the cave on crimps.  There are boulders beneath and behind you as you climb, so be careful!  Extra pads and a spotter helpful.

name: Holiday in costco
description: Starts on jugs up to small crimps and as dynamic move

name: Stoner Hueco Route
description: Sit start.  Move up huecos to hit an undercling and grab the top.

name: Tedd's
description: Climb face on left side of the obtuse arete.

name: Tony's
description: Ascend face just right of the obtuse arete.

name: Cobra Kai
description: Overhanging, R leaning arete highball.  Classic!  It would be nice if someone pulled the bolts and patched this.

name: Direct Power
description: Sit start in the back of the cave.  Move out and pull over the roof on crimps.  Hard mantle to the easy finish.

name: Halfway to Jackpot
description: Sit start on pockets in the back of the cave, work your way out and up.  On Jackpot boulder.

name: Power Scherer
description: Sit start in the back of the cave.  Work out horizontal on flat jugs, when you reach the end of the huecos, pull up to reach a right hand hold and thrutch to a left hand crimp.  Mantle and finish up the arete.

name: The Bat Cave
description: Sit start.  Climb the southeast arete of Kid Boulder and mantle out the right side (don't finish on Holey Arete).  Be careful you don't stick your hand into the "bat cave" or you will get a nice handful of wet guano.  This feels very exposed; it's a highball by Dierkes standards and you are climbing over a tree and some rocks.  It would be a very nasty fall if you were to slip.  Holds are all there though and a good heelhook will easily help you mantle out over the daunting finish. Fun!

name: Brown Plate Special
description: Stand start, although sit variation doesn't look too hard.  Work up crimps to the large, two handed undercling, then dyno to the top.

name: Center Crack
description: On painted boulder, climb up and follow the thin crack just right of Center Left v0 (the large obvious path of least resistance).

name: Cube Arete
description: Sit start.  Work up the arete on the SE corner of the Cube.

name: Cube Corner Arete
description: V5 sit start.  V0-V1 stand.

name: Cube Descent
description: Sit start.  Climb the easy face to the top.

name: The Cubicle
description: Sit start in the hueco.  Throw to a high hand pocket, work your feet up and top out.

name: Dihedral Downclimb
description: Sit start, or whatever.  Stem your way to the top of the boulders.  The easiest way up and down the Cube.

name: Dimple Arete
description: Sit start.  Work up slabby, blunt arete using the shallow dimples.  Feels exposed!

name: Easy Huecos
description: Sit start.  Climb the easy huecos left of Snapper.

name: Hash Pipe
description: Sit start under the overhang.  Move up the tricky overhanging face on crimps and pockets that always seem to be facing the wrong way.  Throw to the lip and mantle out.

name: Holey Arete
description: Sit start.  Good, easy fun on a beautifully featured arete.  It's worth climbing just to feel all the holds.  Also the best downclimb for the rock.  Probably most people's first "boulder problem" at Dierkes as it can easily be done in your tennis shoes.

name: Johnny's Country Store
description: Just right of Center Crack on the corner.  Start with a poor right hand and left hand on a crimp.  One move wonder to a jug up high, then topout.

name: Kid Seam
description: Sit start.  Work up thin seam, then top out using slopey holds that you wish were better!

name: Kid Toprope
description: Sit start.  There's a single bolt on top of the boulder if you feel like setting up a toprope for the kiddos.  Easily accessed by climbing Holey Arete to the right.  Any route you take up this face is ~Veasy to V0.

name: Lay the Pipe
description: Sit start on the Southwest arete.  Work up the arete and then finish with some very balancey and technical moves.

name: No Hands Left
description: Avoiding the excellent left hand crack, climb up the edges and pockets to the lip

name: Painted Arete
description: Sit start in fist sized hueco.  Work up the arete on more huecos to easy top out.  Also a good downclimb for other problems.

name: Painted Center
description: Going up through the best holds on the face. Very fun movement, kind of big. If you feel something crawl on your hand in that last large jug you aren't the only one...

name: Painted Corner
description: Work up the corner with right hand in vertical hueco and left on crimps.  Hard top out.

name: Painted Downclimb
description: Sit start in low hueco.  Work up on pockets to the large underclings.  Snag the top of the boulder and top out.  A decent downclimb for the other problems.

name: Peace Pipe
description: Sit start on the obvious layback flake.  Climb the flake up until it starts trending left, then take pockets to the top.

name: Pipe Down
description: Sit start.  The obvious Northeast corner.  Can be used as the boulder's down climb (as the name suggests), or you can butt slide down the north slab.

name: Pipe Load
description: Sit or stand start, doesn't really matter.  Grab the overhead feature hanging down and work up and out the roof.  You will be grappling for feet (hint: remember the start hold)

name: Pipe Up
description: Sit start.  Work your way up the right side of a nice arete.  When you reach the apex, pull up and over the top to a nice finish jug and easy top out.  Don't fall! It would hurt to land on that pipe.

name: Rubix
description: The most obvious line on the Cube.  Sit start in a huge hueco.  Work up sharp, shallow pockets until you can get into a big jug.  Snag the lip and try to mantle.  Much harder than it looks!

name: Snapper
description: Sit start in pockets.  Move up and right on crimps.   Get your feet up and throw for the top.  Avoid the easy jugs to the left to maintain the grade.

name: Stump the Chump
description: Sit start with L hand in the Rubix hueco.  Use the arete and face holds to reach the lip.

name: Bucket List
description: Sit start.  Climb the obvious and huge "bucket" features on the right side of the Traverse Wall.

name: Chocolate Center
description: Sit start at base of crack.  Work up and right, match crimp rail, snag sidepull on shallow hueco, and throw for the top.

name: Chocolate Crack
description: Sit start.  Work up the fun crack to easy finish.

name: Chocolate Crack Right
description: Alternate start to Chocolate Crack.  Sit start with left hand in crack and right on sidepull.  Work up the crack with your left and the flake with your right until they meet.  Finish on the top 1/2 of Chocolate Crack.

name: Chocolate Eliminates
description: Sit start at base of huecos.  Work up huecos to high undercling.  Throw to the slopey top and mantle out.  The wall to your right is off.

name: Chocolate Flake
description: Sit start.  Climb obvious flake without using the wall to your left (Chocolate Eliminates).

name: Chocolate Left
description: Stand start on small crimps on left side of Chocolate Face.  Work up on crimps, snag a sidepull in the shallow hueco on your right, and slap for the slopey top.  A hard mantle!

name: Clean and Crank  3
description: Sit start with foot in ground level hueco.  Work up pockets and edges to the top.

name: Evil Twin
description: Sit start in corner of Star Boulder.  Work up hueco until you can get a good undercling.  A good pinch intermediate is out right.  Throw hard to 3 finger pocket around the corner, adjust your feet, and then throw again for the top rail.  Hint: a good toe-hook might make all the difference.

name: Honeycomb
description: The coolest looking wall at Dierkes.  Sit start in the mess of huecos.  Looks like a VO, but the top out is not straightforward.  The guidebook call it V5, I don't think so.  Deceivingly hard. Go left from the top of the huecos following a small crack for full quality.

name: Hueco Slugfest
description: Sit start in obvious mess of huecos on right side of Pocket Warmup.  Climb out the easy huecos to a surprisingly difficult top out.

name: Left Hand Mono
description: Start with Left finger on mono.  Work the corner up and top out.

name: The Mono Problem
description: Start with Right finger in mono.  Get high feet and throw for the good undercling.  Work the ridge up and left and top out.  Someone has probably done the sit start for this, but I'm not sure what it would go at.

name: Pocket Change
description: Sit start.  Climb the "coin" sized line of pockets without using the huge hueco features to the right, or dishes to the left.

name: Shallow Pocket Right
description: Sit start in large hueco just right of the pocket warmup problem.  Move up the hueco to your own set of shallow pockets, hit a crimp, then throw to the finish jug and top out.

name: Shallow Pocket Warmup
description: Stand start with fingertips in tiny, crimp pocket.  Work up shallow pockets and a left hand sloper to top out.  For full value, don't use the crimp above Shallow Pocket Right.

name: Slab Arete
description: Start just left of the stairs.  Walk up easy slab to the top of the Honeycomb Boulder.

name: Star Bulge
description: Sit start in obvious, plate sized hueco.  Rally up crimps and edges to the top.

name: Star Right
description: Sit start in huecos at base of arete.  Climb straight up and out the arete.  To maintain the grade, stay on the arete and dont stem off the wall behind you/to your right.

name: Tweaker
description: Work up the crimpy face to the right of the mono problems.  Don't tweak anything!

name: Undercling King
description: Sit start at the base of the flake.  Climb up the flake on underclings and finish out the top.  Same top-out as for Honeycomb (crux).

name: The Yaniro Problem
description: Sit start in crack left of mono problem.  Lieback your way up the crack; when it becomes to small for fingers, get ready to throw to a small divot just right of the seam, high on the face.  Its sharp!  Hold on and inch your way up to the top edge and mantle out.  The lack of feet make it feel sketchy but it's a fun problem!  Avoid the flakey crimps out left as they appear to be part of another problem.

name: Chris Hill Problem
description: Start on chalked up side pulls right of right arete, and go straight up the face.

name: Cobra Center
description: Same start as for King Cobra.  Work your way straight up through the huecos and pockets before throwing to a slopey rail.

name: Cobra Right
description: Climb the difficult face just to the right of the heavily featured Cobra Center.

name: Crack is Whack
description: A fun, right trending crack just to the Left of the Cobra routes.  Sit start, then follow it to an easy top-out.

name: Dimples
description: Sit start.  Climb the left facing flake by liebacking and crimping some of the "dimples" on the face.

name: Finger Crack
description: Sit start.  Pull hard to gain high hold.  A couple of finger locks and easy moves will get you to the top out.

name: Fingerlockin' Good
description: Sit start on a rail with a high foot in the hole in the wall, bump R onto new rail, then throw into a flat pocket.  From here, use some footwork trickery and balance to get up and plunge your fingers into the slot in the crack.  A few more fingerlocks and you are home free.  Avoid the McCrimpin holds.

name: Flexy Flakes
description: Start at the base of Crack is Whack.  When the crack cuts Right, continue straight up the face on some suspect, hollow flakes.

name: High Holes
description: Sit start.  Climb the obvious line of huecos just right of Snakebite.  When the huecos end, undercling and throw for the very fun finish.

name: Infamous Fingertip Mantle
description: Tiptoe up absurdly hard slab.

name: King Cobra
description: A great route! Standing start on a boulder under the Cobra roof.  Work up and left on the obvious flake on great holds.  The feature hanging down to your left, "Snatch Bar", is off.

name: Mail Slot
description: Work hard to establish yourself on the slab face and then try and get to the juggy "Mail Slot."

name: Mail Slot Corner
description: Stand start.  Climb the right arete/corner of Mail Slot Boulder.

name: McCrimpin
description: If you start standing with R hand in pocket and left hand on side-pull, this probably goes at V2. Alternatively, you can sit start on the same rail as Fingerlockin', grab a left hand intermediate, then throw R hand into the pocket and go for the sidepull with your L.  The sit probably bumps it to v3-v4.  Use your balance, pull on a few thin crimps and top out.

name: Pinch Arete
description: (Pinch Arete Left) Sit start.  Work your way up arete and dyno for high jug.  Move far left to the rail after nailing the dyno, and top out.  Alternate finish (Pinch Arete Right) goes right after dyno to jug.  Goes at roughly same grade ~V5/V6.

name: Slip, Slap, Slide
description: Sit start near the small ramp R of the cobra problems.  L hand on rail and R in 2 fingered pocket down low.  Climb the tufa-like feature on pinches and slopers and finish out the crack at the top.  The Dimples flake to your right is off.

name: Snakebite
description: Climb very small  and sharp crimps up and out.  Sit start maybe bumps grade to V4.  The key to sending is high pain tolerance!

name: Snatch Bar
description: Work your way up the left side of Cobra boulder on crimps, "snatch" the hanging stalactite feature behind your head, and top out.  To maintain the grade, the left wall is off.

name: Stepladder
description: Sit start, just left of the Cobra problems.  Climb the huge buckets up and out.  Also the best down-climb in the area.

name: Peter Pan
description: Start up some fun easy climbing to a good rest just before the crux.  work you way up slopers and side pulls to a good crimp rail.  Make a big move right and hold on to the top.  Avoid the wall to your left through the crux for full value.

name: Bulging Bedbug Bank
description: Blocky start up broken, but solid rock just left of sheer red face. Fun finish on short, upper face.

name: Chestnuts Roasting on a Dumpster Fire
description: Tricky technical start leads to even trickier crux move near sixth bolt as you move onto arete.

name: Forest Fire Picnic
description: Head up broad corner left of bolt line (next to red streak), moving right after second bolt to small ledges. Head straight up cream colored face into mini dihedral and red rock, following bolt line. Crux is around fifth bolt.

name: Leukemia for Lollipops
description: Crux is near fourth bolt as you transition onto dark face.

name: Presidential Pussygrabber
description: A beautiful finger crack start ends just as it gets good, leading to the "Idaho flake" and the crux move just above. Ledge to right is off route.

name: Shitty Kitty Litter Glitter
description: Pitch 1 (5.10b): Climb to ledge, then pull roof (crux) above ledge. Follow bolt line to reach a fingertip crack with thrilling exposure (second crux), then on to a good belay station. Pitch 2 (5.10a): Second pitch gets easier as you go, especially as route ascends a few ledges near the top. Route finishes at a belay station at the canyon rim, allowing climbers to walk off at this point. Note: 70 m rope needed if rappelling or top-roping either pitch of this route.

name: Unicorn Glue Factory
description: Look for jumbled boulders at base of climb. Technical, cruxy start, then traverse to more blocky features before finishing up on a nice crack.

name: Vomito de Gatito
description: Starts just to the right of the undercut arete. Technical, thin moves around 2nd bolt, then work your way up one side of the arete to the other.

name: Butterfly Effect
description: Video for full details: https://youtu.be/amBzAPaxdqw  Aesthetic line with green lichen.    Starts on the best part of the granite rail and moves through some medium edges (in the slanted cracks). The crux is a big move to a diagonal slot jug.  From here make 3-4 moves straight up on jugs and then exit right, stepping onto a decent sized ledge.

name: Blast Off
description: Very fun climb with unique holds.

name: Burnt Shadow
description: Follow the line of edges

name: Down Climb/ Mantel
description: 1 move wonder.

name: Easy Thirteen
description: On the first set of boulders nearest to the pull out "Superman Boulder" Crack facing the road

name: Slabs in Heat
description: Meh

name: Superman Crack
description: Slightly overhanging crack

name: Top Down dirty
description: start on a obvious rail go for the top expect mediocre rock quality. useful as a warm up.

name: Smelly Dark Hole
description: The climb is 15-20 moves long through a horizontal roof. exit the cave topping out on a jug above the cave entrance, going any further is not recommended

name: D.O.A.
description: This is a fun crack climb ranging in size from fingers to thin hands.  After the initial crack you get a pretty good rest stance right before the crux at the top.

name: Floating on Gravel
description: This climb starts out as a scaly chosswidth, but it turns into quality climbing once you get through the first 15 feet or so. From the ground, climb the scaly but easy wide crack. The rock quality cleans up considerable once you reach the roof with a hand crack in it. You can clip a bolt on the 5.12 route TVOD at this point if you want. After pulling the first roof, work your way up the left arching 4" crack. Now you're under a roof split by two cracks ranging from about 1-3", with a surprising amount of exposure below you. Pull some very fun roof moves and you're pretty much done. The bolts out right didn't seem to work sell for setting up a TR so we built a gear belay above the lip and walked off the top once done(some additional shenanigans omitted). I know my description makes it sound utterly terrible, but it's worth checking out for the two roof cruxes and the 4" arching crack(if you're into that sort of thing).

name: Good Friday
description: Stemmy moves down low lead to a step left, and then a nice finish on a fun finger crack.

name: Groveler
description: Another burly Dark Side sport route. The first few feet are pretty casual, but don't get too used to it. Once you pass that first bolt, you're working hard until you get your feet over the roof. There isn't much of a distinct crux on this route,  just pretty sustained 5.11 for the middle half of the route.

name: Physical Graffiti
description: Decent route. After the third bolt on God route go left. There is a large pocket over the roof. Don't fall near the chains, you'll be a little ways past the last bolt.

name: Promiscuity Crack
description: Follows a crack in a shallow R-facing dihedral to a stance before a right leaning finger crack which leads up a left-facing ramp through the crux. Lock and lieback to a stemming stance and clip the chains on the left.

name: Safety Dance
description: One of the several bolted cracks at the Dark Side.  Excellent sustained finger and hand jams eventually take you to the interesting boulder-problem finish.

name: The Virgin
description: This route starts out with somewhat insecure moves straight off the deck, with the added bonus of a bad landing if you blow it before making the first clip. The climbing remains technical and sustained until a restful stance below the obvious crux of the route, the overhanging wall split by a tips-width crack. Clip the bolt(probably very hard to reach for short people), and go for it! Anchors are a body length above the crux bolt.

name: Wire Brush Hair Cut
description: This route begins with some interesting stemming and liebacking. After the second bolt, move up and right to the arete on big holds. The fourth bolt, which protects the crux, can be clipped from a nice stance. The crux itself is a neat boulder problem involving crimps, side pulling, and a tough move to a good right hand from which to clip the next bolt.    From here, things ease up, but not too much as you're left pumped and pulling up to a strenuous mantel before finishing on a slightly runout but easy slab.    It is also apparently possible to go out right at the crux on larger holds, bringing the grade down to 11b.

name: Ambition is Critical
description: Start by climbing a broken pillar to a high first bolt.  Continue up a dihedral, clipping 2 more bolts, and mantle onto the ledge below the big roof. Clip your last bolt in the bottom of the roof, start traversing left on a juggy slot and snag jugs left of the bolt.  Pull the roof and mantle to the chains (crux).

name: Basalt Somersault
description: A very nice dihedral with some great stemming and smearing.

name: Boys-r-Blue
description: Short climb with some fun bouldery moves. Worth checking out.

name: Citizens Against Spiders
description: This dihedral has some fun moves and good pro.

name: The Cleaning Lady
description: Go straight up the dihedral.  Using the outer holds lessens the rating a tad from what's in the Epeldi book.      Climbing it as a true crack definitely puts it at 5.8.  Nice double finger length to hand jams at the top of the crack.     Topping out at the chains isn't so obvious, but the hand holds are there.

name: Dirty Luck
description: The business end starts off the ground. Use the pockets and small rails to gain the nice finger to hand jam crack.    This is a full value 8 that's more difficult than its neighbor, The Cleaning Lady.

name: Eyeless in Gaza
description: Nice little inside corner to chains. Good pro. No distinct crux but a nice warm up.

name: Gargling Vinegar
description: Short dihedral with easy stemming up to an anchor below a roof.  A nice climb to set up as a toprope for less experienced climbers.

name: Hershey Squirt
description: This is the first bolted route at the head of East Car Body.  This route is short and blowing the third clip could result in a ground fall.  Not recommended for the faint of heart or inexperienced 5.10 leaders.

name: Holiday in Cambodia
description: A fun climb up the outside of a narrow column.  Most of the route follows widely spaced jugs using fun moves. After clipping the last bolt, shorter folks will either have to dyno or use small crimps and even smaller feet to reach the finishing jug. Fun!

name: The Industrial Age
description: This climb starts on big edges down low, goes up and over a bulgy section, and has a few interesting last moves before the chains. This is one of the easier bolted leads at the cliffs in my opinion.

name: Jen's Dilemma
description: Finger Crack to chains

name: Lichen Lunch
description: A smearing, stemmy sort of route with a couple thoughtful cruxy sections. The cruxes are well protected by bolts. Good footwork is Key.

name: Macabre Roof
description: This climb features beautiful double hand cracks that eventually lead up to a roof, which is split in the middle by a crack. In Sandi Epeldi's book the roof is described as "a classic boulder problem in the sky", and I'd have to agree.

name: Neon Leprechaun
description: Start just right of Gargling Vinegar, passing 3 bolts to the obvious large ledge below the roof.  Clip the last bolt and venture out left on exposed rock to the anchors.

name: The Pansy - Direct
