description: This route climbs the double dihedral and roof directly below the anchors for The Pansy, merging with it at the 3rd bolt.  This adds some fun jamming and tricky stemming, you get to bypass the rather easy and boring start of the original Pansy, and you still get to climb the Pansy's crux.  Highly recommended!    Start in the dihedral using a nice handcrack on the right until you reach the roof.  Pull the roof using finger locks and smeary stemming.      After the fun climbing up to and over the roof, climb some loose terrain without protection until you reach the 3rd bolt of The Pansy.  Finish with the tough (interesting) part of The Pansy.

name: The Pansy
description: The first half of this route features easy stemming between good features.  Somewhere around the 3rd bolt the route traverses left and gets a little tricky.  It's all there, but I found it a little hard to figure out the right sequence.

name: Raisin the Titanic
description: If you're willing to put up with a junky start, there's a nice left leaning finger and hands crack just right of Whaleback Crack. I recommend starting as for Whaleback crack and then breaking right onto this route vs starting in the next dihedral over. The crack starts very thin, then turns to big/ off fingers, with some hand size pods closer to the anchor.

name: Rock Hudson
description: A fun sport route, this route has a good variety of movement. It starts out with some technical moves off the deck, then some pulling hard on big slopey holds up the arete, followed by some technical stemming back in the dihedral.

name: The Scream
description: This route starts out relatively easy, but the crack gets pretty thin about halfway up. It would be pretty hairy without the lone bolt up there. Good quality, with moves that will make you think.

name: Spasm
description: This is the Hand/Fist width crack a few feet to the right of The Cleaning Lady and Dirty Luck. It shares anchors with those routes. I think I only placed #2s and #3s.

name: Sperm Whale
description: Climb the obvious column just right of Ambition is Critical (the column that looks like it shouldn't still be standing).  The first bolt is a rusty 1/4", but there's only 3 bolts on the route so you might as well clip it.  Once you get the beta dialed in it's climbable.  Exciting finish... Just give in to the whipper and hope the column still stands.

name: The Spice of Life
description: Climb low-5th class, broken rock to a ledge and the first bolt at 15-20'. Clipping this with a long draw will reduce drag. From here, follow the obvious line up increasingly better rock to the 5th and last bolt just above the small roof. Clip this and move straight up, pulling on pockets and edges of varying degrees of positivity to the chains.    The route is a bit contrived as it is possible to use the left arete after the last bolt to bring the route down to .10b as listed in the book. This       involves moving into what I thought to be dangerous fall potential above a broken column top.     If the starting bit of rock and the upper contrivances are disregarded, this thing is pretty good. It protects well (when climbed directly) and the boulder problem at the crux is fun and on great rock.

name: Temporary Insanity
description: Starts on top of a short pillar.  Work the dihedral up to the cool flake-like feature.  Super fun!

name: Terminal Hypocrisy
description: This is the third bolted route from the head of East Car Body.  Although this route is fairly short it is a bold lead with widely spaced bolts.  The crux falls around the second bolt.  This route requires good foot work, is thought provoking and you may even get a pump on due to the small side pulls and crimps. Sustained and technical climbing until the third bolt where the route eases up with large jugs to the chains.

name: Tin Man
description: This route never really gives you much room to breath. The start moves through crimps and rounded off sidepulls leading into an easy runout between bolts 3 and 4 before leaving you empty handed on a blank face between bolts 4 and 5...Oh and the cracks on either side of the column are off limits. Good luck!

name: Two Studs
description: Typical Black Cliffs dihedral with a tricky finish through the bulge.  Definitely thought provoking.

name: Whaleback Crack
description: Ascend an obvious dihedral, then follow the crack to climber's left about 30' up. The crack widens to perfect hands near the top, making for an exciting finish.

name: Whimper
description: Clip the first 3 bolts of Wimp Roof and split left, clipping 2 more bolts on the way to the chains. Fun climbing with an exciting finish.

name: Whitehead Crack
description: Follow the long corner just left of Rock Hudson(11a sport).  The crack is small, so plan accordingly.  Surprisingly hard finish as you work right at the top of the corner.

name: Wimp Roof
description: Easy climbing leads to a big roof. Same start as Whimper, go slightly right at third bolt and climb under the roof. Powerful moves and good foot work.

name: Bad Dog
description: Don't use the GOOD DOG crack or you're off route.

name: Buttface
description: This route is pretty straightforward, just climb the column using large positive edges.  I didn't notice any distinct crux, although the route was sustained.

name: Cat Face
description: Climb the dihedral and face to an awkward mantle move. Make sure you're a solid 10 climber or you may not like this route.

name: Dog Face
description: Sustained technical climbing up an arete that is just featured enough to go.  Balancy climbing up the outside of the arete leads to a big move left to good jug.  After the jug the climbing gets thin, with several sidepulls and slopers and not much for feet.  Extremely fun!

name: Energy Crisis
description: Book states "one of best crack at the BC." Make sure you're solid 10 leader. If I remember right the feet weren't very solid.

name: Good Dog
description: Sustained crack climbing. Finish at Bad Dog chains.

name: Helios
description: Excellent crack climb that is sustained and difficult for the grade.  Be prepared to jam, finger lock, stem, smear, and maybe employ a little magic to get to the top!  This climb starts from the top of a high ledge and not from the ground; it's a pity this isn't longer.

name: In Your Face
description: Enjoy the starting few easy moves to the first bolt, as they are the last you'll get.  Sustained stemming and crimping on small but positive edges are the norm for the rest of the way up the face/corner.      After you're nice and pumped from the small crimps on the first 2/3 of the route, the widely spaced jugs at the bulge may seem a bit harder to hang onto than they feel like they should.  Once on top of the bulge positive edges and pockets take you up the slightly more than vertical finishing face.      Stellar!

name: Lights Out
description: Starts out with easy stemming to the high first bolt, then goes left onto the arete for the rest of the way.  One hard move passing the first bolt is followed up with fun jug pulling for the next couple bolts.  After the third bolt the business begins, with fun crimps and sidepulls the rest of the way.

name: Loss of Face
description: Steady climbing with no particular crux.

name: Max V
description: Another great Face Canyon sport route. Fun stems and thin face moves up the column face on bullet-proof basalt. There is a thought-provoking crux sequence waiting up near the last bolt.     As usual, stay out of the crack left of the column for full value.    Good clips, spaced a little more comfortably than a lot of the other sport routes here. In my opinion, this would be a good first 11 lead.

name: Pizza Face
description: The first half of the route is sustained and technical. Make it to the fourth bolt and you're done with the route. Stick clip the first bolt.

name: Power Failure
description: Great crack, starts with fingertips and steadily opens up until the offwidth (crux) at top. Plug those boat anchors up top and go for it!

name: Saving Face
description: This climb starts out easy with mediocre pro, then leads to a nice finger crack in a corner. Great pro and fun climbing once you make it to the crack.

name: Surf's Up
description: This is an excellent crack climb!   Great jams and finger locks with decent stances for placing gear.  If you come to this area this climb should be on your todo list!

name: Your Face Or Mine
description: Pull through an awkward start past the first bolt to a ledge. Easier climbing on good edges and sidepulls brings you to a shake at the 4th bolt.    The crux lies above and demands some fairly technical movement and a somewhat stressful fifth clip. Mantle and finish on a few feet of easy ground to the chains.     Aside from the start and the usual Black Cliffs contrivances (cracks on either side are off), this is a really good route.

name: 3 Guys 3 Cracks  1
description: This  is the leftmost of the 3 guys 3 cracks. It starts below several consecutive overhangs, goes straight up the overhangs on huge holds, and follows the left crack to the chains.

name: 3 Guys 3 Cracks  2
description: The middle of the 3 guys 3 cracks. Pretty much climb straight up to the chains.

name: 3 Guys 3 Cracks  3
description: The rightmost of the 3 guys 3 cracks. Climb up the blocky crack and stay in the right crack until a traverse left just below the chains. I thought the traverse was a bit awkward.

name: Cochise Crack
description: Dihedral with an offwidth crack to the left and some smaller placements to the right.  Easy 5.5ish climbing to the roof.  Crux is just above roof topping out at the Metolius anchors.

name: Jim Fall Memorial
description: Stem up a casual dihedral to a roof, finger lock and scum your way to the top.

name: Poodle Boy
description: A really enjoyable climb with some sweet lieback moves on top flake.

name: The Remnant
description: One of the best 11's at the cliffs. Getting to the third bolt is 5.8, then you've got 20 feet of bouldery fun. Don't fall clipping the chains! Make sure to take a long draw for the 4th bolt or your biner will be resting on the edge of the ledge.

name: Fairway to Heaven
description: This route no longer exists, as this portion of the wall sloughed off from the main cliff body. Description here for historical purposes only.  Big moves to good holds up the outside of a slightly overhanging pillar.

name: Feelin' Green
description: From below this route looks thinner and harder than it actually is.  Climb the mossy pillar to a bolt, then traverse right and finish on the Irreconcilable Differences fist crack. As you climb, good incut edges, that were invisible from below, appear just where you need them.

name: The Garden
description: Finger Lock and Jam heaven!  Those with small hands will be rewarded on this sustained climb.  Excellent crack climbing and technical stemming.  The crack can feel a bit greasy on a hot day.

name: Geologic Time Includes Now
description: In April 2014 a good portion of the Green Acres wall collapsed, unveiling this sweet finger crack. A few days later, I cleaned it out, pried off a few sketchy blocks and cleared off a belay platform, so now it's good to go.    Climb the sweet finger crack, placing gear from tricky jams. At the top of the crack, traverse left across big but pumpy holds to The Garden's anchors. It's not very tall but it definitely packs a punch!

name: GW Loves Peanut Butter
description: Jam jam jug, jam jam jug . . . Keep repeating all the way to the top.  Great fun!  Finish up and right at the Pidgeon Holer anchors.

name: Irreconcilable Differences
description: Black cliffs crack climbing at its finest!  Don't miss the occasional feet that pop up on the aretes.

name: Order From Anarchy
description: This excellent route starts on a technical finger/hand crack to a small roof/bulge.  Pull the bulge on good but spaced hand jams.  Above the bulge, a final boulder problem to gain the anchors is protected by one bolt which may be difficult to clip for the short folks.

name: Pigeon Holer
description: This climb ascends a crack that starts as finger tips, and gets progressively wider until you can get inside and make some awkward moves to the anchor.

name: Piss & Vinegar
description: This is a splitter fist/offwidth crack in a right facing corner.  It would be much more difficult if it didn't have the opposite corner to stem off of for most of the height.  The rock making up the offwidth (90% of the climb) is very good, but after the crack ends you need to make a couple easy but committing face moves on less than inspiring rock.

name: Urge to Purge
description: Ascend the crack/dihedral to the roof.  At the roof, make an interesting traverse right, clip the bolt at the top of Feelin' Green and then continue traversing to the fist crack at the top of Irreconcilable Differences.  Finish at the Irreconcilable Differences anchor.

name: Firefighter
description: This route starts with some funky stemming moves past 3 bolts (crux).  After the bolts, the stemming becomes more positive and a crack opens up on the left side of the route that takes good gear.  Watch for loose blocks.

name: Modern Mythology
description: A thin awkward start leads to excellent sustained stemming moves higher up.  After the 2nd bolt, this climb is very well protected.  The fun continues all the way to the top, so don't let up until you get to the anchors!
The rock is in good condition. It's a nice climb, for basalt. Not super memorable, but worth the trip.

name: Ajax
description: The crux is near the top. It's a nice climb to a sweet crux.  Fall shade until 10am.

name: Almer Casile Memorial Buttress
description: Fun 5.8

name: The Arrow
description: I'm mainly posting this route to advise people to avoid it, the climbing wasn't great, and it the anchor in the Epeldi book isn't there anymore! It starts in a chimney, climbs a finger crack and goes up and around a wide flaring roof. I used the chains to the right on Weenie Roast but it wasn't exactly ideal.

name: Bad Ethics
description: Climb easy basalt until you reach two bolts placed next to eachother (use the one on the right, the one on the left is loose) with a bulge above.

name: Big Head Ed
description: This is listed in Boise Climbs with a thumb down due to some loose rocks.  It seems pretty solid now.  However there is a loose flake about two thirds of the way up.  This route is just to the left of Fat Ankles.  It is possible to TR this by climbing Fat Ankles first.  Lots of good places for gear if you want to lead.

name: Bloody Crack
description: A wide crack (BD 5-6) leading up to and through a roof.

name: Boulder Holder
description: Start in the dihedral to the right of 'Nut n' a Sling', pass a small roof, and climb the hand crack until level with the anchors to your left, then traverse to them. Easy to find solid gear on this one.

name: Burgermeister Meisterburger
description: Fun little climb that can be top roped after you lead Heat Miser on the right.  Good placement for gear on the lower half but gets very thin towards the top.

name: Bwana the Mighty Metolious Hunter
description: The usual Black Cliffs' "boulder problem in the sky." Enjoyable climbing overall, if somewhat short.

name: Chicken Wings
description: Climb up a nice, right-facing corner on tips and good edges (8 or 9-ish) until beneath a roof feature. The original line, 'Wooly Footed Vixen,' (10-) veers right here. Chicken Wings is actually a variation to this and heads directly over the roof passing one bolt. The headwall above the roof sports the crux on thin, bouldery climbing. A bit of a slap in the face after the lower bit. Fun movement on mostly clean rock.

name: Fat Ankles
description: Some smearing and stemming around the 3rd bolt make the crux.  It's a reach for the chains if you're not tall.

name: The Father
description: This is a pretty cool route with great exposure at the crux. It goes up a scaly crack to a roof, then left at the roof. The moves to get out from under the roof are the crux. It takes great pro the whole route as long as you're careful about the flakiness in the lower crack.

name: Heat Miser
description: It called heat miser for a reason.  In late spring/early summer it heats up pretty fast on a sunny day.

name: In Vitro
description: Great climb. Lower grade up until the crux where you pass over a roof. There is potential for a nasty fall if you biff the move over the bulge while leading, but there is additional protection part way up the bulge.    There is a small shelf to take a breather after making it over the roof and enjoy the view before reaching the anchor.

name: In Vivo
description: Fun, steep moves lead to a good stance after the third bolt. From here, head up and right past the fourth clip, to a steep, featured arete.

name: Jenga
description: This route is listed in Boise Climbs. It is the crack to the left of Little Boots and shares chains with that route. The bottom half is easy. Crux is near the top.  The holds get thin but a leap of faith is rewarded with bomber holds.  From there pull yourself up onto the shelf and you have reached the chains.

name: Kip to a Handstand
description: Easy ground leads to a boulder problem pulling over the roof (not as hard as it looks).

name: Lightning Crack
description: The namesake lightning crack zigzag is the top quarter/third of the climb..Not sure if the bottom is the tight dihedral, or the face just right of the dihedral, but both are fun!

name: Little Boots
description: Climb a cool dihedral with lots of holds and gear placement options.  Easy stemming leads to a crack surrounded by smooth walls where you will have to commit to jamming or liebacking (crux).  A few moves of that and then easy cruising to the chains.

name: Little Flower
description: This route is just right of Fat Ankles, and can be top roped from the anchors on that route. The bottom part includes a little vertical bushwhacking! Syringa, I believe, Idaho's state flower and quite pretty when blooming.    It is not great rock on the bottom half, pretty broken up, but that also means an abundance of easy hand and foot holds. Very easy climbing, perhaps even 5.4. The top half would go to the Fat Ankles anchors, and be a little more difficult.

name: Loaded Gun
description: Climber's left side of the Mid Cliffs. Climb the hand sized crack right of Tidy Up, to shared anchors.  Starts on obvious belay platform.  See picture.

name: Lucky Pierre
description: Start up the crack/corner right of the bolts, moving onto the pillar before the small roof. Fun climbing.

name: Mike the Dog
description: Follow thin hands crack to a roof with a bolt on the lip.

name: More Than I Can Chew
description: Crux is near the top.

name: Nash-e-mun
description: Good for first-timers on top rope.  Good first lead.  A few fun variations.

name: Nikita
description: Easier than it looks, thanks to holds which are hard to see from below, but the gear is fairly small the whole way. Crux comes at a bulge 2/3 of the way up where the feet disappear for a bit.

name: Number Nine
description: Nothing special, just another ok 5.8 trad climb at the cliffs. There's no gear for the first 15ft or so but it is all secure easy climbing. The rest of the route takes solid gear.

name: Nut 'n a Sling
description: Start with standard Black Cliff's stemming between columns, which leads up to a short crux, with a final thoughtful move to the chains. There is some loose rock on the sides of this climb.

name: Orientationally Confused
description: The crack to the right of Memorial Buttress. Fairly straightforward crack with no distinct crux. Good pro.

name: Potato Flake
description: A nice moderate trad line with good pro, this one starts on top of a column in a dihedral, then it follows a cool flake up to the anchors.

name: Prominent Crack
description: This is a nice well protected trad climb that doesn't see much traffic. Unfortunately the climb starts out ledgy and vegetated, but once the real climbings begin, the quality is solid. Climb twin cracks to a hand crack and then a wide pod going out a bulge. Surmounting the bulge is the crux, and will likely lure you into a beached whale position.

name: The Puffer
description: Easy moves lead to fun face climbing. Crux is at the top.  Fall Shade until 10am.

name: Rainbow Warrior
description: This is a classic route that seems to have developed a serious reputation. In my opinion, the serious stories I have heard about it are not warranted--it is a well-protected route. Certainly worth checking out!Relatively easy climbing (5.10 or so) for the first four bolts leads to a technical traverse at the fifth bolt. Traverse left on thunderclings to a deep slot around the base of the arete. From there, a stellar boulder problem climbs the arete, finishing with a big move to a good, sloping jug just above the anchor. Don't sell yourself short by trying to clip the anchor without doing the last move--it's a great finish! (Although it is a bit of a heart breaker!)Apparently a direct variation exists that skips the left traverse, but I haven't tried it. I have heard it ups the grade a couple letters.

name: Raptor's Revenge
description: This is the hand/fist crack just left of Heat Miser, and can share that anchor. Can be top roped, once the rope is up on Heat Miser. I'm quite petite, so it was good feet and a big chunk of arm, in the crack!

name: Rectal Cranial Insertion
description: The crack with a small roof between 'More Than I Can Chew' and 'Memorial Buttress'. It's short but has some interesting moves and good pro.

name: Snake Eyes
description: Great sport route with 4 bolts to Met Rap anchors.  The real trick is getting yourself to stay left around the 3rd bolt, it's seductive to go right where it drops the grade to a 5.7.  On tr, going up the right has a lot of balancy high-stepping and helps one develop good technique.

name: The Spear
description: The Spear is capped by an excellent finger crack crux near the top, but you have to pay your dues to get there. Start up junky rock on either side of the detached column, making sure not to kill yourself or your belayer with a loose block. I suspect this column has shifted out from the wall since the Epeldi guidebook was written. Once on top of the column, place a high piece, take a few deep breaths and punch it to the chains.

name: Squirt Gun
description: Standard straightforward black cliffs trad climbing for the first 2/3rds with a cool bulge with great holds at the top. If 5.8 trad is your jam, check it out. Chains are located inconveniently too far to the right, but are workable.

name: Steep Disorder
description: Thin crack leads to short steep face protected by one bolt at crux. Finish moves on face are fun!

name: Sugar Magnolia
description: Dihedral to the left of Lucky Pierre. Easy moves in the dihedral lead to some weirdness on the way to the chains.

name: Swallow
description: Directly to the left of Kip to a Handstand. Straightforward face climbing for the first 3 bolts. Step across a gap to a solid stance to clip the 4th bolt. Excellent route for leaders looking to push past 5.10a.

name: Sweat Engine
description: Follows mostly positive crimps and edges up a column face for several bolts until the rock turns to a blonde color and becomes pocketed. The crux pulls through some of these pockets with a couple slopers.     Enjoyable climbing the whole way. A great Black Cliffs 5.10!

name: Tidy Up
description: Opportunities to place supplementary gear if desired. Well protected for only having three bolts. Crux comes at the top.

name: Unknown
description: Not sure what this is called.  There are chains at the top but this isn't listed in the 2003 version of Boise Climbs and wasn't on MP.  There are bushes growing in this crack and pigeons roosting in it.  But it is a fun route.  Holds are good.

name: Wizard's Sleeve
description: This climb goes up a dihedral, goes left at a roof, and has an interesting thin face section leading to a chain anchor.

name: All the Way Home
description: Standard Black Cliff's broken jugs and side pulls lead you into a corner where you can clip the last bolt. From here, you need to transition to slab (crux) and make a few delicate moves to clip the chains.

name: Bryan's Route
description: The crux is the last several moves before the chains.

name: Bushwhacker
description: Plenty of holds, some gardening needed.  No poison ivy on route, but some near by, so be wary.

name: Epic for the Masses
description: Crux is an undercling/finger crack over a bulge at the top to the chains.  The start is a fun offwidth.

name: Funky
description: This route ascends a very obvious dihedral. Decent gear placements, with a lot of stemming moves. Near the top, the route overhangs, and the crux is pulling a move over the 'beak' to top out.

name: The King With A Crowbar
description: Climb standard Black Cliffs dihedral/stemming up towards a bulge. Clip the last bolt as you size up the bulge and then commit. The holds over the bulge are surprisingly good but you will struggle to find the feet you need to get the send. Mantle over the bulge and clip the chains. Super fun!

name: Rhus Radicans
description: If you know your plant names, you won't be too surprised to find some poison ivy at the base of this route. It's easy to avoid though. Start on a column top in a dihedral, enjoy the small cracks on both sides, and clip a bolt at the bulge and enjoy the fun climbing to the chains.

name: Stone Tools
description: Possibly one of the best 10s in the area. The climb starts after a 20-25 foot scramble up a series of blocks at which point you can clip the first bolt. Climb through four more bolts and encounter a bulgy crux well above the last bolt. Pull the bulge to a three bolt anchor with chains.

name: Sweet Thing
description: The crux is a big bulge at the top.

name: Ugly Duckling
description: This route starts after about a 15 foot scramble up some large blocks. It is short, steep, and well protected. Some feel the crux is in the lower steep section and others think it is the upper section between bolts 5, 6, and 7. Did I say well protected, I meant over bolted...be careful not to z-clip through the lower section of this climb.

name: BSU Fantasy
description: No single crux.  Just sustained, enjoyable moves.

name: Furst As Sent
description: Directly left of Stems and Jammies. The route name is painted at the base. Great pro until just below the top, where the crack widens and flares out before stopping abruptly. The moves after are somewhat balancy and slabby.

name: Jungle Book
description: Crack to chains right next to Mean Adene. Hand crack to top of column then face climb to small overhang use hand crack finish to chains

name: Little Nest
description: This climb is a jug haul. Big huge holds that you can get both hands on. It is a great first lead for somebody. It's four bolts to chains. The crux comes on the last move. You step out from a ledge onto a face and pull onto another ledge.

name: Mean Adene
description: Fun bolted line just left of Sweet Adene.  There is a crux down low, and then there are well spaced giant jug ledges the most of the rest of the way.  Fun crux sequence at the top finishes it out.

name: Mood Swing
description: Climb the finger crack between White Wash and Perception vs. Reality until it ends.  Veer left to finish on White Wash anchors,(5.8) or go right to finish out on Perception vs Reality(5.10a). Either way is worthwhile.

name: Perception vs. Reality
description: The crux is moving over the bulge, after the last bolt, to the anchors.  Get creative with your footwork and you will send.

name: Populace Offwidth
description: Straightforward offwidth crack that leads to anchors for Stems and Jammies.   Numerous crimps available both left and right if you’re inclined to use them.

name: School Daze
description: Pretty straightforward Black Cliffs 5.7 trad climbing. There are two dihedrals you can climb for the first half, the left of which had positive edges of all sizes, nice finger and hand jams, and some blocky moves toward the top. Not classic by any means but it's a worthwhile easy trad lead or TR for your newbie friends.

name: Stems and Jammies
description: This is a chimney climb.  It has great gear placements all the way up.  I'd say the crux is a small buldge about 3/4 the way up.  Great climb to practice placements on.

name: Sweet Adene
description: A great 5.8 for the area.  The crux is a small roof above the 5th bolt.

name: Sweet and Sour
description: Dihedral left of Sweet Adene. Mix of finger crack and face holds, and merges with Sweet Adene at the top to the anchors. Crux is pulling the move over the jutting rock at the top.

name: White Wash
description: A very enjoyable 5.9 that always draws a crowd.

name: No Bolts To Blind You
description: Starting just to the right of large sage brush, work your way up a blocky "corner system" with thin pro. After the first 15 feet, you are aiming for the left side of the bulge/nose where there is a nice offwidth crack to arm bar in to the top. Highlights are some "thought provoking" traverse moves, nice exposure, and of course, the off width finish. Thinly protected. Build your own anchor up top.

name: Rodeo Flips
description: The only bolted route on the wall. You can walk down around the base of the wall to reach the route, or rap in from the top. There are rap bolts near the top of the cliff, but not safely accessible without building an anchor etc before reaching over the edge. It's a fun route with mostly jugs until about 3/4 of the way when the holds disappear and you have to wander around a bit to reach the next bolt.

name: Allison Wonderland
description: Tech and sustained climb that requires imagination (as the Boise Climb guide states.)

name: Beefcurtain
description: starts in a finger crack, great rock.

name: Boise Gunfighter
description: One of Boise's best- naw definitely the best route at the grade. The crux comes down low (2nd bolt?) with a left hand sloper move coming around a little roof. Up higher past some fingery moves, the route joins a right facing corner system created by an eerie hanging basalt column. Climb through this section carefully and be sure your belayer is well out of the crash zone should this column ever cut loose while the route is being climbed! It never gave us any indication that it was loose, but its fall could be disastrous. Just look around at the base to see how many similar columns have cratered over time.  Next climb right a bit and encounter the awesome section of steep en-tabulated basalt. A touch of the jail-house in Boise. Athletic and pumping moves through this section will keep you smiling! Exit the en-tabulated section climbing left,and finish on some pocketed angular basalt to clip the chains!

name: Chronic Load
description: The start is hard, then pulling the roof (kneelock) and the moves after are sustained 5.11.

name: Doctor Hemlock
description: Climb the crack past 4 bolts then merge with Simple Physics.

name: Full Bred
description: Good warmup for the Scary Canyon climbs.

name: Men Who Pause
description: Awesome line in Scary Canyon established by Tedd Thompson and Pokey Amory. The lower half presents typical Black Cliffs tricky climbing on polished basalt and the technical crux of the route with slightly sporty bolt spacing (a stick is clip useful for the start). Milk an okay rest below the headwall and enjoy the spectacular finish on positive steep edges and pockets. This is one of the better sport routes in the canyon.

name: Onion Boy
description: Like its neighboring climbs, the crux is in the first few bolts, with thin, technical climbing on smooth basalt. Bring your A-game for the start (or a stick-clip) then be rewarded with a fun 5.9 crack and dihedral that cruises to the anchors.

name: Public Service
description: This is the furthest left route.

name: Simple Physics
description: Fairly sustained climbing. Be careful clipping second clip.

name: Angry Bunnies
description: Unique route with some fun moves through the last two bolts.

name: Another Face in the Crowd
description: Unlike most aretes at the Black Cliffs, this one has no holds! (Well, not many.)  Bring a full bag of tricks for this one. Pinch, grab slopers, stem, drop knees, and smear your way up fun but difficult feature climbing.  Top third eases considerably with the appearance of actual holds.  The inobvious nature of this route would make it very proud onsight—I would love to see someone make the attempt!

name: Bag of Stems
description: This is the chimney to the right of Unknown Leon. There is nowhere good to place protection until you go above and stand on a small boulder wedged in the bottom of the chimney, which is about 15 ft up. There are a couple horizontal cracks after that, and after that there is a 20 ft blank section. I climbed facing away from the cliffs, and about 5 ft below the anchor was a pocket behind me that was deep enough to stuff a C3 into.    The chimney walls are well featured and offer very secure stances. Bring a solid mental game.

name: Basic Training
description: Start on easy climbing up the outside of the short pillar.  Once on top of the pillar climb the crack in the dihedral to the anchors.  The crack behind the pillar starts as tips and gradually widens to fingers and then small hands.  It's a pity the crack doesn't start from the ground . . .

name: Big Fat Crack
description: Follow the big fat crack most of the way up. Once you finish that you'll have a large ledge to rest on before making your way up to chains to anchor on.

name: Bologna Pony
description: This route is a must do.  Climb the overhanging basalt column to the chains at the top. The crux is at the top.

name: Bologna Pony, var.
description: Climb Bologna Pony, but stay to the right of the last bolts to climb the thin face on some very small crimps to the anchor.

name: Buster Bronco
description: Cruiser crack/stem line that protects well (eats up mid-size nuts). Traverse to the right across a ramp atop the main pillar at the top of the climb to reach the anchors shared with the two lines to the right of this.

name: Copperhead
description: This is an excellent crack climb with great pro!    Start in a dihedral with a finger crack in the back.  enjoy great fingers and stemming, until the crack widens to perfect hands under a roof.  Pull the roof using finger locks and small edges for feet, and finish up an easier hand size crack to the anchors

name: Coupe de Ville
description: Fun route.  Good holds at the beginning.  Gets harder as you go.  Crux is near the top.  Thin cracks to climb over a shelf.  Big holds above the shelf.  Book rates this as 5.8 but feels more like 5.9 around the crux.  You can hike around to the top and set this up as top rope.

name: Desperate Indulgence
description: Climb the corner and finger crack to the large ledge at mid-route.  A series of positive but well spaced edges will take you the rest of the way to the anchors.

name: Detox
description: Easy crack and column climbing leads to a thoughtful crux at a slab face. Clip the lone bolt and choose your own adventure to get to the chains. Working too far left will decrease the difficulty while sticking to slab alone will make it harder.

name: Face in the Crowd
description: 1st-2nd bolt, 3rd-4th bolt, palm and smear, fingers

name: Falling Object
description: Crack to the right of Jump Chump. Easy climbing leads to a roof crack with sporty moves that can be well protected. After pulling the crux, finish at the Safe Sex Subaru anchors to the right.

name: First Lead
description: Aptly named! Easy to climb, easy to place gear, easy to practice top belay, and I was able to follow and clean with my very meager skills.

name: Frosted Flake
description: Follow a discontinuous seam on classic Black Cliffs edges until mid height, where the route steepens and the jams and pro get wider (fingers to a couple of hand jams) before getting quite thin again.  Small stoppers and cams from .3 to .5. A two-foot section will take a #1 or a #2.  Rap rings at top.

name: Goodbye Mr. Purple
description: From Boise Climbs: The intended line does not include using The Temple crack.  However, an edge at the left end of The Temple arch is considered to be on route.

name: Hex Breaker
description: Tricky moves off the deck without gear leading to solid pro about 20 feet up. Clip the fixed nut and pull the roof with some smeary feet. There are rumors that a block came off making the throw above the roof more solid and the grade soft (it was originally rated 5.11c).

name: Hilti Dust
description: A fun 5.11 for the Black Cliffs. Short dihedral leads you onto a couple bouldery face moves.

name: Holiday Nuts
description: This line is not in the 4th edition of Boise Climbs. It’s very likely this has been climbed before, but I have found no information, so I’m basing the description and rating off the one time I’ve been on it.  If anyone knows of a prior ascent, please let me know who it was and what, if anything, they named this, and I will correct the details here. And if you climb this, please input your assessment of the grade.  Standard Black Cliffs face climbing on positive edges, but the difficulty here lies in protecting the route with only small gear, hence the name.  Line merges at the top and shares anchors with The Layback.

name: In Between
description: Pretty easy to top rope this (there are rappel bolts located above the climb which can be easily accessed by a short hike up the gully to the left of this route).  Fun little climb.  Start is super easy and then sustained 5.10 territory.

name: Jump Chump
description: Easy, fun climbing over large blocks until 3rd bolt. At the 3rd bolt, the route earns the "jump" part of it's name. Short climbers BEWARE! Steep 8' section with thin holds, leads to a pretty good rail and then chains.

name: Kowallis and Richards Hardware Bin
description: From Boise Climbs: Dihedral to the Goodbye Mr. Purple chains

name: The Layback
description: Layback, stem, and chimney the bottom section. Pull a small roof with big holds and finish on easy slab.  Epeldi guide lists this route as having no anchors, but this route currently has a two-bolt anchor.

name: Lithium Deficiency
description: Fun route with a committing feel up top, good gear, just save the small cams for last!

name: Locker-box
description: Face climbing for the first half to a fun bulging hand crack.   If anyone has info on prior assents let me know.

name: Lunch Ledge
description: Fun little climb.  Starts off working up a nice crack, fairly easy.  Gets harder as you go.

name: Minuteman
description: Climb up a dark dihedral until you reach a bulge.  Work up a solid crack and pull over the bulge on great, juggy holds.  This is a great climb! Don't miss it.

name: Mystery Route
description: The crux is near the middle of the climb, and the ascent is a bit precarious for the next several feet.

name: Neophyte Flight
description: A fun crack with a tricky crux going over a bulge.  Get the beta right and it's not that hard, but if not it will feel harder than the grade indicates.

name: No Name
description: A fun dihedral with sparse pro leads to the first of two roof cruxes. The first roof is easier than the second but is mentally challenging since you’re pulling on a huge, loose block.   Be advised—this may hold; it may not.  The second roof goes on big holds and requires creative footwork and long reaches.

name: Overlord
description: Stem up a dihedral to a boulder problem above the 2nd bolt. Use some very small foot holds and lots of friction to set yourself up for a large move out right, clip the 3rd bolt and get creative pulling the roof. Get on it!

name: Petty Theft
description: Thinning edges lead to a crux REACH involving a palming sloper/crimp.  Latch this rig, get your feet up, and crank!

name: Rigid Digits
description: Challenging dihedral left of Jump Chump that requires some overlap with that route. Subsequent to the 2016 Epeldi guide, this route has been equipped with its own anchors.  Stemming, crimping, and liebacking on a positive but flared crack make for varied climbing that would be difficult to protect.

name: Safe Sex Subaru
description: Harder to protect than to climb, Safe Sex Subaru follows a thin crack and plenty of face holds. Pull over a small roof on creative feet.

name: Short Crack
description: If a rope is already up on Spiny Trouble, this is a nifty hand (arm) crack, with plenty to work with. As a beginner, I enjoyed it! The top would be Spiny Trouble, if you use those anchors. supposedly the route has anchors clear up top, but those are likely ancient. I have no idea what the two parts combined should go at.  Edit to add (8/19/18): Someone has added shiny new hangers, with properly painted chains, to this route. There are also some anchors on top, near the path. They seemed solid, but who knows how ancient they are? They are also set very far apart.

name: Spiny Trouble
description: The furthest left route at The Shorts.

name: Swimmin' in Ignorance
description: Start by face climbing up towards a high first bolt. Place a few pieces of gear in a small crack before you reach the bolt. Clip two bolts, then pull onto a ledge under the roof. Lean back and clip your last bolt at the edge of the roof. Pull the roof on huge jugs but marginal feet to another ledge with the chains.

name: The Temple
description: Begins as a great hand crack with ample feet for easy placements. The crack peters out up top and leaves a thin, slabby face to the left and a steep face with chains above to the right.

name: Tijuana T
description: Fun crack climb that gets exciting at the top.  Taking the trail on the left side of the cliffs will put you up top were you can set this route up TR.

name: Toddler
description: A lot of people lead this as a first climb. It's an easy climb that is well protected. The crux comes at the top with a bulge.  The anchors are on the top of the block at the top of the route, and not visible until the top. Runners are needed to extend the anchors if you wish to top rope it.

name: Trimmed Bush
description: Climb the crack that is five feet to the right of Bologna Pony.  The crack starts as fingers and goes to hands at the top. One of the better crack climbs at the Black Cliffs.

name: Unknown
description: Unsure if this has a name.  Near the top you can find a fun move if you stay to the left, probably 5.8 territory.  Staying in the crack on the right is probably easier though.

name: Unknown
description: This is an interesting climb with a couple of possible variations.  If you stick to the left there is a fun roof to pull over (5.9).  Taking the right side is easier.  There is a lot of loose rock near the top.  Be careful when setting anchor or top rope that you don't knock rock down on your partner.  Lots of good places for pro.

name: Unknown Leon
description: The route starts with fun moves up the wide finger crack and arete.  After clipping the second bolt, the crux moves go up and right from the end of the crack.  If you figure out the crux don't let up, as there are several delicate slab moves that must still be overcome to gain the anchors.  A very engaging climb!    The chimney to the right of the arete is off.

name: Win, Lose, or Draw
description: Fun climbing leads to the 3rd bolt, where the main line of this route goes right using BIG reaches to good holds.  As implied by the name, there are three possible ways to climb the top of this route: 5.10c variation: Move right at the third bolt and stay right as you make your way to the anchors.5.11b/c variation: Go left at the third bolt to climb through the vertical seam. After clipping the fourth bolt, go back right to finish on the 10c main line.5.11d variation: Stay to the left of the fourth bolt for the most challenging finish to this climb.

name: [Redacted]
description: This route offers a unique contrast between its lower and upper sections.    Scramble up some broken choss for ~20 feet until you can step up and clip. The technical crux comes at and above bolt 2 with stems and side-pulls leading to a somewhat difficult third clip.    After this, the route steepens and offers great movement between spaced, positive holds all the way to the top.    Have your belayer watch you closely through the crux as you end up a bit above bolt 2 with the choss ledge not far below.

name: Beta Junkie
description: Anyone who can tell me how to actually climb this route gets a gold star...ok, Hard start move fast on small footholds and smearing using undercling hold with right hand. Climb the route near the bolt line using the cracks and legdes. Hand jam and work your way to the face below a huge jug, dyno here and work your way to the steep roof. Side pull on left, stay center, step high left and smear foot on side of roof, stand, reach high right to good hold stem your way to the chains. This route is awesome and is easy to toprope to get it dialed before you lead it. Classic route, exposed at times, fun and well bolted.

name: Bosom Buddies
description: "2 bolts and supplementary pro to the Number Eight anchors.  This line was previously a toprope problem that ended at the Number Eight Left anchors.  The original finish is probably best avoided due to loose blocks." -Epeldi

name: Circumciser
description: Climb this basalt column to the top. I find the crux to be the top part of the climb while others find it to be the bottom part of the climb. The route is well protected and fun!

name: Fly the Friendly Skies
description: Dihedral to roof with no anchors

name: Full Tilt Boogie
description: Start on relatively easy slabby pillar on jugs.  Wander up this towards the roof, clipping bolts as you go.  Just before the roof is a cruxy slab move to reach the roof but the business is still waiting.  Crank the roof on surprisingly good holds to the ledge where you can reach the chains.  I recommend going out the central/right side of the roof or you may set yourself up for a nasty whipper.

name: Grandpa's Route
description: This is a bolted route up the face of a column between Balloon Party and Raptor Arete on the Tall Cliffs, I do not know the name or the grade but can mark the bolt line, please update if you know the grade or name of the route

name: Hara-Kiri in a Combine
description: Fun route with some intimidation factor. It climbs better than it looks from the ground. Move up the column face slightly left of the bolt line for several clips before crossing right and up to a fingers/ring-locks crack. Plug a piece or two from great stances and then up to another bolt. From here, head left and clip another bolt to protect the crux. I remember finding a nice knee-bar rest here. Fun, bouldery moves lead into an obtuse corner feature and jugs at the anchors.    Also known as Seppuku, Hara-kiri is primarily described as the now-abolished Japanese ritual of suicide by disembowelment. The act was performed to allow samurai facing certain death the ability to die with honor and to avoid torture by enemy captors.

name: Headlights in the Fog
description: "Climb straight up the serrated face to the Number Eight anchors" -Epeldi

name: Horrible Human History
description: Finely tuned leading skills recommended, this climb is given a thumbs up in Sandy Epeldi's Boise climbs book

name: Joe Pro
description: Lichen covered face and crack just right of Muchachas Borrachas.  Wide finger crack slightly off the deck with multiple protectable cracks as you ascend widening near the top right of Muchachas Borrachas anchors

name: Muchachas Borrachas
description: Scramble up some blocky terrain to the first bolt.  With the first bolt at your neck, pull the crux moves that are a bit trickier than they look.  Easy slab climbing past the next two bolts leads to the anchor.

name: My Stinky Hole
description: A fun, yet appropriately named, route.  Climb the column without using the cracks on either side.    A tricky start on thin holds through a roof (crux) leads to the first bolt.  If you don't want to commit to the moves before the first bolt, you can climb the crack next to the column, clip bolt #1 from there, then downclimb and start the route with the rope clipped above.      After the initial crux, easy but fun jug pulling up the vertical column commences past several more bolts before reaching a bird-poo covered ledge (Hence the name).      From the ledge, clip the last bolt and head up and slightly left onto steep rock.  You may want to bring some tiny nuts or cams to protect the final awkward step to the right to gain the anchors.

name: Number Eight
description: Easy Stemming leads to an interesting sequence towards the top . . .

name: Number Eight Left
description: Crack to chain anchor, exit right when crack ends.  Anchors over the top of the prow

name: Raptor Arete
description: Fun arete/face climb with a steep finish.

name: Rosy Palms
description: Short but sweet!  Scramble up the blocky terrain to the overhanging roof crack and commence jamming!  The crack varies from hands to fists.    Sandi Epeldi's book gives this route 5.11C, but when we climbed it we felt that it wasn't harder than 5.10.  The jams are solid the whole way, and if you look around there are a few key feet that help.  Whatever the grade, it's a fun climb with great pro!

name: Thanks for the Mammaries
description: Climb up the column face to anchors at the top.  Very enjoyable climb..

name: Unknown bolted route between Number Eight and Dolly
description: This route is between number eight and dolly and is a bolted line.  I don't know the grade or any other info on it, can't find it in a guide, if you know more let me know

name: Barry, Barry
description: Fun face climbing with good protection where you need it.  Nice steep finish.

name: Bolts-n-Burger
description: The crux is at the top.

name: Circuit Breaker
description: Extremely fun climbing up a pronounced column.  Weave between the left, right, and center of the column as you go.  As usual for the Black Cliffs, the finishing moves do not disappoint!

name: Constant Current
description: Another great Black Cliffs trad climb that demands a variety of crack climbing skills! Start in a corner with sweet double cracks that go from wide hands to fists. After topping out on the column on the left side, get ready for some perfect finger locks. Entertaining face climbing follows all the way to the anchors. Great climb, and a bit of a proud lead for a 5.8. Edit: Two photos show two different routes. The darker photo is Constant Current, the lighter photo is actually Barry Barry.

name: Crunchy Frogs
description: Weird thought-provoking moves.  It's all there but not exactly obvious (at least to me).  Greasy on a hot day.  This climb is a bit spicy due to interesting bolt placement that puts you in ledge-fall territory near the second AND third bolts.

name: Dawn Patrol
description: Typical sport route for this area. Crux between 2nd & 3rd bolts; take care not to blow the 3rd clip as it could hurt.

name: Dos Pescadores
description: Start on Thursday Knights, but cut right after the 3rd bolt. Get a good rest on the ledge before the finish, then climb up an overhanging face with impeccable rock using widely spaced finger locks. Tough finishing moves!

name: The Doug Scott Route
description: Fun jammin!  Sandy Epeldi's book describes this as "the best jam crack in the area."  The crack starts about 15 off the deck and there isn't much for pro before that.    Watch for nested owls after the roof at the end of the crack.

name: Excalibur
description: Yet another retro-bolted crack climb.  This climb follows a nice finger crack for most of it's length, and then moves right at the top to join the anchors for Thursday Knights.  Fun moves and good pro!

name: The Flying Circus
description: Superb jamming up a hand crack with a crux move to the anchors on top.  Excellent!

name: French Fried
description: Is the climb fried or are you?  Small edges interspersed with rest jugs climb the middle of the pillar followed by a brief roof to reach the chains.

name: Generic Crack
description: Crack directly right of Row Your Boat. Follow the crack to the top of the pillar, then head left to the Row Your Boat anchors. Alternatively, head right for a 5.10d variation, but with no anchors.

name: Lancelot
description: Crack to Flying Circus anchors.  Starts low with hand jams and quickly turns to standard Black Cliffs "sport climbing while plugging gear in a crack".  One loose block at the top that's marked, but doesn't appear to be going anywhere.  After I climbed it, I rapped the route and cleaned off all the loose stuff I could find so it's good to go.

name: Lizard Breath
description: Fun climb with slightly slopey holds near the bottom that become more positive as you get higher up.

name: Nemesis
description: A delicate and engaging thin seam just to the right of The Throb. I think the intended line goes directly up and right to the anchors on Kaopectate, but you can also finish left on The Throb with good pro and exciting movement. One of the best cracks at the cliffs!

name: Ohm's Law
description: This is a very entertaining climb!  It follows a finger crack up a corner, with plenty of edges for your feet for *most* of the climb.  The crux is in the middle and involves a few moves without the straightforward feet, but with good finger locks.  The moves at the top are fun too, and easier than they look from below.

name: Pabst Smear
description: Technical and sustained palming, smearing, and stemming.  Don't underestimate the finish, this route doesn't let up until you are at the anchor!    Apparently this route originally went on gear and was subsequently retro-bolted.  Without the bolts the pro looked like it would be very thin and tricky! What a bold FA!

name: Pictures of Lily
description: Technical and sustained climbing using various small holds the whole way.  The reach from the final stance to the anchors is long and could prove problematic for the vertically challenged . . .

name: Row Your Boat
description: Climb up bolted column face without straying into Bolts and Burgers on the left or the sweet looking hand crack on the right.  Crimpy crux near the top of the pillar.  Mantle onto the top of the pillar, clip the last bolt, and then a few more easy moves land you at the chains.

name: The Standard
description: One of the original black cliffs climbs. Route starts in a chimney right above a fallen column. Ample holds, easy chimney, and takes good pro.

name: Steve’s Offwidth
description: Straightforward 5” offwidth crack with plenty of constrictions offering very secure feet.

name: Stretch Armstrong
description: A very fun addition to West Carbody. Stick-clip the first bolt or clip it from the Velcro Fly start column. The first 4 bolts are characterized by good quality Black Cliffs 5.10+ arete climbing on interesting holds. Cop a rest when you can on the blocky section near the top , clip that last bolt, and punch it through an overhanging boulder problem to the anchors. It is possible to clip the last bolt and skirt out right to the Velcro Fly anchors to avoid the 5.11d+ crux

name: The Throb
description: Fun climbing that starts out easy in a small vertical open book with a crack and ample holds.  At the top of the open book move right and get ready for the business!  Ascend the overhanging corner/finger-crack above to the anchors.

name: Thursday Knights
description: Fun dihedral stemming leads to an overhanging finish on positive holds. Great climb!

name: Velcro Fly
description: Follow the finger crack in the corner. Don't miss all the good holds on the arête to the left. If you finish straight up the finishing move to the anchor is really hard! You can also finish up and right and then traverse back left if you can't get the last move.

name: Wounded Knee
description: A fine offwidth established by Bob Boyles in the mid 70s.  About the route, Bob offers the following observations:  “The distance between the good pro is rather far and I'm sure I would have grounded out if I popped out higher up. I always thought the "wounded" knee jam lower down was the crux. That's where you have to pull your knee out where the crack pinches down a bit.”

name: The Gulcher
description: A very long route with more than one crux. There is a set of anchors at mid-point if you don't have a 70m rope. It has been described as 2 pitch route because of these anchors. Don't short yourself by stopping there!

name: The Holy Grail
description: This multi-pitch sport route is the tallest in Hell's Canyon.  It has 4 eleven pitches, with the hardest moves at the very top.  You can rapel the route, 70 meter rope recommended (the third pitch is 30m), or walk off to the north.  This is a really fun route with a lot of variety.As of 7/8/20, I know of only one other group that has climbed the route.  Isaac and I did the FFA trading pitches, so there is an opportunity for someone to snag the first individual free ascent.I'm anxious to confirm the grades, so please let me know what you think after you climb it.

name: Mental Wounds
description: This is the third route from the end on the exposed part of grassy ledge that runs along the base.

name: Moon Shadow
description: To date this last route on the right side.

name: Propitious
description: This is on the the right side second to last

name: Wild Bills Flying Circus
description: This is the route # 5 from the left side.

name: War and Peace
description: Amazing pocket jugs on a 45 degree wall leads to a sequential crux finish

name: Beware of Meese
description: Climb the overhanging rail utilizing heel hooks and making powerful moves to crystals. Keep it together for a physical topout.

name: Fetus Clunk
description: A sister problem to the Cooper's Rock "Cletus Funk". Get a heel hook and throw for the top, using an intermediate if you want.

name: Grazing Allotment
description: Start on the undercling and sidepull. Move up through the large sidepull and crimp, smear and throw for the top.

name: Abbey Road
description: Start far to the right of Highway to Hell and traverse into the start of Highway to Hell and just go up Highway to Hell. It's a traversal.

name: Highway to Hell
description: Start wherever and go straight up. Be careful the rock sucks.

name: 1984 is a Reality
description: Climb the crack

name: Down With Big Brother
description: At the front of the formation climb up face or crack to ledge then climb the crack through the overhang

name: Thought Police
description: Stem your way up the dihedral, short but fun

name: unclimbed crack
description: Probably never climbed but looks like the best climb in the area starts off as hands and widens will need some big gear to protect the top.

name: Till Dawn Ridge
description: Boise has it all, especially when you look enough!I spotted this rock ridge on a trail run on nearby Cervidae Peak. Closer inspection revealed a fun ridge scramble! This ridge climbs toward the summit of Mack/Numnut Peak. It is perfect for testing new approach shoes or alpine training.The highlight of the ridge (first two sections) is 1000 feet long and gains 500 feet. With an average slope of 45 degrees. Exposure on the ridge is mostly minimal, but there are some spicy sections. Opportunities abound to hop on and off the ridge. Various ways exist to climb the ridge, creating a custom adventure from 3rd class to easy 5th class.Route:First section: Rock Fin The beginning of the ridge starts at an intersecting creek bed. This first section is steep, fun, and ends shortly after a rock fin.  Second section: Towers The second section contains several distinct towers, offering the cruxes of the route. An unmistakable White Pinnacle "The Flaming Sword" is found during this section. This is the most engaging and exposed section. There is a rock cairn marking the end of this section.  Third section: Discontinuous Wrap-up After the towers the ridge become discontinuous and less steep. You can hike a wandering animal trail or do an occasional third class problem.  Once you have topped out the ridge you can continue to the summit of Mack/Numnut Peak, or run down one of the various ridges. Either way it's a great workout with an alpine rock feel.  I first summited the ridge at sunrise, hence the name: “Till Dawn Ridge."  The ridge is likely a dike of the Snake River Plain made of basalt with intruding granite.I am sure that I wasn't the first to spot or climb this ridge, but I could not find any information on it.

name: Teething
description: Looks like a fun route to climb. We didn't have time to actually climb it ourselves so Goodluck!

name: Trainers
description: Crux is near the top. Fun Climb! Pro thins out towards the top. X's in the picture are for potential trad placement spots

name: Booyakasha
description: Dirty when the FFA was done 8-23-2016.  Bad feet and bad, run-out protection between the flake and the flat part that can be walked across, which is where the PG-13 rating comes into play.  Falling on this route can result in a pendulum, and zippering gear on this low, traversing route can easily result in a ground fall.

name: Memorial Route (aka Caudill Queen King Route *original name*)
description: The crux comes on the 6th and 7th pitches which in my opinion both go at 5.8+.  Take plenty of quickdraws because the crux is slabby, but the bolts are quite close together at the hard parts.  On some of the easier pitches there is decent runout.  All bolted anchors.  Comes really close to the regular route at pitch 5 or so.    Additional user submitted route info:   Some more info on the pitches 1-5.7, 2-4th, 3-5.4, 4-5.7,5-5.8, 6-5.8+, 7-5.8, 8-5.7 (5.9 if you follow the bolt line over the roof and do not go left)

name: Regular Route
description: Can be pitched out however you want. I've done it in 10 pitches and I've also done it in 6 with a 70m rope to it's full capacity on every pitch.

name: Scenic Traction
description: 1. Climb up cracks, then trend up and right to a ledge system and an old two-bolt anchor beneath a long vertical crack (5.6, 180').   2. Clip an old pin in the crack above, then angle up and left into the middle of the steeper face. Climb straight up past two bolts, then run it out to a ledge. (5.9+R, 120').   3. Continue straight up on easier terrain, then step right to another pair of older bolts (5.7, 80').   4. Angle up and left into the middle of the face, then straight up, with occasional gear. Belay after 180', under a Cadillac size, two-foot thick, V-shaped flake. This is somewhat below, and 80 feet left of, a prominent left-facing dihedral with a large lone tree. You will be directly under a large dead tree at the top of the cliff.   (5.8R, 180').   5. Layback up and left around the V-shaped flake, then gain a small ledge and left-facing dihedral/flake. Up this, then run it out up a nice rippled face to a small ledge and two-bolt anchor. (5.8R, 180').   6. Continue straight up on never-ending dike ripples, passing occasional flakes for gear, and belay at a fat right-facing flake, just before the angle eases, just as the rope runs out (5.8R, 205')   7. Continue to the top (190', 5.7)

name: Slippery Slope
description: Friction slab at its best.  The crux sections are bolted very well but a light rack to 1 inch helps in  between.  Poor pro and few bolts lead to some interesting run-outs on a couple of the easy pitches.  Overall a phenomenal route.

name: 5.11 roof
description: This route is a little more sparse on bolts compared to other routes at the thinking spot. The climbing is no harder than 5.9 except for the roof. The roof is a cool bouldery move with a bolt right at the lip. There are anchors up high (170 ft), but probably easiest to angle left after the 3rd bolt above the roof and use the Oh Eight anchors if free.

name: 5.7 corner
description: Good 2 pitch trad climb with fixed pin and a 1/4 inch bolt on first pitch. Follow a low angle corner with good protection up to a tree. Belay near or above the tree. Second pitch goes up the obvious steeper corner with good protection, then around onto a ramp and traverses to the right and up and over a blocky bulge. There is a steep corner finish, but it is currently full of moss.

name: Arete Route
description: This route starts on the right side of the arete splitting the west and south sides of the thinking spot. Follow 3 bolts on the right side then step around to the left side and easier climbing up a slab to the anchors.

name: Beginner 1
description: Right hand route of the three shorter sport routes to the left of the Sparkle Dance left facing corner. These three routes are a great spot for kids and folks new to climbing.

name: Beginner 2
description: Middle of three shorter sport routes left of the sparkle dance left facing corner. Great route for kids.

name: Beginner 3
description: Left most of three shorter bolted routes. Great spot for intro to climbing and with kids.

name: Big Ernies Revenge
description: Two pitch route: first pitch is a hand and fist crack with a lot of features as well as the crack- 5.9. No bolts aside the anchors which are two bolts with quicklinks. The second pitch is well bolted. It is really varied, including some chimneying, stemming, and a few bulges to pull over. Anchors are near the top of the cliff, two bolts with quicklinks. Can walk off or do two rappels with a single 60m rope.

name: Cheers Mr Smith
description: This is a bit steeper than most other T-spot routes. Starts up an easy wide crack until the first bolt can be clipped, then  past three more bolts through a light colored layback rib, over a bulge and into less steep terrain for the last two bolts. Rap rings for anchors.

name: Civil Disobedience
description: This is a mixed pitch above the 5.7 corner. There are bolted anchors from the top of the 5.7 corner to both belay this pitch and rappel from. This route goes up the left crack on gear and into a short dihedral where the first bolt is, then out the steep section on big holds past a couple more bolts. It turns the lip, then up a corner with a good crack and natural protection, then steps right and past a couple more bolts on easier ground up to the anchors.   To descend rap/lower off the top anchors (~90 ft), then rap from the anchors atop the first pitch, a 70m will reach, a 60m rope won't

name: Dirty August
description: Goes up past some big huecos, a bit reachy at the crux, could be a bit harder for folks under 5'10". A fun way to do this is to link it with the second pitch on Big Ernies Revenge for a long sport pitch.

name: Fire on the Mountain
description: P1 (24m):  Climbs through several ledges, with huecos and jug rails between.  The 10a crux is a distinct section of blank rock, in the middle of the pitch, offering little more than smeared feet and a very short (6")  vertical finger crack, to setup for a large reach.  Some body english will make this crux engaging and accurate at 10-    P2 (18m):  An easier pitch climbs through a series of larger ledges, on jugs.  This pitch also offers a distinct crux from a solid stance on a large foot ledge with a couple crimps and only smeared feet, to mantle the left slanting ramp feature halfway through.  Again, smart movement will make this crux about 9+    Descent:     a)  The route (both pitches) can be rappelled with an 80m rope (to the op of the boulder that is on the right of the start), with rope stretch exactly.     b)  Each pitch could be rappelled individually with a 60m rope.     c)  The (huge) ledge at P2 anchors could be traversed left, and up.  Some bolts exist to protect the traverse around the left arete (easy 4/5th class).  Hike off climber's right.

name: Oh Eight
description: One of the better pitches at the thinking spot. Varied climbing and well bolted.

name: Perkolator
description: A short scramble gets you up to the steep start. It is a good idea to stick clip the first bolt as there are a few hollow flakes/holds at the beginning. Mostly made up of good holds with a couple of reachy crux sections.  If you want to top rope this route, it is an easy traverse from the ledge above the anchors of Dirty August, or the anchors on the first pitch of Big Ernie's Revenge to access the anchors atop this route.

name: Rodin's Belly Button
description: An overhanging route going through three roofs. Nine bolts up to an anchor with rap rings. To get back down below the approach scramble, with a 70 m rope you can rappel down from the route anchors, or use the big rap bolt at the base of the route.

name: Silver Rush
description: Slabby sport route with a few distinct crux sections. Starts to the left of a shallow seam with juggy flakes. First pitch is ~ 10- with 10 bolts, second pitch ~ 5.9 and a little dirtier, just doesn't get climbed as much. For the second pitch you can follow it all the way to the top of the cliff, or belay at some anchors 30 ft below the top, then do a short pitch to the top. It is neat to do the whole thing in one pitch, but takes some long runners and rope management to prevent bad rope drag. Sometimes there are quicklinks on the top, though pulling a rope through these if rappelling can be tough. If rappelling from the top a 60m rope doesn't quite make it to the first pitch anchors. Probably easier walking off if topping out.

name: Sparkle Dance
description: An interesting trad route that collects moss. It is a good route, though it could really do with some more traffic to clean up. A crack system to the left of the overhanging sport route - perkolator. Will feel a bit slick with the moss in the crack.

name: Sport route 1
description: The first pitch of this route goes around 5.7/8 and goes up to a bolted anchor. This is around 100 feet and if you only intend on doing the first pitch you need two ropes to rappell. The second pitch has a definite crux pulling over a bulge.  Very fun and protected by a bolt at your waist.  Two bolt anchor on the top.  You could rappell the route, but the walkoff only takes ten minutes.

name: The Thinker
description: Route goes up a ramp, through some blocky terrain, over a bulge, through a roof and up a dark upper headwall. You need a full 70 m to reach the ground.

name: Unnamed
description: A fun route with large holds and varied climbing.

name: Unnamed
description: A well bolted route, with the crux in the middle. It is possible to wander left and right and make it a bit easier.  There is an upper extension that goes to the top that was added last year, five more bolts and checks in at 5.11 if you reach around the left side of the arete, more difficult if you stay on the right side.

name: Unnamed
description: The first three bolts lead to a ledge about 1/3 of the way up, then clip a bolt and make a dynamic move starting up the upper 2/3 of the route with a further 5 bolts to the anchors. The upper 2/3 is the best climbing, with good rests between crux sections.

name: Unnamed Chimney
description: Awesome chimney splitting the formation.  3rd class scrambling to get up into it.  About half way up the climber is totally inside the rock.  The top is probably the crux with a few alternate finishes that probably go at 5.9 and 5.10+.  Really fun climb.  To descend walk climbers right untill you see a trail.  Take this trail all the way down to the base.  Another option is scrambling 4th class when the trail breaks off.  It is obvious.

name: Zig Zag corner
description: Starts in a corner below the large chimney on the north end of the thinking spot. The route wanders a bit, zig zagging up corner systems. The slightly overhung top is the crux, and can be avoided by traversing a ramp to the right before the steeper final corner. Can be done in one pitch, though expect bad rope drag. There are various decent locations for a belay part way up.

name: Snapper
description: This is a bolted (6) sport route that could also be trad led.   Fun route that takes you to the lower of the two spires.  Pass the shuts and climb around to the left of the lower spire to gain its apex.    Scramble up from the belay area to the right to gain the crack.  Clip the bolt then get out on the face and use whatever you want.

name: Stepping Razor
description: The crux is right off the ground and extends until the 3rd bolt. Really fun route that demands strong calves and a cool head. Falling before the first bolt would end pretty bad. The rock surface does not lend itself to smearing so some creativity is required for your feet. The middle of the route is the easiest and allows for a decent rest, and while the top isn't as hard as the bottem it still requires some delicate footwork.

name: Tool Boys
description: Might be a decent route if it had more traffic. The rock is a bit chossy around the last two bolts where it gets a bit slabby.

name: After Midnight
description: A continuation to Midnight Visitor.  From the Midnight Visitor Anchors, climb up and right, using a crack, and then some more knobby face, past 4 bolts to a higher anchor.      You could link the two climbs into one long pitch . . .    To descend, a double rope rap will get you all the way down, or with one rope do two raps, stopping at the Midnight Visitor anchors.

name: Backslide
description: A fun, unusual sport route that includes a couple chimney sections at the bottom and the top. Mind the crumbling rock on the left side as you start.

name: Computer Girl
description: Bouldery start from 10 feet off the ground (crux) provides spice from the get go (stick clip the first bolt if you want piece of mind).  Stay on the slab at the very left edge.   Second crux is pulling the smaller bulge (grabbing the tree reduces the difficulty). Saunter up the rest of the way to the bolts.    P2 goes up and left. After clipping a couple of bolts, wrap around to the large chimney (use a 48' runner to reduce drag).  Climb the chimney/crack straight up.  Clip the final bolt to gain the summit.

name: Deliverance
description: Follow a low angle crack to a chimney with a crack in each corner. The crux is pulling an overhanging bulge in the back of the chimney. The route ends on a ledge with a tree and one bolt (with just a hanger).   Repel with a 70m rope. You could probably us a 60m but may have to down climb a little at the end. Tie stopper knots.  The rock is dirty but could be cleaned up with traffic. There is some weak rock at the top but should clean up too.

name: For Whom the Bell Tolls
description: The crack and flake line that is the first line of bolts left of Backslide. Climb through a hard slot (crux, maybe 5.10?, handjams VERY useful & sharp) into a corner below a massive flake.   Layback and jam the flake to the chains.

name: Heart of Darkness
description: Start up Midnight Visitor for the first 3 bolts, then do a delicate traverse right, passing one bolt and then joining up with the top of Junkie Cosmonaut.  When you get to the anchors at the top of Junkie Cosmonaut, keep climbing onto the next pitch, which is called Shades of Grey.      Overall this felt less sustained than the neighboring Midnight Visitor/After Midnight linkup, but it has a couple steep tricky cruxes that take some figuring out and demand strong toes.

name: Life Without Beer
description: Knob pulling at it's finest!  It's a pity this one isn't longer.    Getting to the first bolt takes some courage, as you have to pull what may be the crux move over a nasty landing to get to it.

name: Midnight Visitor
description: Excellent face climbing up a beautiful knobby face, and a nice long sustained pitch to boot.  This one is a must do!    The first bolt can be clipped by standing on the large obvious foot hold at the start, although getting onto the foothold requires a move.      After clipping the bolt, pull the crux move over the initial bulge, and then enjoy the beautiful sustained knob pulling all the way to the anchor.  Stellar!

name: Odd Job
description: This is a fun route on good rock in a great location. It starts with friction slab, followed by sustained edging on protruding crystals, and crack climbing. The bolts are spaced enough to make things a bit spicy without being overly dangerous.    Pitch 1: Start up the toe of the West Face of Goldfinger Rock, clipping spaced bolts for about 50m to a two bolt belay at a decent stance. This pitch is a foot workout!    Pitch 2: Continue up above bolted belay, clipping ~4 bolts, and then work your way up the wide crack on the left. I wouldn't have minded having a #5 to protect the offwidth, but if you're solid on wide climbing you'll find it pretty secure and easy. As you climb up the crack, it gets thinner and eventually peters out, at which point you transfer right to another crack which leads to the summit.    I built a gear belay with large nuts/cams at the top, or you can sling blocks. There may be bolts on top of the summit block; I can't say for sure since we stopped 10ft short of the true summit.

name: Mr. Jugs
description: See the guidebook for details (downloadable).    This is one of several climbs on Patina Pin with lower difficulty ratings, but, they are committing climbs. If a second cannot follow and clean these routes, it will take thought to clean on rappel.

name: Top Rope
description: This is up the flake, then straight up to the anchor. Can be done as top rope, but someone will need to lead a route to get the rope up there.

name: Access Corner
description: This is route number 4 in the Klosof guide for Terrapin: "Corner to right of first three routes until on top of back of Franklin’s Tower. Webbing may be found to descend. Not recommended."

name: Bee Line
description: Fun route, start up the same slab as Sandy Line/Fall Line and shares the first (and maybe second) bolt. Crux is more of a mental one as there is a slightly tricky move where the slab meets the face and there is potential to deck on the slab below. After that its just face climbing. Can be done on Top Rope after leading Fall Line, best to run a few directional draws to reduce any swing.

name: Borrowed Shoe
description: From Klosof: "Climb to pocket & follow bolt line to top. 5-6 quick draws plus long slings for shared anchor."

name: Dancin' in the Streets
description: From Klosof: "Climb up to first bolt of Shakedown Street & traverse right to separate line of bolts. Continue up to rounded arête past face holds. Well protected, use a 60 meter rope to descend with one rope. 8-9 quick draws plus anchor."

name: Fade Away
description: This is route number 3 in the Klosof guide for Terrapin: "Climb up past bolts from top of notch looking for line of bolts leading right. Follow bolts up & right to same anchor as Touch of Gray. 8+ quick draws plus anchor."  The lower half of this shares bolts with "Touch of Gray"

name: Fall Line
description: Great route. Lots of fun climbing including slab, face, arete, and some crack. Shares a few bolts with Sandy Line and then moves up the adjacent face . Kind of a 'choose your own adventure'at the top. The crux is more mental than anything as there is a slightly run out section after you leave the slab with the potential to deck on the slab, however the climbing is easy and fun and an astute belayer can help minimize fall distance. As with any route in the Pins and Needles area, take a 70m rope and/or take two. 60m will work but you may have to get creative with it on other climbs in this area. Knot your ends!!

name: Franklin's Tower
description: Short and Sweet! This is a fun climb that starts with smearing and mantling up a boulder, then up the tower full of honeycomb-looking shuteye chickenheads.
