Super fun climb, great for beginners and novice leaders. Could also be started from behind the boulder, but where's the fun in that? 60m rope ok on this one.

name: Harvest Winds
description: From Klosof: "Climb thin right leaning crack past bolt & step left at top of seam to line of bolts. Continue up arête to anchors. 8-9 quick draws plus anchor."

name: Lickety Split
description: Follows a series of pockets up a narrow sluice like feature to a pair of anchors with chains. Fun climb, but can abrade a rope. Best belayed from top and rappelled down. 5-6 bolts.

name: Ripples
description: This is route number 1 in the Klosof guide for Terrapin: "Climb up past bolts from top of notch up & left onto rounded arête continuing up featured face to anchors. 8+ quick draws plus anchor"

name: Route 16- Klosoff Guide
description: Starts up a slab before hitting the wall. Good rock. There is a large rock just left of the route near the top that is tempting to grab, but seems like it might one day shift. Afternoon shade.

name: Route 17- Klosoff Guide
description: Nice climb that starts halfway up the right side of the slab. 7 bolts to anchor.

name: Sandy Line
description: Aptly named with much of the route under 5.7. All the fun is in the last 20 ft. Can get down with a 60m, but watch your ends if you have reason to believe your rope is short.

name: Shakedown Street
description: Great route to the summit of the Terrapin. Bolted for 2 pitches but can be done in one with either a two rope or double rap. Belay station at first anchor isn't great. Might as well do the whole thing in one shot and have the follower bring a second rope if you have the capability/draws. As per usual in this area, bring a 70m (and a spare if possible) or be prepared to get creative with a 60m

name: Sky Ladder
description: #19 in the guidebook. The climb itself isn't terrible, but the location and condition of the anchor are questionable at best. The anchor is off to the climber's right and top-roping this route could damage a rope quite easily. As the guidebook says, it's probably best to belay followers from the top.     In addition, one anchor has been significantly eroded and both anchors are extremely loose. They have been placed on a rather hollow sounding flake to boot. This anchor is shared with 'Borrowed Shoe.' Use at your own risk!

name: Top Rope
description: This is number 14 in the Klosof guide: "Climb over large grainy huecos through roof & onto slab above. Continue up slab. Anchors accessed from the Virgin."

name: Touch of Gray
description: This is route number 2 in the Klosof guide for Terrapin: "Climb up past bolts from top of notch straight up through groove at top, traverse right onto face, mantle up & climb to anchors. 8+ quick draws plus anchor."

name: Virgin
description: This is route 15 from the Klosof guide: "Climb up featured face past a natural gear & a couple of bolts to crack on right. Follow crack on right with traditional gear to 2 bolt anchor."

name: 9mm
description: Sit start on small pillar and Follow the small crack to the top, meets Less Than about half way up

name: Deathhedral
description: Sit start on good holds and move up through the dihedrals and left of the small roof

name: Directly Less Than
description: Start is the same as Less Than but go strait up the vertical crack

name: Less Than
description: Sit Start at bottom of large crack that look like a less than symbol ( < ) Great Fun!

name: Nose Job
description: Follow Arette and break left at top

name: Thats Pretty Tal
description: Start under small roof and move up the face topping out following the gray streak

name: The Block
description: Start on low right side of the large block. move to the large block and compress your way up. Use the face hold to help bump if your shorter. top out the easiest way possible.

name: Blue Belly
description: Sit start the obvious crack (same start as project to left)  and follow it to the top

name: Cow girl
description: Sit start on slowly ledges and climb left of the dihedral

name: Don't forget the Party Gnome's
description: Sit start and climb the obvious line

name: don't tell mom
description: start is the same as don't forget the party gnomes, go left tot he aerate and go up finishing on the face, enjoy the pockets.

name: Dry your eye
description: start on lower jug and move up and through the roof

name: Follow your nose
description: Sit under under the bulge. and pull to the top

name: Moped
description: Sit start the massive undercling and move up and under the roof

name: Nose goes
description: Sit start low and to the left under the small overhang, then move up into the finger crack (remember nose goes) and then up to good jugs and feet!  a great climb on some steep and short (15ft) wit and easy finish! one of the better routes out there.

name: Open Project
description: sit start same as Blue Belly butclimb the face left of the crack and up the wave and over **open project**

name: Premature chalkulation
description: Stat low in dihedral on good left rail move up towards to the right arete and a cool big more to get you around the conner then its big jugs to the end

name: Wind of liberty
description: start with matched hands and move up the budge

name: Eagle Powers
description: First ten feet border on a scramble, the rest of the climb follows a dihedral crack to the top. Not all crack climbing, though.

name: Stickup
description: Crack climbing about half way up until you top out.

name: Catalysis
description: Truly a beautiful line. Follow strikingly minuscule crimps up a slightly overhanging face.  Beta Video

name: Humping the Lorax
description: One long move on decent holds to a cruxy friction mantle.

name: It's a Peach
description: Sit Start at the small yellow corner with your left hand in a nice pocket top out on the gently overhanging wall

name: Mastermind
description: Sit start on a big pocket, match on the big sloper and crimp up until you hit the lip.

name: Mastermind the Easy Way
description: Same start as 'Mastermind,' slap sloper with right hand only and head left immediately to top-out.

name: Peaches
description: The namesake route takes a line of crimpers straight up the middle of the face. Sit/squat-start on an obvious sidepull, pimp your way thought perfect incuts and try to save some juice for the final throw to the last hold...AMAZING boulder problem!!

name: Peachonator
description: Sit start on a big hold under roof, traverse left to a big low pocket, go left until you hit the warm up problem, top-out.

name: Shelf
description: Start on some great sidepull edges on the underside of the overhang left of Peaches and launch to the jugs at the lip. Blast your way up the face using some tweaky 1- & 2-finger pockets avoiding the chossy rock to the left. This thing is surprisingly fun!!

name: Warm Up
description: Same start as 'It's a Peach,' after first two moves go right and straight up a lay back feature.

name: Determinism
description: Crux section is the steepest section right before and after bolt #3. Check out the video for more details: https://youtu.be/UWVM5JxsnPA

name: Martian Monster
description: A clean corner with good gear leads to a nicer hand crack up high. Trad gear with a bolted anchor. There is a bolt on an outcropping on the hillside above for top access.

name: A day in the Wife
description: Begin up easy terrain to the left of Hole.  Simple climbing leads up to a large pod with some vegetation nearby.  An old bolt line is left of the shinier new bolts which is what was used before a natural line of climbing revealed itself.  Clip the newer brighter fixe bolts and launch onto a sustained chipped masterpiece.      Sequential moves, no real crux, awesome friendly drilled pockets highlight this route

name: Boo
description: Boo, in my opinion, is probably the most striking and aesthetic line in the Amphitheater.  With a strenuous and resistant start, gentle overhang, roof, and steep headwall, you will need plenty of endurance.  Begin on a section of steep draining drilled pockets for a few bolts.  The angle lessons but continuous movement makes you keep momentum until you hit a large flat jug.  The first real crux is figuring out how on earth you are supposed to get your feet on said jug.  Good luck.      Fun moves lead up to the juggy roof and although the holds are good, it is steep! Above the roof the angle lessons and you are gifted with a huge flat (although fairly sharp) jug.  Rest well here because the real crux is above.      After exiting the rest you eventually move up to a small incut crimp for both hands.  Clip and launch into the slightly runout crux sequence which revolves around a sloping sidupull and a big move to a pinch.  Some airy fall potential provides enough motivation to try a little harder here.  Clip the last bolt and battle a few small crimps to the glory jug at the chains!    The route was originally named "Boo" because of a large tree that I guess you would fall into when you took the big whip off the upper crux.  It was scary so...BOO!

name: Chicken Choker
description: An extension of Chicken Dinner, Chicken Choker fires the headwall above the roof. Once you reach the large hole at the roof's corner (the ninth/anchor bolt of Chicken Dinner), clip the hanging draw to your left that escapes the route via a short traverse (the direct/right line is Yellow Man). Gain a comfortable no-hands stance on somewhat suspect rock and clip the 10th bolt before launching up the headwall. Once you leave the rest, the route climbs solid rock with lots of small edges and slopers reminiscent of Rifle's Anti-Phil wall. You will encounter one shallow, drilled pocket before the chains, but the remainder of the route is natural. Watch for rope drag along the edge of the roof, and be prepared to holler at your belayer when clipping. Chicken Choker is essentially a link-up of Chunder and Chicken Dinner, sharing the same headwall finish as Chunder.

name: Chicken dinner
description: Chicken dinner is a route that stops halfway and is comprised of huge moves on many drilled pockets in a steep permadrawed section of the cave.  Unrelenting moves on drilled jugs, pockets, and edges lead to not-very-difficult crux moves before a final redpoint crux below the yellow rock in the cave. The route finishes at the 8th bolt.  From here continuing onto the headwall it becomes chicken Choker (left, stays at about 13a) or Yellow Man (straight up, 13b)      Didn't feel like there was anything harder than maybe V3 on the whole, the challenge comes from linking it all together.

name: Chunder
description: Chunder begins on a two-finger pocket for the left hand a drilled handle-like pocket for the right. Stick clip the first (a black hanger) or second bolt (fixed draw), and crank a short boulder problem to a jug at the second bolt. Get a good rest, then fire the next few bolts of long moves on drilled pockets to a brief reprieve mid-cave. Shake here, then launch through the route's three-bolt power-endurance crux, until you reach the jug haul finish of Chicken Dinner. Climb up to the big hole, shake, then traverse left to a no-hands rest in a sizeable pod below the headwall. The character of the route shifts from extremely steep pocket-pulling to delicate, balancey movement on crimps and slopers. Hold it together for the headwall, and you've sent one of the Amphitheater's prize routes.

name: Devil Drives a Deere
description: consistent climbing with no real crux moves

name: Free Ballin'
description: A great, short, energy-sapping power route.  Begin with establishing in an undercling rail and either go out left or straight up big move to get to the pod and only rest on the route.  From there, sequential moves on mostly drilled holds get you through the wild crux at bolt 4 and the sustained race to the chains at the ceiling.

name: Gilliwrinkle
description: Be prepared to try hard! Fun bouldering to the third bolt leads you to a slab and a good rest out right. Another boulder problem awaites!

name: Hole
description: Climb a low angled slab into a sizable hole (hence the name), where you can get a nice rest, then launch up into great pocket pulling face climbing.

name: John Deere
description: Last bolt boulder problem, pumpy climbing until there

name: Lard
description: This is the basic warmup in the cave.  Starts in the center of the amphitheater and finishes in a sometimes wet pod with moss around it.  Climbs steeper than it looks

name: Sgt. Stoger
description: Techy crux at 3/4 height

name: Shiver me Timbers
description: Starts the same as Walkin' the Plank on the far right side of the crag.  Instead, move leftwards to another bolt line that finishes just after pulling onto the slab.  Bouldery, steeper start, and juggy finish and some slight choss, though nothing broke when we did it

name: Soul Harvester
description: Soul Harvester starts on Tractor Girl/boy but cuts right after the 4th bolt and follows 5 more bolts to finish in the ceiling at the end of the long rail.  It's longer than tractor girl but the last bolt is mostly a jug rail the whole way.      For most, the sequence mandates that you decide which route (tractor/soul harvester) you're going to do at the 3rd bolt then forces a right left right or left right left.  Pretty cool!    Expect lots of left heel hooks and not-super-great right feet underneath the rail where it is steeper.

name: Tractor Boy
description: One of the most mega lines at the crag taking a steep line out the cave to a pumping headwall above.  Begin as for tractor girl and rest well at the pod in the roof.  From there follow more drilled pockets to a large rail with poor feet.  A few boulder problems with rests in between will test all your endurance on the beautiful headwall above.

name: Tractor Girl
description: Another wildy steep drilled out route.  This is basically half of Tractor Boy and stops at the pod rest.  Start with the high first bolt, clip the second bolt way behind you and grab the rest you can.  After clipping the third bolt climb the big sequential moves up through bolt 5.  Tackle the crux a few different ways and get another rest at bolt 6 before the pumping finish to the pod.  You are only cool if you sink the kneebar before clipping the bolt!    Get some energy back and keep going on tractor boy!

name: Walking the Plank
description: Extension to Shiver me Timbers or its own independent line (to the right). Start on either route, SMT seems to be a nicer option with a bouldery sequence down low to jugs.    instead of clipping the anchor clip a bolt on the slab and work your way towards the tiered roof climbing above.  Drilled pockets give way to a crux towards the end and a runout above the last bit for a rightward traverse to the anchor.

name: Whole Lotta Cotton
description: Strap in for this one, 'cause it ain't over 'til it's over. Get off the ground and onto a blank slab. Smear and stem your way up through the first few bolts, slapping your hands around for any vestige of a good handhold and craning your neck to see the feet. Once you pull off the slab, find a good stance and a shake and get ready to tackle the vertical headwall. Balance, sidepull, and crimp your way up through the last three bolts in sustained, technical climbing until the anchors. Clip the chains, rejoice, and take up blood doping before your forearms hurt this bad again.

name: Yellow Man
description: Direct extension to chicken dinner. This route is mega! Once you finish dinner, scope out a good rest in the pod, then do a big reach to a drilled pocket and launch out huge moves on good holds to a another rest before the dyno. Huck your meat to a great jug and embark on a rightward traverse on small holds. The next section is more delicate and balancy which dumps you directly into some very resistant 5.12 climbing on crimps and pockets to the chains. Sick!

name: Bitch Magnet
description: Walk up the left-facing ramp and lean over to clip the first bolt. Walk up a bit more, grab the bucket, clip the second bolt, and get down to business. Make a few big crosses and long moves between huge pockets and get ready for the crux at the last bolt.  Crank down on a few crimps, paddle helplessly at the footholds like you were tossed into the pool for a swimming lesson, and lunge for the jug to finish it up. Great climbing!

name: Brother Speed
description: Brother Speed features long, powerful moves between flakes, edges, and pockets, separated by decent rests. Two distinct cruxes guard the chains: a long, lateral reach to an undercling pocket at the fourth bolt, and a dynamic pull to gain the final bolt. Excellent positions and challenging movement.

name: Flowers and Bunnies
description: An ugly duckling of the Projects area. Flowers and Bunnies climbs an easy, juggy slab for the first three bolts, until you're forced to climb the narrow ramp. Teeter your way up the ramp, looking left, right, up, down, and deep inside yourself for hidden holds. You may not like it, but that's okay. Someday, he'll be a swan.

name: St. Ides
description: After a discouraging boulder problem off the ground, the route pulls onto a ledge and into a juggy stem corner. Work your way through the easy climbing to a delicate finish on small holds.

name: Funky Buddha
description: The wall's titular route, Funky Buddha tackles the center of the vertical headwall past Buddha's bellybutton (the large, round hueco just above the slab). Smear your way up some waterpolished divots to a rest in the hueco. From there, edge, smear, and sidepull your way up some of Riggins' best limestone edges. Expect to feel a little air between your knees above the bolts. Thought-provoking and a bit pumpy.

name: Misty and Dale's Excellent Adventure
description: Climb through the first few easy bolts and crank through a short, steep section of climbing on positive edges. Pull onto the ledge above the crux section, shake out, and relax for the next couple bolts. On the headwall, the climbing thins out for a technical pump crux just below the anchor.

name: Rage Against the Janine
description: A tricky start off the ground leads into pleasant slab edging and big handholds.

name: Voice of the Voiceless
description: Voice of the Voiceless offers a satisfying capstone to Rage Against the Janine. After climbing Janine's pleasant slab, Voiceless launches up steep jugs to the top of the headwall. Powerful movement on great (though sharp holds) will earn you a nice view of McClinery Ridge.

name: What Is, Is
description: Fun, straightforward slab climbing leads up to a series of sidepulling flakes. Sustained, slightly overhung climbing on these positive incuts gets you to the anchors.

name: Night Shade
description: 5 bolts to anchors.

name: Forcemeat
description: Begin by laying back on a flake of left-facing crimps to reach the clipping edge at the first bolt. Crimp your way through positive edges to an undercling crux at the third bolt. Make an awkward clip, then keep it together through water-sculpted stone to the top of the route, stemming and high-stepping your way to victory. Reminiscent of Rifle's more-vertical routes, with excellent rock quality on its upper half.

name: Kleenex
description: Start by standing pulling off a fallen log into a big pocket from which you'll clip the first bolt. Pull some long, delightful moves on solid pockets for four bolts, take a deep breath at the flake undercling, and put your thinking cap on for the delicate, crimpy crux to pull onto the headwall and clip the anchors.

name: Rug Doctor
description: Start out in the stem corner for the first half of the climb, enjoying some rare hand jams for the area. After the first few bolts, pull out of the corner onto the face where a balancey crux reaches high to a solid pocket. Continue up peacefully to the anchors.

name: Salmonella Inn
description: Ascends the arete to the climber’s left of Rug Doctor. Joins “Back Out” after the first two bolts. A little dirty in sections.

name: Undertow
description: The wall's namesake route. Good but not great. A thin and powerful boulder problem above the third bolt is the routes hardest move, but expect the middle section to be quite sustained and shoulder intensive. Small feet and a flurry of thin crimps, shallow pockets and underclings make this this route technical and powerful- it feels hard for 12c. A great rest is found before the final bouldery moves that lead to the anchor. It seemed the chains were placed in a bad spot...I had to clip them from way left of the anchor leaning off a left hand pocket with small feet and a lot of body tension. Some holds have been chipped or enhanced.

name: Gray Matter
description: Short and powerful jug hauling. Crank through long moves on big ledges and jug edges up to the third bolt. Snatch the only crimp on the climb, lean into a sidepull rail, and keep it cool on a few delicate moves up to the anchors.

name: Bugle
description: Fun tecnical and sequential route. The current warm up for the area with many good holds and forgiving positions. Climbs up an awesome right facing corner with sweet lie backing!

name: First Come First Serve
description: A little bit of everything. Consistent bouldery moves through an overhang w/ perma draws lead to a crux exit onto the vertical headwall. Some crimps and technical steep slab are the gatekeeper to the final 5.10 terrain.

name: Sour Power
description: A superb climb! Start on a slab that leads into a progressively more overhanging face until you reach a roof. Navigate the roof through through underclings and big reaches. After the roof the technical crux awaits with some the best compression crimp moves Ive climbed on.

name: Amber Alert
description: Pull big moves on sloping rails on the far right side of the Bee Block.

name: Bee Block Direttissima
description: This is it--the business, the main event, the proud King line of Bee Block. Screw your courage to the sticking place and venture forth. Climb the steepest (ha ha) portion in the center of the formation.

name: Bombus
description: Just relax, breathe, and enjoy the sound of the creek behind you--because this route's over as soon as you get off the ground!  An excellent route for young children, the acrophobic, or a brand new climber.

name: Hive Mind
description: This route ascends the obvious plumb line up the formation just uphill and left of Bee Block. Positive feet and fun features from bottom to top. Walk off or build a very long, extended top rope anchor.

name: Itty Bitty Wings
description: An easy, un-intimidating introduction to traditional climbing. Climb the highly featured right side of Bee Block face.

name: V is for Bee Venom
description: Dabble in a bit of wide crack climbing on this one. Pick your poison, the left-leaning hand crack, or the fists and offwidth. Both are moderately enjoyable and would be quite fun if they were, say, 70 feet taller.

name: Roadside Boulder Problem
description: If climbing in the road (literally) is your thing, give this short easy problem a try. Don't get run over. The rock is slick, but the pockets are positive.

name: Twinkle Toes
description: A legitimate route in Rocky Canyon! Start by climbing good pocketed rock and clip three bolts. Continue up the slab and plug gear until you reach Metolius rap hangers. Probably the best (accessible-to-the-public) route in the Canyon.

name: Mr. Big Stuff
description: Small feet with a slight overhang make the starting move difficult. Committing top out.

name: Bastille Wall
description: A Classic! This route can be approached several ways: walking below the start of Stony Staircase, scrambling up directly from the highway, or climbing 35 Miles Per Hour.  It begins near a large dead tree on the ground in a shallow groove with a bush in it.    P1)  Climb past a few bolts under the white right-facing, arching wall to the lone dead tree on a ledge.    P2) Go up the crack above, to a bolt then traverse right onto a ledge with a two bolt belay.    P3) The third pitch can be climbed three ways, depending on how hard you want to make it.      1)	5.8 A0.  Climb up from the belay and traverse right to the bolts. Aid (French free) across the spinning hangers to gain the crack.      2)	Walk right on the ledge to directly below the aid bolts.  Free climb straight up past a bolt (5.11) to gain the crack.      3)	Traverse right on the ledge, go up a ramp heading right past a pin, then undercling the flake (5.9+) back left to the crack.   Either way, ascend the ramp and head left to the arch and a gear belay.    P4)  Traverse under the overhang hanging belay at a piton (back it up) at the far end of the overhang.    P5) Pull the roof and continue up the stellar vertical crack system to the trees.    Descend the Stony Staircase rappels (see Lightning Dome - Right Side)

name: Welcome to the Clearwater
description: Approach: Scramble up 3rd class gully about 200’ up and left of the start to Bastille Wall.  Route starts in low angle wind tunnel behind the big block that towers over the aforementioned route. P1: Fun but short finger crack leads to right trending slopey ledge past 7 bolts to 3 bolt anchor. Bolts are in good shape relatively speaking, but the lichen makes for some interesting slab moves.  5.9 slab P2:  Unprotected slab moves (don’t factor 2!) to right trending, lower angle crack onto a large grassy ledge system.  Could use some more gardening.  5.7  P3:  Low 5th class to the left and up behind large block at the top.   Descent:  We rapped Sticky Fingers.  Hadn’t been done in a while guessing from the tat. Gear: rack to 3”, double ropes, extra tat for the raps

name: Black Pine Chimney
description: This is the obvious chimney slot just left of the Black Pine Tree.    A really fun chimney that can be climbed facing in or out.  Either way, work up an increasingly tight squeeze until popping out on a bolted belay ledge.

name: Black Pine Face
description: This well protected bolt line climbs the clean face to the right of Black Pine Chimney and should not to be missed.      From the Black Pine tree, clip the obvious bolt on the arête, then balance and smear up the excellent face to the belay ledge and a rappel anchor.

name: Momentary Lapse of Reason
description: A long and mostly moderate slab climb that was originally led on poorly placed pitonssomething to ponder while sketching your way up the runout to the anchor!  This route is easily top roped after leading Black Pine Chimney or Black Pine Face.    Begin at the base of the slab about 40 feet down from Black Pine Face.  Follow the bolts to the top.   It is possible to move left into Black Pine Face after a few bolts and keep the grade at 5.8 all the way to the top.

name: Mosquito
description: Pretty good crack climbing for the first half then flaring but easy terrain.  Left facing corner to the left of black pine face.  A 70 meter rope will get you to a good belay ledge (.75 and smaller cams or larger gear in a big flake) were you can walk off to climbers left.  There are a couple class 4 moves to get down.  Can also traverse this ledge up and to the right to get to the upper ledges.    Cleaned on 6/5/20

name: Fat Albert
description: Long known as Fat Albert this route was originally called Exfoliation Expressway.  Either way this is the most classic and unique climb on the Clearwater.  This good beginners lead follows a clean dihedral for about 25 meters before tunneling underneath a natural arch to the belay.  Dont miss it!  It is nearly impossible to top rope this route since lowering through the arch isnt easily accomplished and the pendulum is nasty!    P1)  Start up the low angle corner using hand jams (superb!) and laybacking until forced to undercling the roof at the top.  Just as things start looking desperate, squeeze into the arch and pop out on the belay ledge.

name: Midnight Fright
description: Simply a spectacular climb for the grade, Midnight Fright should be on everyones tick list.  Go climb it!  It is possible to top rope this route with two ropes, but the rope drag is tremendous.     Enjoy the stellar hand crack to a small stance.  Step right and jam the flared fist-crack past the tree.  Good offwidth moves lead to a slab and finally a live belay tree.

name: Two Minutes to Midnight
description: A fun and clean slab on the arête left of Midnight Fright.      Start on the left edge of the slab and climb past six bolts and a belay tree.

name: Stony Staircase
description: The best beginners multipitch at Lightning Dome.  The second pitch starts with a bit of a runout, but the climbing is easy.      P1) From the left side of the boulder-covered approach ledge, climb the funky right facing corner and slab (3) to an au cheval move.  Head left on a small ledge system past a bush and a 2 bolt belay. 5.6 100      P2) Climb off the ledge straight up or right (right being easier), then move left to a hidden-from-below bolt after about 40.  Climb the flake/cracks above to a 2 bolt anchor. 5.6 100    P3) Continue up and left to the right-facing slanting dihedral and climb it to its top.  The belay is best positioned just above the first stunted tree. 5.5 60    P4) Scramble left to the Y shaped rappel tree.

name: Beyond Thunderdome
description: Start up the light-colored corner of Road Warrior, but escape the roof by underclinging to the right in a hand and finger crack. Follow this crack out the roof to the tree above.

name: Mad Max
description: Climb up easy rock to a challenging jog left into a steep fist crack.  Continue up the lower angle wide crack to the top. Be aware of expanding cracks and blocks when placing protection.

name: Toecutter
description: A smaller orange roof split by a narrow crack left of Road Warrior roof crack. This crack is the highlight of the route.   Start about 10’ left of “Road Warrior” in a short right-facing corner with a bush in it. Face moves lead up to the crux roof. Pull the bulge on jugs and perfect finger jams—the crux and best climbing on the route. Mosey up the dark slab   to the top.

name: 35 Miles Per Hour
description: This is a direct start to the Bastille Wall that begins between the road curve sign and a pine tree. Unfortunately, this route has been overgrown since the first ascent and needs to be reclaimed. Scout the bolt locations before starting!    P1) Scratch up the slab, pull the roof at a bolt, and continue up to a ledge with   bolts.    P2) Move right into a groove, following bolts to a ledge.    P3) Go left past some boulders to a belay at a tree.   Walk off left or continue up Bastille Wall.    (above information is from Kurt Hicks)

name: Brown Sugar
description: A very enjoyable route--this is crag classic that features great climbing, good exposure, and clean rock throughout!  Walk about 100 right of the road curve sign to the base of a dark groove.      P1) Start in the gully with a hand crack in it.  Continue up the obvious narrow brown streak of clean rock to an anchor.      P2) Continue up the brown rock to an anchor, occasionally clipping bolts.    P3) Another pitch on brown rock leads to an anchor.    P4) Trend right into a raspberry-filled gully and up to a ledge with a small bush and a belay station.  It is possible to do two double rope rappels from here to the ground using a tree for the second rappel.    P5) Traverse under the orange overhang to a belay on a boulder covered ledge.    P6-7) Head up and right to the top, following the bolts.    Rappel Sticky Fingers with 2 ropes.

name: Emotional Rescue
description: If climbing all of Brown Sugar scares you or you don't have the whole day to dedicate, this is an easy way to escape from the first pitch.    Start as for Brown Sugar. About 2/3 the way up pitch 1, escape from the friction slab by hand traversing right on a ledge, past a bolt, to a belay. Scramble off to climber’s right and down to the Road Warrior Area. Alternately, rappel off a block back to the highway.    (Route Beta from Kurt Hicks)

name: Head Trip
description: A play on words, this route was the scene of a very runout first ascent when the unknowing FA party started up an unfinished line and ran out the last two pitches without any of the current protection bolts!    P1)  Smear, edge and mantle past six widely spaced bolts to an anchor on a large knob.      P2 & 3) Follow the crest of the rib, past bolts, to the top.    Rappel the route or walk off to climbers right.

name: Mick's Lips
description: An alternate finish to Brown Sugar, this route starts at the end of pitch 5 of “Brown Sugar.” It offers spectacular exposure from high on the Rolling Stone Wall.    P1) Beginning after pitch 5 of "Brown Sugar", move off the ledge, traversing left past bolts above the lip of the orange   overhang. Belay at an anchor in a gully that is not visible from below.   P2) Continue up easier rock past some bolts to the trees.   Rappel “Sticky Fingers” with 2 ropes    Beta provided by Kurt Hicks

name: Mickey Mantle Mantra
description: P1) Steep entry moves past a bolt turn to fun slab climbing and a hanging anchor.  30M    P2)  Continue up the slab (5.9+) to a steep wall.  A fixed piton protects the steep moves before more bolts lead right to a rap anchor on a ledge.  30M    Rappel the route with one rope.  Knot the ends of your rope.

name: Sticky Fingers
description: Probably the best route on the Rolling Stone Wall, even though it suffers from having all ¼ bolts.      P1) Climb the green slab above to an anchor on a grassy ledge.  25M.    P2) Lead directly up off the ledge, then right on huge knobs for 50 of unprotected 5.6 slab climbing to reach a slanting crack in a U-shaped groove.  Follow bolts after the crack to a semi-hanging anchor.    P3) More steep friction climbing in water-worn grooves leads to the last anchor.    Rappel the route with 2 ropes.

name: Ape Man
description: Sit start at the base of the steep left-leaning corner. Powerful and crimpy moves lead to a big rail followed by progressively easier but highball terrain.

name: Bad Ass Slab
description: Step off rock and up the slab, angle right towards diagonal left to right feature. Easy yet committing moves to the top. No distinct crux, fun climbing.

name: Break Down
description: Sit start at a good jug (the initial loose hold that the route was named after appears to have broken off) and make a semi dynamic move up into a good hand jam in the overhanging "crack" formed by the two boulders leaning together.  Another move or two in the crack gets you to the finishing jugs and an easy mantel to top out.

name: Coco the Junkie Pimp
description: One move wonder. grab the obvious rail mid face paste your feet fire for the top.

name: The Goodies
description: #7 in Swan Falls Guide. A two move power problem. Sit down and commence crimping.

name: Pig Face
description: Fun compression out a small "cave" throw to a big jug top out.

name: Red Arete
description: Grab the perfect arete and lieback up the beautiful featureless face.  The arete gets much more positive as you get higher.  It's not that high, but the landing is awkward which gives it a bit of headiness.

name: Split
description: Find the vertical seam and layback it from a sit start.  The rock is rough and sharp, but the moves are fun.

name: The Austrian
description: Sit Start on a large undercling flake and ascend the arete to the top.

name: The Austrian
description: Same as The Austrian (V6) except begin as a sit start.

name: Backside Break
description: Start sitting on a pinch and edge and work up straight through the block (loose) through a large side-pull and establish on top of the boulder.

name: Black Slabbath
description: Start matched on the obvious good hold in the middle of the face. Edge up the slab through shallow dishes while making use of similar holds for your feet.

name: California love
description: Starts on giant jug sidepull up and left though crimps.

name: Flaky Center
description: Begin on a triangle shaped start hold and make your way up past a slanting seam to a shallow slot. From here make a long move to a crimp and top out.  Book has V3/4 but seems pretty hard for that. I gave it solid V4 on here.

name: Flaky Left
description: Pull on a high crimp and sidepull. Climb up until reaching back around the blunt arete for a slopey jug to top out.

name: Flaky Sidepulls
description: Start on opposing side pulls and climb straight up through crimps to a semi-engaging top-out that ends in jugs.

name: Kegelmaster
description: Crux is pulling off the ground, pretty chill after opening move. Start seated on sidepull seam move up for a move or two to jugs and an easy top out

name: Manchild
description: Start on obvious chalked ledge go right and up, going left is harder with a much worse landing and probably more classic

name: Rex Kwan do
description: Boulder starts seated on obvious pointed ledge, make tough moves up the arete until you can bust out right to a good sidepull Then continue working your way up the arete

name: Surgery
description: Start down and to the left on two underclings. Smear feet and power through an undercling sequence out right to a large sidepull jug. Recharge for a moment then reach out through slopey, blocky rails and oppose your body tension until ready to dunk the blind jug. Try not to end up in the bush!

name: Veto aka hotchaw
description: Start on crimps on face, move right to good sidepull, then bump up through right hand sidepulls to the top of the boulder.  Can start on underling feature to add a few grades of difficulty

name: Follicle
description: Sit start with both hands on the arete. Move up the arete using any of the holds and top out the boulder straight up or up and right.

name: Hairpin Arete - Stand Start
description: Heel hook and slap up the arete.  Fun!    The sit start is supposed to be V5.

name: Hairpin Face
description: Climb straight up the overhanging face using large edges.  The climb features great movement and fancy footwork on impeccable rock.  If you're in the area, this one is a must do!

name: Mystery Box
description: Climb the slab face to the left of Follicle. Small crimps and delicate feet lead to an exciting move(s) to the lip. Top out.  This climb is not in the Swan Falls Bouldering guidebook. I don't know its history, name, suggested grade, etc., so if anyone has any info, please share.  Not really sure about the grade, but felt about as hard as other V3 slabs I've done, but your experience could be much different.

name: Raw Tips
description: Start at the face level crimps, get your foot to stick to some tiny dishes, and make a reach for a higher left hand edge.  If you can make the reach and stand up without your foot popping, you're basically done.  Finish on good holds to the top.

name: Rock Snob Boulder group, V easy face
description: This is an unnamed boulder with an easy face, and easy access off the top. My first shot at bouldering!

name: Rock Snob Boulder group, V0- route
description: Climb the white arete. Second photo is a very easy face.

name: Rock snob Boulder, north face
description: Climb the right side face, on crimps.

name: Rock snob boulder, north face
description: Climb the arete, from the north side (to the right of the north face)

name: Rock Snob V1
description: Head up the slab without using either arete.

name: Run Away
description: Climb the up the arete and then move right before the loose rock, sharing the top out with "Raw Tips".  To start, look for a sidepull for the left hand around the left side of the arete, and a ripply crimp for the right hand around the right side of the arete.  Apparently a sit-start variation is also possible, obviously increasing the difficulty.

name: Slabby Side
description: Start on the right side of the Hairpin Arete, pinching the arete with your left hand, and using a shallow right hand mono.  Stand up and pull onto the slab above (fun crux).  Once established on the slab, it's easy climbing to the top.

name: Inbred
description: Sit start. Follow the obvious line up and left of the steep face.  Amazing!

name: Inbred Direct
description: Just left of Inbred, sit start on the low flake.  Climb up obvious but contrived line.

name: Chunky
description: Sit start and charge up on big holds. Do some laps, good pump.

name: Campus
description: climb the right side arete

name: Mondo Generator
description: super fun swan falls classics

name: Mondola
description: Start on the left facing ear hold, and move right to an obvious crimp. Move up to a finger lock/sidepull. Multiple options to finish. An instant classic!  Beta Video

name: Monkey Swing
description: big swing

name: Groove Right
description: Sit start, climb up the arete on ride side of the huge scar.

name: Orgasmo
description: Fun low-ball, start matched on brick at the back of the cave, a couple moves out of the dabby roof to a chill top out

name: Tall Face
description: Climb up the tall face on widely spaced edges.

name: Thin Face
description: Scratch your way up the thinness on the left side of Tall Face

name: Death Proof
description: Start on a good edge down low, some start with a heel hand match. Move up then left on steep slopers until you can slap the arete. From here easier but scarier climbing awaits. Grab the send and become "Death Proof"

name: Bite the Bullet
description: Just to the left of crack is a pockmarked face.

name: Pullout Finger Crack
description: Sit start at the bottom of crack and follow it up. Nice moves.

name: Make it F**** up
description: Start on jug underlings, up to good edge, find a way to get to the next jug and avoid dabbing ( this is the move that gives the boulder it's name). From the jug traverse right and top out in the slot.

name: Mountaineering
description: Chimney and wedge your way up the gap between the boulders (just left of Spice World Arete). Expect awkward moves up high.

name: Rifleman
description: Starts low seated up and left though cool holds

name: Scary Spice
description: Start 10' left of the crack at a big left-facing sidepull. Climb straight up to a "scary" top out.

name: Slot Traverse
description: Route #67 in Swan Falls guide. Sit start at the low slot. Traverse right past another slot and a deep two-finger pocket to the prow and up.

name: Spice Rack
description: Sit start at the base of the right-leaning diagonal seam. Follow the seam up and right. A poor landing and loose holds add some excitement. Stacking crash pads will bring the difficulty down to V2.

name: Spice World Arete
description: The classic overhanging arete. Start both hands on the big ledge.

name: Sporty Spice
description: Starting at the Old Spice Crack, diagonal left past the pocket to a spooky exit onto the slab.

name: Two Finger
description: Route #68 in Swan Falls guide. Start at a two finger pocket and wander up the prow.

name: Chris' Loss
description: A cool sloper traverse near "Chris' Mantel" (listed in the guidebook). Start on the obvious sloper low and left. Traverse right and all the way up the sloper-rail to the incut edge.

name: Agra
description: Crimp up edges on the face just left of the large fracture, avoiding the use of the lip of the arete to the right.  The moves are sustained and the crux is near the top.  Beware the razor crystal on the last crimp!    If you exit right onto the arete it goes at V1.

name: Be like Mike
description: jump start to a medium edge near the left arete peddle your feet and grab jugs.

name: Blues Man
description: Follow perfect ring locks to the top.

name: Face Mecca
description: Start in the center of the face, with big edges for hands, and not much for feet.  Make a big reach to the slopers on top of the boulder, and pull over.

name: High Heels
description: Sit start at the horizontal rail.  Heel hook and throw for the jug to the left. Cool one move wonder.

name: Inbred Low Traverse
description: traverse right for a bit then either stick to small moves on slopers or do a big move straight for the jug top out above jug.

name: Mecca Right
description: Sit start at the right arete and pull up on jugs.

name: Mecca Traverse
description: Start on Mecca Right, then traverse left using good edges for hands and small chips for feet.  Go past Face Mecca and finish up the left side of the Mecca Boulder.  Tough edging!

name: Mumtaz Mahal
description: Traverse the diagonal seam up and right to the large fracture. Route #60 in the Swan Falls Bouldering guide.

name: Palm Pilot
description: Sit start using the diagonal ledge feature as a side pull.  Pull up onto the low ledge and mantle on to the top.  Keep your eyes open features to reach to on the initial pull . . .

name: Sari Charlie
description: Pull onto the rail throw right hand to the right arete hand heel match go for small hold on face top out.

name: Toro
description: Wonderful route working out of overhang with crimps and core tension/foot trickery.

name: Dihedrral
description: Lieback and stem up a nice finger crack that becomes increasingly dirty as you climb higher. Bring a brush if you're planning a toprope session. There are much better routes in The Arena, but this makes for a good warmup.

name: Back Drop
description: Sit start at two low crimps and then climb up the center of the wall on good holds. (Description via Boise Climbs)

name: Slip Fault
description: Sit Start on an obvious sloper rail to the right of Back Drop and then trend left to the Back Drop finish. (Description via Boise Climbs)

name: Comfortably Numb
description: Climb straight up on sidepulls and small edges. If you're not tall then you might need a cheater stone to start.

name: Corner to Pocket Traverse
description: Start on Corner Crack and traverse left on the ledge. Finish at Two Finger Pocket route.

name: Hunchback Layback
description: Starts in an excellent corner with perfect finger locks and stemming to a small ledge halfway up.  The rock at the top is questionable, lending to an exciting topout way above your pad.      The time to try this climb is in the winter, when the large poison ivy  bush at the base dies away.

name: Mickey Mantel
description: Mantley and fun!  Climb up the 3 obvious ledges to a sandy topout.

name: Sharp Arete
description: This route ascends the obvious sharp arete on the large detached boulder in the Big Times Area. Ascend the arete without using the block on the left. Mind the poison ivy at the base of the climb if you're climbing in the spring/summer/fall.

name: Tall Face
description: Not sure if this has a name already, positive other have done it before me. Start in the middle of the trail side face on two shoulder high crimps reach up for a left hand side pull, take a right hand intermediate, set up and make a move for the obvious rail. plan your descent ahead of time lots of poison ivy.

name: Wayback Layback
description: Liebacks and smears

name: Blast Hole
description: Stem and layback using the drill scar.      Don't let the easy rating fool you, this route gets committing up high . . .

name: Boulder Crack
description: Layback and stem up the corner using the finger crack.  Fun!

name: C & L Route
description: The easiest route in the immediate vicinity.  Climb the slab to the top.

name: Drill Crack
description: Climb up the drill scar to a sandy mantel.  The mantel isn't as bad as it sounds.

name: Drilled Pockets
description: Sit start at the drilled pockets on the arete.  High step onto a dubious foot and rock over to a shallow mono on the slab to the right.  Easy slabbing gets you to the top from there.

name: Mantel and Pop
description: Starts with a delicate mantel onto a ledge.  After standing on the ledge "pop" for the top and then do another mantel, only this time it's sandier and more committing.

name: Penicillin
description: Fight the barn-door & layback up the left side of the arete on fairly positive (but spaced) holds between the Drill Crack and the Blast Hole.

name: Sleeping Dog
description: Starts with a jug undercling that can be used to step up and reach the next undercling and a crimp.  Make one more move to gain good holds.  Fun move!

name: Super Crack
description: Climb the seam, which seemed just a hair too small for my fingers.  It opens up a bit 2/3 the way up.

name: Tubular
description: Climb up to the blast hole and then make a big move for the top.  Fun and easy.

name: The Whole Ordeal
description: Beautiful stemming corner with a seam that occasionally opens up enough to sneak a couple digits in.

name: Bob Down Under
description: Sit start at the back of the cave on the left side.  Climb straight out along the ceiling and over the lip.

name: Bob the Seal
description: Sit start and pull on the obvious chalked scoop to a crimp then shoot for deep holds on the lip of the rock.  The topout is challening and is the namesake of the route.

name: Bob's Down Under Traverse
description: A low traverse on slopers, start on the far right side of the boulder. traverse all the way left and exit onto the upper lip and mental. Jug hold near the end of the climb is broken off making the climb more difficult than the guide book suggests.

name: Bob's Nose
description: Start by reaching up to jugs on the right side of the roof.  Pull over the roof.

name: DiscomBOBulator
description: Traverse the lip of the roof from left to right.  Crux is somewhere near the middle.  Finish on Bob the Seal.

name: Behind the Bush
description: Sit start with a obvious vertical right hand side pull and a sloping rail for the left hand make 1 long move to a jug then take it straight up on edges w/ good feet.

name: Emphysema
description: Awesome compression line on all natural features.    Sit start on the right side of the smoke me boulder, your left hand low with a left heel hook your right hand on a arete feature. make a long move out left to a opposing arete throw up a right heel and squeeze your way to the top.

name: Sit Down and smoke me
description: Sit start w/ bad feet, hands low on the left leaning rail. make a move or two up the rail toss for the lip and top out. supposedly a key foot hold has broken making the start harder.

name: Smoke me Traverse
description: Stand start on the left leaning rail make a move to gain the lip traverse right on the lip top out on the right side of the boulder

name: Beef Man
description: Beef Man shares the first three bolts with Too Easy. After clipping the third bolt, you will traverse under the obvious roof block. Save some power for the finish. The crux awaits. Clip two more bolts and finish on Too Easy anchors.

name: Blodo Manfreak
description: Despite the claim of Too Easy, Blodo Manfreak is the easiest route on this wall. Only the finish presents any real challenge. Holds progressively thin as you near the anchors.

name: Too Easy
description: Easy climbing leads to a challenging traverse.

name: Below the Roof Traverse
description: Lots of holds makes for several options.  Staying low and avoiding the good holds about 10ft up felt harder, maybe V1.  There are supposedly brittle holds very high.

name: Ceiling Crack
description: Starts at the perpendicular intersection of the two roof cracks in the ceiling of the cave.  Jam out the horizontal roof (rough jams!) to the rail and finish with a mantel.

name: Electric Cross Direct
description: This actually consists of several fun problems.  Pull the roof of the Electric Cross Traverse straight up pretty much anywhere along it. Gets maybe slightly harder from left to right, but all about V0.

name: Electric Cross Traverse
description: Traverse the lip of the roof on positive holds.  Fun and Pumpy!

name: Headstone Crack
description: Start on jugs then commit to the rough (and steep) finger crack, finish with an airy mantle.  Cool problem!

name: The Mushroom
description: This route uses face holds for a couple moves and then pulls the roof on the left side on positive holds with a committing mantle to topout.

name: Crackerjack
description: Climb up the thin face immediately right of The Crystal.  The lunge for the top can be hairy if you're not tall.  A V3 variation goes without using the Crystal for a handhold.

name: The Crystal Butt Start
description: A SDS variation of The Crystal.  Start on the right facing lieback feature then transition into The Crystal.

name: The Crystal
description: Starts on the left facing lieback and a right crimp.  Smear up to the quartz crystal then make the big move for the top.

name: Fortress Regular Route
description: Start with your right hand on the bid edge and climb up.  There is a left-facing flake that sounds hollow.  Don't pull too hard on it...

name: Fortress Right Corner
description: Think hard about the landing before committing to the crux finish.

name: Gastons
description: A very big step up leads to the obvious opposing sidepulls and delicate smears.

name: Left Hand Start
description: Start with your left hand on the obvious edge and climb straight up.

name: Microman
description: Will your feet to stick as you slap up the rounded lieback feature.

name: Right Hand Start
description: Start with your right hand on the obvious edge and climb straight up.

name: Bobby's Traverse
description: Traverse from right to left, without using the top of the wall, starting in a shallow corner.  This climb has some fun sequences, but unfortunately it also has several ledges mixed in which interrupt the rhythm.

name: The Cutting Edge Traverse
description: Approx. 45 feet of traversing left to right from a large crack to easy climbing.  Lots of good feet on this one, and a few sucker holds littered throughout as well.

name: Humdrum
description: Step up and grab the jug, then continue grabbing jugs all the way to the top.

name: Junior Achievement
description: A nice layback problem that is not too tough.

name: Kobe's Forehead
description: Make one move to a jug, and then a good sized reach to the fragile mossy rock above . . .

name: Laid Back
description: Start at big slopey ledge and lieback the crack.

name: Nova
description: Fun and balancy laybacking up the finger crack.  This problem is pretty short, so it would be a good choice for those who don't like to climb high off the deck.

name: Pop Tart
description: Step onto the wall using crimps and then "pop" for the flat-topped hold.  After latching this hold, make several more moves to your choice of moss covered holds to topout.

name: Psycho Braill
description: Starts at a small (12") roof.  Pull over the roof to slopey pockets and crimps.  Figuring out which edges are good and which just look good is half the battle.

name: Santa's Secret
description: Finger locks to jugs.  Pretty easy.

name: Sudden Meltdown
description: Harder than it looks!  This is a great problem that rewards balance and good beta more than strength.      Traverse right to left starting at the Junior Achievement Crack.  The route has two distinct halves, broken up by a good crack in the middle.  After a few easy moves the first half consists of techy, balancy climbing using small crimps and a mono.  After the crack you have some larger holds to work with, but they are spaced far apart.  The final rail is a bit pumpy after the rest of the traverse.    Overall a great problem with several thought provoking cruxes.  Maybe one of the best at Table Rock?

name: Super Nova
description: This is the same route as Nova but with a sit start.  The sit start makes it much harder.

name: Zimbo
description: Crimp up small holds on a vertical face following the right angling seam.  The jug to the right is a different route.

name: Oyster Bar
description: Sit start on obvious jugs in the back of the cave near the crack and climb straight up the oyster like ceiling, avoid using anything on the right side of the large crack. Use underclings, shallow pockets, good crimps, precision footwork, and some slopers in order to finish inside the oyster's shell! (by all means you can top the entire boulder after that, but its 12 more feet of chossy mossy sketchiness!)

name: Pocket Paradise
description: Approach the wall on the far left of the caves and grab a sloper with both hands. immediately above your head is a series of pockets leading right towards a sloped rail. match with hands on top to finish this problem. Elusive feet make this a fun campus! finish to the right for a little harder finish.

name: Rhino's horn
description: Stand Right under the horn, match on the slope and start pulling on obvious jugs and follow the arete. Best holds are to the left of the horn. mantle the horn, find your balance and top out using the dihedral. Don't fall!

name: The Grinch
description: Use crimpy side pulls and gastons for your left hand, and the peanut butter pockets for your right.  Not much for feet on this one.

name: Nuclear Sunset
description: Start on Propeller. At the first roof, make a traversing move left, followed by a powerful bouldery sequence to gain a finger crack. This route has been lead, and even soloed a handful of times! Shares anchors with Propeller

name: Peanut Butter Left Arete
description: Climb the arete on the left side of the Peanut Butter Pockets boulder using the lip and some slopey feet.

name: Peanut Butter Pockets
description: The moves are fun if you don't mind climbing on drilled pockets.  Use the good drilled two finger pockets, and some small nubs for feet, to gain the top, finish with a mantle.

name: Peanut Butter Prophecy
description: Sit start on the right arete, then span over to the pockets out left. Adds a few more moves and a lot more fun to Peanut Butter Pockets.

name: Peanut Butter Right Arete
description: Climb the arete to the right of Peanut Butter Pockets. Somewhat positive moves down low lead to a long reach for the lip up high.  Fun!

name: Snake Corner
description: Lieback or stem up the finger crack in the dihedral just right of 'Propeller'. The worthwhile section is quite short.

name: Heel Hook
description: Start by hanging from obvious slopers. Throw up a heel and start pulling!  Go straight up using slopey holds and edges.

name: Sweaty Peach
description: Hopefully you brought your chalk, this one is harder than it looks!    Sit start at some slopers, then pull up and traverse to the left, around the corner, and finish by climbing up Heel Hook.

name: Under The Table
description: This is one of table rocks best

name: Ol' Pen
description: The line is directly up the middle, on the East side of boulder. The climb starts with left hand in center and right hand further out right. Compression moves and slabby feet up through the small shelf, then reach for the top. Easy top out. Down climb on the south side of boulder.

name: 96° F
description: Start with foot or feet on the small ledge just off the ground, with hands on either side on decent sized sidecrimps. Then move up to small pockets and large rounded jug. Continue to the two opposing cracks on the upper face and top out.

name: Air It Out
description: Good holds down low lead to bigger moves as you get higher.  Get some air while you reach for the right side of the prow and work your way to the top.

name: Erectile Dysfunction
description: Use slippery slopers, cruxy crimps, fancy footwork, and mad mantle skills to tackle this monster! Viagra is aid.

name: Fistful of Inspiration
description: Short, overhanging offwidth leads to fist jams and then wide hands.   Good clean stone in the crack, still a bit dirty on the topout. I brushed it some, but it will take some time to clean up.

name: Fully Functional
description: Overhanging face climbing on huge holds leads to a mantle topout on smaller but still easy holds.

name: Green Mossy Skull
description: Start on left hand side-pull and right hand slopy crimp off to the right side. Move up, staying below the clear crack, and then left. Top out just right of tree.

name: High Moon
description: Right foot starts on bottom right outcropping, left hand in a good 2-3 finger pocket, right hand on a jug. Work your way up, traversing left, reach for upper slopy hold on right.

name: Rags Among Riches
description: Good crimps and sidepulls lead you across the rock to a large crack.  Climb up the crack to the left on slopers and crimps to top out right below the peak.

name: Reach for it
description: A variant to Warm-Up Problem.  This adds a sit start and goes right halfway up while I think Warm-Up goes left.  Once you get over the bulge stay right to make the problem harder.  Going left makes it V0.

name: Unknown Problem
description: Boulder 4 from the area pictures provided by Gary Mattos. This is a fun boulder with sharp rock. Start with hands down low on either side of the block and then start bumping, hooking, and tossing to the obvious horn and top out.

name: Vegan Power
description: Utilize the same sit start as for Weiner in the Window and make the first big move out to the pocket. From here continue working left, staying low on the overhung face avoiding the jug rail just above. Continue working left until you reach the last big pocket on the overhung face and work up and left to top out with easier moves. See video in comments for complete beta.

name: Warm-up
description: Small, sharp holds. on a leaning ledge. As you move up the holds get bigger.

name: Warm-up Problem
description: Start on the corner and then go up and left on good holds. Top out.

name: Weiner in the Window
description: A couple big moves lead you to an easy top out. Sit Start using the three finger pocket and the sidepull directly below it. Commit to the pocket out left and then work your way straight up in line with right hand. A few key foot placements and hand adjustments aid in this routes completion. See video in comments for complete beta.
